{"title_page": "Xing Ailan", "text_new": "{{short description|Chinese discus thrower}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name        = Xing Ailan\n| full_name   = \n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| nationality = Chinese\n| sport       = Athletics\n| event       = Discus throw\n| club        = \n| collegeteam =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1965|2|23|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| height      =\n| weight      =\n}}\n\n'''Xing Ailan''' (born 23 February 1965) is a Chinese [[Sport of athletics|athlete]]. She competed in the [[Athletics at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's discus throw|women's discus throw]] at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/xi/xing-ailan-1.html |title=Xing Ailan Olympic Results |accessdate=14 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Footer Asian Champions women's discus throw}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Xing, Ailan}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Chinese female discus throwers]]\n[[Category:Olympic athletes of China]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{PRChina-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chinese discus thrower}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name        = Xing Ailan\n| full_name   = \n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| nationality = Chinese\n| sport       = Athletics\n| event       = Discus throw\n| club        = \n| collegeteam =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1965|2|23|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| height      =\n| weight      =\n}}\n\n'''Xing Ailan''' (born 23 February 1965) is a Chinese [[Sport of athletics|athlete]]. She competed in the [[Athletics at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's discus throw|women's discus throw]] at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/xi/xing-ailan-1.html |title=Xing Ailan Olympic Results |accessdate=14 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Footer Asian Champions women's discus throw}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Xing, Ailan}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Chinese female discus throwers]]\n[[Category:Olympic athletes of China]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{PRChina-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xing_Ailan"}
{"title_page": "1881 in Australia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2011}}\n{{Year in Australia|1881}}\nThe following lists events that happened during '''1881 in Australia'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n\n=== Governors===\n[[Governors of the Australian states|Governors of the Australian colonies]]:\n* [[Governors of New South Wales|Governor of New South Wales]]- [[Augustus Loftus|Lord Augustus Loftus]]\n* [[Governors of Queensland|Governor of Queensland]]- [[Arthur Edward Kennedy|Sir Arthur Kennedy]]\n* [[Governors of South Australia|Governor of South Australia]]- [[William Jervois|Sir William Jervois]]\n* [[Governors of Tasmania|Governor of Tasmania]] - [[George Strahan (colonialist)|Major Sir George Strahan]]\n* [[Governors of Victoria|Governor of Victoria]]- [[George Phipps, 2nd Marquess of No\nmanby|George Phipps, Marquess of Normanby]]\n* [[Governor of Western Australia]]- [[William Robinson (Australian governor)|Sir William Robinson]]\n\n===Premiers===\n[[Premiers of the Australian states|Premiers of the Australian colonies]]:\n* [[Premiers of New South Wales|Premier of New South Wales]] - [[Henry Parkes|Sir Henry Parkes]]\n* [[Premiers of Queensland|Premier of Queensland]] - [[Thomas McIlwraith]]\n* [[Premiers of South Australia|Premier of South Australia]] - [[William Morgan (Australian politician)|William Morgan]] till 24 June then [[John Cox Bray|Sir John Cox Bray]]\n* [[Premiers of Tasmania|Premier of Tasmania]] - [[William Giblin]]\n* [[Premiers of Victoria|Premier of Victoria]] - [[Graham Berry]] until 9 July then [[James Service]]\n\n==Events==\n* 18 June - The [[Art Gallery of South Australia]] opened by [[Prince Albert Victor, Duke of Clarence]].\n\n==Census==\nIn the mid-19th century the colonial statisticians encouraged compatibility between the colonies in their respective censuses, and in 1881 a [[Census in Australia|census]] was held simultaneously in each of the colonies.<ref name=\"ABSCensusHist2005\">{{cite web | year = 2005 | url = http://www.abs.gov.au/Ausstats/abs@.nsf/Previousproducts/1301.0Feature%20Article92005?opendocument&tabname=Summary&prodno=1301.0&issue=2005&num=&view= | title = The population census - a brief history | work = 1301.0 - Year Book Australia, 2005 | publisher = [[Australian Bureau of Statistics]] | accessdate = 2006-06-25}}</ref> This was part of a census of the [[British Empire]].  The questions posed in the colonies were not uniform.\n\nThe population of Australia was 2,250,194.<ref name = \"1881Events\">{{cite book |editor1=Aplin, Graeme |editor2=S.G. Foster |editor3=Michael McKernan | title = Australians: Events and Places | year = 1987 | publisher = Fairfax, Syme & Weldon Associates | location = Broadway, New South Wales, Australia  | isbn = 0-949288-13-6 | page = 97}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+ '''1881 census results'''\n!NSW\n!Vic\n!Qld\n!Tas\n!SA\n!NT\n!WA\n!'''Australia'''\n|-\n|751,468\n|862,346\n|213,525\n|115,704\n|276,414\n|9,797\n|29,708\n|'''2,250,194'''\n|}\n\nNorthern Territory was counted within South Australia (286,211) and was 3,451 plus 6,346 Aboriginals in settled districts.  The population of Western Australia did not include full-blood Aborigines.<ref name = \"1881Events\"/>\n\nThe population of greater Melbourne was 282,947 and of Sydney was 224,939.<ref name = \"1881Events\"/>\n<!--\n==Exploration and settlement==\n-->\n<!--\n==Science and technology==\n-->\n\n==Arts and literature==\n{{main|1881 in Australian literature}}\n\n==Sport==\n* ''Zulu'' wins the [[Melbourne Cup]]\n\n==Births==\n* 10 January - [[Leslie Rainey]], cricketer, footballer and tennis player (died 1962)\n* 6 April - [[Frank Leslie Thomson Wilmot]], Australian poet (died 1942).\n* 11 September - [[William Jolly]], first Lord Mayor of Brisbane (died 1955)\n\n==Deaths==\n* 2 August - [[Marcus Clarke]], author (born 1846)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Australia}}\n{{Oceania topic|1800 in|countries_only=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1881 in Australia}}\n[[Category:1881 by country|Australia]]\n[[Category:1881 in Australia| ]]\n[[Category:Years of the 19th century in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2011}}\n{{Year in Australia|1881}}\nThe following lists events that happened during '''1881 in Australia'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n\n=== Governors===\n[[Governors of the Australian states|Governors of the Australian colonies]]:\n* [[Governors of New South Wales|Governor of New South Wales]]- [[Augustus Loftus|Lord Augustus Loftus]]\n* [[Governors of Queensland|Governor of Queensland]]- [[Arthur Edward Kennedy|Sir Arthur Kennedy]]\n* [[Governors of South Australia|Governor of South Australia]]- [[William Jervois|Sir William Jervois]]\n* [[Governors of Tasmania|Governor of Tasmania]] - [[George Strahan (colonialist)|Major Sir George Strahan]]\n* [[Governors of Victoria|Governor of Victoria]]- [[George Phipps, 2nd Marquess of Normanby|George Phipps, Marquess of Normanby]]\n* [[Governor of Western Australia]]- [[William Robinson (Australian governor)|Sir William Robinson]]\n\n===Premiers===\n[[Premiers of the Australian states|Premiers of the Australian colonies]]:\n* [[Premiers of New South Wales|Premier of New South Wales]] - [[Henry Parkes|Sir Henry Parkes]]\n* [[Premiers of Queensland|Premier of Queensland]] - [[Thomas McIlwraith]]\n* [[Premiers of South Australia|Premier of South Australia]] - [[William Morgan (Australian politician)|William Morgan]] till 24 June then [[John Cox Bray|Sir John Cox Bray]]\n* [[Premiers of Tasmania|Premier of Tasmania]] - [[William Giblin]]\n* [[Premiers of Victoria|Premier of Victoria]] - [[Graham Berry]] until 9 July then [[James Service]]\n\n==Events==\n* 18 June - The [[Art Gallery of South Australia]] opened by [[Prince Albert Victor, Duke of Clarence]].\n\n==Census==\nIn the mid-19th century the colonial statisticians encouraged compatibility between the colonies in their respective censuses, and in 1881 a [[Census in Australia|census]] was held simultaneously in each of the colonies.<ref name=\"ABSCensusHist2005\">{{cite web | year = 2005 | url = http://www.abs.gov.au/Ausstats/abs@.nsf/Previousproducts/1301.0Feature%20Article92005?opendocument&tabname=Summary&prodno=1301.0&issue=2005&num=&view= | title = The population census - a brief history | work = 1301.0 - Year Book Australia, 2005 | publisher = [[Australian Bureau of Statistics]] | accessdate = 2006-06-25}}</ref> This was part of a census of the [[British Empire]].  The questions posed in the colonies were not uniform.\n\nThe population of Australia was 2,250,194.<ref name = \"1881Events\">{{cite book |editor1=Aplin, Graeme |editor2=S.G. Foster |editor3=Michael McKernan | title = Australians: Events and Places | year = 1987 | publisher = Fairfax, Syme & Weldon Associates | location = Broadway, New South Wales, Australia  | isbn = 0-949288-13-6 | page = 97}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+ '''1881 census results'''\n!NSW\n!Vic\n!Qld\n!Tas\n!SA\n!NT\n!WA\n!'''Australia'''\n|-\n|751,468\n|862,346\n|213,525\n|115,704\n|276,414\n|9,797\n|29,708\n|'''2,250,194'''\n|}\n\nNorthern Territory was counted within South Australia (286,211) and was 3,451 plus 6,346 Aboriginals in settled districts.  The population of Western Australia did not include full-blood Aborigines.<ref name = \"1881Events\"/>\n\nThe population of greater Melbourne was 282,947 and of Sydney was 224,939.<ref name = \"1881Events\"/>\n<!--\n==Exploration and settlement==\n-->\n<!--\n==Science and technology==\n-->\n\n==Arts and literature==\n{{main|1881 in Australian literature}}\n\n==Sport==\n* ''Zulu'' wins the [[Melbourne Cup]]\n\n==Births==\n* 10 January - [[Leslie Rainey]], cricketer, footballer and tennis player (died 1962)\n* 6 April - [[Frank Leslie Thomson Wilmot]], Australian poet (died 1942).\n* 11 September - [[William Jolly]], first Lord Mayor of Brisbane (died 1955)\n\n==Deaths==\n* 2 August - [[Marcus Clarke]], author (born 1846)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Australia}}\n{{Oceania topic|1800 in|countries_only=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1881 in Australia}}\n[[Category:1881 by country|Australia]]\n[[Category:1881 in Australia| ]]\n[[Category:Years of the 19th century in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "49.178.55.179", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eGovernors)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1881_in_Australia"}
{"title_page": "Vaisakhi", "text_new": "\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{infobox holiday\n  | holiday_name  = Vaisakhi\n  | image         = Handsworth Vaisakhi.jpg\n  | caption       = Vaisakhi is the birthday of Khalsa Panth<ref name=senker10/>\n  | nickname      = Baisakh, Vaisakh\n  | observedby    = [[Sikhs]], [[Punjabi Hindus]]\n  | observances  = Prayers, [[procession]]s, raising of the [[Nishan Sahib]] flag, Fairs.\n  | celebrations = Parades and Nagar Kirtan, Fairs, Amrit Sanchaar (baptism) for new Khalsa\n  | type         = Hindu\n  |longtype      = religious, cultural\n  |date2018 = Sat, 14 April\n  |date2019 = Sun, 14 April<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.india.gov.in/calendar/calendar.php?date=2019-04 |title=April 2019 Official Central Government Holiday Calendar |accessdate=17 December 2017 |publisher = Government of India}}</ref>\n  |date2020 = Mon, 13 April<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.india.gov.in/calendar/calendar.php?date=2020-04 |title=April 2020 Official Central Government Holiday Calendar |accessdate=17 December 2017 |publisher = Government of India}}</ref>\n  | significance = Solar New Year,<ref name=\"ColeSambhi1995p63\"/> Harvest festival, birth of the [[Khalsa]], Punjabi new year\n}}\n\n'''Vaisakhi''' ([[IAST]]: {{IAST|vis\u0101kh\u012b}}), also known as '''Baisakhi''' is a historical and religious festival in [[Hinduism]] and [[Sikhism]]. It is usually celebrated on 13 or 14 April every year,<ref>{{cite book|author=Harjinder Singh|title=Vaisakhi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bCReCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA2|publisher=Akaal Publishers|page=2}}</ref><ref name=\"Gupta2006p998\">{{cite book|author1=K.R. Gupta|author2=Amita Gupta|title=Concise Encyclopaedia of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9dNOT9iYxcMC&pg=PA998 |year=2006|publisher=Atlantic Publishers|isbn=978-81-269-0639-0|page=998}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/naperville-sun/community/chi-ugc-article-sikh-religious-society-organizes-two-day-con-2017-11-18-story.html|title=Sikh Religious Society Organizes Two -day Conference in Chicago to Implement Mool Nanakshahi Calendar|last=Bodiwala|first=Suresh|date=November 18, 2017|work=Chicago Tribune|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171120024123/http://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/naperville-sun/community/chi-ugc-article-sikh-religious-society-organizes-two-day-con-2017-11-18-story.html|archivedate=November 20, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Singh1998\">{{cite book|author=Harbans Singh|title=The Encyclopaedia of Sikhism: S-Z|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XhXYAAAAMAAJ&dq=nanakshahi+and+khalsa+calendars&focus=searchwithinvolume|date=1 January 1998|publisher=Publications Bureau|isbn=978-81-7380-530-1}}</ref> which commemorates the formation of [[Khalsa]] panth of warriors under [[Guru Gobind Singh]] in 1699.<ref name=senker10>{{cite book|author=Cath Senker|title=My Sikh Year|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PsQozVTKW44C&pg=PA10|year=2007|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-4042-3733-9|page=10}}, At Vaisakhi, Sikhs remember how their community, the Khalsa, first began.\"</ref><ref name=\"ColeSambhi1995p63\"/><ref name=bbcv>BBC Religions (2009), [http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/sikhism/holydays/vaisakhi.shtml Vaisakhi and the Khalsa]</ref><ref name=\"Jacobsen2008p192\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WT2odZ7_d7MC&pg=PA192|title=South Asian Religions on Display: Religious Processions in South Asia and in the Diaspora|author=Knut A. Jacobsen|publisher=Routledge|year=2008|isbn=978-1-134-07459-4|page=192}}, '''Quote:''' \"Baisakhi is also a Hindu festival, but for the Sikhs, it celebrates the foundation of the Khalsa in 1699.\"</ref>\n\nIn Hinduism, Vaisakhi celebrates the Solar new year, based on the [[Vikram Samvat]] calendar. Vaisakhi marks the first day of the month of [[Vaisakha]]. It is additionally a spring harvest festival for Hinduism and Sikhs.<ref name=bbcv/>\n\nIn Sikhism, Vaisakhi marks the start of the Khalsa in 1699 by [[Guru Gobind Singh]].\n\nVaisakhi observes major events in the history of Sikhism and the [[Indian subcontinent]] that happened in the [[Punjab region]].<ref name=bakshi208/><ref>{{cite book|author1=William Owen Cole|author2=Piara Singh Sambhi|title=The Sikhs: Their Religious Beliefs and Practices|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zIC_MgJ5RMUC |year=1995|publisher=Sussex Academic Press|isbn=978-1-898723-13-4|pages=135\u2013136}}</ref> The significance of Vaisakhi as a major Sikh festival marking the birth of Sikh order started after the persecution and execution of [[Guru Tegh Bahadur]] for refusing to convert to Islam under the orders of the Mughal Emperor [[Aurangzeb]]. This triggered the coronation of the tenth Guru of Sikhism and the historic formation of [[Khalsa]], both on the Vaisakhi day.<ref name=\"Seiple 2013 96\">{{cite book | last=Seiple | first=Chris | title=The Routledge handbook of religion and security | publisher=Routledge | location=New York | year=2013 | isbn=978-0-415-66744-9 | page=96}}</ref><ref name=\"pashaura236\"/><ref name=\"Harkirat S. Hansra 2007 28\u201329\">{{cite book|author=Harkirat S. Hansra|title=Liberty at Stake, Sikhs: the Most Visible|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RDlMUfGiEO8C&pg=PA28 |year=2007|publisher=iUniverse|isbn=978-0-595-43222-6 |pages=28\u201329}}</ref> Vaisakhi was also the day when colonial British empire officials committed the [[Jallianwala Bagh massacre]] on a gathering, an event influential to the Indian movement against colonial rule.<ref name=bakshi208>S. R. Bakshi, Sita Ram Sharma, S. Gajnani (1998) Parkash Singh Badal: Chief Minister of Punjab. APH Publishing [https://books.google.com/books?id=cyebnJdCFlEC&pg=PA208 pages 208\u2013209]</ref>\n\nOn Vaisakhi, Gurdwaras are decorated and hold [[kirtan]]s, Sikhs visit and bathe in lakes or rivers before visiting local Gurdwaras, community fairs and ''nagar kirtan'' processions are held, and people gather to socialize and share festive foods.<ref name=\"Gupta2006p998\"/><ref name=bakshi208/><ref name=\"LeeNadeau2011p1012\">{{cite book|author1=Jonathan H. X. Lee|author2=Kathleen M. Nadeau|title=Encyclopedia of Asian American Folklore and Folklife |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9BrfLWdeISoC&pg=PA1012 |year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-35066-5|pages=1012\u20131013}}</ref>\n\nFor many Hindus, the festival is their traditional solar new year, a harvest festival, an occasion to bathe in sacred rivers such as Ganges, Jhelum, and Kaveri, visit temples, meet friends and take part in other festivities. In other parts of India, the Vaisakhi festival is known by various regional names.<ref name=\"Roy2005p479\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IKqOUfqt4cIC&pg=PA479|title=Traditional Festivals: A Multicultural Encyclopedia|author=Christian Roy|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2005|isbn=978-1-57607-089-5|pages=479\u2013480}}</ref>\n\n==Date==\nVaisakhi is traditionally observed on 13 or 14 April, every year.<ref name=\"Gupta2006p998\"/> The festival is important to both Sikhs and Hindus.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2008p192\"/> The festival coincides with other new year festivals celebrated on the first day of Vaisakh in other regions of the [[Indian Subcontinent]] such as [[Pohela Boishakh]], [[Bohag Bihu]], [[Vishu]], [[Puthandu]] among others.<ref>Crump, William D.  (2014), [https://books.google.com/books?id=cDTfCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA114 Encyclopedia of New Year's Holidays Worldwide], MacFarland, page 114</ref><ref name=\"PechilisRaj2013p48\"/>\n\n==Spelling and pronunciation==\nThe spelling varies with region. In Punjab region, ''Vaisakhi'' is common, but in the [[Doabi]] and [[Malwi dialect|Malwai]] dialects, speakers often substitute a ''B'' for a ''V''.<ref name=\"Archived copy\">{{Cite web |url=http://punjabrevenue.nic.in/gaz_gdr5.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=26 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304123940/http://punjabrevenue.nic.in/gaz_gdr5.htm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The spelling used depends on the dialect of the writer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1CB_aQY5TcY-oJ6GwVjx55Lqd153eihGl/view?usp=sharing|title=Pronunciation of Vaisakhi|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Sikhism==\n{{Sikhism sidebar}}\n{{Main|Khalsa}}\n\n===History===\nSince the time of Guru Amar Das it has been customary for Sikhs to assemble before their Guru on three of the most important Hindu festival occasions \u2013 Vaisakhi, Divali, and Maha Shivaratri. The alternative view is that Guru Amar Das chose [[Makar Sankranti|Maghi]], instead of Maha Shivaratri.<ref>Fauja Singh, Gurbachan Singh Talib (1975), Punjabi University [https://books.google.com/books?id=7g0eAAAAMAAJ Guru Tegh Bahadur: Martyr and Teacher]</ref><ref>H. S. Singha (2000), Hemkunt Press [https://books.google.com/books?id=gqIbJz7vMn0C&pg=PA16 The Encyclopedia of Sikhism (over 1000 Entries)] page 16</ref>\n\nSubsequent events gave a new meaning to the festival which is, in part, a remembrance of the foundation of the Khalsa Sikh order which started after the ninth [[Guru Tegh Bahadur]] was persecuted and then beheaded under the orders of the Mughal Emperor [[Aurangzeb]], after he stood up for freedom of religious practice and refused to convert to Islam.<ref name=\"Seiple 2013 96\"/><ref name=\"pashaura236\" /> The guru's martyrdom triggered the coronation of the tenth and last Guru of Sikhism, and the formation of the ''sant-sipahi'' group of [[Khalsa]],<ref name=\"Chanchreek 2007 142\">{{cite book|last=Chanchreek|first=Jain|title=Encyclopaedia of Great Festivals|year=2007|publisher=Shree Publishers & Distributors|isbn=9788183291910|page=142}}</ref><ref name=\"Dugga 2001 33\">{{cite book|last=Dugga|first=Kartar|title=Maharaja Ranjit Singh: The Last to Lay Arms|year=2001|publisher=Abhinav Publications|isbn=9788170174103|page=33}}</ref> both on the Vaisakhi day.<ref name=\"pashaura236\">{{cite book | author=Pashaura Singh and Louis Fenech | title=The Oxford handbook of Sikh studies | publisher=Oxford University Press | location=Oxford, UK | year=2014 | isbn=978-0-19-969930-8 | pages=236\u2013237}}</ref>\n\nThe Vaisakhi festival Khalsa tradition started in the year 1699,<ref name=bakshi208/> as it is on this day that the 10th Guru of the Sikhs, [[Guru Gobind Singh]] laid down the foundation of the [[Khalsa|Panth Khalsa]], that is the Order of the Pure Ones, by baptizing Sikh warriors to defend religious freedoms.<ref>Pashaura Singh (2005), ''Understanding the Martyrdom of Guru Arjan'', Journal of Punjab Studies, 12(1), pages 29\u201362</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Johar|first1=Surinder|title=Guru Gobind Singh: A Multi-faceted Personality|date=1999|publisher=M.D. Publications |isbn=978-8175330931|page=89}}</ref><ref name=\"Gandhi\">{{cite book | title=History of Sikh Gurus Retold: 1606 -1708 | publisher=Atlantic Publishers | author=Singh Gandhi, Surjit | year=2008 | pages=676\u2013677 | isbn=8126908572}}</ref> This gave rise to the Vaisakhi or Baisakhi festival being observed as a celebration of Khalsa panth formation and is also known as Khalsa Sirjana Divas<ref>Laws of the State of Illinois Enacted by the ... General Assembly at the Extra Session. (2013) State Printers. [https://books.google.com/books?id=adPXhc84ZMwC page 7772]</ref> and Khalsa Sajna Divas.<ref>Singh, Jagraj (2009) A Complete Guide to Sikhism. Unistar Books [https://books.google.com/books?id=rFm9_Jc1ykcC&pg=PA311 page 311]</ref> The festival is celebrated on Vaisakhi day (typically 14 April), since 1699. The Birth of the Khalsa Panth was either on 13 April 1699<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|last1=Purewal|first1=Pal|title=Vaisakhi Dates Range According To Indian Ephemeris By Swamikannu Pillai \u2013 i.e. English Date on 1 Vaisakh Bikrami|url=http://www.purewal.biz/PastVaisakhiDates.pdf|website=www.purewal.biz|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref> or 30 March 1699.<ref>Kaur, Madanjit (2007). Unistar Books [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZG4MycGdpjAC&pg=PA149 Guru Gobind Singh: Historical and Ideological Perspective], page 149</ref> Since 2003, the Sikh Gurdwara Prabhandak Committee named it Baisakh (Vaisakh), making the first day of the second month of Vaisakh according to its new [[Nanakshahi calendar]].<ref>{{cite book|author=W. H. McLeod|title=The A to Z of Sikhism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vgixwfeCyDAC&pg=PA143|year=2009|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6344-6|pages=143\u2013144}}</ref>\n\nA special celebration takes place at [[Talwandi Sabo]] (where [[Guru Gobind Singh]] stayed for nine months and completed the recompilation of the [[Guru Granth Sahib]]),<ref>{{cite news |title=Vaisakhi celebrated with fervour, gaiety|author=Tribune News service|newspaper=The Tribune, Chandigarh|date=14 April 2009}}</ref> in the [[Gurudwara]] at [[Anandpur Sahib]] the birthplace of the [[Khalsa]], and at the [[Harmandir Sahib|Golden Temple]] in [[Amritsar]].\n\n===Sikh New Year===\nAccording to the Khalsa sambat, the Khalsa calendar starts with the creation of the Khalsa which is 1 Vaisakh 1756 Bikrami (30 March 1699).<ref>Dogra, Ramesh Chander and Dogra, Urmila (2003) Page 248 The Sikh World: An Encyclopedic Survey of Sikh Religion and Culture. UBS Publishers Distributors Pvt Ltd {{ISBN|81-7476-443-7}}</ref><ref>The Panjab in 1839\u201340: selections from the Punjab akhbars, Punjab intelligence, etc., preserved in the National Archives of India, New Delhi (1952) Sikh History Society [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Q645AQAAIAAJ&dq=khalsa+sammat&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=+sammat]</ref> Accordingly, Vaisakhi has been the traditional Sikh New Year.<ref name=senker10/><ref name=\"ColeSambhi1995p63\">{{cite book|author1=William Owen Cole|author2=Piara Singh Sambhi|title=The Sikhs: Their Religious Beliefs and Practices |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zIC_MgJ5RMUC&pg=PA63 |year=1995|publisher=Sussex Academic Press|isbn=978-1-898723-13-4|page=63}}, '''Quote:''' \"The Sikh new year, Vaisakhi, occurs at Sangrand in April, usually on the thirteenth day.\"</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Nick Hunter|title=Celebrating Sikh Festivals|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QLBeCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA10|year=2016|publisher=Raintree|isbn=978-1-4062-9776-8|page=10}}</ref> The festival has been traditionally observed in the [[Punjab region]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=d195AAAAMAAJ|title=Festivals in World Religions|first=Alan|last=Brown|year= 1986|publisher=Longman|accessdate=14 September 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>Simon J Bronner (2015), Routledge [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FvjqBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA1132 Encyclopedia of American Folklife], page 1132</ref> The alternative Nanakshahi calendar begins its year a month earlier on 1 Chait which generally falls on 14 March and begins with the birth year of the Guru Nanak Dev in 1469.<ref>Kapel, Marin (2006) The Structure and Mathematics of the Principal Calendars of the Western World: Muslim, Gregorian, Jewish, and Other Systems. Edwin Mellen Press [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=paYSAQAAIAAJ&dq=nanakshahi+year+14+march&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=14+march]</ref>\n\n===Nagar Kirtan===\nSikh communities organise processions called ''nagar kirtan'' (literally, \"town hymn singing\"). These are led by five khalsa who are dressed up as ''Panj Pyaare'', and the processions through the streets. The people who march sing, make music, sing hymns from the Sikh texts. Major processions also carry a copy of the [[Guru Granth Sahib]] in reverence.<ref name=bbcv/>\n\n===Harvest festival===\n[[File:Common good.jpg|thumb|left|Two Sikh men celebrating Vaisakhi by giving away free sugarcane juice.]]\n[[File:Kothe-da-mela.jpg|thumb|Vaisakhi ''mela'']]\nVaisakhi is a harvest festival for people of the [[Punjab region]].<ref>Bakshi, S. R. Sharma, Sita Ram (1998) Parkash Singh Badal: Chief Minister of Punjab [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cyebnJdCFlEC&dq=baisakhi+punjabi+festival&source=gbs_navlinks_s]</ref> In the Punjab, Vaisakhi marks the ripening of the [[rabi crop|rabi]] harvest.<ref>Dogra, Ramesh Chander and Dogra, Urmila (2003) Page 49 The Sikh World: An Encyclopedic Survey of Sikh Religion and Culture. UBS Publishers Distributors Pvt Ltd {{ISBN|81-7476-443-7}}</ref> Vaisakhi also marks the Punjabi new year.<ref>Sainik Samachar: The Pictorial Weekly of the Armed Forces, Volume 33 (1986) Director of Public Relations, Ministry of Defence, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=t1jfAAAAMAAJ&q=Punjabi+new+year&dq=Punjabi+new+year&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjXluL21O3SAhUrI8AKHfVkAro4ChDoAQgoMAM]</ref> This day is observed as a thanksgiving day by farmers whereby farmers pay their tribute, thanking God for the abundant harvest and also praying for future prosperity.<ref>Dhillon, (2015) Janamsakhis: Ageless Stories, Timeless Values. Hay House [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=OXtVDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT197&dq=punjabi+calendar&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjkwr3R6OrSAhVEBMAKHduoBjYQ6AEIHzAB#v=onepage&q=punjabi%20calendar&f=false]</ref> The harvest festival is celebrated by Sikhs and Punjabi Hindus.<ref>Gupta, Surendra K.  (1999) Indians in Thailand, Books India International [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5rBuAAAAMAAJ&dq=baisakhi+harvest+punjab+hindus+and+sikhs&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=barley]</ref> Historically, during the early 20th century, Vaisakhi was a sacred day for Sikhs and Hindus and a secular festival for all Muslims and non-Muslims including Punjabi Christians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=tNAxAQAAIAAJ&dq=baisakhi+harvest+punjab+hindus+and+sikhs&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=turbaned+sikhs|title=Link: Indian Newsmagazine|date=13 April 1987|via=Google Books}}</ref> In modern times, sometimes Christians participate in Baisakhi celebrations along with Sikhs and Hindus.<ref>Nahar, Emanual (2007) Minority politics in India: role and impact of Christians in Punjab politics. Arun Pub. House. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vl9uAAAAMAAJ&dq=punjabi+christians+baisakhi+india&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=baisakhi+]</ref>\n\n====Aawat pauni====\n[[File:Bhangra 1.jpg|thumb|right|Bhangra dance on Vaisakhi is a Sikh tradition]]\n[[Aawat pauni]] is a tradition associated with harvesting, which involves people getting together to harvest the wheat. Drums are played while people work. At the end of the day, people sing [[Doha (poetry)|dohay]] to the tunes of the drum.<ref>Dr Singh, Sadhu (2010) Punjabi Boli Di Virasat. Chetna Prakashan. {{ISBN|817883618-1}}</ref>\n\n====Fairs and dances====\nThe harvest festival is also characterized by the folk dance, [[Bhangra (dance)|Bhangra]] which traditionally is a harvest dance.\n\nFairs or ''[[Mela]]s'' are held in many parts of [[Punjab, India]] to mark the new year and the harvesting season. Vaisakhi fairs take place in various places, including [[Jammu]] City, Kathua, Udhampur, Reasi and Samba,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/jammu-and-kashmir/baisakhi-celebrated-with-fervour-gaiety-in-jk_1578749.html|title=Baisakhi celebrated with fervour, gaiety in J&K|date=14 April 2015|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> in the Pinjore complex near [[Chandigarh]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7d3rX5jr1WQC&dq=haryana%20baisakhi&source=gbs_navlinks_s|title=Tourism Management: Problems and Prospects|first=Bijender K.|last=Punia|date=1 January 1994|publisher=APH Publishing|accessdate=14 September 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref> in [[Himachal Pradesh]] cities of Rewalsar, Shimla, Mandi and Prashar Lakes.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Hinduism==\n{{Hinduism}}\n[[File:Ganges at Haridwar, Uttarakhand.jpg|thumb|left|Bathing in rivers is a Vaisakhi tradition]]\nThe first day of Vaisakh marks the traditional solar new year<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=PGXgssv08PgC&pg=PA61 |title=Indian Astronomy: An Introduction|first=S. Balachandra|last=Rao|date=1 January 2000|publisher=Universities Press|accessdate=14 September 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>Tribune 15 April 2011 Baisakhi fervour at Haridwar Lakhs take dip in holy Ganga [http://www.tribuneindia.com/2011/20110415/dplus.htm#1]</ref> and it is an ancient festival that predates the founding of Sikhism. The harvest is complete and crops ready to sell, representing a time of plenty for the farmers. Fairs and special thanksgiving pujas (prayers) are common in the Hindu tradition.<ref name=\"Rinehart2004p139\">{{cite book|author=Robin Rinehart|title=Contemporary Hinduism: Ritual, Culture, and Practice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hMPYnfS_R90C&pg=PA139|year=2004|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-57607-905-8|page=139}}</ref>\n\nThe first day of Vaisakh marks the solar new year.<ref name=\"BBC Hinduism\">{{cite web |title= BBC \u2013 Religion: Hinduism \u2013 Vaisakhi|publisher=[[BBC]]|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/hinduism/holydays/vaisakhi.shtml |accessdate=22 January 2012}}</ref> It is the New Year's Day for Hindus in [[Assam]], [[West Bengal|Bengal]], [[Bihar]], [[Himachal Pradesh]], [[Haryana]], [[Kerala]], [[Odisha]], [[Punjab, India|Punjab]]<ref>Crump, William D.  (2014) Encyclopedia of New Year's Holidays Worldwide. McFarland [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cDTfCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA114&dq=vaisakhi+punjabi+hindu+new+year&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwijseXUpvvSAhWrC8AKHS2cDXsQ6AEIKjAD#v=onepage&q=vaisakhi%20punjabi%20hindu%20new%20year&f=false]</ref> [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[Uttrakhand]] and other parts of India.<ref name=\"BBC Hinduism\" /><ref name=\"PechilisRaj2013p48\" /> However, this is not the universal new year for all Hindus. For some, such as those in and near Gujarat, the new year festivities coincide with the five-day [[Diwali]] festival.<ref name=\"PechilisRaj2013p48\" /> For others, the new year falls on [[Cheti Chand]], [[Gudi Padwa]] and [[Ugadi]] which falls a few weeks earlier.<ref name=\"PechilisRaj2013p48\">{{cite book|author1=Karen Pechilis| author2=Selva J. Raj|title= South Asian Religions: Tradition and Today|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=kaubzRxh-U0C&pg=PA48| year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-44851-2|pages=48\u201349}}</ref><ref name=\"Falzon2004p62\">{{cite book|author=Mark-Anthony Falzon|title=Cosmopolitan Connections: The Sindhi Diaspora, 1860\u20132000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ljbS-I5Y8WMC&pg=PA62|year=2004|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-14008-5|page=62}}</ref>\n\n[[File:4 girls celebrating Assamese Bihu.jpg|thumb|left |Celebrating Bohag Bihu in Assam]]\nIt is regionally known by many names among the Hindus, though the festivities and its significance is similar. It is celebrated by Hindus bathing in sacred rivers, as they believe that river goddess Ganges descended to earth on Vaisakhi.<ref name=\"Rinehart2004p139\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5kl0DYIjUPgC&pg=PA81 |title=The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Hinduism: A-M|first=James G.|last=Lochtefeld|date=1 January 2002|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|accessdate=14 September 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref> Some rivers considered particularly sacred include the Ganges, Jhelum and Kaveri. Hindus visit temples, meet friends and party over festive foods.<ref name=\"Roy2005p479\"/>\n\nVaisakhi coincides with the festival of '[[Vishu]]' celebrated in [[Kerala]] a day after Vaisakhi. The festivities include fireworks, shopping for new clothes and interesting displays called 'Vishu Kani'. Hindus make arrangements of flowers, grains, fruits which friends and family visit to admire as \"lucky sight\" (''Vishukkani''). Giving gifts to friends and loved ones, as well as alms to the needy, are a tradition of Kerala Hindus on this festive day.<ref name=\"Roy2005p479\"/>\n\nVaisakhi is celebrated as [[Bohag Bihu|Bohag (Rongali) Bihu]] in [[Assam]] and as Pohela Boishakh in [[West Bengal|Bengal]], but typically one or two days after Vaisakhi.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aghr.cag.gov.in/holidays.pdf |title=2017 Official Central Government Holiday Calendar |accessdate=4 March 2017 |publisher = Government of India}}</ref>\n\n===Regional variations===\n[[File:Mathapoo vishu.jpg|thumb|Some Indians mark their traditional new year with fireworks]]\nThe following is a list of new year festivals:<ref name=\"BBC Hinduism\"/><ref>Crump, William D.  (2014), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cDTfCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA114 Encyclopedia of New Year's Holidays Worldwide], MacFarland, page 114</ref><ref name=\"PechilisRaj2013p48\"/>\n* ''Bikhu'' or ''Bikhauti'' in the [[Kumaon division|Kumaon]] region of [[Uttarakhand]], India\n* ''[[Bisu (festival)|Bisu]]'' \u2013 Tulu New Year Day amongst the [[Tulu people]] in India\n* ''[[Bohag Bihu]]'' in [[Assam]], India\n* ''[[Kodava people|Edmyaar 1 (Bisu Changrandi)]]'' \u2013 [[Kodava people|Kodava]] New Year.\n*''JurShital'' (New Year) in [[History of Mithila|Mithila]] (parts of [[Nepal]] and [[Bihar]], India)\n* ''[[Vishuva Sankranti|Maha Vishuva Sankranti]]'' (or Pana Sankranti) in [[Odisha]], India\n* ''Naba Barsha'' or ''[[Pohela Boishakh]]'' in [[West Bengal]] and [[Tripura]], India, [[Nepal]] and [[Bangladesh]]\n* ''[[Puthandu]]''  in [[Tamil Nadu]], India\n*''[[Ugadi]]'' in [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Karnataka]] and [[Telangana]], India\n* ''[[Vishu]]''  in [[Kerala]], India\n\nThe new year falls on or about the same day every year for many Buddhist communities in parts of South and Southeast Asia. This is likely an influence of their shared culture in the 1st millennium CE.<ref name=\"PechilisRaj2013p48\"/> Some examples include:\n*''[[Sinhalese New Year|Aluth Avuruthu]]'' in [[Sri Lanka]].<ref name=\"reeves174\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4N5UAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA174|title=The Encyclopedia of the Sri Lankan Diaspora|author=Peter Reeves|publisher=Didier Millet|year=2014|isbn=978-981-4260-83-1|page=174}}</ref>\n*''[[Bikram Samwat]]'' / ''Vaishak Ek'' in [[Nepal]]\n* ''[[Cambodian New Year|Chol Chnam Thmey]]'' in [[Cambodia]]\n* ''[[Songkran (Lao)|Pii Mai Lao]]'' in [[Laos]]\n*''[[Songkran (Thailand)|Songkran]]'' in [[Thailand]]\n* ''[[Thingyan]]'' in [[Myanmar]]\n\n====Bikhoti festival====\nThe Bikhoti Festival of [[Uttrakhand]] involves people taking a dip in holy rivers. A popular custom involves beating symbolic stones representing demons with sticks. The fair is celebrated in various major centres including Sealdah, Bageshwar and Dwarahat and involves much singing and dancing, accompanied by local drums and other instruments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.edgeofindia.com/locations/uttarakhand/bageshwar/when-to-go/festivals_culture.aspx|title=Festivals and Culture}}</ref>\n\n====Vishu====\n[[File:Vishukani.jpg|thumb|left|A Vishukkani tray before Krishna (Vishnu), a Kerala Hindu tradition]]\nVishu is a Hindu festival celebrated on the same day as Vaisakhi in the Indian state of [[Kerala]], and falls on the first day of Malayali month called Medam.<ref name=vishugok>[https://kerala.gov.in/major-festivals Major festivals of Kerala], Government of Kerala (2016)</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=J. Gordon Melton|title=Religious Celebrations: An Encyclopedia of Holidays, Festivals, Solemn Observances, and Spiritual Commemorations |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lD_2J7W_2hQC&pg=PA633 |year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-59884-206-7|page=633}}</ref> The festival is notable for its solemnity and the general lack of pomp and show that characterize other Hindu festivals of Kerala such as [[Onam]].<ref name=vishugok/><ref name=\"Jagannathan2005p76\">{{cite book| author=Maithily Jagannathan|title=South Indian Hindu Festivals and Traditions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xcIrkKUJH9QC|year = 2005|publisher = Abhinav Publications|isbn= 978-81-7017-415-8|pages=76\u201377}}</ref>\n\nThe festival is marked by family time, preparing colorful auspicious items and viewing these as the first thing on the Vishu day. In particular, Malayali Hindus seek to view the golden blossoms of the Indian laburnum (''Kani Konna''), money or silver items (''Vishukkaineetam''), and rice.<ref name=vishugok/><ref name=\"Jagannathan2005p76\"/> The day also attracts firework play by children,<ref name=vishugok/><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Thiruvananthapuram/city-celebrates-vishu/article399057.ece |title=City celebrates Vishu |publisher=The Hindu |date=16 April 2010 |accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref> wearing new clothes (''Puthukodi'') and the eating a special meal called ''[[Sadya]]'', which is a mix of salty, sweet, sour and bitter items.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/when-the-laburnum-blooms/article1696077.ece |title=When the Laburnum blooms |publisher=The Hindu |date=14 April 2011 |accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref> The Vishu arrangement typically includes an image of [[Vishnu]], typically as [[Krishna]]. People also visit temples on the day.<ref name=\"Dalal2010p461\">{{cite book|author=Roshen Dalal|title=Hinduism: An Alphabetical Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DH0vmD8ghdMC&pg=PA461|year=2010|publisher=Penguin Books|isbn=978-0-14-341421-6|page=461}}</ref>\n\n====Bohag Bihu====\n[[File:Dhuliya performing in an open stage bihu.jpg|thumb|Festive Bihu with Dhuliya is an Assamese Hindu tradition on this day.]]\nBohag Bihu or Rangali Bihu marks the beginning of the Assamese New Year on 13 April. It is celebrated for seven days Vishuva Sankranti (Mesha Sankranti) of the month of Vaisakh or locally 'Bohag' (Bhaskar Calendar). The three primary types of Bihu are Rongali Bihu, Kongali Bihu, and Bhogali Bihu. Each festival historically recognizes a different agricultural cycle of the paddy crops. During Rangali Bihu there are 7 pinnacle phases: 'Chot', 'Raati', 'Goru', 'Manuh', 'Kutum', 'Mela' and 'Chera'.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\n====Maha Vishuva Sankranti====\n[[Maha Vishuva Sankranti]] marks the Oriya new year in [[Odisha]]. Celebrations include various types of folk and classical dances, such as the Shiva-related [[Chhau dance]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Sitakant Mahapatra|title=Chhau Dance of Mayurbhanj|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4VHkAAAAMAAJ |year=1993|publisher=Vidyapuri|page=86}}</ref> More popularly it is known as Pana Sankranti(\u0b2a\u0b23\u0b3e \u0b38\u0b02\u0b15\u0b4d\u0b30\u0b3e\u0b28\u0b4d\u0b24\u0b3f). On this day people hang pieces of Neem branches with leaves in front of their houses believed to have health benefits. They prepare a liquid mixture of jaggery, mango, pepper and other ingredients which is called Pana(\u0b2a\u0b23\u0b3e). An earthen pot with a small hole and a grass(\u0b15\u0b41\u0b41\u0b36) within the hole at the bottom is hung over the Tulasi (\u0b24\u0b41\u0b41\u0b41\u0b33\u0b38\u0b40 \u0b1a\u0b09\u0b30\u0b3e). The pot is filled with water daily which acts as a drip to protect the sacred plant from the summer heat.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n====Pahela Baishakh====\n{{main|Pohela Boishakh}}\n[[File:Colors of Celebration!-4.JPG|thumb|Pohela Boishakh celebrations in Dhaka, Bangladesh.]]\nThe Bengali new year is celebrated as Pahela Baishakh on 14 April every year, and a festive [[Mangal Shobhajatra]], started by students of Dhaka University in Bangladesh in 1989,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/2017/04/14/66874/%27Mongol-Shobhajatra%27-parades-city-streets|title='Mongol Shobhajatra' parades city streets|website=The Financial Express Online Version|access-date=16 April 2017}}</ref> is organized in the [[Indian states]] of West Bengal and Tripura, as well as modern-day nation of Bangladesh. This celebration was listed in 2016 by the [[UNESCO]] as a cultural heritage of humanity.<ref>[http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/en/RL/mangal-shobhajatra-on-pahela-baishakh-01091 Mangal Shobhajatra on Pahela Baishakh], UNESCO</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/unesco-cultural-heritage-list-adds-mangal-shobhajatra-1323331|title=Unesco lists Mangal Shobhajatra as cultural heritage|date=1 December 2016|work=The Daily Star|access-date=16 April 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe festival is celebrated as a national holiday in [[Bangladesh]]. Also spelled Pohela Boishakh is also known as Nobo Barsho as it is the first day of the Bengali month of Bongabdo. Fairs are organised to celebrate the event which provides entertainment including the presentation of folk songs.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\n====Puthandu====\nPuthandu, also known as ''Puthuvarusham'' or ''Tamil New Year'', is the first day of the month ''Chithirai'' on the [[Tamil calendar]].<ref name=\"Dalal2010p406\">{{cite book|author=Roshen Dalal|title=Hinduism: An Alphabetical Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DH0vmD8ghdMC |year=2010|publisher=Penguin Books|isbn=978-0-14-341421-6|page=406}}</ref><ref name=\"Melton2011p633\">{{cite book|author=J. Gordon Melton|title=Religious Celebrations: An Encyclopedia of Holidays, Festivals, Solemn Observances, and Spiritual Commemorations |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lD_2J7W_2hQC&pg=PA633|year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-59884-206-7|page=633}}</ref><ref name=reeves174/>\n\nOn this day, Tamil people greet each other by saying \"Putt\u0101\u1e47\u1e6du v\u0101\u1e3bttukka\u1e37!\" or \"I\u1e49iya putt\u0101\u1e47\u1e6du nalv\u0101\u1e3bttukka\u1e37!\", which is equivalent to \"Happy new year\".<ref>{{cite book|author=William D. Crump|title=Encyclopedia of New Year's Holidays Worldwide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cDTfCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA220 |year=2014|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-9545-0|page=220}}</ref> The day is observed as a family time. Households clean up the house, prepare a tray with fruits, flowers and auspicious items, light up the family [[Puja (Hinduism)|Puja]] altar and visit their local temples. People wear new clothes and youngster go to elders to pay respects and seek their blessings, then the family sits down to a vegetarian feast.<ref>{{cite book|author=Samuel S. Dhoraisingam|title=Peranakan Indians of Singapore and Melaka |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QHwcAgAAQBAJ |year=2006|publisher=Institute of Southeast Asian Studies|isbn=978-981-230-346-2|page=38}}</ref>\n\n====Jurshital in Bihar====\nIn the Mithal region of [[Bihar]] and [[Nepal]], the new year is celebrated as Jurshital.<ref>Hari Bansh Jha (1993) The terai community and national integration in Nepal.[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JShuAAAAMAAJ&q=JurShital+new+year&dq=JurShital+new+year&hl=en&sa=X&ei=yFYzVZaiD5LaaPLFgCg&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAQ]</ref> It is traditional to use lotus leaves to serve [[sattu]] (powdered meal derived from grains of red gram and jau (Hordeum vulgare) and other ingredients) to the family members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ugVFAQAAIAAJ&q=Jurshital&dq=Jurshital&hl=en&sa=X&ei=J6MzVYuBGtOWavbCgIgO&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAw|title=Ethnobotany|date=1 January 2002|publisher=Aavishkar Publishers, Distributors|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Sikh celebrations outside India==\n{{multiple image|total_width=260|perrow=2|caption_align=center\n| header = Celebration around the world\n| image1 =Vaisakhi1.jpg\n| caption1 = A depiction of [[Guru Gobind Singh]] initiating the first five members of the [[Khalsa]]\n| image2 = Panj Pyare, leading a procession.jpg\n| caption2 = The [[Panj Pyare]] at Vaisakhi 2007 [[Wolverhampton]], UK\n| image3 = Vaisakhi 2012 London - 22.jpg\n| caption3 = Vaisakhi at [[Trafalgar Square]], London\n| image4 = Vaisakhi 2012 London - 21.jpg\n| caption4 = Vaisakhi 2012 at [[Trafalgar Square]], London\n| image5 = Vaisakhi 2012 London - 23.jpg\n| caption5 = Vaisakhi 2012 at [[Trafalgar Square]], London\n| image6 = Vaisakhi Sikh festival in Birmingham 2013.jpg\n| caption6 = Vaisakhi celebrations in Birmingham\n| image7 = Panj Pyare, leading a procession.jpg\n| caption7 = The [[Panj Pyare]] at Vaisakhi 2007 [[Wolverhampton]], UK\n| image8 = Dessert on tray.jpg\n| caption8 = [[Jalebi]]yan being served at Vaisakhi Day, 11 April 2009, [[Vancouver]] Canada\n| image9 = Airplane-mobile.jpg\n| caption9 = 2009 [[Vancouver]] Sikh Vaisakhi parade\n| image10 = Sikh Motorcycle Club at Vaisakhi.jpg\n| caption10 = Sikh Motorcycle Club at Vaisakhi 2007 [[Vancouver, British Columbia]], Canada\n| image11 =  Sikh Motorcycle Club at Vaisakhi.jpg\n| caption11 = Sikh Motorcycle Club at Vaisakhi 2007 [[Vancouver, British Columbia]], Canada\n| image12 =  Vaisakhi fair mela in Surrey Canada.jpg\n| caption12 = Vaisakhi festival in Surrey, BC, Canada\n| image13 = Vaisakhi Day Celebration (8651688584).jpg\n| caption13= A band performs at Vaisakhi day celebrations in Kuala Lumpur (2013)\n| image14 = Vaisakhi parade 2017 (33217388724).jpg\n| caption14= Vaisakhi 2017, Punjabi Market, Vancouver\n}}\n\n===Pakistan===\nPakistan has many sites that are of historic importance to the Sikh faith, such as the birthplace of Guru Nanak. These sites attract pilgrims from India and abroad every year on Vaisakhi.<ref>[https://www.dawn.com/news/1176098 Glare and galore at Baisakhi festival], The Dawn, Pakistan (15 April 2015)</ref><ref>[http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/vaisakhi-2015-sikh-devotees-celebrate-major-festival-india-pakistan-photos-1496358 Vaisakhi 2015: Sikh devotees celebrate major festival in India and Pakistan], David Sims, International Business Times</ref> Pakistan used to have many more Sikhs, but a vast majority moved to India during the 1947 India-Pakistan partition. Contemporary Pakistan has about 20,000 Sikhs in a total population of about 200 million Pakistanis, or about 0.01%.<ref>Ary News 17 April 2015 Sikh pligrims gather in Pakistan for Vaisakhi festival [http://arynews.tv/en/sikh-pligrims-gather-in-pakistan-for-vaisakhi-festival/]</ref> These Sikhs, and thousands more who arrive from other parts of the world for pilgrimage, observe Vaisakhi in [[Punjab, Pakistan|Western Punjab]] (Pakistan) with festivities centered on the [[Panja Sahib]] complex in [[Hasan Abdal]], [[Gurudwara]]s in [[Nankana Sahib]], and in various historical sites in [[Lahore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/world-news/sikhs-throng-pakistan-shrine-for-baisakhi_10037124.html|title=Sikh throng Pakistan shrine for Vaisakhi|author=Muhammad Najeeb Hasan Abdal|date=12 April 2008|work=Thaindian News|publisher=www.thaindian.com|accessdate=22 January 2012}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|On 8 April 2016, Punjabi Parchar at Alhamra (Lahore) organised a show called Visakhi mela, where the speakers pledged to \"continue our struggle to keep the Punjabi culture alive\" in Pakistan through events such as Visakhi Mela.<ref>Pakistan Today (8 April 2016) [http://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2016/04/08/promoting-peace-with-punjabi-at-visakhi-mela/ Punjabi Parchar spreads colours of love at Visakhi Mela]</ref> Elsewhere Besakhi fairs or melas are held in various places including [[Eminabad]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/953015|title=A fair dedicated to animal lovers|date=20 April 2009|website=DAWN.COM}}</ref> and [[Dera Ghazi Khan]].<ref>Agnes Ziegler, Akhtar Mummunka (2006) The final Frontier: unique photographs of Pakistan. Sang-e-Meel Publications [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=AhNuAAAAMAAJ&q=besakhi+mela+sakhi&dq=besakhi+mela+sakhi&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQ67W705zTAhVrKsAKHZ5iBJIQ6AEIHDAA]</ref>}}\n\nAccording to Aziz-ud-din Ahmed, [[Lahore]] used to have Baisakhi Mela after the harvesting of the wheat crop in April. However, adds Ahmed, the city started losing its cultural vibrancy in 1970s after Zia-ul-Haq came to power, and in recent years \"the [[Pakistan Muslim League (N)]] government in Punjab banned kite flying through an official edict more under the pressure of those who want a puritanical version of Islam to be practiced in the name of religion than anything else\".<ref>[http://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2015/02/21/cultural-decline-in-lahore/ Cultural Decline in Pakistan], Pakistan Today, Aziz-ud-din Ahmed (21 February 2015)</ref> Unlike the Indian state of Punjab that recognizes the Vaisakhi Sikh festival as an official holiday,<ref>[http://punjab.gov.in/list-of-holidays Official Holidays], Government of Punjab, India (2016)</ref> the festival is not an official holiday in Punjab or Sindh provinces of Pakistan as Sikhs constitute a very small number in terms of population.<ref>[http://www.schools.punjab.gov.pk/system/files/Notification_2.pdf Official Holidays 2016], Government of Punjab \u2013 Pakistan (2016)</ref><ref>[http://www.kmc.gos.pk/Contents.aspx?id=48 Official Holidays 2016], Karachi Metropolitan, Sindh, Pakistan</ref>\n\n===Canada===\nIn the [[British Columbia|Province of British Columbia]], large, local Sikh communities in the cities of [[Vancouver, British Columbia|Vancouver]], [[Abbotsford, British Columbia|Abbotsford]], and [[Surrey, British Columbia|Surrey]] hold their annual Vaisakhi celebrations in April,<ref>Global News 12 April 2015 Vaisakhi celebrated at parade in south Vancouver [http://globalnews.ca/news/1934020/vaisakhi-celebrated-at-parade-in-south-vancouver/]</ref> which include two [[Nagar Kirtan]] (parades). The Vancouver parade starts at Ross Street Temple<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kdsross.com/|title=Khalsa Diwan Society &#124; Vancouver}}</ref> and makes its way through the traditional [[Punjabi Market, Vancouver|Punjabi Market]] in South Vancouver.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/thousands-brighten-vancouver-streets-to-mark-vaisakhi-1.4620393|title=Thousands brighten Vancouver streets to mark Vaisakhi|newspaper=CBC News|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> One week later, the festival in Surrey is one of the largest such celebrations outside of India, having attracted over 200,000 people in 2014,<ref>VancouverDesi.com 14 April 2015 What you need to know about the Vaisakhi parade [http://www.vancouverdesi.com/news/nridiaspora/what-you-need-to-know-about-the-vaisakhi-parade/865596/]</ref> over 350,000 in 2015, and approached 400,000 in 2016. The 2017 attendance in Surrey reportedly topped 400,000, causing organizers to consider future distribution of the festival over several days and local cities, particularly in areas of economic disadvantage which would benefit from the generous charitable efforts seen during Vaisakhi celebrations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/0423-surrey-vaisakhi|title=Surrey's Vaisakhi parade draws record attendance in massive celebration of diversity and inclusion|newspaper=Vancouver Sun|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/up-to-400k-people-expected-to-attend-2017-surrey-vaisakhi-parade-1.4080812|title=Up to 400K people expected to attend 2017 Surrey Vaisakhi parade|newspaper=CBC News|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> Record attendance was again experienced in April 2018 in the 20th annual Surrey Vaisakhi parade, with the [[RCMP]] officially estimating the crowd at over half a million people in a city with a 2016 census population of 517,887.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.northdeltareporter.com/news/surreys-vaisakhi-parade-biggest-ever/|title=Surrey's Vaisakhi parade biggest ever|newspaper=North Delta Reporter|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> Starting at the Gurdwara Dashmesh Darbar Temple (12885 85th Avenue in Surrey), the parade features a variety of floats, community groups, free food, live music and dancers and performers, and travels along 124th Street, turns left onto 75th Avenue, continues on 76th Avenue, onto 128th Street, then back to the Temple.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.surreyvaisakhiparade.com/files/parade-map.php|title=Surrey Vaisakhi Parade Map|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> [[Kelowna]]'s annual Vaisakhi parade is held a week after Surrey's parade each year and begins and ends at the Sikh Temple on Rutland Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.castanet.net/edition/news-story-224630-1-.htm#224630|title=Vaisakhi Parade Saturday|newspaper=Castanet|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref> [[Greater Victoria|Victoria]]'s all-day Vaisakhi celebration features a parade that begins and ends at Gurdwara Singh Sabha, 470 Cecelia Road. The 2018 celebrations on 29 April would be the first held in Victoria in over 100 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/vaisakhi-victoria-parade-1.4635163|title=After 100 years, Vaisakhi returns to Victoria|newspaper=CBC|accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Alberta|Province of Alberta]], the [[Edmonton]] Vaisakhi parade is held in May and travels between the Gurdwara Singh Sabha (4504 Millwoods Road S) & Gurdwara Millwoods (2606 Millwoods Road E) temples.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vaisakhiparade.com|title=Vaisakhi 2018|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Nova Scotia|Province of Nova Scotia]], the [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]]-based Maritime Sikh Society holds Vaisakhi celebrations in April featuring [[Sikh music|Shabad Kirtan]] performed by professional ragis (musicians).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://maritimesikhsociety.com/|title=Maritime Sikh Society \u2013 About Us|accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Ontario|Province of Ontario]], the [[Toronto]] Vaisakhi Parade is held in April, starting at the Canadian National Exhibition grounds and traveling east to Toronto City Hall, finishing almost three hours later. Following the parade, dignitaries address the gathering until late afternoon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.toronto.com/events/khalsa-day-parade/|title=Khalsa Day Parade Celebrate the founding of the Sikh community. at Better Living Centre|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> In the city of [[Malton, Mississauga|Malton]], a three-hour Nagar Kirtan parade winds from Morning Star, Goreway, Derry Rd, & Airport Rd to Malton Gurdwara Sahib. In the city of [[Brampton]], the Gurudwara Sikh Sangat temple and Gobind Sarvar Gurmat School hold Vaisakhi cultural events such as yoga, pagh (turban) tying, storytelling, and food fairs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gobindsarvarbrampton.com/school/yolo-event/vaisakhi-cultural-food-fair/|title=Vaisakhi Cultural Food Fair|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Saskatchewan|Province of Saskatchewan]], the [[Saskatoon]] Vaisakhi parade is held in May, starting and ending at the Gurudwara Sahib Temple at 331 Lowe Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatoon/sikh-parade-saskatoon-crowd-1.4134571|title=1st-ever Saskatoon Sikh Parade was so busy it spurred a traffic advisory|accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\nThe [[United Kingdom]] has a large Sikh community originating from the Indian sub-continent, [[East Africa]]<ref>S. K. Rait (2005) Sikh Women in England: Their Religious and Cultural Beliefs and Social Practices [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hRfkTq1ykSIC&dq=sikhs+in+england&source=gbs_navlinks_s]</ref> and [[Afghanistan]]. The largest concentrations of [[Sikhs]] in the UK are to be found in the West Midlands (especially [[Birmingham]] and [[Wolverhampton]]) and [[London]].<ref>Amarjeet Singh (2014) Indian Diaspora: Voices of Grandparents and Grandparenting [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vo_HBAAAQBAJ&dq=largest+sikh+community+in+england+birmingham&source=gbs_navlinks_s]</ref> The Southall [[Nagar Kirtan]] is held on a Sunday a week or two before Vaisakhi. The Birmingham [[Nagar Kirtan]] is held in late April in association with Birmingham City Council,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.birmingham.gov.uk/vaisakhi|title=Things to do \u2013 Birmingham City Council|first=Birmingham City|last=Council|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> and is an annual event attracting thousands of people which commences with two separate nagar kirtans setting off from [[gurdwara]]s in the city and culminating in the Vaisakhi [[Mela]] at Handsworth Park.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-birmingham-17805970|accessdate=10 May 2012|newspaper=BBC News|date=22 April 2012|title=Thousands join Sikh Vaisakhi celebrations in Birmingham}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\nAmongst Sikh populations in the [[United States]], there is usually a parade commemorating the Vaisakhi celebration. In [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nycsikhdayparade.com/|title=Annual NYC Sikh Day Parade|date=30 April 2012|publisher=www.nycsikhdayparade.com|accessdate=22 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322192021/http://www.nycsikhdayparade.com/|archivedate=22 March 2012}}</ref> people come out to do \"[[Selfless service|Seva]]\" (selfless service) such as giving out free food, and completing any other labor that needs to be done. In [[Los Angeles, California]], the local Sikh community consisting of many [[gurdwara]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gururamdasashram.org/baisakhi|title=Baisakhi \u2013 Guru Ram Das Ashram|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> holds a full day [[Kirtan]] (spiritual music) program followed by a parade.\n\n===Malaysia===\nThe Sikh community, a subgroup of the [[Malaysian Indian]] ethnic minority race, is an [[ethnoreligious]] minority in Malaysia, which is why Vaisakhi is not a public holiday. However, in line with the government's efforts to promote integration among the country's different ethnic and religious groups, the prime minister, [[Najib Razak]] has announced that beginning 2013, all government servants from the Sikh [[Malaysian Indian]] community will be given a day off on Vaisakhi Day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2012/5/8/nation/11249703&sec=nation|title=Sikh civil servants get Vaisakhi holiday|accessdate=15 February 2013|newspaper=The Star Online|date=8 May 2012}}</ref> Vaisakhi 'open houses' are also held across the country during the day of the festival, or the closest weekend to it.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n{{Punjabi fairs and festivals}}\n{{Punjab, India}}\n{{Sikhism}}\n{{HinduFestivals}}\n{{Hindudharma}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Sikh festivals]]\n[[Category:New Year in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:New Year in India]]\n[[Category:Religious festivals in India]]\n[[Category:Punjabi festivals]]\n[[Category:Festivals in Punjab, Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Religious festivals in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:April observances]]\n[[Category:Observances on non-Gregorian calendars]]<!--Please do not remove this category, this article needs to be sorted into a calendar category-->\n[[Category:Harvest festivals]]\n[[Category:Spring (season) events in Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{infobox holiday\n  | holiday_name  = Vaisakhi\n  | image         = Handsworth Vaisakhi.jpg\n  | caption       = Vaisakhi is the birthday of Khalsa Panth<ref name=senker10/>\n  | nickname      = Baisakh, Vaisakh\n  | observedby    = [[Sikhs]], [[Punjabi Hindus]]\n  | observances  = Prayers, [[procession]]s, raising of the [[Nishan Sahib]] flag, Fairs.\n  | celebrations = Parades and Nagar Kirtan, Fairs, Amrit Sanchaar (baptism) for new Khalsa\n  | type         = Hindu\n  |longtype      = religious, cultural\n  |date2018 = Sat, 14 April\n  |date2019 = Sun, 14 April<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.india.gov.in/calendar/calendar.php?date=2019-04 |title=April 2019 Official Central Government Holiday Calendar |accessdate=17 December 2017 |publisher = Government of India}}</ref>\n  |date2020 = Mon, 13 April<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.india.gov.in/calendar/calendar.php?date=2020-04 |title=April 2020 Official Central Government Holiday Calendar |accessdate=17 December 2017 |publisher = Government of India}}</ref>\n  | significance = Solar New Year,<ref name=\"ColeSambhi1995p63\"/> Harvest festival, birth of the [[Khalsa]], Punjabi new year\n}}\n\n'''Vaisakhi''' ([[IAST]]: {{IAST|vis\u0101kh\u012b}}), also known as '''Baisakhi''' is a historical and religious festival in [[Hinduism]] and [[Sikhism]]. It is usually celebrated on 13 or 14 April every year,<ref>{{cite book|author=Harjinder Singh|title=Vaisakhi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bCReCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA2|publisher=Akaal Publishers|page=2}}</ref><ref name=\"Gupta2006p998\">{{cite book|author1=K.R. Gupta|author2=Amita Gupta|title=Concise Encyclopaedia of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9dNOT9iYxcMC&pg=PA998 |year=2006|publisher=Atlantic Publishers|isbn=978-81-269-0639-0|page=998}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/naperville-sun/community/chi-ugc-article-sikh-religious-society-organizes-two-day-con-2017-11-18-story.html|title=Sikh Religious Society Organizes Two -day Conference in Chicago to Implement Mool Nanakshahi Calendar|last=Bodiwala|first=Suresh|date=November 18, 2017|work=Chicago Tribune|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171120024123/http://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/naperville-sun/community/chi-ugc-article-sikh-religious-society-organizes-two-day-con-2017-11-18-story.html|archivedate=November 20, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Singh1998\">{{cite book|author=Harbans Singh|title=The Encyclopaedia of Sikhism: S-Z|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XhXYAAAAMAAJ&dq=nanakshahi+and+khalsa+calendars&focus=searchwithinvolume|date=1 January 1998|publisher=Publications Bureau|isbn=978-81-7380-530-1}}</ref> which commemorates the formation of [[Khalsa]] panth of warriors under [[Guru Gobind Singh]] in 1699.<ref name=senker10>{{cite book|author=Cath Senker|title=My Sikh Year|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PsQozVTKW44C&pg=PA10|year=2007|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-4042-3733-9|page=10}}, At Vaisakhi, Sikhs remember how their community, the Khalsa, first began.\"</ref><ref name=\"ColeSambhi1995p63\"/><ref name=bbcv>BBC Religions (2009), [http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/sikhism/holydays/vaisakhi.shtml Vaisakhi and the Khalsa]</ref><ref name=\"Jacobsen2008p192\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WT2odZ7_d7MC&pg=PA192|title=South Asian Religions on Display: Religious Processions in South Asia and in the Diaspora|author=Knut A. Jacobsen|publisher=Routledge|year=2008|isbn=978-1-134-07459-4|page=192}}, '''Quote:''' \"Baisakhi is also a Hindu festival, but for the Sikhs, it celebrates the foundation of the Khalsa in 1699.\"</ref>\n\nIn Hinduism, Vaisakhi celebrates the Solar new year, based on the [[Vikram Samvat]] calendar. Vaisakhi marks the first day of the month of [[Vaisakha]]. It is additionally a spring harvest festival for Hinduism and Sikhs.<ref name=bbcv/>\n\nIn Sikhism, Vaisakhi marks the start of the Khalsa. This was in 1699 that the Khalsa was created so this is the beginning of the Khalsa.\n\nVaisakhi observes major events in the history of Sikhism and the [[Indian subcontinent]] that happened in the [[Punjab region]].<ref name=bakshi208/><ref>{{cite book|author1=William Owen Cole|author2=Piara Singh Sambhi|title=The Sikhs: Their Religious Beliefs and Practices|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zIC_MgJ5RMUC |year=1995|publisher=Sussex Academic Press|isbn=978-1-898723-13-4|pages=135\u2013136}}</ref> The significance of Vaisakhi as a major Sikh festival marking the birth of Sikh order started after the persecution and execution of [[Guru Tegh Bahadur]] for refusing to convert to Islam under the orders of the Mughal Emperor [[Aurangzeb]]. This triggered the coronation of the tenth Guru of Sikhism and the historic formation of [[Khalsa]], both on the Vaisakhi day.<ref name=\"Seiple 2013 96\">{{cite book | last=Seiple | first=Chris | title=The Routledge handbook of religion and security | publisher=Routledge | location=New York | year=2013 | isbn=978-0-415-66744-9 | page=96}}</ref><ref name=\"pashaura236\"/><ref name=\"Harkirat S. Hansra 2007 28\u201329\">{{cite book|author=Harkirat S. Hansra|title=Liberty at Stake, Sikhs: the Most Visible|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RDlMUfGiEO8C&pg=PA28 |year=2007|publisher=iUniverse|isbn=978-0-595-43222-6 |pages=28\u201329}}</ref> Vaisakhi was also the day when colonial British empire officials committed the [[Jallianwala Bagh massacre]] on a gathering, an event influential to the Indian movement against colonial rule.<ref name=bakshi208>S. R. Bakshi, Sita Ram Sharma, S. Gajnani (1998) Parkash Singh Badal: Chief Minister of Punjab. APH Publishing [https://books.google.com/books?id=cyebnJdCFlEC&pg=PA208 pages 208\u2013209]</ref>\n\nOn Vaisakhi, Gurdwaras are decorated and hold [[kirtan]]s, Sikhs visit and bathe in lakes or rivers before visiting local Gurdwaras, community fairs and ''nagar kirtan'' processions are held, and people gather to socialize and share festive foods.<ref name=\"Gupta2006p998\"/><ref name=bakshi208/><ref name=\"LeeNadeau2011p1012\">{{cite book|author1=Jonathan H. X. Lee|author2=Kathleen M. Nadeau|title=Encyclopedia of Asian American Folklore and Folklife |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9BrfLWdeISoC&pg=PA1012 |year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-35066-5|pages=1012\u20131013}}</ref>\n\nFor many Hindus, the festival is their traditional solar new year, a harvest festival, an occasion to bathe in sacred rivers such as Ganges, Jhelum, and Kaveri, visit temples, meet friends and take part in other festivities. In other parts of India, the Vaisakhi festival is known by various regional names.<ref name=\"Roy2005p479\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IKqOUfqt4cIC&pg=PA479|title=Traditional Festivals: A Multicultural Encyclopedia|author=Christian Roy|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2005|isbn=978-1-57607-089-5|pages=479\u2013480}}</ref>\n\n==Date==\nVaisakhi is traditionally observed on 13 or 14 April, every year.<ref name=\"Gupta2006p998\"/> The festival is important to both Sikhs and Hindus.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2008p192\"/> The festival coincides with other new year festivals celebrated on the first day of Vaisakh in other regions of the [[Indian Subcontinent]] such as [[Pohela Boishakh]], [[Bohag Bihu]], [[Vishu]], [[Puthandu]] among others.<ref>Crump, William D.  (2014), [https://books.google.com/books?id=cDTfCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA114 Encyclopedia of New Year's Holidays Worldwide], MacFarland, page 114</ref><ref name=\"PechilisRaj2013p48\"/>\n\n==Spelling and pronunciation==\nThe spelling varies with region. In Punjab region, ''Vaisakhi'' is common, but in the [[Doabi]] and [[Malwi dialect|Malwai]] dialects, speakers often substitute a ''B'' for a ''V''.<ref name=\"Archived copy\">{{Cite web |url=http://punjabrevenue.nic.in/gaz_gdr5.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=26 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304123940/http://punjabrevenue.nic.in/gaz_gdr5.htm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The spelling used depends on the dialect of the writer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1CB_aQY5TcY-oJ6GwVjx55Lqd153eihGl/view?usp=sharing|title=Pronunciation of Vaisakhi|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Sikhism==\n{{Sikhism sidebar}}\n{{Main|Khalsa}}\n\n===History===\nSince the time of Guru Amar Das it has been customary for Sikhs to assemble before their Guru on three of the most important Hindu festival occasions \u2013 Vaisakhi, Divali, and Maha Shivaratri. The alternative view is that Guru Amar Das chose [[Makar Sankranti|Maghi]], instead of Maha Shivaratri.<ref>Fauja Singh, Gurbachan Singh Talib (1975), Punjabi University [https://books.google.com/books?id=7g0eAAAAMAAJ Guru Tegh Bahadur: Martyr and Teacher]</ref><ref>H. S. Singha (2000), Hemkunt Press [https://books.google.com/books?id=gqIbJz7vMn0C&pg=PA16 The Encyclopedia of Sikhism (over 1000 Entries)] page 16</ref>\n\nSubsequent events gave a new meaning to the festival which is, in part, a remembrance of the foundation of the Khalsa Sikh order which started after the ninth [[Guru Tegh Bahadur]] was persecuted and then beheaded under the orders of the Mughal Emperor [[Aurangzeb]], after he stood up for freedom of religious practice and refused to convert to Islam.<ref name=\"Seiple 2013 96\"/><ref name=\"pashaura236\" /> The guru's martyrdom triggered the coronation of the tenth and last Guru of Sikhism, and the formation of the ''sant-sipahi'' group of [[Khalsa]],<ref name=\"Chanchreek 2007 142\">{{cite book|last=Chanchreek|first=Jain|title=Encyclopaedia of Great Festivals|year=2007|publisher=Shree Publishers & Distributors|isbn=9788183291910|page=142}}</ref><ref name=\"Dugga 2001 33\">{{cite book|last=Dugga|first=Kartar|title=Maharaja Ranjit Singh: The Last to Lay Arms|year=2001|publisher=Abhinav Publications|isbn=9788170174103|page=33}}</ref> both on the Vaisakhi day.<ref name=\"pashaura236\">{{cite book | author=Pashaura Singh and Louis Fenech | title=The Oxford handbook of Sikh studies | publisher=Oxford University Press | location=Oxford, UK | year=2014 | isbn=978-0-19-969930-8 | pages=236\u2013237}}</ref>\n\nThe Vaisakhi festival Khalsa tradition started in the year 1699,<ref name=bakshi208/> as it is on this day that the 10th Guru of the Sikhs, [[Guru Gobind Singh]] laid down the foundation of the [[Khalsa|Panth Khalsa]], that is the Order of the Pure Ones, by baptizing Sikh warriors to defend religious freedoms.<ref>Pashaura Singh (2005), ''Understanding the Martyrdom of Guru Arjan'', Journal of Punjab Studies, 12(1), pages 29\u201362</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Johar|first1=Surinder|title=Guru Gobind Singh: A Multi-faceted Personality|date=1999|publisher=M.D. Publications |isbn=978-8175330931|page=89}}</ref><ref name=\"Gandhi\">{{cite book | title=History of Sikh Gurus Retold: 1606 -1708 | publisher=Atlantic Publishers | author=Singh Gandhi, Surjit | year=2008 | pages=676\u2013677 | isbn=8126908572}}</ref> This gave rise to the Vaisakhi or Baisakhi festival being observed as a celebration of Khalsa panth formation and is also known as Khalsa Sirjana Divas<ref>Laws of the State of Illinois Enacted by the ... General Assembly at the Extra Session. (2013) State Printers. [https://books.google.com/books?id=adPXhc84ZMwC page 7772]</ref> and Khalsa Sajna Divas.<ref>Singh, Jagraj (2009) A Complete Guide to Sikhism. Unistar Books [https://books.google.com/books?id=rFm9_Jc1ykcC&pg=PA311 page 311]</ref> The festival is celebrated on Vaisakhi day (typically 14 April), since 1699. The Birth of the Khalsa Panth was either on 13 April 1699<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|last1=Purewal|first1=Pal|title=Vaisakhi Dates Range According To Indian Ephemeris By Swamikannu Pillai \u2013 i.e. English Date on 1 Vaisakh Bikrami|url=http://www.purewal.biz/PastVaisakhiDates.pdf|website=www.purewal.biz|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref> or 30 March 1699.<ref>Kaur, Madanjit (2007). Unistar Books [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZG4MycGdpjAC&pg=PA149 Guru Gobind Singh: Historical and Ideological Perspective], page 149</ref> Since 2003, the Sikh Gurdwara Prabhandak Committee named it Baisakh (Vaisakh), making the first day of the second month of Vaisakh according to its new [[Nanakshahi calendar]].<ref>{{cite book|author=W. H. McLeod|title=The A to Z of Sikhism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vgixwfeCyDAC&pg=PA143|year=2009|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6344-6|pages=143\u2013144}}</ref>\n\nA special celebration takes place at [[Talwandi Sabo]] (where [[Guru Gobind Singh]] stayed for nine months and completed the recompilation of the [[Guru Granth Sahib]]),<ref>{{cite news |title=Vaisakhi celebrated with fervour, gaiety|author=Tribune News service|newspaper=The Tribune, Chandigarh|date=14 April 2009}}</ref> in the [[Gurudwara]] at [[Anandpur Sahib]] the birthplace of the [[Khalsa]], and at the [[Harmandir Sahib|Golden Temple]] in [[Amritsar]].\n\n===Sikh New Year===\nAccording to the Khalsa sambat, the Khalsa calendar starts with the creation of the Khalsa which is 1 Vaisakh 1756 Bikrami (30 March 1699).<ref>Dogra, Ramesh Chander and Dogra, Urmila (2003) Page 248 The Sikh World: An Encyclopedic Survey of Sikh Religion and Culture. UBS Publishers Distributors Pvt Ltd {{ISBN|81-7476-443-7}}</ref><ref>The Panjab in 1839\u201340: selections from the Punjab akhbars, Punjab intelligence, etc., preserved in the National Archives of India, New Delhi (1952) Sikh History Society [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Q645AQAAIAAJ&dq=khalsa+sammat&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=+sammat]</ref> Accordingly, Vaisakhi has been the traditional Sikh New Year.<ref name=senker10/><ref name=\"ColeSambhi1995p63\">{{cite book|author1=William Owen Cole|author2=Piara Singh Sambhi|title=The Sikhs: Their Religious Beliefs and Practices |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zIC_MgJ5RMUC&pg=PA63 |year=1995|publisher=Sussex Academic Press|isbn=978-1-898723-13-4|page=63}}, '''Quote:''' \"The Sikh new year, Vaisakhi, occurs at Sangrand in April, usually on the thirteenth day.\"</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Nick Hunter|title=Celebrating Sikh Festivals|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QLBeCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA10|year=2016|publisher=Raintree|isbn=978-1-4062-9776-8|page=10}}</ref> The festival has been traditionally observed in the [[Punjab region]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=d195AAAAMAAJ|title=Festivals in World Religions|first=Alan|last=Brown|year= 1986|publisher=Longman|accessdate=14 September 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>Simon J Bronner (2015), Routledge [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FvjqBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA1132 Encyclopedia of American Folklife], page 1132</ref> The alternative Nanakshahi calendar begins its year a month earlier on 1 Chait which generally falls on 14 March and begins with the birth year of the Guru Nanak Dev in 1469.<ref>Kapel, Marin (2006) The Structure and Mathematics of the Principal Calendars of the Western World: Muslim, Gregorian, Jewish, and Other Systems. Edwin Mellen Press [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=paYSAQAAIAAJ&dq=nanakshahi+year+14+march&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=14+march]</ref>\n\n===Nagar Kirtan===\nSikh communities organise processions called ''nagar kirtan'' (literally, \"town hymn singing\"). These are led by five khalsa who are dressed up as ''Panj Pyaare'', and the processions through the streets. The people who march sing, make music, sing hymns from the Sikh texts. Major processions also carry a copy of the [[Guru Granth Sahib]] in reverence.<ref name=bbcv/>\n\n===Harvest festival===\n[[File:Common good.jpg|thumb|left|Two Sikh men celebrating Vaisakhi by giving away free sugarcane juice.]]\n[[File:Kothe-da-mela.jpg|thumb|Vaisakhi ''mela'']]\nVaisakhi is a harvest festival for people of the [[Punjab region]].<ref>Bakshi, S. R. Sharma, Sita Ram (1998) Parkash Singh Badal: Chief Minister of Punjab [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cyebnJdCFlEC&dq=baisakhi+punjabi+festival&source=gbs_navlinks_s]</ref> In the Punjab, Vaisakhi marks the ripening of the [[rabi crop|rabi]] harvest.<ref>Dogra, Ramesh Chander and Dogra, Urmila (2003) Page 49 The Sikh World: An Encyclopedic Survey of Sikh Religion and Culture. UBS Publishers Distributors Pvt Ltd {{ISBN|81-7476-443-7}}</ref> Vaisakhi also marks the Punjabi new year.<ref>Sainik Samachar: The Pictorial Weekly of the Armed Forces, Volume 33 (1986) Director of Public Relations, Ministry of Defence, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=t1jfAAAAMAAJ&q=Punjabi+new+year&dq=Punjabi+new+year&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjXluL21O3SAhUrI8AKHfVkAro4ChDoAQgoMAM]</ref> This day is observed as a thanksgiving day by farmers whereby farmers pay their tribute, thanking God for the abundant harvest and also praying for future prosperity.<ref>Dhillon, (2015) Janamsakhis: Ageless Stories, Timeless Values. Hay House [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=OXtVDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT197&dq=punjabi+calendar&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjkwr3R6OrSAhVEBMAKHduoBjYQ6AEIHzAB#v=onepage&q=punjabi%20calendar&f=false]</ref> The harvest festival is celebrated by Sikhs and Punjabi Hindus.<ref>Gupta, Surendra K.  (1999) Indians in Thailand, Books India International [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5rBuAAAAMAAJ&dq=baisakhi+harvest+punjab+hindus+and+sikhs&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=barley]</ref> Historically, during the early 20th century, Vaisakhi was a sacred day for Sikhs and Hindus and a secular festival for all Muslims and non-Muslims including Punjabi Christians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=tNAxAQAAIAAJ&dq=baisakhi+harvest+punjab+hindus+and+sikhs&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=turbaned+sikhs|title=Link: Indian Newsmagazine|date=13 April 1987|via=Google Books}}</ref> In modern times, sometimes Christians participate in Baisakhi celebrations along with Sikhs and Hindus.<ref>Nahar, Emanual (2007) Minority politics in India: role and impact of Christians in Punjab politics. Arun Pub. House. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vl9uAAAAMAAJ&dq=punjabi+christians+baisakhi+india&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=baisakhi+]</ref>\n\n====Aawat pauni====\n[[File:Bhangra 1.jpg|thumb|right|Bhangra dance on Vaisakhi is a Sikh tradition]]\n[[Aawat pauni]] is a tradition associated with harvesting, which involves people getting together to harvest the wheat. Drums are played while people work. At the end of the day, people sing [[Doha (poetry)|dohay]] to the tunes of the drum.<ref>Dr Singh, Sadhu (2010) Punjabi Boli Di Virasat. Chetna Prakashan. {{ISBN|817883618-1}}</ref>\n\n====Fairs and dances====\nThe harvest festival is also characterized by the folk dance, [[Bhangra (dance)|Bhangra]] which traditionally is a harvest dance.\n\nFairs or ''[[Mela]]s'' are held in many parts of [[Punjab, India]] to mark the new year and the harvesting season. Vaisakhi fairs take place in various places, including [[Jammu]] City, Kathua, Udhampur, Reasi and Samba,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/jammu-and-kashmir/baisakhi-celebrated-with-fervour-gaiety-in-jk_1578749.html|title=Baisakhi celebrated with fervour, gaiety in J&K|date=14 April 2015|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> in the Pinjore complex near [[Chandigarh]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7d3rX5jr1WQC&dq=haryana%20baisakhi&source=gbs_navlinks_s|title=Tourism Management: Problems and Prospects|first=Bijender K.|last=Punia|date=1 January 1994|publisher=APH Publishing|accessdate=14 September 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref> in [[Himachal Pradesh]] cities of Rewalsar, Shimla, Mandi and Prashar Lakes.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Hinduism==\n{{Hinduism}}\n[[File:Ganges at Haridwar, Uttarakhand.jpg|thumb|left|Bathing in rivers is a Vaisakhi tradition]]\nThe first day of Vaisakh marks the traditional solar new year<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=PGXgssv08PgC&pg=PA61 |title=Indian Astronomy: An Introduction|first=S. Balachandra|last=Rao|date=1 January 2000|publisher=Universities Press|accessdate=14 September 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>Tribune 15 April 2011 Baisakhi fervour at Haridwar Lakhs take dip in holy Ganga [http://www.tribuneindia.com/2011/20110415/dplus.htm#1]</ref> and it is an ancient festival that predates the founding of Sikhism. The harvest is complete and crops ready to sell, representing a time of plenty for the farmers. Fairs and special thanksgiving pujas (prayers) are common in the Hindu tradition.<ref name=\"Rinehart2004p139\">{{cite book|author=Robin Rinehart|title=Contemporary Hinduism: Ritual, Culture, and Practice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hMPYnfS_R90C&pg=PA139|year=2004|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-57607-905-8|page=139}}</ref>\n\nThe first day of Vaisakh marks the solar new year.<ref name=\"BBC Hinduism\">{{cite web |title= BBC \u2013 Religion: Hinduism \u2013 Vaisakhi|publisher=[[BBC]]|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/hinduism/holydays/vaisakhi.shtml |accessdate=22 January 2012}}</ref> It is the New Year's Day for Hindus in [[Assam]], [[West Bengal|Bengal]], [[Bihar]], [[Himachal Pradesh]], [[Haryana]], [[Kerala]], [[Odisha]], [[Punjab, India|Punjab]]<ref>Crump, William D.  (2014) Encyclopedia of New Year's Holidays Worldwide. McFarland [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cDTfCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA114&dq=vaisakhi+punjabi+hindu+new+year&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwijseXUpvvSAhWrC8AKHS2cDXsQ6AEIKjAD#v=onepage&q=vaisakhi%20punjabi%20hindu%20new%20year&f=false]</ref> [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[Uttrakhand]] and other parts of India.<ref name=\"BBC Hinduism\" /><ref name=\"PechilisRaj2013p48\" /> However, this is not the universal new year for all Hindus. For some, such as those in and near Gujarat, the new year festivities coincide with the five-day [[Diwali]] festival.<ref name=\"PechilisRaj2013p48\" /> For others, the new year falls on [[Cheti Chand]], [[Gudi Padwa]] and [[Ugadi]] which falls a few weeks earlier.<ref name=\"PechilisRaj2013p48\">{{cite book|author1=Karen Pechilis| author2=Selva J. Raj|title= South Asian Religions: Tradition and Today|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=kaubzRxh-U0C&pg=PA48| year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-44851-2|pages=48\u201349}}</ref><ref name=\"Falzon2004p62\">{{cite book|author=Mark-Anthony Falzon|title=Cosmopolitan Connections: The Sindhi Diaspora, 1860\u20132000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ljbS-I5Y8WMC&pg=PA62|year=2004|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-14008-5|page=62}}</ref>\n\n[[File:4 girls celebrating Assamese Bihu.jpg|thumb|left |Celebrating Bohag Bihu in Assam]]\nIt is regionally known by many names among the Hindus, though the festivities and its significance is similar. It is celebrated by Hindus bathing in sacred rivers, as they believe that river goddess Ganges descended to earth on Vaisakhi.<ref name=\"Rinehart2004p139\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5kl0DYIjUPgC&pg=PA81 |title=The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Hinduism: A-M|first=James G.|last=Lochtefeld|date=1 January 2002|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|accessdate=14 September 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref> Some rivers considered particularly sacred include the Ganges, Jhelum and Kaveri. Hindus visit temples, meet friends and party over festive foods.<ref name=\"Roy2005p479\"/>\n\nVaisakhi coincides with the festival of '[[Vishu]]' celebrated in [[Kerala]] a day after Vaisakhi. The festivities include fireworks, shopping for new clothes and interesting displays called 'Vishu Kani'. Hindus make arrangements of flowers, grains, fruits which friends and family visit to admire as \"lucky sight\" (''Vishukkani''). Giving gifts to friends and loved ones, as well as alms to the needy, are a tradition of Kerala Hindus on this festive day.<ref name=\"Roy2005p479\"/>\n\nVaisakhi is celebrated as [[Bohag Bihu|Bohag (Rongali) Bihu]] in [[Assam]] and as Pohela Boishakh in [[West Bengal|Bengal]], but typically one or two days after Vaisakhi.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aghr.cag.gov.in/holidays.pdf |title=2017 Official Central Government Holiday Calendar |accessdate=4 March 2017 |publisher = Government of India}}</ref>\n\n===Regional variations===\n[[File:Mathapoo vishu.jpg|thumb|Some Indians mark their traditional new year with fireworks]]\nThe following is a list of new year festivals:<ref name=\"BBC Hinduism\"/><ref>Crump, William D.  (2014), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cDTfCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA114 Encyclopedia of New Year's Holidays Worldwide], MacFarland, page 114</ref><ref name=\"PechilisRaj2013p48\"/>\n* ''Bikhu'' or ''Bikhauti'' in the [[Kumaon division|Kumaon]] region of [[Uttarakhand]], India\n* ''[[Bisu (festival)|Bisu]]'' \u2013 Tulu New Year Day amongst the [[Tulu people]] in India\n* ''[[Bohag Bihu]]'' in [[Assam]], India\n* ''[[Kodava people|Edmyaar 1 (Bisu Changrandi)]]'' \u2013 [[Kodava people|Kodava]] New Year.\n*''JurShital'' (New Year) in [[History of Mithila|Mithila]] (parts of [[Nepal]] and [[Bihar]], India)\n* ''[[Vishuva Sankranti|Maha Vishuva Sankranti]]'' (or Pana Sankranti) in [[Odisha]], India\n* ''Naba Barsha'' or ''[[Pohela Boishakh]]'' in [[West Bengal]] and [[Tripura]], India, [[Nepal]] and [[Bangladesh]]\n* ''[[Puthandu]]''  in [[Tamil Nadu]], India\n*''[[Ugadi]]'' in [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Karnataka]] and [[Telangana]], India\n* ''[[Vishu]]''  in [[Kerala]], India\n\nThe new year falls on or about the same day every year for many Buddhist communities in parts of South and Southeast Asia. This is likely an influence of their shared culture in the 1st millennium CE.<ref name=\"PechilisRaj2013p48\"/> Some examples include:\n*''[[Sinhalese New Year|Aluth Avuruthu]]'' in [[Sri Lanka]].<ref name=\"reeves174\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4N5UAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA174|title=The Encyclopedia of the Sri Lankan Diaspora|author=Peter Reeves|publisher=Didier Millet|year=2014|isbn=978-981-4260-83-1|page=174}}</ref>\n*''[[Bikram Samwat]]'' / ''Vaishak Ek'' in [[Nepal]]\n* ''[[Cambodian New Year|Chol Chnam Thmey]]'' in [[Cambodia]]\n* ''[[Songkran (Lao)|Pii Mai Lao]]'' in [[Laos]]\n*''[[Songkran (Thailand)|Songkran]]'' in [[Thailand]]\n* ''[[Thingyan]]'' in [[Myanmar]]\n\n====Bikhoti festival====\nThe Bikhoti Festival of [[Uttrakhand]] involves people taking a dip in holy rivers. A popular custom involves beating symbolic stones representing demons with sticks. The fair is celebrated in various major centres including Sealdah, Bageshwar and Dwarahat and involves much singing and dancing, accompanied by local drums and other instruments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.edgeofindia.com/locations/uttarakhand/bageshwar/when-to-go/festivals_culture.aspx|title=Festivals and Culture}}</ref>\n\n====Vishu====\n[[File:Vishukani.jpg|thumb|left|A Vishukkani tray before Krishna (Vishnu), a Kerala Hindu tradition]]\nVishu is a Hindu festival celebrated on the same day as Vaisakhi in the Indian state of [[Kerala]], and falls on the first day of Malayali month called Medam.<ref name=vishugok>[https://kerala.gov.in/major-festivals Major festivals of Kerala], Government of Kerala (2016)</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=J. Gordon Melton|title=Religious Celebrations: An Encyclopedia of Holidays, Festivals, Solemn Observances, and Spiritual Commemorations |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lD_2J7W_2hQC&pg=PA633 |year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-59884-206-7|page=633}}</ref> The festival is notable for its solemnity and the general lack of pomp and show that characterize other Hindu festivals of Kerala such as [[Onam]].<ref name=vishugok/><ref name=\"Jagannathan2005p76\">{{cite book| author=Maithily Jagannathan|title=South Indian Hindu Festivals and Traditions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xcIrkKUJH9QC|year = 2005|publisher = Abhinav Publications|isbn= 978-81-7017-415-8|pages=76\u201377}}</ref>\n\nThe festival is marked by family time, preparing colorful auspicious items and viewing these as the first thing on the Vishu day. In particular, Malayali Hindus seek to view the golden blossoms of the Indian laburnum (''Kani Konna''), money or silver items (''Vishukkaineetam''), and rice.<ref name=vishugok/><ref name=\"Jagannathan2005p76\"/> The day also attracts firework play by children,<ref name=vishugok/><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Thiruvananthapuram/city-celebrates-vishu/article399057.ece |title=City celebrates Vishu |publisher=The Hindu |date=16 April 2010 |accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref> wearing new clothes (''Puthukodi'') and the eating a special meal called ''[[Sadya]]'', which is a mix of salty, sweet, sour and bitter items.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/when-the-laburnum-blooms/article1696077.ece |title=When the Laburnum blooms |publisher=The Hindu |date=14 April 2011 |accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref> The Vishu arrangement typically includes an image of [[Vishnu]], typically as [[Krishna]]. People also visit temples on the day.<ref name=\"Dalal2010p461\">{{cite book|author=Roshen Dalal|title=Hinduism: An Alphabetical Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DH0vmD8ghdMC&pg=PA461|year=2010|publisher=Penguin Books|isbn=978-0-14-341421-6|page=461}}</ref>\n\n====Bohag Bihu====\n[[File:Dhuliya performing in an open stage bihu.jpg|thumb|Festive Bihu with Dhuliya is an Assamese Hindu tradition on this day.]]\nBohag Bihu or Rangali Bihu marks the beginning of the Assamese New Year on 13 April. It is celebrated for seven days Vishuva Sankranti (Mesha Sankranti) of the month of Vaisakh or locally 'Bohag' (Bhaskar Calendar). The three primary types of Bihu are Rongali Bihu, Kongali Bihu, and Bhogali Bihu. Each festival historically recognizes a different agricultural cycle of the paddy crops. During Rangali Bihu there are 7 pinnacle phases: 'Chot', 'Raati', 'Goru', 'Manuh', 'Kutum', 'Mela' and 'Chera'.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\n====Maha Vishuva Sankranti====\n[[Maha Vishuva Sankranti]] marks the Oriya new year in [[Odisha]]. Celebrations include various types of folk and classical dances, such as the Shiva-related [[Chhau dance]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Sitakant Mahapatra|title=Chhau Dance of Mayurbhanj|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4VHkAAAAMAAJ |year=1993|publisher=Vidyapuri|page=86}}</ref> More popularly it is known as Pana Sankranti(\u0b2a\u0b23\u0b3e \u0b38\u0b02\u0b15\u0b4d\u0b30\u0b3e\u0b28\u0b4d\u0b24\u0b3f). On this day people hang pieces of Neem branches with leaves in front of their houses believed to have health benefits. They prepare a liquid mixture of jaggery, mango, pepper and other ingredients which is called Pana(\u0b2a\u0b23\u0b3e). An earthen pot with a small hole and a grass(\u0b15\u0b41\u0b41\u0b36) within the hole at the bottom is hung over the Tulasi (\u0b24\u0b41\u0b41\u0b41\u0b33\u0b38\u0b40 \u0b1a\u0b09\u0b30\u0b3e). The pot is filled with water daily which acts as a drip to protect the sacred plant from the summer heat.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n====Pahela Baishakh====\n{{main|Pohela Boishakh}}\n[[File:Colors of Celebration!-4.JPG|thumb|Pohela Boishakh celebrations in Dhaka, Bangladesh.]]\nThe Bengali new year is celebrated as Pahela Baishakh on 14 April every year, and a festive [[Mangal Shobhajatra]], started by students of Dhaka University in Bangladesh in 1989,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/2017/04/14/66874/%27Mongol-Shobhajatra%27-parades-city-streets|title='Mongol Shobhajatra' parades city streets|website=The Financial Express Online Version|access-date=16 April 2017}}</ref> is organized in the [[Indian states]] of West Bengal and Tripura, as well as modern-day nation of Bangladesh. This celebration was listed in 2016 by the [[UNESCO]] as a cultural heritage of humanity.<ref>[http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/en/RL/mangal-shobhajatra-on-pahela-baishakh-01091 Mangal Shobhajatra on Pahela Baishakh], UNESCO</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/unesco-cultural-heritage-list-adds-mangal-shobhajatra-1323331|title=Unesco lists Mangal Shobhajatra as cultural heritage|date=1 December 2016|work=The Daily Star|access-date=16 April 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe festival is celebrated as a national holiday in [[Bangladesh]]. Also spelled Pohela Boishakh is also known as Nobo Barsho as it is the first day of the Bengali month of Bongabdo. Fairs are organised to celebrate the event which provides entertainment including the presentation of folk songs.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\n====Puthandu====\nPuthandu, also known as ''Puthuvarusham'' or ''Tamil New Year'', is the first day of the month ''Chithirai'' on the [[Tamil calendar]].<ref name=\"Dalal2010p406\">{{cite book|author=Roshen Dalal|title=Hinduism: An Alphabetical Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DH0vmD8ghdMC |year=2010|publisher=Penguin Books|isbn=978-0-14-341421-6|page=406}}</ref><ref name=\"Melton2011p633\">{{cite book|author=J. Gordon Melton|title=Religious Celebrations: An Encyclopedia of Holidays, Festivals, Solemn Observances, and Spiritual Commemorations |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lD_2J7W_2hQC&pg=PA633|year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-59884-206-7|page=633}}</ref><ref name=reeves174/>\n\nOn this day, Tamil people greet each other by saying \"Putt\u0101\u1e47\u1e6du v\u0101\u1e3bttukka\u1e37!\" or \"I\u1e49iya putt\u0101\u1e47\u1e6du nalv\u0101\u1e3bttukka\u1e37!\", which is equivalent to \"Happy new year\".<ref>{{cite book|author=William D. Crump|title=Encyclopedia of New Year's Holidays Worldwide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cDTfCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA220 |year=2014|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-9545-0|page=220}}</ref> The day is observed as a family time. Households clean up the house, prepare a tray with fruits, flowers and auspicious items, light up the family [[Puja (Hinduism)|Puja]] altar and visit their local temples. People wear new clothes and youngster go to elders to pay respects and seek their blessings, then the family sits down to a vegetarian feast.<ref>{{cite book|author=Samuel S. Dhoraisingam|title=Peranakan Indians of Singapore and Melaka |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QHwcAgAAQBAJ |year=2006|publisher=Institute of Southeast Asian Studies|isbn=978-981-230-346-2|page=38}}</ref>\n\n====Jurshital in Bihar====\nIn the Mithal region of [[Bihar]] and [[Nepal]], the new year is celebrated as Jurshital.<ref>Hari Bansh Jha (1993) The terai community and national integration in Nepal.[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JShuAAAAMAAJ&q=JurShital+new+year&dq=JurShital+new+year&hl=en&sa=X&ei=yFYzVZaiD5LaaPLFgCg&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAQ]</ref> It is traditional to use lotus leaves to serve [[sattu]] (powdered meal derived from grains of red gram and jau (Hordeum vulgare) and other ingredients) to the family members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ugVFAQAAIAAJ&q=Jurshital&dq=Jurshital&hl=en&sa=X&ei=J6MzVYuBGtOWavbCgIgO&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAw|title=Ethnobotany|date=1 January 2002|publisher=Aavishkar Publishers, Distributors|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Sikh celebrations outside India==\n{{multiple image|total_width=260|perrow=2|caption_align=center\n| header = Celebration around the world\n| image1 =Vaisakhi1.jpg\n| caption1 = A depiction of [[Guru Gobind Singh]] initiating the first five members of the [[Khalsa]]\n| image2 = Panj Pyare, leading a procession.jpg\n| caption2 = The [[Panj Pyare]] at Vaisakhi 2007 [[Wolverhampton]], UK\n| image3 = Vaisakhi 2012 London - 22.jpg\n| caption3 = Vaisakhi at [[Trafalgar Square]], London\n| image4 = Vaisakhi 2012 London - 21.jpg\n| caption4 = Vaisakhi 2012 at [[Trafalgar Square]], London\n| image5 = Vaisakhi 2012 London - 23.jpg\n| caption5 = Vaisakhi 2012 at [[Trafalgar Square]], London\n| image6 = Vaisakhi Sikh festival in Birmingham 2013.jpg\n| caption6 = Vaisakhi celebrations in Birmingham\n| image7 = Panj Pyare, leading a procession.jpg\n| caption7 = The [[Panj Pyare]] at Vaisakhi 2007 [[Wolverhampton]], UK\n| image8 = Dessert on tray.jpg\n| caption8 = [[Jalebi]]yan being served at Vaisakhi Day, 11 April 2009, [[Vancouver]] Canada\n| image9 = Airplane-mobile.jpg\n| caption9 = 2009 [[Vancouver]] Sikh Vaisakhi parade\n| image10 = Sikh Motorcycle Club at Vaisakhi.jpg\n| caption10 = Sikh Motorcycle Club at Vaisakhi 2007 [[Vancouver, British Columbia]], Canada\n| image11 =  Sikh Motorcycle Club at Vaisakhi.jpg\n| caption11 = Sikh Motorcycle Club at Vaisakhi 2007 [[Vancouver, British Columbia]], Canada\n| image12 =  Vaisakhi fair mela in Surrey Canada.jpg\n| caption12 = Vaisakhi festival in Surrey, BC, Canada\n| image13 = Vaisakhi Day Celebration (8651688584).jpg\n| caption13= A band performs at Vaisakhi day celebrations in Kuala Lumpur (2013)\n| image14 = Vaisakhi parade 2017 (33217388724).jpg\n| caption14= Vaisakhi 2017, Punjabi Market, Vancouver\n}}\n\n===Pakistan===\nPakistan has many sites that are of historic importance to the Sikh faith, such as the birthplace of Guru Nanak. These sites attract pilgrims from India and abroad every year on Vaisakhi.<ref>[https://www.dawn.com/news/1176098 Glare and galore at Baisakhi festival], The Dawn, Pakistan (15 April 2015)</ref><ref>[http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/vaisakhi-2015-sikh-devotees-celebrate-major-festival-india-pakistan-photos-1496358 Vaisakhi 2015: Sikh devotees celebrate major festival in India and Pakistan], David Sims, International Business Times</ref> Pakistan used to have many more Sikhs, but a vast majority moved to India during the 1947 India-Pakistan partition. Contemporary Pakistan has about 20,000 Sikhs in a total population of about 200 million Pakistanis, or about 0.01%.<ref>Ary News 17 April 2015 Sikh pligrims gather in Pakistan for Vaisakhi festival [http://arynews.tv/en/sikh-pligrims-gather-in-pakistan-for-vaisakhi-festival/]</ref> These Sikhs, and thousands more who arrive from other parts of the world for pilgrimage, observe Vaisakhi in [[Punjab, Pakistan|Western Punjab]] (Pakistan) with festivities centered on the [[Panja Sahib]] complex in [[Hasan Abdal]], [[Gurudwara]]s in [[Nankana Sahib]], and in various historical sites in [[Lahore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/world-news/sikhs-throng-pakistan-shrine-for-baisakhi_10037124.html|title=Sikh throng Pakistan shrine for Vaisakhi|author=Muhammad Najeeb Hasan Abdal|date=12 April 2008|work=Thaindian News|publisher=www.thaindian.com|accessdate=22 January 2012}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|On 8 April 2016, Punjabi Parchar at Alhamra (Lahore) organised a show called Visakhi mela, where the speakers pledged to \"continue our struggle to keep the Punjabi culture alive\" in Pakistan through events such as Visakhi Mela.<ref>Pakistan Today (8 April 2016) [http://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2016/04/08/promoting-peace-with-punjabi-at-visakhi-mela/ Punjabi Parchar spreads colours of love at Visakhi Mela]</ref> Elsewhere Besakhi fairs or melas are held in various places including [[Eminabad]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/953015|title=A fair dedicated to animal lovers|date=20 April 2009|website=DAWN.COM}}</ref> and [[Dera Ghazi Khan]].<ref>Agnes Ziegler, Akhtar Mummunka (2006) The final Frontier: unique photographs of Pakistan. Sang-e-Meel Publications [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=AhNuAAAAMAAJ&q=besakhi+mela+sakhi&dq=besakhi+mela+sakhi&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQ67W705zTAhVrKsAKHZ5iBJIQ6AEIHDAA]</ref>}}\n\nAccording to Aziz-ud-din Ahmed, [[Lahore]] used to have Baisakhi Mela after the harvesting of the wheat crop in April. However, adds Ahmed, the city started losing its cultural vibrancy in 1970s after Zia-ul-Haq came to power, and in recent years \"the [[Pakistan Muslim League (N)]] government in Punjab banned kite flying through an official edict more under the pressure of those who want a puritanical version of Islam to be practiced in the name of religion than anything else\".<ref>[http://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2015/02/21/cultural-decline-in-lahore/ Cultural Decline in Pakistan], Pakistan Today, Aziz-ud-din Ahmed (21 February 2015)</ref> Unlike the Indian state of Punjab that recognizes the Vaisakhi Sikh festival as an official holiday,<ref>[http://punjab.gov.in/list-of-holidays Official Holidays], Government of Punjab, India (2016)</ref> the festival is not an official holiday in Punjab or Sindh provinces of Pakistan as Sikhs constitute a very small number in terms of population.<ref>[http://www.schools.punjab.gov.pk/system/files/Notification_2.pdf Official Holidays 2016], Government of Punjab \u2013 Pakistan (2016)</ref><ref>[http://www.kmc.gos.pk/Contents.aspx?id=48 Official Holidays 2016], Karachi Metropolitan, Sindh, Pakistan</ref>\n\n===Canada===\nIn the [[British Columbia|Province of British Columbia]], large, local Sikh communities in the cities of [[Vancouver, British Columbia|Vancouver]], [[Abbotsford, British Columbia|Abbotsford]], and [[Surrey, British Columbia|Surrey]] hold their annual Vaisakhi celebrations in April,<ref>Global News 12 April 2015 Vaisakhi celebrated at parade in south Vancouver [http://globalnews.ca/news/1934020/vaisakhi-celebrated-at-parade-in-south-vancouver/]</ref> which include two [[Nagar Kirtan]] (parades). The Vancouver parade starts at Ross Street Temple<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kdsross.com/|title=Khalsa Diwan Society &#124; Vancouver}}</ref> and makes its way through the traditional [[Punjabi Market, Vancouver|Punjabi Market]] in South Vancouver.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/thousands-brighten-vancouver-streets-to-mark-vaisakhi-1.4620393|title=Thousands brighten Vancouver streets to mark Vaisakhi|newspaper=CBC News|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> One week later, the festival in Surrey is one of the largest such celebrations outside of India, having attracted over 200,000 people in 2014,<ref>VancouverDesi.com 14 April 2015 What you need to know about the Vaisakhi parade [http://www.vancouverdesi.com/news/nridiaspora/what-you-need-to-know-about-the-vaisakhi-parade/865596/]</ref> over 350,000 in 2015, and approached 400,000 in 2016. The 2017 attendance in Surrey reportedly topped 400,000, causing organizers to consider future distribution of the festival over several days and local cities, particularly in areas of economic disadvantage which would benefit from the generous charitable efforts seen during Vaisakhi celebrations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/0423-surrey-vaisakhi|title=Surrey's Vaisakhi parade draws record attendance in massive celebration of diversity and inclusion|newspaper=Vancouver Sun|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/up-to-400k-people-expected-to-attend-2017-surrey-vaisakhi-parade-1.4080812|title=Up to 400K people expected to attend 2017 Surrey Vaisakhi parade|newspaper=CBC News|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> Record attendance was again experienced in April 2018 in the 20th annual Surrey Vaisakhi parade, with the [[RCMP]] officially estimating the crowd at over half a million people in a city with a 2016 census population of 517,887.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.northdeltareporter.com/news/surreys-vaisakhi-parade-biggest-ever/|title=Surrey's Vaisakhi parade biggest ever|newspaper=North Delta Reporter|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> Starting at the Gurdwara Dashmesh Darbar Temple (12885 85th Avenue in Surrey), the parade features a variety of floats, community groups, free food, live music and dancers and performers, and travels along 124th Street, turns left onto 75th Avenue, continues on 76th Avenue, onto 128th Street, then back to the Temple.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.surreyvaisakhiparade.com/files/parade-map.php|title=Surrey Vaisakhi Parade Map|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> [[Kelowna]]'s annual Vaisakhi parade is held a week after Surrey's parade each year and begins and ends at the Sikh Temple on Rutland Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.castanet.net/edition/news-story-224630-1-.htm#224630|title=Vaisakhi Parade Saturday|newspaper=Castanet|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref> [[Greater Victoria|Victoria]]'s all-day Vaisakhi celebration features a parade that begins and ends at Gurdwara Singh Sabha, 470 Cecelia Road. The 2018 celebrations on 29 April would be the first held in Victoria in over 100 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/vaisakhi-victoria-parade-1.4635163|title=After 100 years, Vaisakhi returns to Victoria|newspaper=CBC|accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Alberta|Province of Alberta]], the [[Edmonton]] Vaisakhi parade is held in May and travels between the Gurdwara Singh Sabha (4504 Millwoods Road S) & Gurdwara Millwoods (2606 Millwoods Road E) temples.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vaisakhiparade.com|title=Vaisakhi 2018|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Nova Scotia|Province of Nova Scotia]], the [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]]-based Maritime Sikh Society holds Vaisakhi celebrations in April featuring [[Sikh music|Shabad Kirtan]] performed by professional ragis (musicians).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://maritimesikhsociety.com/|title=Maritime Sikh Society \u2013 About Us|accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Ontario|Province of Ontario]], the [[Toronto]] Vaisakhi Parade is held in April, starting at the Canadian National Exhibition grounds and traveling east to Toronto City Hall, finishing almost three hours later. Following the parade, dignitaries address the gathering until late afternoon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.toronto.com/events/khalsa-day-parade/|title=Khalsa Day Parade Celebrate the founding of the Sikh community. at Better Living Centre|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> In the city of [[Malton, Mississauga|Malton]], a three-hour Nagar Kirtan parade winds from Morning Star, Goreway, Derry Rd, & Airport Rd to Malton Gurdwara Sahib. In the city of [[Brampton]], the Gurudwara Sikh Sangat temple and Gobind Sarvar Gurmat School hold Vaisakhi cultural events such as yoga, pagh (turban) tying, storytelling, and food fairs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gobindsarvarbrampton.com/school/yolo-event/vaisakhi-cultural-food-fair/|title=Vaisakhi Cultural Food Fair|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Saskatchewan|Province of Saskatchewan]], the [[Saskatoon]] Vaisakhi parade is held in May, starting and ending at the Gurudwara Sahib Temple at 331 Lowe Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatoon/sikh-parade-saskatoon-crowd-1.4134571|title=1st-ever Saskatoon Sikh Parade was so busy it spurred a traffic advisory|accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\nThe [[United Kingdom]] has a large Sikh community originating from the Indian sub-continent, [[East Africa]]<ref>S. K. Rait (2005) Sikh Women in England: Their Religious and Cultural Beliefs and Social Practices [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hRfkTq1ykSIC&dq=sikhs+in+england&source=gbs_navlinks_s]</ref> and [[Afghanistan]]. The largest concentrations of [[Sikhs]] in the UK are to be found in the West Midlands (especially [[Birmingham]] and [[Wolverhampton]]) and [[London]].<ref>Amarjeet Singh (2014) Indian Diaspora: Voices of Grandparents and Grandparenting [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vo_HBAAAQBAJ&dq=largest+sikh+community+in+england+birmingham&source=gbs_navlinks_s]</ref> The Southall [[Nagar Kirtan]] is held on a Sunday a week or two before Vaisakhi. The Birmingham [[Nagar Kirtan]] is held in late April in association with Birmingham City Council,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.birmingham.gov.uk/vaisakhi|title=Things to do \u2013 Birmingham City Council|first=Birmingham City|last=Council|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> and is an annual event attracting thousands of people which commences with two separate nagar kirtans setting off from [[gurdwara]]s in the city and culminating in the Vaisakhi [[Mela]] at Handsworth Park.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-birmingham-17805970|accessdate=10 May 2012|newspaper=BBC News|date=22 April 2012|title=Thousands join Sikh Vaisakhi celebrations in Birmingham}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\nAmongst Sikh populations in the [[United States]], there is usually a parade commemorating the Vaisakhi celebration. In [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nycsikhdayparade.com/|title=Annual NYC Sikh Day Parade|date=30 April 2012|publisher=www.nycsikhdayparade.com|accessdate=22 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322192021/http://www.nycsikhdayparade.com/|archivedate=22 March 2012}}</ref> people come out to do \"[[Selfless service|Seva]]\" (selfless service) such as giving out free food, and completing any other labor that needs to be done. In [[Los Angeles, California]], the local Sikh community consisting of many [[gurdwara]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gururamdasashram.org/baisakhi|title=Baisakhi \u2013 Guru Ram Das Ashram|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> holds a full day [[Kirtan]] (spiritual music) program followed by a parade.\n\n===Malaysia===\nThe Sikh community, a subgroup of the [[Malaysian Indian]] ethnic minority race, is an [[ethnoreligious]] minority in Malaysia, which is why Vaisakhi is not a public holiday. However, in line with the government's efforts to promote integration among the country's different ethnic and religious groups, the prime minister, [[Najib Razak]] has announced that beginning 2013, all government servants from the Sikh [[Malaysian Indian]] community will be given a day off on Vaisakhi Day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2012/5/8/nation/11249703&sec=nation|title=Sikh civil servants get Vaisakhi holiday|accessdate=15 February 2013|newspaper=The Star Online|date=8 May 2012}}</ref> Vaisakhi 'open houses' are also held across the country during the day of the festival, or the closest weekend to it.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n{{Punjabi fairs and festivals}}\n{{Punjab, India}}\n{{Sikhism}}\n{{HinduFestivals}}\n{{Hindudharma}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Sikh festivals]]\n[[Category:New Year in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:New Year in India]]\n[[Category:Religious festivals in India]]\n[[Category:Punjabi festivals]]\n[[Category:Festivals in Punjab, Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Religious festivals in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:April observances]]\n[[Category:Observances on non-Gregorian calendars]]<!--Please do not remove this category, this article needs to be sorted into a calendar category-->\n[[Category:Harvest festivals]]\n[[Category:Spring (season) events in Pakistan]]\n", "name_user": "TheEagleNebula", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed bad grammar in paragraph 3 and added information about the founder - \"...the start of the Khalsa. This was in 1699 that the Khalsa was created so this is the beginning of the Khalsa.\" - to - \"...in 1699 byGuru Gobind Singh.\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vaisakhi"}
{"title_page": "Colwyn Bay", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| country                     = Wales\n| welsh_name                  = Bae Colwyn\n| label_position              = bottom\n| constituency_welsh_assembly = [[Clwyd West (Assembly constituency)|Clwyd West]]\n| population                  = 34,284\n| population_ref              = ''(2011)''\n| coordinates                 = {{coord|53.29|-3.70|display=inline,title}}\n| official_name               = Colwyn Bay\n| community_wales             = Colwyn Bay\n| unitary_wales               = [[Conwy County Borough|Conwy]]\n| lieutenancy_wales           = [[Clwyd]]\n| constituency_westminster    = [[Clwyd West (UK Parliament constituency)|Clwyd West]]\n| post_town                   = COLWYN BAY\n| postcode_district           = LL28, LL29\n| postcode_area               = LL\n| dial_code                   = 01492\n| os_grid_reference           = SH865785\n| static_image_name           = Colwyn Bay - geograph.org.uk - 131878.jpg\n| static_image_caption        = Colwyn Bay\n}}\n\n'''Colwyn Bay''' ({{lang-cy|Bae Colwyn}}) is a [[town]], [[Community (Wales)|community]] and [[seaside resort]] in [[Conwy County Borough]] on the north coast of [[Wales]] overlooking the [[Irish Sea]]. Eight neighbouring communities are incorporated within its postal district. Established as its own separate parish in 1844 with just a small grouping of homes and farms where the community of [[Old Colwyn]] stands today, Colwyn Bay has expanded to become the second-largest community and business centre in the north of Wales as well as the [[list of urban areas in Wales by population|15th largest]] in the whole of Wales with the urban statistical area\u2014including Old Colwyn, [[Rhos-on-Sea]], and [[Mochdre, Conwy|Mochdre]] and [[Penrhyn Bay]]. having a population of 34,284 at the 2011 census  <ref>https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/reports/localarea?compare=W37000408</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:(Pier and Pavillion, Colwyn Bay, Wales) (LOC) (3751644619).jpg|thumb|\"Pier and Pavilion, Colwyn Bay, Wales\", ca. 1890 - 1900.]]\nThe western side of Colwyn Bay, [[Rhos-on-Sea]], includes a number of historic sites associated with St Trillo and [[Ednyfed Fychan]], the 13th century general and councillor to [[Llywelyn the Great]].\n\nThe name 'Colwyn' may be named after 'Collwyn ap Tangno' who was Lord of Eifionnydd, Ardudwy and part of the Ll\u0177n peninsula,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/ecco/004874860.0001.000/1:14.2?rgn=div2;view=fulltext|title=The history of the parishes of Whiteford, and Holywell:|website=quod.lib.umich.edu|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180512175344/https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/ecco/004874860.0001.000/1:14.2?rgn=div2;view=fulltext|archivedate=12 May 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> or the River Colwyn in Old Colwyn.\n\n== Government ==\n[[Bay of Colwyn Town Council]] is a statutory body, covering the [[community (Wales)|communities]] in the urban area. The mayor for 2019 to 2020 is Councillor Neil Bastow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.colwyn-tc.gov.uk/town-council/the-mayor-20142015/|title=The Mayor 2017/2018|website=www.colwyn-tc.gov.uk|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-27|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127202745/http://www.colwyn-tc.gov.uk/town-council/the-mayor-20142015/|archivedate=27 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe town is situated about halfway along the north coast of Wales, between the sea and the Pwllycrochan Woods on the towering hillside. Groes yn Eirias (Welsh:''Cross in Torch'') was once a separate hamlet centred on the Glyn farmhouse (c1640) but the area is now occupied by the Glyn estate and [[Eirias Park]].\n\n=== Climate ===\nAs with the rest of the [[British Isles]], Colwyn Bay experiences a [[maritime climate]] with cool summers and mild winters, and often high winds. The local climate is well known for the prevalence of [[Foehn wind]]s - where winds from the South pass over the nearby mountains and warm and dry on their descent, leading to far higher temperatures than otherwise might be expected; the area held the Welsh high temperature record for February at 18.7&nbsp;\u00b0C from 23 February 2012 to 24 February 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/climate-extremes/#?tab=climateExtremes|title=UK climate|first=Met|last=Office|website=www.metoffice.gov.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103004237/https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/climate-extremes/#?tab=climateExtremes|archivedate=3 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Colwyn Bay 36m asl, 1981-2010 \n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan record high C = 16.1\n|Feb record high C = 18.7\n|Mar record high C = 21.4\n|Apr record high C = 24.8\n|May record high C = 28.1\n|Jun record high C = 30.3\n|Jul record high C = 33.0\n|Aug record high C = 32.4\n|Sep record high C = 28.3\n|Oct record high C = 27.2\n|Nov record high C = 18.3\n|Dec record high C = 16.4\n|year record high C = 33.0\n|Jan high C = 8.5\n|Feb high C = 8.4\n|Mar high C = 10.3\n|Apr high C = 12.1\n|May high C = 15.2\n|Jun high C = 17.6\n|Jul high C = 19.6\n|Aug high C = 19.4\n|Sep high C = 17.4\n|Oct high C = 14.3\n|Nov high C = 11.1\n|Dec high C = 8.9\n|year high C = 13.6\n|Jan low C = 2.8\n|Feb low C = 2.7\n|Mar low C = 4.1\n|Apr low C = 5.3\n|May low C = 7.7\n|Jun low C = 10.4\n|Jul low C = 12.5\n|Aug low C = 12.5\n|Sep low C = 10.7\n|Oct low C = 8.1\n|Nov low C = 5.7\n|Dec low C = 3.2\n|year low C = 7.2\n|Jan record low C = -9.9\n|Feb record low C = -7.2\n|Mar record low C = -9.3\n|Apr record low C = -4.2\n|May record low C = -1.7\n|Jun record low C = 2.4\n|Jul record low C = 5.7\n|Aug record low C = 4.0\n|Sep record low C = 0.6\n|Oct record low C = -3.8\n|Nov record low C = -7.3\n|Dec record low C = -10.4\n|year record low C = -10.4\n|Jan precipitation mm = 74.7\n|Feb precipitation mm = 53.0\n|Mar precipitation mm = 57.5\n|Apr precipitation mm = 50.7\n|May precipitation mm = 52.9\n|Jun precipitation mm = 56.1\n|Jul precipitation mm = 52.1\n|Aug precipitation mm = 64.6\n|Sep precipitation mm = 70.2\n|Oct precipitation mm = 96.8\n|Nov precipitation mm = 89.8\n|Dec precipitation mm = 90.2\n|year precipitation mm = 808.7\n|Jan sun = 56.2\n|Feb sun = 81.8\n|Mar sun = 115.0\n|Apr sun = 162.8\n|May sun = 209.0\n|Jun sun = 185.6\n|Jul sun = 189.6\n|Aug sun = 174.7\n|Sep sun = 135.2\n|Oct sun = 108.2\n|Nov sun = 59.9\n|Dec sun = 44.1\n|year sun = 1522.0\n|source 1 = [[Met Office]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19812010/sites/colwyn_bay.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121007095626/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19812010/sites/colwyn_bay.html | url-status = dead | archive-date = 7 October 2012 | title = Colwyn Bay 1981-2010 averages | accessdate = 24 August 2012 | publisher = [[Met Office]] }}</ref>\n|date=September 2011\n}}\n\n== Demography ==\nPrior to local government reorganisation on 1 April 1974 Colwyn Bay was a [[municipal borough]] with a population of around 25,000, but in 1974 this designation disappeared leaving five separate parishes, known as [[Community (Wales)|communities]] in Wales, of which the one bearing the name Colwyn Bay encompassed just the central part of the overall town and in the [[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 Census]] contained just 9,742 people, with the others as follows: [[Mochdre, Conwy|Mochdre]] (1,862), [[Rhos-on-Sea]] (7,110), [[Llansanffraid Glan Conwy|Glan Conwy]] (2,290), [[Old Colwyn]] (7,626) and [[Llysfaen]] (2,652). This gives a total figure for the six communities of 31,382, generally referred to as the population of Colwyn Bay, making it the [[List of urban areas in Wales by population|16th largest urban area in Wales]] and the second largest settlement in [[North Wales]]. Bringing 2011 figures into account that figure is now 33,549. The area is sometimes referred to by the name Bay of Colwyn.\n\nAccording to the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]], 17.9% of the population aged three and above noted that they could speak [[Welsh language|Welsh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.comisiynyddygymraeg.cymru/English/Policy,%20research%20and%20data/Census%20Data/Pages/2011CensusresultsbyCommunity.aspx|title=Comisiynydd y Gymraeg - 2011 Census results by Community|website=www.comisiynyddygymraeg.cymru|language=en-us|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914001036/http://www.comisiynyddygymraeg.cymru/English/Policy,%20research%20and%20data/Census%20Data/Pages/2011CensusresultsbyCommunity.aspx|archive-date=14 September 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=2018-01-27|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Census also noted that 29.9% of the population who were born in Wales could speak Welsh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/census/2011/lc2206wa|title=LC2206WA (Welsh language skills by country of birth by age) - Nomis - Official Labour Market Statistics|website=www.nomisweb.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-01-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027181055/https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/census/2011/lc2206wa|archivedate=27 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Economy ==\nThe town is dominated by the tourist trade, because of its famous beaches. Colwyn Bay is a [[Fairtrade Town]] as certified by the [[Fairtrade Foundation]] as part of the Fairtrade Towns scheme.\n\n== Culture ==\nColwyn Bay hosted the [[National Eisteddfod]] in 1910 and 1947. Also The Victoria Pier hosted many dances and shows during the 20th century and became popular with touring bands and artistes through the 1960s up until the final gig there in August 2008.<ref>http://link2wales.co.uk/2012/crudblog/dixieland-colwyn-bay-pier/</ref>\n\n== Community facilities ==\nThe town has parks and gardens and a number of natural amenities such as [[Eirias Park]]. Colwyn Bay has received a gold award 8 times in the Wales in Bloom competition. In 2009 and 2010 the town has been invited to enter Britain in Bloom and has been awarded silver gilt in both years. The [[Welsh Mountain Zoo]] is nearby.\n\nThe Porth Eirias Watersports Centre offers tuition in sailing, windsurfing and power boating as well as kayak and canoe hire. In 2013 it was nominated for ''[[Building Design]]'''s [[Carbuncle Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Britain's ugliest new buildings named|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/travelnews/10252696/Britains-ugliest-new-buildings-named.html|publisher=Daily Telegraph|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328061531/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/travelnews/10252696/Britains-ugliest-new-buildings-named.html|archivedate=28 March 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Landmarks ==\nThe [[Victoria Pier]] was closed to the public in 2009, when a dispute between [[Conwy County Borough Council]] and the pier's owner led to him being declared bankrupt. The fate of the pier was initially uncertain; the council hoped it would be \"substantially\" demolished for \"health and safety and visual reasons to be able to re-open that section of the beach\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/whats-happening-colwyn-bay-pier-11746721|title=Ask Daily Post: What is going on with Colwyn Bay Pier?|first=David|last=Powell|date=14 August 2016|website=dailypost.co.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161101041105/http://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/whats-happening-colwyn-bay-pier-11746721|archivedate=1 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \nIn January 2017, the lower end of the pier partially collapsed into the sea and Conwy Council subsequently announced plans to dismantle and store the pier, with a view of restoring it at a later date.<ref>{{cite web|title=Engineers assess collapsed Colwyn Bay Victoria Pier damage|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-38841948|website=BBC News|accessdate=2 February 2017|date=2 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204152314/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-38841948|archivedate=4 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Collapsed Colwyn Bay Pier to be dismantled for 'protection'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-38943101|website=BBC News|accessdate=12 February 2017|date=11 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211222737/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-38943101|archivedate=11 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The pier was finally demolished in May 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=End of the pier as demolition completed at Colwyn Bay|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-wales-44113372/end-of-the-pier-as-demolition-completed-at-colwyn-bay|website=BBC|accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Llety'r Dryw]] is a Grade II listed house in Abergele Road, built for the uncle of [[Anthony Eden, 1st Earl of Avon|Anthony Eden]] and now used as the training centre for [[North Wales Police]]. [[Llys Euryn]] is a medieval manor house on [[Bryn Euryn]], now in ruins.\n\n[[Colwyn Bay Community Hospital]] was completed in 1925.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://colwynbayheritage.org.uk/sidney-colwyn-foulkes/|title=Sidney Colwyn Foulkes|publisher=Colwyn Bay Heritage|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Transport ==\nThe town is served by [[Colwyn Bay railway station]] located in the town centre on the [[North Wales Coast Line]] with trains run by [[Transport for Wales Rail|Transport for Wales]] and [[Avanti West Coast]]. \nThe [[A55 road]] passes through the town, running parallel to the [[North Wales Coast Line]].\n\n===Tramline===\nThe [[Llandudno and Colwyn Bay Electric Railway]] operated an electric tramway service between  [[Llandudno]] and [[Rhos-on-Sea]] from 1907 and extended to Colwyn Bay in 1908. The service closed in 1956.<ref>''The Golden Age of Tramways''. Published by Taylor and Francis.</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nColwyn Bay has three [[secondary school]]s - one private and two state. [[Eirias High School]] is in [[Eirias Park]] and [[Ysgol Bryn Elian]] is in [[Old Colwyn]]. Ysgol Bryn Elian mainly serves Old Colwyn and Eirias High School mainly serves Colwyn Bay, Rhos on Sea and Penrhyn Bay. [[Rydal Penrhos|Rydal Penrhos School]] is a Methodist public school, which is on multiple sites in the town. The town's primary schools are Ysgol Nant y Groes, Ysgol Pen-y-Bryn, Ysgol T Gwynn Jones, Ysgol Hen Golwyn, and Saint Joseph's R.C. Primary and the Welsh-language [https://web.archive.org/web/20110726173438/http://www.bodalaw.ik.org/ Ysgol Bod Alaw].\n\n== Religious sites ==\nChurches in and around the town include the parish church [[St Paul's Church, Colwyn Bay|St Paul's Church]], [[St David's Welsh Church, Colwyn Bay|St David's Welsh Church]], [[St John the Baptist's Church, Old Colwyn|St John the Baptist's Church]], [[St. Joseph's Roman Catholic Church, Colwyn Bay|St Joseph's Roman Catholic Church]] and [[Christ Church, Bryn-y-Maen]] to the south of the town.\n\n== Sport ==\nThe local football team is [[Colwyn Bay F.C.]] who play in the [[Cymru North]], the second tier of Welsh football. The local cricket team is Colwyn Bay Cricket Club who play at [[Penrhyn Avenue]] and the rugby union team is [[Colwyn Bay RFC]]. As of 2012, the [[RGC 1404]] rugby team play at [[Eirias Stadium]] in Colwyn Bay as part of a development venture by the WRU.\n\nColwyn Bay Golf Club (now defunct) was founded in 1893. The club and course closed in 1959 and the land was used for a housing development.<ref>[http://www.golfsmissinglinks.co.uk/index.php/wales-64/1031-colwyn-bay-golf-club-upper-colwyn-conwy \u201cColwyn Bay Golf Club\u201d] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150327052047/http://www.golfsmissinglinks.co.uk/index.php/wales-64/1031-colwyn-bay-golf-club-upper-colwyn-conwy |date=27 March 2015 }}, \u201cGolf\u2019s Missing Links\u201d.</ref>\n\nThe Black Cat Cycling Club, founded in 2014, is based in Colwyn Bay <ref>{{cite web|title=The Black Cat Cycling Club Club profile|url=https://www.britishcycling.org.uk/club/profile/6881/the_black_cat_cycling_club|website=British Cycling|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808191131/https://www.britishcycling.org.uk/club/profile/6881/the_black_cat_cycling_club|archivedate=8 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with members made up of cyclists from the town and the surrounding area.\n\n== Notable people ==\n:''See [[:Category:People from Colwyn Bay]]''\n*[[William Davies (priest)|William Davies]], a Welsh Roman Catholic priest and martyr, beatified in 1987.<ref>[http://wbo.llgc.org.uk/en/s-DAVI-WIL-1593.html Davies, William (d. 1593)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091205111533/http://wbo.llgc.org.uk/en/s-DAVI-WIL-1593.html |date=5 December 2009 }} at [[National Library of Wales]] Dictionary of Welsh Biography</ref> It is believed but not confirmed that he was born at Groes yn Eirias in 1555.\n*[[Paula Yates]].\n*[[Carl Dale]], footballer for [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] and [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], as well as several non-league clubs.\n*[[James Bond]] actor [[Timothy Dalton]].\n*[[Richard Ellis (astronomer)|Richard Ellis]], the California-based astronomer, was born and went to school in Old Colwyn\n*Cricketer [[Tony Lewis]] who captained Glamorgan.\n*[[Member of Parliament|MP]] [[Alun Michael]].\n*Soap star [[William Roache]], ([[Ken Barlow (Coronation Street)|Ken Barlow]] in ''[[Coronation Street]]''), who attended Rydal Penrhos, a private school in the town.\n*[[Rachel Taylor (rugby player)|Rachel Taylor]] - Welsh [[Women's international rugby union|women's rugby international player]]<ref>[http://www.wru.co.uk/19814.php?player=54286&includeref=dynamic Squad Profiles: Wales Women] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011230158/http://www.wru.co.uk/19814.php?player=54286&includeref=dynamic |date=11 October 2016 }} at Welsh Rugby Union, 2012</ref> \n*[[Mickey Thomas (footballer)|Mickey Thomas]] who played for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], [[Shrewsbury Town]] and [[Wrexham F.C.|Wrexham]] lives in Mochdre.\n*[[Mike Walker (Welsh footballer)|Mike Walker]] ex professional footballer and former manager of [[Everton FC]] and [[Norwich City FC]]\n*[[Helen Willetts]], a [[BBC]] weather reporter.\n*[[Terry Jones]] actor, Comedian group of [[Monty Python]]\nbts\n\n== See also ==\n[[File:Clowyn bay 1.jpg|thumb|right|Colwyn Bay in the early 2000s.]] \n* [[Mochdre, Conwy|Mochdre]], a village to the west that was originally part of the Borough.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Colwyn Bay}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Colwyn Bay}}\n* [http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/place/1085 A Vision of Britain Through Time]\n* [http://www.colwyncouncil.co.uk/ Bay of Colwyn Town Council]\n* [http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/wales/conwy/colwyn+bay British Listed Buildings]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130115083135/http://www.clwydfhs.org.uk/eglwysi/colwynbay.htm Clwyd Churches]\n* [http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/wal/DEN/ColwynBay/index.html Genuki]\n* [https://www.geograph.org.uk/browse.php?p=340609 Geograph]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101128114540/http://www.colwyn-bay.com/ Guide to Colwyn Bay]\n* [http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadAreaSearch.do?a=7&c=llannefydd+community&d=16&r=1&i=1001&m=0&s=1366018543964&enc=1&areaSearchText=Colwyn+Bay&areaSearchType=16&extendedList=true&searchAreas= Office for National Statistics]\n\n{{Conwy}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Colwyn Bay| Colwyn Bay]]\n[[Category:Towns in Conwy County Borough]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| country                     = Wales\n| welsh_name                  = Bae Colwyn\n| label_position              = bottom\n| constituency_welsh_assembly = [[Clwyd West (Assembly constituency)|Clwyd West]]\n| population                  = 34,284\n| population_ref              = ''(2011)''\n| coordinates                 = {{coord|53.29|-3.70|display=inline,title}}\n| official_name               = Colwyn Bay\n| community_wales             = Colwyn Bay\n| unitary_wales               = [[Conwy County Borough|Conwy]]\n| lieutenancy_wales           = [[Clwyd]]\n| constituency_westminster    = [[Clwyd West (UK Parliament constituency)|Clwyd West]]\n| post_town                   = COLWYN BAY\n| postcode_district           = LL28, LL29\n| postcode_area               = LL\n| dial_code                   = 01492\n| os_grid_reference           = SH865785\n| static_image_name           = Colwyn Bay - geograph.org.uk - 131878.jpg\n| static_image_caption        = Colwyn Bay\n}}\n\n'''Colwyn Bay''' ({{lang-cy|Bae Colwyn}}) is a [[town]], [[Community (Wales)|community]] and [[seaside resort]] in [[Conwy County Borough]] on the north coast of [[Wales]] overlooking the [[Irish Sea]]. Eight neighbouring communities are incorporated within its postal district. Established as its own separate parish in 1844 with just a small grouping of homes and farms where the community of [[Old Colwyn]] stands today, Colwyn Bay has expanded to become the second-largest community and business centre in the north of Wales as well as the [[list of urban areas in Wales by population|15th largest]] in the whole of Wales with the urban statistical area\u2014including Old Colwyn, [[Rhos-on-Sea]], and [[Mochdre, Conwy|Mochdre]] and [[Penrhyn Bay]]. having a population of 34,284 at the 2011 census  <ref>https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/reports/localarea?compare=W37000408</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:(Pier and Pavillion, Colwyn Bay, Wales) (LOC) (3751644619).jpg|thumb|\"Pier and Pavilion, Colwyn Bay, Wales\", ca. 1890 - 1900.]]\nThe western side of Colwyn Bay, [[Rhos-on-Sea]], includes a number of historic sites associated with St Trillo and [[Ednyfed Fychan]], the 13th century general and councillor to [[Llywelyn the Great]].\n\nThe name 'Colwyn' may be named after 'Collwyn ap Tangno' who was Lord of Eifionnydd, Ardudwy and part of the Ll\u0177n peninsula,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/ecco/004874860.0001.000/1:14.2?rgn=div2;view=fulltext|title=The history of the parishes of Whiteford, and Holywell:|website=quod.lib.umich.edu|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180512175344/https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/ecco/004874860.0001.000/1:14.2?rgn=div2;view=fulltext|archivedate=12 May 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> or the River Colwyn in Old Colwyn.\n\n== Government ==\n[[Bay of Colwyn Town Council]] is a statutory body, covering the [[community (Wales)|communities]] in the urban area. The mayor for 2019 to 2020 is Councillor Neil Bastow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.colwyn-tc.gov.uk/town-council/the-mayor-20142015/|title=The Mayor 2017/2018|website=www.colwyn-tc.gov.uk|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-27|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127202745/http://www.colwyn-tc.gov.uk/town-council/the-mayor-20142015/|archivedate=27 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe town is situated about halfway along the north coast of Wales, between the sea and the Pwllycrochan Woods on the towering hillside. Groes yn Eirias (Welsh:''Cross in Torch'') was once a separate hamlet centred on the Glyn farmhouse (c1640) but the area is now occupied by the Glyn estate and [[Eirias Park]].\n\n=== Climate ===\nAs with the rest of the [[British Isles]], Colwyn Bay experiences a [[maritime climate]] with cool summers and mild winters, and often high winds. The local climate is well known for the prevalence of [[Foehn wind]]s - where winds from the South pass over the nearby mountains and warm and dry on their descent, leading to far higher temperatures than otherwise might be expected; the area held the Welsh high temperature record for February at 18.7&nbsp;\u00b0C from 23 February 2012 to 24 February 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/climate-extremes/#?tab=climateExtremes|title=UK climate|first=Met|last=Office|website=www.metoffice.gov.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103004237/https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/climate-extremes/#?tab=climateExtremes|archivedate=3 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Colwyn Bay 36m asl, 1981-2010 \n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan record high C = 16.1\n|Feb record high C = 18.7\n|Mar record high C = 21.4\n|Apr record high C = 24.8\n|May record high C = 28.1\n|Jun record high C = 30.3\n|Jul record high C = 33.0\n|Aug record high C = 32.4\n|Sep record high C = 28.3\n|Oct record high C = 27.2\n|Nov record high C = 18.3\n|Dec record high C = 16.4\n|year record high C = 33.0\n|Jan high C = 8.5\n|Feb high C = 8.4\n|Mar high C = 10.3\n|Apr high C = 12.1\n|May high C = 15.2\n|Jun high C = 17.6\n|Jul high C = 19.6\n|Aug high C = 19.4\n|Sep high C = 17.4\n|Oct high C = 14.3\n|Nov high C = 11.1\n|Dec high C = 8.9\n|year high C = 13.6\n|Jan low C = 2.8\n|Feb low C = 2.7\n|Mar low C = 4.1\n|Apr low C = 5.3\n|May low C = 7.7\n|Jun low C = 10.4\n|Jul low C = 12.5\n|Aug low C = 12.5\n|Sep low C = 10.7\n|Oct low C = 8.1\n|Nov low C = 5.7\n|Dec low C = 3.2\n|year low C = 7.2\n|Jan record low C = -9.9\n|Feb record low C = -7.2\n|Mar record low C = -9.3\n|Apr record low C = -4.2\n|May record low C = -1.7\n|Jun record low C = 2.4\n|Jul record low C = 5.7\n|Aug record low C = 4.0\n|Sep record low C = 0.6\n|Oct record low C = -3.8\n|Nov record low C = -7.3\n|Dec record low C = -10.4\n|year record low C = -10.4\n|Jan precipitation mm = 74.7\n|Feb precipitation mm = 53.0\n|Mar precipitation mm = 57.5\n|Apr precipitation mm = 50.7\n|May precipitation mm = 52.9\n|Jun precipitation mm = 56.1\n|Jul precipitation mm = 52.1\n|Aug precipitation mm = 64.6\n|Sep precipitation mm = 70.2\n|Oct precipitation mm = 96.8\n|Nov precipitation mm = 89.8\n|Dec precipitation mm = 90.2\n|year precipitation mm = 808.7\n|Jan sun = 56.2\n|Feb sun = 81.8\n|Mar sun = 115.0\n|Apr sun = 162.8\n|May sun = 209.0\n|Jun sun = 185.6\n|Jul sun = 189.6\n|Aug sun = 174.7\n|Sep sun = 135.2\n|Oct sun = 108.2\n|Nov sun = 59.9\n|Dec sun = 44.1\n|year sun = 1522.0\n|source 1 = [[Met Office]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19812010/sites/colwyn_bay.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121007095626/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19812010/sites/colwyn_bay.html | url-status = dead | archive-date = 7 October 2012 | title = Colwyn Bay 1981-2010 averages | accessdate = 24 August 2012 | publisher = [[Met Office]] }}</ref>\n|date=September 2011\n}}\n\n== Demography ==\nPrior to local government reorganisation on 1 April 1974 Colwyn Bay was a [[municipal borough]] with a population of around 25,000, but in 1974 this designation disappeared leaving five separate parishes, known as [[Community (Wales)|communities]] in Wales, of which the one bearing the name Colwyn Bay encompassed just the central part of the overall town and in the [[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 Census]] contained just 9,742 people, with the others as follows: [[Mochdre, Conwy|Mochdre]] (1,862), [[Rhos-on-Sea]] (7,110), [[Llansanffraid Glan Conwy|Glan Conwy]] (2,290), [[Old Colwyn]] (7,626) and [[Llysfaen]] (2,652). This gives a total figure for the six communities of 31,382, generally referred to as the population of Colwyn Bay, making it the [[List of urban areas in Wales by population|16th largest urban area in Wales]] and the second largest settlement in [[North Wales]]. Bringing 2011 figures into account that figure is now 33,549. The area is sometimes referred to by the name Bay of Colwyn.\n\nAccording to the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]], 17.9% of the population aged three and above noted that they could speak [[Welsh language|Welsh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.comisiynyddygymraeg.cymru/English/Policy,%20research%20and%20data/Census%20Data/Pages/2011CensusresultsbyCommunity.aspx|title=Comisiynydd y Gymraeg - 2011 Census results by Community|website=www.comisiynyddygymraeg.cymru|language=en-us|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914001036/http://www.comisiynyddygymraeg.cymru/English/Policy,%20research%20and%20data/Census%20Data/Pages/2011CensusresultsbyCommunity.aspx|archive-date=14 September 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=2018-01-27|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Census also noted that 29.9% of the population who were born in Wales could speak Welsh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/census/2011/lc2206wa|title=LC2206WA (Welsh language skills by country of birth by age) - Nomis - Official Labour Market Statistics|website=www.nomisweb.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-01-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027181055/https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/census/2011/lc2206wa|archivedate=27 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Economy ==\nThe town is dominated by the tourist trade, because of its famous beaches. Colwyn Bay is a [[Fairtrade Town]] as certified by the [[Fairtrade Foundation]] as part of the Fairtrade Towns scheme.\n\n== Culture ==\nColwyn Bay hosted the [[National Eisteddfod]] in 1910 and 1947. Also The Victoria Pier hosted many dances and shows during the 20th century and became popular with touring bands and artistes through the 1960s up until the final gig there in August 2008.<ref>http://link2wales.co.uk/2012/crudblog/dixieland-colwyn-bay-pier/</ref>\n\n== Community facilities ==\nThe town has parks and gardens and a number of natural amenities such as [[Eirias Park]]. Colwyn Bay has received a gold award 8 times in the Wales in Bloom competition. In 2009 and 2010 the town has been invited to enter Britain in Bloom and has been awarded silver gilt in both years. The [[Welsh Mountain Zoo]] is nearby.\n\nThe Porth Eirias Watersports Centre offers tuition in sailing, windsurfing and power boating as well as kayak and canoe hire. In 2013 it was nominated for ''[[Building Design]]'''s [[Carbuncle Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Britain's ugliest new buildings named|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/travelnews/10252696/Britains-ugliest-new-buildings-named.html|publisher=Daily Telegraph|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328061531/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/travelnews/10252696/Britains-ugliest-new-buildings-named.html|archivedate=28 March 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Landmarks ==\nThe [[Victoria Pier]] was closed to the public in 2009, when a dispute between [[Conwy County Borough Council]] and the pier's owner led to him being declared bankrupt. The fate of the pier was initially uncertain; the council hoped it would be \"substantially\" demolished for \"health and safety and visual reasons to be able to re-open that section of the beach\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/whats-happening-colwyn-bay-pier-11746721|title=Ask Daily Post: What is going on with Colwyn Bay Pier?|first=David|last=Powell|date=14 August 2016|website=dailypost.co.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161101041105/http://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/whats-happening-colwyn-bay-pier-11746721|archivedate=1 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \nIn January 2017, the lower end of the pier partially collapsed into the sea and Conwy Council subsequently announced plans to dismantle and store the pier, with a view of restoring it at a later date.<ref>{{cite web|title=Engineers assess collapsed Colwyn Bay Victoria Pier damage|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-38841948|website=BBC News|accessdate=2 February 2017|date=2 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204152314/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-38841948|archivedate=4 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Collapsed Colwyn Bay Pier to be dismantled for 'protection'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-38943101|website=BBC News|accessdate=12 February 2017|date=11 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211222737/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-38943101|archivedate=11 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The pier was finally demolished in May 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=End of the pier as demolition completed at Colwyn Bay|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-wales-44113372/end-of-the-pier-as-demolition-completed-at-colwyn-bay|website=BBC|accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Llety'r Dryw]] is a Grade II listed house in Abergele Road, built for the uncle of [[Anthony Eden, 1st Earl of Avon|Anthony Eden]] and now used as the training centre for [[North Wales Police]]. [[Llys Euryn]] is a medieval manor house on [[Bryn Euryn]], now in ruins.\n\n[[Colwyn Bay Community Hospital]] was completed in 1925.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://colwynbayheritage.org.uk/sidney-colwyn-foulkes/|title=Sidney Colwyn Foulkes|publisher=Colwyn Bay Heritage|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Transport ==\nThe town is served by [[Colwyn Bay railway station]] located in the town centre on the [[North Wales Coast Line]] with trains run by [[Transport for Wales Rail|Transport for Wales]] and [[Avanti West Coast]]. \nThe [[A55 road]] passes through the town, running parallel to the [[North Wales Coast Line]].\n\n===Tramline===\nThe [[Llandudno and Colwyn Bay Electric Railway]] operated an electric tramway service between  [[Llandudno]] and [[Rhos-on-Sea]] from 1907 and extended to Colwyn Bay in 1908. The service closed in 1956.<ref>''The Golden Age of Tramways''. Published by Taylor and Francis.</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nColwyn Bay has three [[secondary school]]s - one private and two state. [[Eirias High School]] is in [[Eirias Park]] and [[Ysgol Bryn Elian]] is in [[Old Colwyn]]. Ysgol Bryn Elian mainly serves Old Colwyn and Eirias High School mainly serves Colwyn Bay, Rhos on Sea and Penrhyn Bay. [[Rydal Penrhos|Rydal Penrhos School]] is a Methodist public school, which is on multiple sites in the town. The town's primary schools are Ysgol Nant y Groes, Ysgol Pen-y-Bryn, Ysgol T Gwynn Jones, Ysgol Hen Golwyn, and Saint Joseph's R.C. Primary and the Welsh-language [https://web.archive.org/web/20110726173438/http://www.bodalaw.ik.org/ Ysgol Bod Alaw].\n\n== Religious sites ==\nChurches in and around the town include the parish church [[St Paul's Church, Colwyn Bay|St Paul's Church]], [[St David's Welsh Church, Colwyn Bay|St David's Welsh Church]], [[St John the Baptist's Church, Old Colwyn|St John the Baptist's Church]], [[St. Joseph's Roman Catholic Church, Colwyn Bay|St Joseph's Roman Catholic Church]] and [[Christ Church, Bryn-y-Maen]] to the south of the town.\n\n== Sport ==\nThe local football team is [[Colwyn Bay F.C.]] who play in the [[Cymru North]], the second tier of Welsh football. The local cricket team is Colwyn Bay Cricket Club who play at [[Penrhyn Avenue]] and the rugby union team is [[Colwyn Bay RFC]]. As of 2012, the [[RGC 1404]] rugby team play at [[Eirias Stadium]] in Colwyn Bay as part of a development venture by the WRU.\n\nColwyn Bay Golf Club (now defunct) was founded in 1893. The club and course closed in 1959 and the land was used for a housing development.<ref>[http://www.golfsmissinglinks.co.uk/index.php/wales-64/1031-colwyn-bay-golf-club-upper-colwyn-conwy \u201cColwyn Bay Golf Club\u201d] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150327052047/http://www.golfsmissinglinks.co.uk/index.php/wales-64/1031-colwyn-bay-golf-club-upper-colwyn-conwy |date=27 March 2015 }}, \u201cGolf\u2019s Missing Links\u201d.</ref>\n\nThe Black Cat Cycling Club, founded in 2014, is based in Colwyn Bay <ref>{{cite web|title=The Black Cat Cycling Club Club profile|url=https://www.britishcycling.org.uk/club/profile/6881/the_black_cat_cycling_club|website=British Cycling|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808191131/https://www.britishcycling.org.uk/club/profile/6881/the_black_cat_cycling_club|archivedate=8 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with members made up of cyclists from the town and the surrounding area.\n\n== Notable people ==\n:''See [[:Category:People from Colwyn Bay]]''\n*[[William Davies (priest)|William Davies]], a Welsh Roman Catholic priest and martyr, beatified in 1987.<ref>[http://wbo.llgc.org.uk/en/s-DAVI-WIL-1593.html Davies, William (d. 1593)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091205111533/http://wbo.llgc.org.uk/en/s-DAVI-WIL-1593.html |date=5 December 2009 }} at [[National Library of Wales]] Dictionary of Welsh Biography</ref> It is believed but not confirmed that he was born at Groes yn Eirias in 1555.\n*[[Paula Yates]].\n*[[Carl Dale]], footballer for [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] and [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], as well as several non-league clubs.\n*[[James Bond]] actor [[Timothy Dalton]].\n*[[Richard Ellis (astronomer)|Richard Ellis]], the California-based astronomer, was born and went to school in Old Colwyn\n*Cricketer [[Tony Lewis]] who captained Glamorgan.\n*[[Member of Parliament|MP]] [[Alun Michael]].\n*Soap star [[William Roache]], ([[Ken Barlow (Coronation Street)|Ken Barlow]] in ''[[Coronation Street]]''), who attended Rydal Penrhos, a private school in the town.\n*[[Rachel Taylor (rugby player)|Rachel Taylor]] - Welsh [[Women's international rugby union|women's rugby international player]]<ref>[http://www.wru.co.uk/19814.php?player=54286&includeref=dynamic Squad Profiles: Wales Women] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011230158/http://www.wru.co.uk/19814.php?player=54286&includeref=dynamic |date=11 October 2016 }} at Welsh Rugby Union, 2012</ref> \n*[[Mickey Thomas (footballer)|Mickey Thomas]] who played for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], [[Shrewsbury Town]] and [[Wrexham F.C.|Wrexham]] lives in Mochdre.\n*[[Mike Walker (Welsh footballer)|Mike Walker]] ex professional footballer and former manager of [[Everton FC]] and [[Norwich City FC]]\n*[[Helen Willetts]], a [[BBC]] weather reporter.\n*[[Terry Jones]] actor, Comedian group of [[Monty Python]]\n\n== See also ==\n[[File:Clowyn bay 1.jpg|thumb|right|Colwyn Bay in the early 2000s.]] \n* [[Mochdre, Conwy|Mochdre]], a village to the west that was originally part of the Borough.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Colwyn Bay}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Colwyn Bay}}\n* [http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/place/1085 A Vision of Britain Through Time]\n* [http://www.colwyncouncil.co.uk/ Bay of Colwyn Town Council]\n* [http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/wales/conwy/colwyn+bay British Listed Buildings]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130115083135/http://www.clwydfhs.org.uk/eglwysi/colwynbay.htm Clwyd Churches]\n* [http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/wal/DEN/ColwynBay/index.html Genuki]\n* [https://www.geograph.org.uk/browse.php?p=340609 Geograph]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101128114540/http://www.colwyn-bay.com/ Guide to Colwyn Bay]\n* [http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadAreaSearch.do?a=7&c=llannefydd+community&d=16&r=1&i=1001&m=0&s=1366018543964&enc=1&areaSearchText=Colwyn+Bay&areaSearchType=16&extendedList=true&searchAreas= Office for National Statistics]\n\n{{Conwy}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Colwyn Bay| Colwyn Bay]]\n[[Category:Towns in Conwy County Borough]]\n", "name_user": "2.103.74.176", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eNotable people)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colwyn_Bay"}
{"title_page": "Aleph (Japanese cult)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Shinreikyo}}\n{{short description|Japanese cult and terrorist organization}}\n{{more citations needed|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox religion\n| name                = Aleph\n| native_name         = {{lang|ja|\u30a2\u30ec\u30d5}} \n| image               = Jp aunshinrikyo logo flag.gif\n| imagewidth          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Religious flag version of Aum Shinrikyo symbol\n| abbreviation        = \n| type                = [[Japanese new religions|Japanese new religious movement]]\n| main_classification = [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] [[new religious movement]]\n| orientation         = [[Dharmic]]\n| scripture           = \n| theology            = Western [[Millenarianism]] (formerly)\n| polity              = \n| governance          =\n| structure           = Yoga meetings\n| leader_title        = \n| leader_name         = \n| leader_title1       = \n| leader_name1        = \n| leader_title2       = \n| leader_name2        = \n| fellowships_type    =\n| fellowships         = \n| fellowships_type1   =\n| fellowships1        =\n| associations        = \n| area                = [[Japan]] \n| headquarters        = \n| founder             = [[Shoko Asahara]]\n| founded_date        = {{Start date and age|1984}}\n| founded_place       = [[Tokyo]], Japan\n| separated_from      = \n| parent              = \n| merger              = \n| absorbed            =\n| separations         = [[Hikari no Wa]] (2008)\n| merged_into         =\n| defunct             =\n| congregations_type  =\n| congregations       = \n| members             = Approximately 1,650 (2011)<ref name=npa/>\n| ministers_type      =\n| ministers           = \n| missionaries        =\n| temples             =\n| hospitals           = \n| nursing_homes       = \n| aid                 = \n| primary_schools     = \n| secondary_schools   = \n| tertiary            = \n| other_names         = {{nihongo|'''Aum Shinrikyo'''|\u30aa\u30a6\u30e0\u771f\u7406\u6559|Oumu Shinriky\u014d||lead=no}} (1984\u20132007)\n| publications        = \n| footnotes           = \n| website             = {{url|aleph.to}}\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Aleph'''|\u30a2\u30ec\u30d5|Arefu||lead=yes}}, formerly {{nihongo|'''Aum Shinrikyo'''|\u30aa\u30a6\u30e0\u771f\u7406\u6559|Oumu Shinriky\u014d||lead=no}}, is a Japanese [[doomsday cult]] founded by [[Shoko Asahara]] in 1984. It carried out the deadly [[Tokyo subway sarin attack]] in 1995 and was found to have been responsible for [[Matsumoto sarin attack|another smaller sarin attack]] the previous year.\n\nThe group has never confessed; they claim that those who carried out attacks did so secretly, without being known to other executives and ordinary believers. Asahara broadcast his singing, insisting on his innocence through a radio broadcast relayed from Russia and directed toward [[Japan]].<ref>{{cite web|website=FAS.org|publisher=Federation of American Scientists|author=Senate Government Affairs Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations|date=31 October 1995|url=https://fas.org/irp/congress/1995_rpt/aum/part06.htm|title=VI. Overseas Operations: Global Proliferation of Weapons of Mass Destruction: A Case Study on the Aum Shinrikyo|access-date=24 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 July 2018, after exhausting all appeals, Asahara and six followers were executed as a punishment for the 1995 attacks and other crimes,<ref>{{cite news|first=Austin|last=Ramzy|url=https://nyti.ms/2KSPKGb|title=Japan Executes Cult Leader Behind 1995 Sarin Gas Subway Attack|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc-executions\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/amp/world-asia-43395483|title=Tokyo Sarin attack: Aum Shinrikyo cult leaders executed|work=[[BBC News]]|date=6 July 2018|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref> and the remaining six on death row were executed on 26 July.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-44962581</ref> At 12:10 am, on New Year's Day 2019, at least nine people were injured (one seriously) when [[2019 Tokyo car attack|a car was deliberately driven into crowds]] celebrating the new year on [[Takeshita Street]] in Tokyo. Local police reported the arrest of Kazuhiro Kusakabe, the suspected driver, who allegedly admitted to intentionally ramming his vehicle into crowds to protest his opposition to the death penalty, specifically in retaliation for the execution of the aforementioned Aum cult members.\n\nAum Shinrikyo, which split into Aleph and [[Hikari no Wa]] in 2007, had already been [[List of designated terrorist groups|formally designated a terrorist organization]] by several countries, including [[Russia]],<ref name=rt/> [[Canada]],<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://laws.justice.gc.ca/eng/regulations/SI-2004-155/FullText.html?pedisable=true|title=Order Recommending that Each Entity Listed as of 23 July 2004, in the Regulations Establishing a List of Entities Remain a Listed Entity|via=justice.gc.ca|publisher=Government of Canada|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210083332/http://laws.justice.gc.ca/eng/regulations/SI-2004-155/FullText.html?pedisable=true|archivedate=10 December 2014|journal=[[Canada Gazette]]|volume=Part II, 138|number=24}}</ref> [[Kazakhstan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/para/etlo.htm|title= East Turkistan Liberation Organization (ETLO)|website=Globalsecurity.org|access-date=10 July 2018}}</ref> the [[United States]],<ref name=cfr.org/> as well as the [[European Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/policies/fight-against-terrorism/terrorist-list|title=EU terrorist list|website=europa.eu|publisher= The Council of the European Union}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Public Security Intelligence Agency]] considered Aleph and Hikari no Wa to be branches of a \"dangerous religion\"<ref name=\"NPA-whitepaper-2009\">[[National Police Agency (Japan)]] (2009), {{nihongo|[http://www.npa.go.jp/english/kokusai9/WHITE_PAPER_on_POLICE2009.htm \"The White Paper on Police 2009]|\u5e73\u621021\u5e74\u8b66\u5bdf\u767d\u66f8|Heisei Nij\u016bichi nen Keisatsu Hakusyo}}, GYOSEI Corporation,  pg. 160.<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed --></ref> and it announced in January 2015 that they would remain under surveillance for three more years.<ref name=jiji/> The Japanese government ended surveillance of Hikari no Wa in 2017, but continued to keep Aleph under watch.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2017/09/25/national/crime-legal/court-lets-aum-splinter-group-hikari-no-wa-off-surveillance-keeps-aleph-check|title=Court lets Aum splinter group Hikari no Wa off surveillance but keeps Aleph in check|date=25 September 2017|accessdate=12 July 2018|work=Japan Times}}</ref>\n\n==Doctrine==\nShinrikyo Aum is a [[Syncretism|syncretic]] belief system that draws upon Asahara's idiosyncratic interpretations of elements of early [[History of Buddhism in India|Indian Buddhism]] and [[Tibetan Buddhism]], as well as [[Hinduism]], taking [[Shiva]] as the main image of worship and incorporating [[Millenarianism|millennialist]] ideas from [[Christianity]], [[Yoga]], and the writings of [[Nostradamus]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Aptitude for Destruction: Case Studies of Organizational Learning in Five Terrorist Groups|url=https://archive.org/details/Aptitude_for_destruction_2|last1=Jackson|first1=Brian Anthony|first2=John C.|last2=Baker|year=2005|publisher=[[RAND Corporation]]|isbn=978-0-8330-3767-1|page=11}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Religious Violence in Contemporary Japan: The Case of Aum Shinriky\u014d|first=Ian|last=Reader|year=2000|publisher=[[University of Hawaii Press]]|isbn=978-0824823405|pages=[https://archive.org/details/religiousviolenc0000read/page/66 66\u201368]|url=https://archive.org/details/religiousviolenc0000read/page/66}}</ref> Its founder, [[Chizuo Matsumoto]], claimed that he sought to restore \"original Buddhism\" but employed Christian millenarian rhetoric.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.cnas.org/files/documents/publications/CNAS_AumShinrikyo_SecondEdition_English.pdf|title=Aum Shinrikyo Insights Into How Terrorists Develop Biological and Chemical Weapons|first1=Richard|last1=Danzig|first2=Marc|last2=Sageman|first3=Terrance|last3=Leighton|first4=Lloyd|last4=Hough|first5=Hidemi|last5=Yuki|first6=Rui|last6=Kotani|first7=Zachary M.|last7=Hosford|year=2000|publisher=[[Center for a New American Security]]|page=10|access-date=14 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316122438/http://www.cnas.org/files/documents/publications/CNAS_AumShinrikyo_SecondEdition_English.pdf|archive-date=16 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nIn 1992, Matsumoto, who had changed his name to [[Shoko Asahara]], published a foundational book, declaring himself to be \"[[Christ (title)|Christ]]\",<ref>{{cite book|title=Deadly Cults: The Crimes of True Believers|last=Snow|first=Robert L.|year=2003|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]]|isbn=978-0-275-98052-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/deadlycultscrime00snow/page/17 17]|url=https://archive.org/details/deadlycultscrime00snow/page/17}}</ref> Japan's only fully enlightened master, as well as identifying himself as the \"[[Lamb of God]]\".<ref>{{cite book|title=The Re-Enchantment of the West: Alternative Spiritualities, Sacralization, Popular Culture, and Occulture|last=Partridge|first=Christopher Hugh|year=2006|publisher=[[Continuum International Publishing Group]]|isbn=978-0-567-04133-3|page=300}}</ref>\n\nAsahara's purported mission was to take upon himself the [[sins]] of the world, and he claimed he could transfer spiritual power to his followers and ultimately take away their sins and bad deeds.<ref>{{cite book|title=The War on Terrorism and the Terror of God|last=Griffith|first=Lee|year=2004|publisher=[[William B. Eerdmans Publishing Company]]|isbn=978-0-8028-2860-6|page=164}}</ref> While some reject Aum Shinrikyo's claims of Buddhist characteristics and affiliations with [[Buddhism]], other scholars refer to it as an offshoot of [[Buddhism in Japan|Japanese Buddhism]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Terror in the Mind of God: The Global Rise of Religious Violence|first=Mark|last=Juergensmeyer|publisher=University of California Press|year=2003|page=103|isbn=0-520-24011-1}}</ref> and this was how the movement generally defined and saw itself.<ref>{{cite book|title=Poisonous Cocktail: Aum Shinrikyo's Path to Violence|first=Ian|last=Reader|publisher=NIAS Publications|year=1996|page=[https://archive.org/details/poisonouscocktai0000read/page/16 16]|isbn=87-87062-55-0|url=https://archive.org/details/poisonouscocktai0000read/page/16}}</ref>\n\nAsahara outlined a doomsday prophecy, which included a [[World War&nbsp;III|third world war]] instigated by the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite book|title=How Terrorism Ends: Understanding the Decline and Demise of Terrorist Campaigns|last=Cronin|first=Audrey Kurth|year=2009|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|isbn=978-0-691-13948-7|page=23}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Robert Jay Lifton]], an American psychiatrist and author:{{quote|[Asahara] described a final conflict culminating in a [[nuclear weapon|nuclear]] '[[Armageddon]]', borrowing the term from the Book of Revelation {{bibleverse-nb||Revelation|16:16}}\"<ref name=lifton>{{cite book|last=Lifton|first=Robert Jay|title= Destroying the World to Save It: Aum Shinrikyo, Apocalyptic Violence, and the New Global Terrorism|place=New York|publisher=Macmillan|year=2000}}</ref>}}\n\nHumanity would end, except for the elite few who joined Aum.<ref name=kaplan2/> Aum's mission was not only to spread the word of [[salvation]], but also to survive these [[End Times]]. Asahara predicted that Armageddon would occur in 1997.<ref name=kaplan2/> Kaplan notes that in his lectures, Shoko Asahara referred to the United States as \"[[The Beast (Revelation)|The Beast]]\" from the Book of Revelation, predicting it would eventually attack Japan.<ref name=kaplan2/>\n\nArthur Goldwag, author of a book on conspiracies and secret societies, characterizes Asahara as one who \"saw dark conspiracies everywhere promulgated by [[Jews]], [[Freemasonry|Freemasons]], the [[Dutch people|Dutch]], the [[British royal family]], and rival [[Religion in Japan|Japanese religions]]\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Cults, Conspiracies, and Secret Societies: The Straight Scoop on Freemasons, the Illuminati, Skull and Bones, Black Helicopters, the New World Order, and Many, Many More|last=Goldwag|first=Arthur|year=2009|publisher=[[Random House]]|isbn=978-0-307-39067-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/cultsconspiracie00gold/page/15 15]|url=https://archive.org/details/cultsconspiracie00gold/page/15}}</ref>\n\nIn the opinion of Daniel A. Metraux, Aum Shinrikyo justified its violence through its own unique interpretation of Buddhist ideas and doctrines, such as the Buddhist concepts of [[Three Ages of Buddhism|''Mapp\u014d'' and ''Sh\u014db\u014d'']]. Aum claimed that by bringing about the end of the world, they would restore ''Sh\u014db\u014d''.<ref>{{cite journal|last= Metraux|first=Daniel A.| journal= Asian Survey| title= Religious Terrorism in Japan: The Fatal Appeal of Aum Shinrikyo| volume= 35|number=12|date=December 1995|page=1153|doi=10.2307/2645835|jstor=2645835}}</ref> Furthermore, Lifton believes, Asahara \"interpreted the Tibetan Buddhist concept of ''[[phowa]]'' in order to claim that by killing someone contrary to the group's aims, they were preventing them from accumulating bad karma and thus saving them\".<ref name=lifton/>\n\nThe name {{nihongo|\"Aum Shinrikyo\"|\u30aa\u30a6\u30e0\u771f\u7406\u6559|Oumu Shinriky\u014d}}, usually rendered in English as \"Aum Supreme Truth\", derives from the [[Sanskrit]] syllable ''[[Om|Aum]]'', used to represent [[Universe|the universe]], followed by the [[Japanese language|Japanese]] ''Shinrikyo'' (meaning, roughly, \"Teaching of Truth\") written in [[kanji]]. (In Japanese, kanji are used to write both words that are originally Japanese as well as [[Sino-xenic]] words, but they are not usually used to transcribe those which are borrowed directly from \"exotic foreign languages\".)\n\nIn 2000, the organization changed its name to \"Aleph\" (a reference to the [[Aleph|first letter]] of the [[Phoenician alphabet|Phoenician]], [[Hebrew alphabet|Hebrew]], and [[Arabic alphabet]]s), and it also replaced its logo.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==History==\nThe movement was founded by [[Shoko Asahara]] in his one-bedroom apartment in [[Tokyo]]'s [[Shibuya]] ward in 1984, starting off as a [[yoga]] and [[meditation]] class<ref>{{cite book|title=Wolves Within the Fold: Religious Leadership and Abuses of Power|last=Shupe|first=Anson D.|year=1998|publisher=[[Rutgers University Press]]|isbn=978-0-8135-2489-4|page=34}}</ref> known as {{nihongo|''Oumu Shinsen no Kai''|\u30aa\u30a6\u30e0\u795e\u4ed9\u306e\u4f1a|\"Aum [[Xian (Taoism)|Immortal Mountain Wizard]] Association\"}} and steadily grew in the following years. It gained official status as a [[religious organization]] in 1989 and attracted a considerable number of graduates from Japan's elite universities, thus being dubbed a \"religion for the elite\".<ref name=controversial>{{cite book|title=Controversial New Religions|last=Lewis|first=James R.|author2=Jesper Aagaard Petersen|year=2005|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0-19-515683-6|page=162}}</ref>\n\n===Activities===\nAlthough Aum was considered controversial in Japan, it had yet to be associated with serious crimes. It was during this period that Asahara became obsessed with [[Bible prophecy|Biblical prophecies]]. Aum's public relations activities included publishing comics and animated cartoons that attempted to tie its religious ideas to popular [[anime]] and [[manga]] themes, including space missions, powerful weapons, world conspiracies, and quest for ultimate truth.<ref>{{cite book|title=Japanese Visual Culture: Explorations in the World of Manga and Anime|last=Macwilliams|first=Mary Wheeler|year=2008|publisher=[[M. E. Sharpe]]|isbn=978-0-7656-1602-9|page=[https://archive.org/details/japanesevisualcu0000unse/page/211 211]|url=https://archive.org/details/japanesevisualcu0000unse/page/211}}</ref> Aum published several magazines including ''[[Vajrayana]] Sacca'' and ''Enjoy Happiness'', adopting a somewhat missionary attitude.<ref name=controversial/>\n\n[[Isaac Asimov]]'s science fiction ''[[Foundation series|Foundation Trilogy]]'' was referenced \"depicting as it does an elite group of spiritually evolved scientists forced to go underground during an age of barbarism so as to prepare themselves for the moment...when they will emerge to rebuild civilization\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2002/aug/24/alqaida.sciencefictionfantasyandhorror|work=The Guardian|location=London, UK|title=What is the origin of the name al-Qaida?|date=24 August 2002|accessdate=25 April 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100405110855/http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2002/aug/24/alqaida.sciencefictionfantasyandhorror|archivedate=5 April 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> Lifton posited that Aum's publications used Christian and Buddhist ideas to impress what he considered to be the more shrewd and educated Japanese who were not attracted to boring, purely traditional [[sermon]]s.<ref name=lifton/>{{rp|258}}\n\nIn private, both Asahara and his top disciples reportedly continued their humble lifestyles, the only exception being the armored [[Mercedes-Benz]] gifted by a wealthy follower.\n\nAdvertising and recruitment activities, dubbed the \"Aum Salvation plan\", included claims of curing physical illnesses with health improvement techniques, realizing life goals by improving intelligence and positive thinking, and concentrating on what was important at the expense of leisure. This was to be accomplished by practising ancient teachings, accurately translated from original [[Pali]] [[sutra]]s (these three were referred to as \"threefold salvation\"). These efforts resulted in Aum becoming one of the fastest-growing religious groups in Japan's history.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\nDavid E. Kaplan and Andrew Marshall, in their 1996 book, ''The Cult at the End of the World: The Terrifying Story of the Aum Doomsday Cult, from the Subways of Tokyo to the Nuclear Arsenals of Russia'', claim that its practices remained secret. Initiation rituals, assert the authors of the book, often involved the use of [[hallucinogen]]s, such as [[Lysergic acid diethylamide|LSD]]. Religious practices often involved extremely ascetic practices claimed to be \"yoga\". These included everything from renunciants being hung upside down to being given [[Electroconvulsive therapy|shock therapy]].<ref name=kaplan2>{{cite book|last1=Kaplan|first1=David E.|first2=Andrew|last2=Marshall|year=1996|title=The Cult at the End of The World|place=London, UK|publisher=Hutchinson}}</ref>\n\n===Incidents before 1995===\nThe [[cult]] started attracting controversy in the late 1980s with accusations of deception of recruits, holding cult members against their will, forcing members to donate money and murdering a cult member who tried to leave in February 1989.<ref name=cultdeath>{{cite news|title=Aum member tells of 2 deaths at compound|work=The Daily Yomiuri|publisher=The Japan News|location=Tokyo|page=1|date=24 September 1995}}</ref><ref name=rearrest>{{cite news|title=Asahara rearrested in 1989 cultist murder|work=The Daily Shimbun|publisher=The Japan News|page=2|date=21 October 1995}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1989, the group's negotiations with [[Sakamoto family murder|Tsutsumi Sakamoto]], an anti-cult lawyer threatening a [[lawsuit]] against them which could potentially bankrupt the group, failed. In the same month, Sakamoto recorded an interview for a talk show on the Japanese TV station [[Tokyo Broadcasting System|TBS]]. The network then had the interview secretly shown to the group without notifying Sakamoto, intentionally breaking [[protection of sources]]. The group then pressured TBS to cancel the broadcast. The following month Sakamoto, his wife and his child went missing from their home in [[Yokohama]].\n\nThe police were unable to resolve the case at the time, although some of his colleagues publicly voiced their suspicions of the group. It was not until after the [[Tokyo subway sarin attack|1995 Tokyo attack]] that they were found to have been [[Sakamoto family murder|murdered]] and their bodies dumped by cult members.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Ian|last=Reader|title=Scholarship, Aum Shinriky\u00f4, and Academic Integrity|journal=Nova Religio: The Journal of Alternative and Emergent Religions|volume=3|number=2|date=April 2000|page=370|doi=10.1525/nr.2000.3.2.368}}</ref><ref name=death>{{cite news|title=Japan Sect's Role in Murder Case Emerges, Prompting Outcry|first=Nicholas D.|last=Kristof|date=14 March 1996|work=New York Times|page=A9}}</ref>\n\nKaplan and Marshall allege in their book that Aum was also connected with such activities as [[extortion]]. The group, authors report, \"commonly took patients into its hospitals and then forced them to pay exorbitant medical bills\".<ref name=kaplan2/>\n\nThe cult is known to have considered [[assassination]]s of several individuals critical of the cult, such as the heads of Buddhist sects [[Soka Gakkai]] and [[Happy Science|The Institute for Research in Human Happiness]]. After cartoonist [[Yoshinori Kobayashi]] began satirizing the cult, he was included on Aum's assassination list. An assassination attempt was made on Kobayashi in 1993.<ref name=david>{{cite news|last1=McNeill|first1=David|title=Nous ne sommes pas Charlie: Voices that mock authority in Japan muzzled|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/community/2015/01/26/issues/nous-ne-sommes-pas-charlie-voices-mock-authority-japan-muzzled|work=The Japan Times|date=26 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1993, cult members sprayed large amounts of liquid containing ''[[Bacillus anthracis]]'' spores from a cooling tower on the roof of Aum Shinrikyo's Tokyo headquarters. However, their plan to cause an [[anthrax]] epidemic failed. The attack resulted in a large number of complaints about bad odors but no infections.<ref name=\"Takahashi2004\">{{cite journal|last1=Takahashi|first1=Hiroshi|title=Bacillus anthracis Bioterrorism Incident, Kameido, Tokyo, 1993|journal=Emerging Infectious Diseases|date=2004|volume=10|issue=1|pages=117\u201320|doi=10.3201/eid1001.030238|pmid=15112666|pmc=3322761}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of 1993, the cult started secretly manufacturing the nerve agent [[sarin]] and, later, [[VX (nerve agent)|VX gas]]. They also attempted to manufacture 1,000 [[automatic rifles]] but only managed to make one.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/837000.stm|title=Japan cultists sentenced to death|date=17 July 2000|work=BBC News|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> Aum tested its sarin on sheep at [[Banjawarn Station]], a remote pastoral property in [[Western Australia]], killing 29 sheep. Both sarin and VX were then used in several assassinations (and attempts) over 1994\u201395.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nOn the night of 27 June 1994, the cult carried out a [[chemical weapon]]s attack against civilians when they released sarin in the central Japanese city of [[Matsumoto, Nagano|Matsumoto]], [[Nagano Prefecture|Nagano]]. With the help of a converted [[refrigerator truck]], members of the cult released a cloud of sarin which floated near the homes of judges who were overseeing a lawsuit concerning a real-estate dispute which was predicted to go against the cult. This [[Matsumoto sarin attack|Matsumoto incident]] killed eight and harmed 500 more.<ref>{{citation|first=Kyle B.|last=Olson|title=Aum Shinrikyo: Once and Future Threat?|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]], Research Planning, Inc.|place=Arlington, Virginia|pmid=10458955|doi=10.3201/eid0504.990409|volume=5|issue=4|pmc=2627754|year=1999|journal=Emerg Infect Dis|pages=513\u20136}}</ref> Police investigations focused only on an innocent local resident, [[Yoshiyuki K\u014dno (victim)|Yoshiyuki Kouno]], and failed to implicate the cult at the time. It was only after the [[Tokyo subway sarin attack|Tokyo subway attack]] that Aum Shinrikyo was discovered to be behind the Matsumoto sarin attack.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn December 1994 and January 1995, Masami Tsuchiya of Aum Shinrikyo synthesized 100 to 200&nbsp;grams of VX which was used to attack three persons. Two persons were injured and a 28-year-old man was killed. He is believed to be the first fully documented victim of VX.<ref>{{cite news|first=Pamela|last=Zurer|title=Japanese cult used VX to slay member|work=Chemical and Engineering News|year=1998|volume=76|number=35}}</ref>\n\nThe VX victim, whom [[Shoko Asahara]] had suspected was a spy, was attacked at 7:00&nbsp;a.m. on 12 December 1994, on the street in [[Osaka]] by [[Tomomitsu Niimi]] and another Aum member, who sprinkled the nerve agent on his neck. He chased them for about {{convert|100|yd|m}} before collapsing, dying 10 days later without coming out of a deep coma. Doctors in the hospital suspected at the time he had been poisoned with an [[organophosphate]] pesticide. But the cause of death was pinned down only after cult members arrested for the [[Tokyo subway sarin attack|subway attack in Tokyo]] in March 1995 confessed to the killing. Ethyl methylphosphonate, methylphosphonic acid, and diisopropyl-2-(methylthio) ethylamine were later found in the body of the victim. Unlike the cases for [[sarin]] ([[Matsumoto incident]] and Sarin gas attack on the Tokyo subway), VX was not used for mass murder.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn February 1995, several cult members kidnapped Kiyoshi Kariya, a 69-year-old brother of a member who had escaped, from a Tokyo street and took him to a compound in [[Kamikuishiki, Yamanashi|Kamikuishiki]] near [[Mount Fuji]], where he was killed. His corpse was destroyed in a [[microwave]]-powered incinerator and the remnants disposed of in [[Lake Kawaguchi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jan/01/aum-shinri-kyo-fugitive|title=Aum Shinrikyo cult fugitive turns himself in after 16 years|work=[[The Guardian]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=1 January 2012}}</ref> Before Kariya was abducted, he had been receiving threatening phone calls demanding to know the whereabouts of his sister, and he had left a note saying, \"If I disappear, I was abducted by Aum Shinrikyo\".{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nPolice made plans to simultaneously raid cult facilities across Japan in March 1995.<ref name=chrono>{{cite news| title=Chronology: Events involving Aum Shinrikyo|work=The Nikkei Weekly|publisher=The Nihon Keizai Shimbun, Incorporated|location=New York|page=Issues & People, page 3|date=22 May 1995}}</ref> Prosecutors alleged Asahara was tipped off about this and that he ordered the Tokyo subway attack to divert police.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n===Tokyo subway sarin attack and related incidents===\n{{main|Tokyo subway sarin attack}}\nOn the morning of 20 March 1995, Aum members released a [[binary chemical weapon]], most closely chemically similar to sarin, in a coordinated attack on five trains in the [[Tokyo subway]] system, killing 13 commuters, seriously injuring 54 and affecting 980 more. Some estimates claim as many as 6,000 people were injured by the sarin. It is difficult to obtain exact numbers since many victims are reluctant to come forward.<ref>Haruki Murakami, Alfred Birnbaum, Philip Gabriel, ''Underground'', Vintage International, 2001.<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed --></ref>\n\nProsecutors allege that Asahara was tipped off by an insider about planned police raids on cult facilities and ordered an attack in central Tokyo to divert police attention away from the group. The attack evidently backfired, and police conducted huge simultaneous raids on cult compounds across the country.<ref>[[Richard Danzig|Danzig, Richard]], [[Marc Sageman]], Terrance Leighton, Lloyd Hough, Hidemi Yuki, Rui Kotani and Zachary M. Hosford, \"[http://www.cnas.org/files/documents/publications/CNAS_AumShinrikyo_Danzig_1.pdf Aum Shinrikyo:  Insights Into How Terrorists Develop Biological and Chemical Weapons] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324102229/http://www.cnas.org/files/documents/publications/CNAS_AumShinrikyo_Danzig_1.pdf|date=24 March 2012}}\", ''[[Center for a New American Security]]'', July 2011; accessed 12 July 2018.</ref>\n\nOver the next week, the full scale of Aum's activities was revealed for the first time. At the cult's headquarters in [[Kamikuishiki, Yamanashi|Kamikuishiki]] on the foot of [[Mount Fuji]], police found explosives, chemical weapons, and a Russian [[Mil Mi-17]] military helicopter. While the finding of [[biological warfare]] agents such as [[anthrax]] and [[Ebola]] [[Cell cultures|cultures]] was reported, those claims now appear to have been widely exaggerated.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Smitheson|first1=Amy E.|title=Ataxia: The Chemical and Biological Terrorism Threat and the US Response|date=9 October 2000|page=77|url=http://www.stimson.org/images/uploads/research-pdfs/atxchapter3.pdf|accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref> There were stockpiles of chemicals that could be used for producing enough sarin to kill four million people.<ref name=CT1>{{cite book|last=Townshend|first=Charles|title=Terrorism: a very short introduction|year=2011|publisher=Oxford Univ. Press|location=Oxford [u.a.]|isbn=9780199603947|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pii3jii9qA4C&pg=PA116&dq=aum+kill+4+million#v=onepage&q=aum%20kill%204%20million|edition=2nd|accessdate=7 August 2012|page=116|quote=(... enough Sarin in Aum's possession to kill over 4 million people).}}</ref>\n\nPolice also found laboratories to manufacture drugs such as [[Lysergic acid diethylamide|LSD]], [[methamphetamine]], and a crude form of [[truth serum]], a safe containing millions of U.S. dollars in cash and gold, and cells, many still containing prisoners. During the raids, Aum issued statements claiming that the chemicals were for fertilizers. Over the next six weeks, over 150 cult members were arrested for a variety of offenses. The media was stationed outside Aum's Tokyo headquarters on Komazawa Dori in [[Aoyama, Tokyo|Aoyama]] for months after the attack and arrests waiting for action and to get images of the cult's other members. On March 30, 1995, Takaji Kunimatsu, chief of the [[National Police Agency (Japan)|National Police Agency]], was shot four times near his house in Tokyo and was seriously wounded. While many suspected Aum involvement in the shooting, the ''[[Sankei Shimbun]]'' reported that [[Hiroshi Nakamura (dissident)|Hiroshi Nakamura]] is suspected of the crime, but nobody has been charged.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nOn 23 April 1995, [[Hideo Murai]], the head of Aum's Ministry of Science, was stabbed to death outside the cult's Tokyo headquarters amidst a crowd of about 100 reporters, in front of cameras. The man responsible, a Korean member of [[Yamaguchi-gumi]], was arrested and eventually convicted of the murder. His motive remains unknown. On the evening of 5 May, a burning paper bag was discovered in a toilet in Tokyo's busy [[Shinjuku station]]. Upon examination it was revealed that it was a [[hydrogen cyanide]] device which, had it not been extinguished in time, would have released enough gas into the ventilation system to potentially kill 10,000 commuters.<ref name=chrono/> On July 4, several undetonated cyanide devices were found at other locations in the Tokyo subway.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/425960/HERES-A-CHRONOLOGY-OF-POISON-GAS-ATTACKS-IN-JAPAN.html|title=Here's a chronology of poison gas attacks in Japan|work=[[Deseret News]]| date= July 5, 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1995/07/04/Four-injured-by-Tokyo-station-gas-fumes/1840804830400|title= Four injured by Tokyo station gas fumes|publisher=United Press International|date=4 July 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Tucker|first1=Jonathan B.|title=Toxic Terror: Assessing Terrorist Use of Chemical and Biological Weapons|date=February 2000|page=219|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MrPyPP7gkHYC|via=Google Books|accessdate=29 September 2017|isbn=9780262700719}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time, numerous cult members were arrested for various offenses, but arrests of the most senior members on the charge of the subway gassing had not yet taken place. In June, an individual unrelated to Aum had launched a copycat attack by hijacking [[All Nippon Airways Flight 857]], a Boeing 747 bound for Hakodate from Tokyo. The hijacker claimed to be an Aum member in possession of sarin and plastic explosives, but these claims were ultimately found to be false.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nAsahara was finally found hiding within a wall of a cult building known as \"The 6th Satian\" in the Kamikuishiki complex on 16 May and was arrested.<ref name=chrono/> On the same day, the cult mailed a parcel bomb to the office of [[Yukio Aoshima]], the governor of Tokyo, blowing off the fingers of his secretary's hand. Asahara was initially charged with 23 counts of murder and 16 other offenses. The trial, dubbed \"the trial of the century\" by the press, ruled Asahara guilty of masterminding the attack and [[Capital punishment in Japan|sentenced him to death]]. The indictment was appealed unsuccessfully. A number of senior members accused of participation, such as Masami Tsuchiya, also received death sentences.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nThe reasons why a small circle of mostly senior Aum members committed atrocities and the extent of personal involvement by Asahara remain unclear, although several theories have attempted to explain these events. In response to the prosecution's charge that Asahara ordered the subway attacks to distract authorities, the defense maintained that Asahara was not aware of events, pointing to his deteriorating health. Shortly after his arrest, Asahara abandoned his post as the organization's leader, and since then has maintained silence, refusing to communicate even with lawyers and family members.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n===After 1995===\n[[File:Anti-Aum Shinrikyo protest.JPG|thumb|300px|An anti-Aum Shinrikyo protest in Japan, 2009.]]\nOn 21 June 1995, Asahara acknowledged that in January 1994 he ordered the killing of a sect member, Kotaro Ochida, a pharmacist at an Aum hospital. Ochida, who tried to escape from a sect compound, was held down and strangled by another Aum member who was allegedly told that he too would be killed if he did not strangle Ochida. On 10 October 1995, Aum Shinrikyo was ordered stripped of its official status as a \"religious [[Juridical person|legal entity]]\" and was declared bankrupt in early 1996. However, the group continues to operate under the constitutional guarantee of [[Freedom of religion in Japan|freedom of religion]], funded by a successful computer business and donations, and under strict [[surveillance]]. Attempts to ban the group altogether under the 1952 Subversive Activities Prevention Law were rejected by the Public Security Examination Commission in January 1997.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nThe group underwent a number of transformations in the aftermath of Asahara's arrest and trial. For a brief time, Asahara's two preteen sons officially replaced him as guru. It re-grouped under the new name \"Aleph\" in February 2000. It announced a change in doctrine: religious texts related to controversial [[Vajrayana]] Buddhist doctrines and the Bible were removed. The group apologized to the victims of the sarin gas attack and established a special compensation fund. Provocative publications and activities that alarmed society are no longer published.{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}}\n\n[[Fumihiro Joyu]], one of the few senior leaders of the group under Asahara who did not face serious charges, became official head of the organization in 1999. [[K\u014dki Ishii]], a legislator who formed an anti-Aum committee in the [[National Diet]] in 1999, was murdered in 2002.\n\nFor over 15 years, only three fugitives were being actively sought. At 11:50&nbsp;p.m. on 31 December 2011, Makoto Hirata surrendered himself to the police and was arrested on suspicion of being involved in the 1995 abduction of Kiyoshi Kariya, a non-member who had died during an Aum kidnapping and interrogation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Aum Shinrikyo cult fugitive surrenders to Japan police|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-16377178|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tokyo subway attack fugitive surrenders|date=1 January 2012|agency=AFP|publisher=News.com.au|url=http://www.news.com.au/world/tokyo-subway-attack-fugitive-surrenders/story-e6frfkyi-1226234294557|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref><ref>[[Kyodo News]], \"[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/nn20120102x1.html 16-year Aum fugitive mum on life on run]\", ''[[Japan Times]]'', January 2011, pg. 1.</ref> On 3 June 2012, police captured Naoko Kikuchi, the second fugitive, acting on a tip from local residents.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://japandailypress.com/additional-details-emerge-about-aum-cult-member-kikuchis-17-years-on-the-run-053368|title=Additional details emerge about Aum cult member Kikuchi's 17 years on the run|work=Japan Daily Press|date=5 June 2012|accessdate=18 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nActing on information from the capture of Kikuchi, including recent photographs showing a modified appearance, the last remaining fugitive, Katsuya Takahashi, was captured on June 15, 2012. He is said to have been the driver in the Tokyo gas attack and was caught in Tokyo, having been on the run for 17 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-18453996|title=Last Aum cult fugitive Katsuya Takahashi arrested in Japan|date=15 June 2012|publisher=BBC|accessdate=18 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn July 6, 2018, Asahara and six other Aum Shinrikyo members were executed by [[hanging]].<ref name=\"executionjapantimes\">{{cite news|url=https://japantoday.com/category/crime/Aum-founder-Asahara-mastermind-behind-1995-sarin-gas-attack-executed|title= Aum cult founder Asahara, 6 members hanged|date=6 July 2018|newspaper=Japan Today|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc-executions\"/> Japan's Justice Minister [[Y\u014dko Kamikawa]] stated that the crimes \"plunged people, not only in Japan but in other countries as well, into deadly fear and shook society to its core.\" [[Amnesty International]] criticized use of the death penalty in the case. While executions are rare in Japan, they have public support according to surveys.<ref name=\"execution2018\">{{cite news|last1=Lies|first1=Elaine|last2=Takenaka|first2=Kiyoshi|title=Japan hangs seven members of doomsday cult that attacked subway with sarin|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-crime-sarin/several-ex-members-of-japan-doomsday-cult-including-leader-executed-media-idUSKBN1JW009|accessdate=12 July 2018|work=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> There were 13 members on death row at the time:\n\n[[File:Anti-aum-flag-japan-2014-11-13.jpg|thumb|An anti-Aum Shinrikyo banner in 2014.]]\nAum Shinrikyo members executed on 6 July 2018:<ref name=\"executionjapantimes\"/>\n* [[Shoko Asahara]], leader of Aum Shinrikyo\n* Yoshihiro Inoue, Aum's \"head of intelligence\" and chief coordinator of the Tokyo subway attack\n* [[Tomomitsu Niimi]], the getaway driver for [[Ikuo Hayashi]], one of the perpetrators of the Tokyo subway attack\n* Tomomasa Nakagawa, a perpetrator of the [[Sakamoto family murder]]\n* [[Kiyohide Hayakawa]], Aum's \"construction minister\", convicted of strangling a young cult member in 1989 suspected of dissidence\n* [[Seiichi Endo]], the \"head scientist\" of Aum Shinrikyo\n* Masami Tsuchiya, Aum Shinrikyo's chief chemist and director of the sarin gas manufacturing\n\nThe six remaining Aum Shinrikyo members were executed on 26 July 2018.<ref>https://japantoday.com/category/crime/Japan-hangs-all-6-remaining-AUM-death-row-inmates</ref><ref name=\"sixremaining\">{{cite news|title=Profiles of top Aum Shinrikyo members, including six still on death row|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2018/07/06/national/crime-legal/profiles-top-aum-shinrikyo-members-including-six-still-death-row|accessdate=10 July 2018|work=The Japan Times Online|date=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n* Yasuo Hayashi, a perpetrator of the Tokyo subway attack\n* [[Kenichi Hirose]], a perpetrator of the Tokyo subway attack\n* Toru Toyoda, a perpetrator of the Tokyo subway attack\n* Masato Yokoyama, a perpetrator of the Tokyo subway attack\n* Kazuaki Okazaki, a perpetrator of the Sakamoto family murder\n* Satoro Hashimoto, a perpetrator of the Sakamoto family murder\n\nShoko Asahara's ashes will be collected by his youngest daughter according to his will. She urged her relatives and cult members to \"put an end to the Aum and stop hating society\". The ashes will be kept at the detention center for the time being for fears of reprisals from other elements of the cult.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://japantoday.com/category/crime/daughter-of-japan-sarin-attack-cult-guru-to-get-his-ashes|title=Ashes of executed Aum leader to be scattered at sea|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Current activities==\n[[file:Aleph-logo.png|thumb|right|250px|Aleph]]\n\nAccording to a June 2005 report by the [[National Police Agency (Japan)|National Police Agency]], Aleph had approximately 1,650 members, of whom 650 [[Intentional community|lived communally]] in compounds.<ref name=\"npa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.npa.go.jp/kouhousi/biki2/sec03/sec03_04.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725105241/http://www.npa.go.jp/kouhousi/biki2/sec03/sec03_04.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=25 July 2011|title=\u30aa\u30a6\u30e0\u771f\u7406\u6559\u5bfe\u7b56\uff08\u8b66\u5bdf\u5e81\uff09|date=25 July 2011|accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> The group operated 26 facilities in 17 [[Prefectures of Japan|prefectures]], and about 120 residential facilities. An article in the ''[[Mainichi Shimbun]]'' newspaper on 11 September 2002 showed that the Japanese public still mistrusts Aleph, and compounds are usually surrounded by protest banners from local residents.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n===Monitoring===\nIn January 2000, the group was placed under surveillance for a period of three years under an anti-Aum law, in which the group is required to submit a list of members and details of assets to the authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/getarticle.pl5|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050323004610/http://www.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/getarticle.pl5|title=Lower House panel approves bills to crack down on Aum|work=The Japan Times|date=17 November 1999|archivedate=23 March 2005|via=japantimes.co.jp|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2003, Japan's [[Public Security Intelligence Agency]] received permission to extend the surveillance for another three years, as they found evidence which suggested that the group still revered Asahara.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/getarticle.pl5|title=Surveillance of Aum to continue on grounds it still poses threat to public|work=Japan Times|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> According to the Religious News Blog report issued in April 2004, the authorities still considered the group \"a threat to society\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.t3.org/Aum.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060722040355/http://www.t3.org/Aum.html|title=A Chronology of Police Actions: Aum Shinri Kyo and the Japanese Police|date=12 January 1997|archivedate=22 July 2006|url-status=dead|website=t3.org|accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 September 2006, Shoko Asahara lost his final appeal against the [[Capital punishment in Japan|death penalty]]. The following day Japanese police raided the offices of Aleph in order to \"prevent any illegal activities by cult members in response to the confirmation of Asahara's death sentence\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/5351376.stm|work=BBC News|title=Japanese police raid cult offices|date=16 September 2006|accessdate=25 April 2010}}</ref> Thirteen cult members were eventually sentenced to death.<ref>Hongo, Jun, \"[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/nn20111122i1.html Last trial brings dark Aum era to end]\", ''[[Japan Times]]'', 22 November 2011, p. 3.</ref>\n\n===Split===\nOn 8 March 2007, [[Fumihiro Joyu]], former Aum Shinrikyo spokesman and head of Aum's [[Moscow]] operation, formally announced a long-expected split.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.religionnewsblog.com/17668/joyu-fumihori-group-leaves-aum-shinrikyo|title=Joyu Group Leaves AUM to Form New Organization|publisher=Religionnewsblog.com|date=8 March 2007|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> Joyu's group, called ''[[Hikari no Wa]]'' (\"The Circle of Light\"), claims to be committed to uniting science and religion and creating \"the new science of the human mind\", having previously aimed to move the group away from its criminal history and toward its spiritual roots.<ref name=cfr.org>{{cite news|last1=Fletcher|first1=Holly|title=CFR Backgrounder: Aum Shinrikyo (archived)|url=http://www.cfr.org/japan/aum-shinrikyo/p9238|work=Council on Foreign Relations|date=19 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, the Public Security Intelligence Agency stated that Aum had about 1,500 members.<ref>{{cite news| work=[[Metropolis (free magazine)|Metropolis]]|title=The Small Print: See Ya!|number=893|date=6\u201319 May 2011|page=4}}</ref> In July 2011 the cult reported its membership as 1,030. The group was reportedly active in trying to recruit new members via social media and proselytizing on college campuses.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[Jiji Press]]|title=Aum cult tops 1,000 followers|work=[[Japan Times]]|date=19 November 2011|page=2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hongo|first=Jun|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/nn20111121x2.html|title=Aum may be gone in name but guru still has following|work=Japan Times|date=22 November 2011|page=2}}</ref>\n\nJapan's Public Security Examination Commission announced in January 2015 that Aum Shinrikyo's two spinoffs would remain under surveillance for three more years starting 1 February 2015.<ref name=jiji>{{cite news|last1=Kyodo|first1=Jiji|title=Surveillance of Aum successor cults extended three more years|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/01/24/national/crime-legal/aum-successor-groups-remain-surveillance-three-years|work=Japan Times|date=24 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Admirers===\nIn 2014, ''[[The Japan Times]]'' alleged that \"good looks and commitment to a cause\", demonstrated by Aleph, \"inspire a new generation of admirers\". Dissatisfaction with society and low degrees of success in life make them \"identify with the cult\" and \"adore the cultists as if they were pop idols\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2014/03/20/national/social-issues/aum-cultists-inspire-a-new-generation-of-admirers|title=Aum cultists inspire a new generation of admirers|first=Tomohiro|last=Osaki|date=20 March 2014|accessdate=6 July 2018| work=Japan Times}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013 investigation and media coverage ===\nSometime after April 2013, the [[Public Security Intelligence Agency]] took a photograph inside of Aleph's facilities.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news-postseven.com/archives/20130808_204027.html|title=\u5143\u30aa\u30a6\u30e0\u306e\u9053\u5834\u3067\u898b\u3064\u304b\u3063\u305f\u516c\u5b89\u8abf\u67fb\u5e81\u9577\u5b98\u306e\u300c\u4e32\u523a\u3057\u5199\u771f\u300d|website=NEWS\u30dd\u30b9\u30c8\u30bb\u30d6\u30f3|language=ja|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref> In this photograph, a bundle of papers is pierced with a knife on an [[altar]]-like object.<ref name=\":0\" /> The papers included photographs of PSIA employees and directors, police officers, and lawyer Taro Takimoto, who helped followers leave Aum Shinrikyo.<ref name=\":0\" /> At least at this point in time, Aleph still displayed portraits of Shoko Asahara and demanded followers' dependence using videos of Asahara.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sankei.com/affairs/news/141108/afr1411080004-n1.html|title=\u516c\u5b89\u8abf\u67fb\u5b98\u306e\u5199\u771f\u4e32\u523a\u3057\u3001\u6559\u56e3\u540d\u96a0\u3057\u52e7\u8a98\u2026\u65e7\u30aa\u30a6\u30e0\u3001\u300c\u53cd\u793e\u4f1a\u6027\u300d\u306f\u7d99\u7d9a|last=INC|first=SANKEI DIGITAL|website=\u7523\u7d4c\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9|language=ja|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>\n\n===2016 Russian crackdown===\nOn 5 April 2016, the [[Investigative Committee of Russia]] announced it opened a criminal case against Aum Shinrikyo followers and that its investigators, along with [[Federal Security Service]] (FSB) forces, were conducting raids in [[Moscow]] and [[Saint Petersburg]] to find them and confiscate literature, religious items and electronic information.<ref>{{cite news|title=Searches underway in Moscow, St. Pete in order to expose Aum Shinrikyo followers|url=http://tass.ru/en/society/867313|newspaper=[[Russian News Agency TASS|TASS]]|location=Moscow|date=5 April 2016|access-date=5 April 2016}}</ref> On 20 September 2016, the Russian government banned Aum Shinrikyo in the country, declaring it a terrorist organization.<ref name=rt>[https://www.rt.com/politics/360006-russia-bans-murderous-japanese-sect Russia bans murderous Japanese sect Aum Shinrikyo as terrorist group], rt.com; accessed 12 July 2018.</ref>\n\n===2017 Aleph raids===\nIn November 2017, Japanese police raided five offices of Aleph in an investigation into the group's recruiting practices after a woman paid tens of thousands of yen for study sessions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2017/11/13/national/crime-legal/offices-aum-successor-adelph-raided-recruiting-practices|title=Offices of Aum successor Aleph raided over recruiting practices|date=13 November 2017|accessdate=6 July 2018|work=Japan Times}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 Tokyo car attack ===\nOn January 1, 2019, in [[Tokyo]], Aum sympathizer Kazuhiro Kusakabe told authorities he [[2019 Tokyo car attack|intentionally rammed into pedestrians]] crowded into narrow [[Takeshita Street]] in [[Harajuku]] district as a terrorist attack in \"retaliation for an execution\". It remains unclear whether he was referencing the 2018 executions of Aum Shinrikyo doomsday cult members directly or making a broader statement. The attack, on [[Japanese New Year|New Year's Day]], left eight injured. A ninth person was also directly injured by the driver.<ref name=\"japantoday1\">{{cite news|url=https://japantoday.com/category/crime/9-injured-as-man-rams-car-into-pedestrians-in-Harajuku-in-retaliation-for-execution|title=9 injured as man rams car into pedestrians in Harajuku in 'retaliation for execution'|newspaper=Japan Today|date=January 1, 2019|access-date=January 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Japan|Religion}}\n*[[List of dates predicted for apocalyptic events]]\n*[[List of people claimed to be Jesus]]\n*[[Yoshihiro Yasuda]], a lawyer who represented Shoko Asahara\n*[[Masaki Kito]], a lawyer who represents Aum victims\n*[[New religious movement]]\n*[[Guhyasam\u0101ja Tantra]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* [[Shoko Asahara]], ''Supreme Initiation: An Empirical Spiritual Science for the Supreme Truth'', 1988, AUM USA Inc., {{ISBN|0-945638-00-0}}. Highlights the main stages of Yogic and Buddhist practice, comparing Yoga-sutra system by Patanjali and the Eightfold Noble Path from Buddhist tradition.\n* [[Shoko Asahara]], ''Life and Death'', (Shizuoka: Aum, 1993). Focuses on the process of Kundalini-Yoga, one of the stages in Aum's practice.\n* [[Shoko Asahara]], ''Disaster Approaches the Land of the Rising Sun: Shoko Asahara's Apocalyptic Predictions'', (Shizuoka: Aum, 1995). A controversial book, later removed by Aum leadership, speaks about possible destruction of Japan.\n* Stefano Bonino, ''Il Caso Aum Shinrikyo: Societ\u00e0, Religione e Terrorismo nel Giappone Contemporaneo'', 2010, Edizioni Solfanelli, {{ISBN|978-88-89756-88-1}}. Preface by Erica Baffelli.\n* Ikuo Hayashi, ''Aum to Watakushi (Aum and I)'', Tokyo: Bungei Shunju, 1998. Book about personal experiences by former Aum member.\n* [[Robert Jay Lifton]], ''Destroying the World to Save It: Aum Shinrikyo, Apocalyptic Violence, and the New Global Terrorism'', Henry Holt, {{ISBN|0-8050-6511-3}}, LoC BP605.088.L54, 1999\n* [[Haruki Murakami]], ''[[Underground (stories)|Underground: The Tokyo Gas Attack and the Japanese Psyche]]'', Vintage, {{ISBN|0-375-72580-6}}, LoC BP605.O88.M8613, 2001. Interviews with victims.\n* ''Global Proliferation of Weapons of Mass Destruction: A Case Study on the Aum Shinrikyo'', [USA] Senate Government Affairs Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations, 31 October 1995. [https://fas.org/irp/congress/1995_rpt/aum/index.html online]\n* [[David E. Kaplan (author)|David E. Kaplan]], and [[Andrew Marshall (Asia journalist)|Andrew Marshall]], ''The Cult at the End of the World: The Terrifying Story of the Aum Doomsday Cult, from the Subways of Tokyo to the Nuclear Arsenals of Russia'', 1996, Random House, {{ISBN|0-517-70543-5}}. An account of the cult from its beginnings to the aftermaths of the Tokyo subway attack, including details of facilities, weapons and other information regarding Aum's followers, activities and property.\n* Ian Reader, ''Religious Violence in Contemporary Japan: The Case of Aum Shinrikyo'', 2000, Curzon Press\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisourcecat|Aum Shinrikyo}}\n{{Commons}}\n*{{official|url=http://English.aleph.to}}\n*[http://www.culteducation.com/asahara.html Shoko Asahara and the Aum Gas Attack]\n*{{in lang|en}} [http://www.moj.go.jp/ENGLISH/PSIA/psia01-04.html PSIA (Public Security Investigative Agency) report]\n\n{{Aum Shinrikyo}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aum Shinrikyo}}\n[[Category:Aum Shinrikyo| ]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Japanese new religions]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist in Asia]]\n[[Category:1984 establishments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Terrorism in Japan]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by the United States]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by Japan]]\n[[Category:Buddhist new religious movements]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by the European Union]]\n[[Category:Apocalypticism]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Shinreikyo}}\n{{short description|Japanese cult and terrorist organization}}\n{{more citations needed|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox religion\n| name                = Aleph\n| native_name         = {{lang|ja|\u30a2\u30ec\u30d5}} \n| image               = Jp aunshinrikyo logo flag.gif\n| imagewidth          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Religious flag version of Aum Shinrikyo symbol\n| abbreviation        = \n| type                = [[Japanese new religions|Japanese new religious movement]]\n| main_classification = [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] [[new religious movement]]\n| orientation         = [[Dharmic]]\n| scripture           = \n| theology            = Western [[Millenarianism]] (formerly)\n| polity              = \n| governance          =\n| structure           = Yoga meetings\n| leader_title        = \n| leader_name         = \n| leader_title1       = \n| leader_name1        = \n| leader_title2       = \n| leader_name2        = \n| fellowships_type    =\n| fellowships         = \n| fellowships_type1   =\n| fellowships1        =\n| associations        = \n| area                = [[Japan]] \n| headquarters        = \n| founder             = [[Shoko Asahara]]\n| founded_date        = {{Start date and age|1984}}\n| founded_place       = [[Tokyo]], Japan\n| separated_from      = \n| parent              = \n| merger              = \n| absorbed            =\n| separations         = [[Hikari no Wa]] (2008)\n| merged_into         =\n| defunct             =\n| congregations_type  =\n| congregations       = \n| members             = Approximately 1,650 (2011)<ref name=npa/>\n| ministers_type      =\n| ministers           = \n| missionaries        =\n| temples             =\n| hospitals           = \n| nursing_homes       = \n| aid                 = \n| primary_schools     = \n| secondary_schools   = \n| tertiary            = \n| other_names         = {{nihongo|'''Aum Shinrikyo'''|\u30aa\u30a6\u30e0\u771f\u7406\u6559|Oumu Shinriky\u014d||lead=no}} (1984\u20132007)\n| publications        = \n| footnotes           = \n| website             = {{url|aleph.to}}\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Aleph'''|\u30a2\u30ec\u30d5|Arefu||lead=yes}}, formerly {{nihongo|'''Aum Shinrikyo'''|\u30aa\u30a6\u30e0\u771f\u7406\u6559|Oumu Shinriky\u014d||lead=no}}, is a Japanese [[doomsday cult]] founded by [[Shoko Asahara]] in 1984. It carried out the deadly [[Tokyo subway sarin attack]] in 1995 and was found to have been responsible for [[Matsumoto sarin attack|another smaller sarin attack]] the previous year.\n\nThe group has never confessed; they claim that those who carried out attacks did so secretly, without being known to other executives and ordinary believers. Asahara broadcast his singing, insisting on his innocence through a radio broadcast relayed from Russia and directed toward [[Japan]].<ref>{{cite web|website=FAS.org|publisher=Federation of American Scientists|author=Senate Government Affairs Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations|date=31 October 1995|url=https://fas.org/irp/congress/1995_rpt/aum/part06.htm|title=VI. Overseas Operations: Global Proliferation of Weapons of Mass Destruction: A Case Study on the Aum Shinrikyo|access-date=24 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 July 2018, after exhausting all appeals, Asahara and six followers were executed as a punishment for the 1995 attacks and other crimes,<ref>{{cite news|first=Austin|last=Ramzy|url=https://nyti.ms/2KSPKGb|title=Japan Executes Cult Leader Behind 1995 Sarin Gas Subway Attack|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc-executions\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/amp/world-asia-43395483|title=Tokyo Sarin attack: Aum Shinrikyo cult leaders executed|work=[[BBC News]]|date=6 July 2018|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref> and the remaining six on death row were executed on 26 July.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-44962581</ref> At 12:10 am, on New Year's Day 2019, at least nine people were injured (one seriously) when [[2019 Tokyo car attack|a car was deliberately driven into crowds]] celebrating the new year on [[Takeshita Street]] in Tokyo. Local police reported the arrest of Kazuhiro Kusakabe, the suspected driver, who allegedly admitted to intentionally ramming his vehicle into crowds to protest his opposition to the death penalty, specifically in retaliation for the execution of the aforementioned Aum cult members.\n\nAum Shinrikyo, which split into Aleph and [[Hikari no Wa]] in 2007, had already been [[List of designated terrorist groups|formally designated a terrorist organization]] by several countries, including [[Russia]],<ref name=rt/> [[Canada]],<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://laws.justice.gc.ca/eng/regulations/SI-2004-155/FullText.html?pedisable=true|title=Order Recommending that Each Entity Listed as of 23 July 2004, in the Regulations Establishing a List of Entities Remain a Listed Entity|via=justice.gc.ca|publisher=Government of Canada|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210083332/http://laws.justice.gc.ca/eng/regulations/SI-2004-155/FullText.html?pedisable=true|archivedate=10 December 2014|journal=[[Canada Gazette]]|volume=Part II, 138|number=24}}</ref> [[Kazakhstan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/para/etlo.htm|title= East Turkistan Liberation Organization (ETLO)|website=Globalsecurity.org|access-date=10 July 2018}}</ref> the [[United States]],<ref name=cfr.org/> as well as the [[European Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/policies/fight-against-terrorism/terrorist-list|title=EU terrorist list|website=europa.eu|publisher= The Council of the European Union}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Public Security Intelligence Agency]] considered Aleph and Hikari no Wa to be branches of a \"dangerous religion\"<ref name=\"NPA-whitepaper-2009\">[[National Police Agency (Japan)]] (2009), {{nihongo|[http://www.npa.go.jp/english/kokusai9/WHITE_PAPER_on_POLICE2009.htm \"The White Paper on Police 2009]|\u5e73\u621021\u5e74\u8b66\u5bdf\u767d\u66f8|Heisei Nij\u016bichi nen Keisatsu Hakusyo}}, GYOSEI Corporation,  pg. 160.<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed --></ref> and it announced in January 2015 that they would remain under surveillance for three more years.<ref name=jiji/> The Japanese government ended surveillance of Hikari no Wa in 2017, but continued to keep Aleph under watch.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2017/09/25/national/crime-legal/court-lets-aum-splinter-group-hikari-no-wa-off-surveillance-keeps-aleph-check|title=Court lets Aum splinter group Hikari no Wa off surveillance but keeps Aleph in check|date=25 September 2017|accessdate=12 July 2018|work=Japan Times}}</ref>\n\n==Doctrine==\nShinrikyo Aum is a [[Syncretism|syncretic]] belief system that draws upon Asahara's idiosyncratic interpretations of elements of early [[History of Buddhism in India|Indian Buddhism]] and [[Tibetan Buddhism]], as well as [[Hinduism]], taking [[Shiva]] as the main image of worship and incorporating [[Millenarianism|millennialist]] ideas from [[Christianity]], [[Yoga]], and the writings of [[Nostradamus]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Aptitude for Destruction: Case Studies of Organizational Learning in Five Terrorist Groups|url=https://archive.org/details/Aptitude_for_destruction_2|last1=Jackson|first1=Brian Anthony|first2=John C.|last2=Baker|year=2005|publisher=[[RAND Corporation]]|isbn=978-0-8330-3767-1|page=11}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Religious Violence in Contemporary Japan: The Case of Aum Shinriky\u014d|first=Ian|last=Reader|year=2000|publisher=[[University of Hawaii Press]]|isbn=978-0824823405|pages=[https://archive.org/details/religiousviolenc0000read/page/66 66\u201368]|url=https://archive.org/details/religiousviolenc0000read/page/66}}</ref> Its founder, [[Chizuo Matsumoto]], claimed that he sought to restore \"original Buddhism\" but employed Christian millenarian rhetoric.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.cnas.org/files/documents/publications/CNAS_AumShinrikyo_SecondEdition_English.pdf|title=Aum Shinrikyo Insights Into How Terrorists Develop Biological and Chemical Weapons|first1=Richard|last1=Danzig|first2=Marc|last2=Sageman|first3=Terrance|last3=Leighton|first4=Lloyd|last4=Hough|first5=Hidemi|last5=Yuki|first6=Rui|last6=Kotani|first7=Zachary M.|last7=Hosford|year=2000|publisher=[[Center for a New American Security]]|page=10|access-date=14 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316122438/http://www.cnas.org/files/documents/publications/CNAS_AumShinrikyo_SecondEdition_English.pdf|archive-date=16 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nIn 1992, Matsumoto, who had changed his name to [[Shoko Asahara]], published a foundational book, declaring himself to be \"[[Christ (title)|Christ]]\",<ref>{{cite book|title=Deadly Cults: The Crimes of True Believers|last=Snow|first=Robert L.|year=2003|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]]|isbn=978-0-275-98052-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/deadlycultscrime00snow/page/17 17]|url=https://archive.org/details/deadlycultscrime00snow/page/17}}</ref> Japan's only fully enlightened master, as well as identifying himself as the \"[[Lamb of God]]\".<ref>{{cite book|title=The Re-Enchantment of the West: Alternative Spiritualities, Sacralization, Popular Culture, and Occulture|last=Partridge|first=Christopher Hugh|year=2006|publisher=[[Continuum International Publishing Group]]|isbn=978-0-567-04133-3|page=300}}</ref>\n\nAsahara's purported mission was to take upon himself the [[sins]] of the world, and he claimed he could transfer spiritual power to his followers and ultimately take away their sins and bad deeds.<ref>{{cite book|title=The War on Terrorism and the Terror of God|last=Griffith|first=Lee|year=2004|publisher=[[William B. Eerdmans Publishing Company]]|isbn=978-0-8028-2860-6|page=164}}</ref> While some reject Aum Shinrikyo's claims of Buddhist characteristics and affiliations with [[Buddhism]], other scholars refer to it as an offshoot of [[Buddhism in Japan|Japanese Buddhism]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Terror in the Mind of God: The Global Rise of Religious Violence|first=Mark|last=Juergensmeyer|publisher=University of California Press|year=2003|page=103|isbn=0-520-24011-1}}</ref> and this was how the movement generally defined and saw itself.<ref>{{cite book|title=Poisonous Cocktail: Aum Shinrikyo's Path to Violence|first=Ian|last=Reader|publisher=NIAS Publications|year=1996|page=[https://archive.org/details/poisonouscocktai0000read/page/16 16]|isbn=87-87062-55-0|url=https://archive.org/details/poisonouscocktai0000read/page/16}}</ref>\n\nAsahara outlined a doomsday prophecy, which included a [[World War&nbsp;III|third world war]] instigated by the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite book|title=How Terrorism Ends: Understanding the Decline and Demise of Terrorist Campaigns|last=Cronin|first=Audrey Kurth|year=2009|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|isbn=978-0-691-13948-7|page=23}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Robert Jay Lifton]], an American psychiatrist and author:{{quote|[Asahara] described a final conflict culminating in a [[nuclear weapon|nuclear]] '[[Armageddon]]', borrowing the term from the Book of Revelation {{bibleverse-nb||Revelation|16:16}}\"<ref name=lifton>{{cite book|last=Lifton|first=Robert Jay|title= Destroying the World to Save It: Aum Shinrikyo, Apocalyptic Violence, and the New Global Terrorism|place=New York|publisher=Macmillan|year=2000}}</ref>}}\n\nHumanity would end, except for the elite few who joined Aum.<ref name=kaplan2/> Aum's mission was not only to spread the word of [[salvation]], but also to survive these [[End Times]]. Asahara predicted that Armageddon would occur in 1997.<ref name=kaplan2/> Kaplan notes that in his lectures, Shoko Asahara referred to the United States as \"[[The Beast (Revelation)|The Beast]]\" from the Book of Revelation, predicting it would eventually attack Japan.<ref name=kaplan2/>\n\nArthur Goldwag, author of a book on conspiracies and secret societies, characterizes Asahara as one who \"saw dark conspiracies everywhere promulgated by [[Jews]], [[Freemasonry|Freemasons]], the [[Dutch people|Dutch]], the [[British royal family]], and rival [[Religion in Japan|Japanese religions]]\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Cults, Conspiracies, and Secret Societies: The Straight Scoop on Freemasons, the Illuminati, Skull and Bones, Black Helicopters, the New World Order, and Many, Many More|last=Goldwag|first=Arthur|year=2009|publisher=[[Random House]]|isbn=978-0-307-39067-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/cultsconspiracie00gold/page/15 15]|url=https://archive.org/details/cultsconspiracie00gold/page/15}}</ref>\n\nIn the opinion of Daniel A. Metraux, Aum Shinrikyo justified its violence through its own unique interpretation of Buddhist ideas and doctrines, such as the Buddhist concepts of [[Three Ages of Buddhism|''Mapp\u014d'' and ''Sh\u014db\u014d'']]. Aum claimed that by bringing about the end of the world, they would restore ''Sh\u014db\u014d''.<ref>{{cite journal|last= Metraux|first=Daniel A.| journal= Asian Survey| title= Religious Terrorism in Japan: The Fatal Appeal of Aum Shinrikyo| volume= 35|number=12|date=December 1995|page=1153|doi=10.2307/2645835|jstor=2645835}}</ref> Furthermore, Lifton believes, Asahara \"interpreted the Tibetan Buddhist concept of ''[[phowa]]'' in order to claim that by killing someone contrary to the group's aims, they were preventing them from accumulating bad karma and thus saving them\".<ref name=lifton/>\n\nThe name {{nihongo|\"Aum Shinrikyo\"|\u30aa\u30a6\u30e0\u771f\u7406\u6559|Oumu Shinriky\u014d}}, usually rendered in English as \"Aum Supreme Truth\", derives from the [[Sanskrit]] syllable ''[[Om|Aum]]'', used to represent [[Universe|the universe]], followed by the [[Japanese language|Japanese]] ''Shinrikyo'' (meaning, roughly, \"Teaching of Truth\") written in [[kanji]]. (In Japanese, kanji are used to write both words that are originally Japanese as well as [[Sino-xenic]] words, but they are not usually used to transcribe those which are borrowed directly from \"exotic foreign languages\".)\n\nIn 2000, the organization changed its name to \"Aleph\" (a reference to the [[Aleph|first letter]] of the [[Phoenician alphabet|Phoenician]], [[Hebrew alphabet|Hebrew]], and [[Arabic alphabet]]s), and it also replaced its logo.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==History==\nThe movement was founded by [[Shoko Asahara]] in his one-bedroom apartment in [[Tokyo]]'s [[Shibuya]] ward in 1984, starting off as a [[yoga]] and [[meditation]] class<ref>{{cite book|title=Wolves Within the Fold: Religious Leadership and Abuses of Power|last=Shupe|first=Anson D.|year=1998|publisher=[[Rutgers University Press]]|isbn=978-0-8135-2489-4|page=34}}</ref> known as {{nihongo|''Oumu Shinsen no Kai''|\u30aa\u30a6\u30e0\u795e\u4ed9\u306e\u4f1a|\"Aum [[Xian (Taoism)|Immortal Mountain Wizard]] Association\"}} and steadily grew in the following years. It gained official status as a [[religious organization]] in 1989 and attracted a considerable number of graduates from Japan's elite universities, thus being dubbed a \"religion for the elite\".<ref name=controversial>{{cite book|title=Controversial New Religions|last=Lewis|first=James R.|author2=Jesper Aagaard Petersen|year=2005|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0-19-515683-6|page=162}}</ref>\n\n===Activities===\nAlthough Aum was considered controversial in Japan, it had yet to be associated with serious crimes. It was during this period that Asahara became obsessed with [[Bible prophecy|Biblical prophecies]]. Aum's public relations activities included publishing comics and animated cartoons that attempted to tie its religious ideas to popular [[anime]] and [[manga]] themes, including space missions, powerful weapons, world conspiracies, and quest for ultimate truth.<ref>{{cite book|title=Japanese Visual Culture: Explorations in the World of Manga and Anime|last=Macwilliams|first=Mary Wheeler|year=2008|publisher=[[M. E. Sharpe]]|isbn=978-0-7656-1602-9|page=[https://archive.org/details/japanesevisualcu0000unse/page/211 211]|url=https://archive.org/details/japanesevisualcu0000unse/page/211}}</ref> Aum published several magazines including ''[[Vajrayana]] Sacca'' and ''Enjoy Happiness'', adopting a somewhat missionary attitude.<ref name=controversial/>\n\n[[Isaac Asimov]]'s science fiction ''[[Foundation series|Foundation Trilogy]]'' was referenced \"depicting as it does an elite group of spiritually evolved scientists forced to go underground during an age of barbarism so as to prepare themselves for the moment...when they will emerge to rebuild civilization\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2002/aug/24/alqaida.sciencefictionfantasyandhorror|work=The Guardian|location=London, UK|title=What is the origin of the name al-Qaida?|date=24 August 2002|accessdate=25 April 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100405110855/http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2002/aug/24/alqaida.sciencefictionfantasyandhorror|archivedate=5 April 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> Lifton posited that Aum's publications used Christian and Buddhist ideas to impress what he considered to be the more shrewd and educated Japanese who were not attracted to boring, purely traditional [[sermon]]s.<ref name=lifton/>{{rp|258}}\n\nIn private, both Asahara and his top disciples reportedly continued their humble lifestyles, the only exception being the armored [[Mercedes-Benz]] gifted by a wealthy follower.\n\nAdvertising and recruitment activities, dubbed the \"Aum Salvation plan\", included claims of curing physical illnesses with health improvement techniques, realizing life goals by improving intelligence and positive thinking, and concentrating on what was important at the expense of leisure. This was to be accomplished by practising ancient teachings, accurately translated from original [[Pali]] [[sutra]]s (these three were referred to as \"threefold salvation\"). These efforts resulted in Aum becoming one of the fastest-growing religious groups in Japan's history.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\nDavid E. Kaplan and Andrew Marshall, in their 1996 book, ''The Cult at the End of the World: The Terrifying Story of the Aum Doomsday Cult, from the Subways of Tokyo to the Nuclear Arsenals of Russia'', claim that its practices remained secret. Initiation rituals, assert the authors of the book, often involved the use of [[hallucinogen]]s, such as [[Lysergic acid diethylamide|LSD]]. Religious practices often involved extremely ascetic practices claimed to be \"yoga\". These included everything from renunciants being hung upside down to being given [[Electroconvulsive therapy|shock therapy]].<ref name=kaplan2>{{cite book|last1=Kaplan|first1=David E.|first2=Andrew|last2=Marshall|year=1996|title=The Cult at the End of The World|place=London, UK|publisher=Hutchinson}}</ref>\n\n===Incidents before 1995===\nThe [[cult]] started attracting controversy in the late 1980s with accusations of deception of recruits, holding cult members against their will, forcing members to donate money and murdering a cult member who tried to leave in February 1989.<ref name=cultdeath>{{cite news|title=Aum member tells of 2 deaths at compound|work=The Daily Yomiuri|publisher=The Japan News|location=Tokyo|page=1|date=24 September 1995}}</ref><ref name=rearrest>{{cite news|title=Asahara rearrested in 1989 cultist murder|work=The Daily Shimbun|publisher=The Japan News|page=2|date=21 October 1995}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1989, the group's negotiations with [[Sakamoto family murder|Tsutsumi Sakamoto]], an anti-cult lawyer threatening a [[lawsuit]] against them which could potentially bankrupt the group, failed. In the same month, Sakamoto recorded an interview for a talk show on the Japanese TV station [[Tokyo Broadcasting System|TBS]]. The network then had the interview secretly shown to the group without notifying Sakamoto, intentionally breaking [[protection of sources]]. The group then pressured TBS to cancel the broadcast. The following month Sakamoto, his wife and his child went missing from their home in [[Yokohama]].\n\nThe police were unable to resolve the case at the time, although some of his colleagues publicly voiced their suspicions of the group. It was not until after the [[Tokyo subway sarin attack|1995 Tokyo attack]] that they were found to have been [[Sakamoto family murder|murdered]] and their bodies dumped by cult members.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Ian|last=Reader|title=Scholarship, Aum Shinriky\u00f4, and Academic Integrity|journal=Nova Religio: The Journal of Alternative and Emergent Religions|volume=3|number=2|date=April 2000|page=370|doi=10.1525/nr.2000.3.2.368}}</ref><ref name=death>{{cite news|title=Japan Sect's Role in Murder Case Emerges, Prompting Outcry|first=Nicholas D.|last=Kristof|date=14 March 1996|work=New York Times|page=A9}}</ref>\n\nKaplan and Marshall allege in their book that Aum was also connected with such activities as [[extortion]]. The group, authors report, \"commonly took patients into its hospitals and then forced them to pay exorbitant medical bills\".<ref name=kaplan2/>\n\nThe cult is known to have considered [[assassination]]s of several individuals critical of the cult, such as the heads of Buddhist sects [[Soka Gakkai]] and [[Happy Science|The Institute for Research in Human Happiness]]. After cartoonist [[Yoshinori Kobayashi]] began satirizing the cult, he was included on Aum's assassination list. An assassination attempt was made on Kobayashi in 1993.<ref name=david>{{cite news|last1=McNeill|first1=David|title=Nous ne sommes pas Charlie: Voices that mock authority in Japan muzzled|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/community/2015/01/26/issues/nous-ne-sommes-pas-charlie-voices-mock-authority-japan-muzzled|work=The Japan Times|date=26 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1993, cult members sprayed large amounts of liquid containing ''[[Bacillus anthracis]]'' spores from a cooling tower on the roof of Aum Shinrikyo's Tokyo headquarters. However, their plan to cause an [[anthrax]] epidemic failed. The attack resulted in a large number of complaints about bad odors but no infections.<ref name=\"Takahashi2004\">{{cite journal|last1=Takahashi|first1=Hiroshi|title=Bacillus anthracis Bioterrorism Incident, Kameido, Tokyo, 1993|journal=Emerging Infectious Diseases|date=2004|volume=10|issue=1|pages=117\u201320|doi=10.3201/eid1001.030238|pmid=15112666|pmc=3322761}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of 1993, the cult started secretly manufacturing the nerve agent [[sarin]] and, later, [[VX (nerve agent)|VX gas]]. They also attempted to manufacture 1,000 [[automatic rifles]] but only managed to make one.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/837000.stm|title=Japan cultists sentenced to death|date=17 July 2000|work=BBC News|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> Aum tested its sarin on sheep at [[Banjawarn Station]], a remote pastoral property in [[Western Australia]], killing 29 sheep. Both sarin and VX were then used in several assassinations (and attempts) over 1994\u201395.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nOn the night of 27 June 1994, the cult carried out a [[chemical weapon]]s attack against civilians when they released sarin in the central Japanese city of [[Matsumoto, Nagano|Matsumoto]], [[Nagano Prefecture|Nagano]]. With the help of a converted [[refrigerator truck]], members of the cult released a cloud of sarin which floated near the homes of judges who were overseeing a lawsuit concerning a real-estate dispute which was predicted to go against the cult. This [[Matsumoto sarin attack|Matsumoto incident]] killed eight and harmed 500 more.<ref>{{citation|first=Kyle B.|last=Olson|title=Aum Shinrikyo: Once and Future Threat?|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]], Research Planning, Inc.|place=Arlington, Virginia|pmid=10458955}}</ref> Police investigations focused only on an innocent local resident, [[Yoshiyuki K\u014dno (victim)|Yoshiyuki Kouno]], and failed to implicate the cult at the time. It was only after the [[Tokyo subway sarin attack|Tokyo subway attack]] that Aum Shinrikyo was discovered to be behind the Matsumoto sarin attack.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn December 1994 and January 1995, Masami Tsuchiya of Aum Shinrikyo synthesized 100 to 200&nbsp;grams of VX which was used to attack three persons. Two persons were injured and a 28-year-old man was killed. He is believed to be the first fully documented victim of VX.<ref>{{cite news|first=Pamela|last=Zurer|title=Japanese cult used VX to slay member|work=Chemical and Engineering News|year=1998|volume=76|number=35}}</ref>\n\nThe VX victim, whom [[Shoko Asahara]] had suspected was a spy, was attacked at 7:00&nbsp;a.m. on 12 December 1994, on the street in [[Osaka]] by [[Tomomitsu Niimi]] and another Aum member, who sprinkled the nerve agent on his neck. He chased them for about {{convert|100|yd|m}} before collapsing, dying 10 days later without coming out of a deep coma. Doctors in the hospital suspected at the time he had been poisoned with an [[organophosphate]] pesticide. But the cause of death was pinned down only after cult members arrested for the [[Tokyo subway sarin attack|subway attack in Tokyo]] in March 1995 confessed to the killing. Ethyl methylphosphonate, methylphosphonic acid, and diisopropyl-2-(methylthio) ethylamine were later found in the body of the victim. Unlike the cases for [[sarin]] ([[Matsumoto incident]] and Sarin gas attack on the Tokyo subway), VX was not used for mass murder.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn February 1995, several cult members kidnapped Kiyoshi Kariya, a 69-year-old brother of a member who had escaped, from a Tokyo street and took him to a compound in [[Kamikuishiki, Yamanashi|Kamikuishiki]] near [[Mount Fuji]], where he was killed. His corpse was destroyed in a [[microwave]]-powered incinerator and the remnants disposed of in [[Lake Kawaguchi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jan/01/aum-shinri-kyo-fugitive|title=Aum Shinrikyo cult fugitive turns himself in after 16 years|work=[[The Guardian]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=1 January 2012}}</ref> Before Kariya was abducted, he had been receiving threatening phone calls demanding to know the whereabouts of his sister, and he had left a note saying, \"If I disappear, I was abducted by Aum Shinrikyo\".{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nPolice made plans to simultaneously raid cult facilities across Japan in March 1995.<ref name=chrono>{{cite news| title=Chronology: Events involving Aum Shinrikyo|work=The Nikkei Weekly|publisher=The Nihon Keizai Shimbun, Incorporated|location=New York|page=Issues & People, page 3|date=22 May 1995}}</ref> Prosecutors alleged Asahara was tipped off about this and that he ordered the Tokyo subway attack to divert police.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n===Tokyo subway sarin attack and related incidents===\n{{main|Tokyo subway sarin attack}}\nOn the morning of 20 March 1995, Aum members released a [[binary chemical weapon]], most closely chemically similar to sarin, in a coordinated attack on five trains in the [[Tokyo subway]] system, killing 13 commuters, seriously injuring 54 and affecting 980 more. Some estimates claim as many as 6,000 people were injured by the sarin. It is difficult to obtain exact numbers since many victims are reluctant to come forward.<ref>Haruki Murakami, Alfred Birnbaum, Philip Gabriel, ''Underground'', Vintage International, 2001.<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed --></ref>\n\nProsecutors allege that Asahara was tipped off by an insider about planned police raids on cult facilities and ordered an attack in central Tokyo to divert police attention away from the group. The attack evidently backfired, and police conducted huge simultaneous raids on cult compounds across the country.<ref>[[Richard Danzig|Danzig, Richard]], [[Marc Sageman]], Terrance Leighton, Lloyd Hough, Hidemi Yuki, Rui Kotani and Zachary M. Hosford, \"[http://www.cnas.org/files/documents/publications/CNAS_AumShinrikyo_Danzig_1.pdf Aum Shinrikyo:  Insights Into How Terrorists Develop Biological and Chemical Weapons] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324102229/http://www.cnas.org/files/documents/publications/CNAS_AumShinrikyo_Danzig_1.pdf|date=24 March 2012}}\", ''[[Center for a New American Security]]'', July 2011; accessed 12 July 2018.</ref>\n\nOver the next week, the full scale of Aum's activities was revealed for the first time. At the cult's headquarters in [[Kamikuishiki, Yamanashi|Kamikuishiki]] on the foot of [[Mount Fuji]], police found explosives, chemical weapons, and a Russian [[Mil Mi-17]] military helicopter. While the finding of [[biological warfare]] agents such as [[anthrax]] and [[Ebola]] [[Cell cultures|cultures]] was reported, those claims now appear to have been widely exaggerated.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Smitheson|first1=Amy E.|title=Ataxia: The Chemical and Biological Terrorism Threat and the US Response|date=9 October 2000|page=77|url=http://www.stimson.org/images/uploads/research-pdfs/atxchapter3.pdf|accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref> There were stockpiles of chemicals that could be used for producing enough sarin to kill four million people.<ref name=CT1>{{cite book|last=Townshend|first=Charles|title=Terrorism: a very short introduction|year=2011|publisher=Oxford Univ. Press|location=Oxford [u.a.]|isbn=9780199603947|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pii3jii9qA4C&pg=PA116&dq=aum+kill+4+million#v=onepage&q=aum%20kill%204%20million|edition=2nd|accessdate=7 August 2012|page=116|quote=(... enough Sarin in Aum's possession to kill over 4 million people).}}</ref>\n\nPolice also found laboratories to manufacture drugs such as [[Lysergic acid diethylamide|LSD]], [[methamphetamine]], and a crude form of [[truth serum]], a safe containing millions of U.S. dollars in cash and gold, and cells, many still containing prisoners. During the raids, Aum issued statements claiming that the chemicals were for fertilizers. Over the next six weeks, over 150 cult members were arrested for a variety of offenses. The media was stationed outside Aum's Tokyo headquarters on Komazawa Dori in [[Aoyama, Tokyo|Aoyama]] for months after the attack and arrests waiting for action and to get images of the cult's other members. On March 30, 1995, Takaji Kunimatsu, chief of the [[National Police Agency (Japan)|National Police Agency]], was shot four times near his house in Tokyo and was seriously wounded. While many suspected Aum involvement in the shooting, the ''[[Sankei Shimbun]]'' reported that [[Hiroshi Nakamura (dissident)|Hiroshi Nakamura]] is suspected of the crime, but nobody has been charged.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nOn 23 April 1995, [[Hideo Murai]], the head of Aum's Ministry of Science, was stabbed to death outside the cult's Tokyo headquarters amidst a crowd of about 100 reporters, in front of cameras. The man responsible, a Korean member of [[Yamaguchi-gumi]], was arrested and eventually convicted of the murder. His motive remains unknown. On the evening of 5 May, a burning paper bag was discovered in a toilet in Tokyo's busy [[Shinjuku station]]. Upon examination it was revealed that it was a [[hydrogen cyanide]] device which, had it not been extinguished in time, would have released enough gas into the ventilation system to potentially kill 10,000 commuters.<ref name=chrono/> On July 4, several undetonated cyanide devices were found at other locations in the Tokyo subway.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/425960/HERES-A-CHRONOLOGY-OF-POISON-GAS-ATTACKS-IN-JAPAN.html|title=Here's a chronology of poison gas attacks in Japan|work=[[Deseret News]]| date= July 5, 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1995/07/04/Four-injured-by-Tokyo-station-gas-fumes/1840804830400|title= Four injured by Tokyo station gas fumes|publisher=United Press International|date=4 July 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Tucker|first1=Jonathan B.|title=Toxic Terror: Assessing Terrorist Use of Chemical and Biological Weapons|date=February 2000|page=219|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MrPyPP7gkHYC|via=Google Books|accessdate=29 September 2017|isbn=9780262700719}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time, numerous cult members were arrested for various offenses, but arrests of the most senior members on the charge of the subway gassing had not yet taken place. In June, an individual unrelated to Aum had launched a copycat attack by hijacking [[All Nippon Airways Flight 857]], a Boeing 747 bound for Hakodate from Tokyo. The hijacker claimed to be an Aum member in possession of sarin and plastic explosives, but these claims were ultimately found to be false.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nAsahara was finally found hiding within a wall of a cult building known as \"The 6th Satian\" in the Kamikuishiki complex on 16 May and was arrested.<ref name=chrono/> On the same day, the cult mailed a parcel bomb to the office of [[Yukio Aoshima]], the governor of Tokyo, blowing off the fingers of his secretary's hand. Asahara was initially charged with 23 counts of murder and 16 other offenses. The trial, dubbed \"the trial of the century\" by the press, ruled Asahara guilty of masterminding the attack and [[Capital punishment in Japan|sentenced him to death]]. The indictment was appealed unsuccessfully. A number of senior members accused of participation, such as Masami Tsuchiya, also received death sentences.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nThe reasons why a small circle of mostly senior Aum members committed atrocities and the extent of personal involvement by Asahara remain unclear, although several theories have attempted to explain these events. In response to the prosecution's charge that Asahara ordered the subway attacks to distract authorities, the defense maintained that Asahara was not aware of events, pointing to his deteriorating health. Shortly after his arrest, Asahara abandoned his post as the organization's leader, and since then has maintained silence, refusing to communicate even with lawyers and family members.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n===After 1995===\n[[File:Anti-Aum Shinrikyo protest.JPG|thumb|300px|An anti-Aum Shinrikyo protest in Japan, 2009.]]\nOn 21 June 1995, Asahara acknowledged that in January 1994 he ordered the killing of a sect member, Kotaro Ochida, a pharmacist at an Aum hospital. Ochida, who tried to escape from a sect compound, was held down and strangled by another Aum member who was allegedly told that he too would be killed if he did not strangle Ochida. On 10 October 1995, Aum Shinrikyo was ordered stripped of its official status as a \"religious [[Juridical person|legal entity]]\" and was declared bankrupt in early 1996. However, the group continues to operate under the constitutional guarantee of [[Freedom of religion in Japan|freedom of religion]], funded by a successful computer business and donations, and under strict [[surveillance]]. Attempts to ban the group altogether under the 1952 Subversive Activities Prevention Law were rejected by the Public Security Examination Commission in January 1997.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nThe group underwent a number of transformations in the aftermath of Asahara's arrest and trial. For a brief time, Asahara's two preteen sons officially replaced him as guru. It re-grouped under the new name \"Aleph\" in February 2000. It announced a change in doctrine: religious texts related to controversial [[Vajrayana]] Buddhist doctrines and the Bible were removed. The group apologized to the victims of the sarin gas attack and established a special compensation fund. Provocative publications and activities that alarmed society are no longer published.{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}}\n\n[[Fumihiro Joyu]], one of the few senior leaders of the group under Asahara who did not face serious charges, became official head of the organization in 1999. [[K\u014dki Ishii]], a legislator who formed an anti-Aum committee in the [[National Diet]] in 1999, was murdered in 2002.\n\nFor over 15 years, only three fugitives were being actively sought. At 11:50&nbsp;p.m. on 31 December 2011, Makoto Hirata surrendered himself to the police and was arrested on suspicion of being involved in the 1995 abduction of Kiyoshi Kariya, a non-member who had died during an Aum kidnapping and interrogation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Aum Shinrikyo cult fugitive surrenders to Japan police|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-16377178|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tokyo subway attack fugitive surrenders|date=1 January 2012|agency=AFP|publisher=News.com.au|url=http://www.news.com.au/world/tokyo-subway-attack-fugitive-surrenders/story-e6frfkyi-1226234294557|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref><ref>[[Kyodo News]], \"[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/nn20120102x1.html 16-year Aum fugitive mum on life on run]\", ''[[Japan Times]]'', January 2011, pg. 1.</ref> On 3 June 2012, police captured Naoko Kikuchi, the second fugitive, acting on a tip from local residents.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://japandailypress.com/additional-details-emerge-about-aum-cult-member-kikuchis-17-years-on-the-run-053368|title=Additional details emerge about Aum cult member Kikuchi's 17 years on the run|work=Japan Daily Press|date=5 June 2012|accessdate=18 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nActing on information from the capture of Kikuchi, including recent photographs showing a modified appearance, the last remaining fugitive, Katsuya Takahashi, was captured on June 15, 2012. He is said to have been the driver in the Tokyo gas attack and was caught in Tokyo, having been on the run for 17 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-18453996|title=Last Aum cult fugitive Katsuya Takahashi arrested in Japan|date=15 June 2012|publisher=BBC|accessdate=18 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn July 6, 2018, Asahara and six other Aum Shinrikyo members were executed by [[hanging]].<ref name=\"executionjapantimes\">{{cite news|url=https://japantoday.com/category/crime/Aum-founder-Asahara-mastermind-behind-1995-sarin-gas-attack-executed|title= Aum cult founder Asahara, 6 members hanged|date=6 July 2018|newspaper=Japan Today|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc-executions\"/> Japan's Justice Minister [[Y\u014dko Kamikawa]] stated that the crimes \"plunged people, not only in Japan but in other countries as well, into deadly fear and shook society to its core.\" [[Amnesty International]] criticized use of the death penalty in the case. While executions are rare in Japan, they have public support according to surveys.<ref name=\"execution2018\">{{cite news|last1=Lies|first1=Elaine|last2=Takenaka|first2=Kiyoshi|title=Japan hangs seven members of doomsday cult that attacked subway with sarin|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-crime-sarin/several-ex-members-of-japan-doomsday-cult-including-leader-executed-media-idUSKBN1JW009|accessdate=12 July 2018|work=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> There were 13 members on death row at the time:\n\n[[File:Anti-aum-flag-japan-2014-11-13.jpg|thumb|An anti-Aum Shinrikyo banner in 2014.]]\nAum Shinrikyo members executed on 6 July 2018:<ref name=\"executionjapantimes\"/>\n* [[Shoko Asahara]], leader of Aum Shinrikyo\n* Yoshihiro Inoue, Aum's \"head of intelligence\" and chief coordinator of the Tokyo subway attack\n* [[Tomomitsu Niimi]], the getaway driver for [[Ikuo Hayashi]], one of the perpetrators of the Tokyo subway attack\n* Tomomasa Nakagawa, a perpetrator of the [[Sakamoto family murder]]\n* [[Kiyohide Hayakawa]], Aum's \"construction minister\", convicted of strangling a young cult member in 1989 suspected of dissidence\n* [[Seiichi Endo]], the \"head scientist\" of Aum Shinrikyo\n* Masami Tsuchiya, Aum Shinrikyo's chief chemist and director of the sarin gas manufacturing\n\nThe six remaining Aum Shinrikyo members were executed on 26 July 2018.<ref>https://japantoday.com/category/crime/Japan-hangs-all-6-remaining-AUM-death-row-inmates</ref><ref name=\"sixremaining\">{{cite news|title=Profiles of top Aum Shinrikyo members, including six still on death row|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2018/07/06/national/crime-legal/profiles-top-aum-shinrikyo-members-including-six-still-death-row|accessdate=10 July 2018|work=The Japan Times Online|date=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n* Yasuo Hayashi, a perpetrator of the Tokyo subway attack\n* [[Kenichi Hirose]], a perpetrator of the Tokyo subway attack\n* Toru Toyoda, a perpetrator of the Tokyo subway attack\n* Masato Yokoyama, a perpetrator of the Tokyo subway attack\n* Kazuaki Okazaki, a perpetrator of the Sakamoto family murder\n* Satoro Hashimoto, a perpetrator of the Sakamoto family murder\n\nShoko Asahara's ashes will be collected by his youngest daughter according to his will. She urged her relatives and cult members to \"put an end to the Aum and stop hating society\". The ashes will be kept at the detention center for the time being for fears of reprisals from other elements of the cult.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://japantoday.com/category/crime/daughter-of-japan-sarin-attack-cult-guru-to-get-his-ashes|title=Ashes of executed Aum leader to be scattered at sea|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Current activities==\n[[file:Aleph-logo.png|thumb|right|250px|Aleph]]\n\nAccording to a June 2005 report by the [[National Police Agency (Japan)|National Police Agency]], Aleph had approximately 1,650 members, of whom 650 [[Intentional community|lived communally]] in compounds.<ref name=\"npa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.npa.go.jp/kouhousi/biki2/sec03/sec03_04.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725105241/http://www.npa.go.jp/kouhousi/biki2/sec03/sec03_04.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=25 July 2011|title=\u30aa\u30a6\u30e0\u771f\u7406\u6559\u5bfe\u7b56\uff08\u8b66\u5bdf\u5e81\uff09|date=25 July 2011|accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> The group operated 26 facilities in 17 [[Prefectures of Japan|prefectures]], and about 120 residential facilities. An article in the ''[[Mainichi Shimbun]]'' newspaper on 11 September 2002 showed that the Japanese public still mistrusts Aleph, and compounds are usually surrounded by protest banners from local residents.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n===Monitoring===\nIn January 2000, the group was placed under surveillance for a period of three years under an anti-Aum law, in which the group is required to submit a list of members and details of assets to the authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/getarticle.pl5|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050323004610/http://www.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/getarticle.pl5|title=Lower House panel approves bills to crack down on Aum|work=The Japan Times|date=17 November 1999|archivedate=23 March 2005|via=japantimes.co.jp|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2003, Japan's [[Public Security Intelligence Agency]] received permission to extend the surveillance for another three years, as they found evidence which suggested that the group still revered Asahara.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/getarticle.pl5|title=Surveillance of Aum to continue on grounds it still poses threat to public|work=Japan Times|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> According to the Religious News Blog report issued in April 2004, the authorities still considered the group \"a threat to society\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.t3.org/Aum.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060722040355/http://www.t3.org/Aum.html|title=A Chronology of Police Actions: Aum Shinri Kyo and the Japanese Police|date=12 January 1997|archivedate=22 July 2006|url-status=dead|website=t3.org|accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 September 2006, Shoko Asahara lost his final appeal against the [[Capital punishment in Japan|death penalty]]. The following day Japanese police raided the offices of Aleph in order to \"prevent any illegal activities by cult members in response to the confirmation of Asahara's death sentence\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/5351376.stm|work=BBC News|title=Japanese police raid cult offices|date=16 September 2006|accessdate=25 April 2010}}</ref> Thirteen cult members were eventually sentenced to death.<ref>Hongo, Jun, \"[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/nn20111122i1.html Last trial brings dark Aum era to end]\", ''[[Japan Times]]'', 22 November 2011, p. 3.</ref>\n\n===Split===\nOn 8 March 2007, [[Fumihiro Joyu]], former Aum Shinrikyo spokesman and head of Aum's [[Moscow]] operation, formally announced a long-expected split.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.religionnewsblog.com/17668/joyu-fumihori-group-leaves-aum-shinrikyo|title=Joyu Group Leaves AUM to Form New Organization|publisher=Religionnewsblog.com|date=8 March 2007|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> Joyu's group, called ''[[Hikari no Wa]]'' (\"The Circle of Light\"), claims to be committed to uniting science and religion and creating \"the new science of the human mind\", having previously aimed to move the group away from its criminal history and toward its spiritual roots.<ref name=cfr.org>{{cite news|last1=Fletcher|first1=Holly|title=CFR Backgrounder: Aum Shinrikyo (archived)|url=http://www.cfr.org/japan/aum-shinrikyo/p9238|work=Council on Foreign Relations|date=19 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, the Public Security Intelligence Agency stated that Aum had about 1,500 members.<ref>{{cite news| work=[[Metropolis (free magazine)|Metropolis]]|title=The Small Print: See Ya!|number=893|date=6\u201319 May 2011|page=4}}</ref> In July 2011 the cult reported its membership as 1,030. The group was reportedly active in trying to recruit new members via social media and proselytizing on college campuses.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[Jiji Press]]|title=Aum cult tops 1,000 followers|work=[[Japan Times]]|date=19 November 2011|page=2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hongo|first=Jun|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/nn20111121x2.html|title=Aum may be gone in name but guru still has following|work=Japan Times|date=22 November 2011|page=2}}</ref>\n\nJapan's Public Security Examination Commission announced in January 2015 that Aum Shinrikyo's two spinoffs would remain under surveillance for three more years starting 1 February 2015.<ref name=jiji>{{cite news|last1=Kyodo|first1=Jiji|title=Surveillance of Aum successor cults extended three more years|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/01/24/national/crime-legal/aum-successor-groups-remain-surveillance-three-years|work=Japan Times|date=24 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Admirers===\nIn 2014, ''[[The Japan Times]]'' alleged that \"good looks and commitment to a cause\", demonstrated by Aleph, \"inspire a new generation of admirers\". Dissatisfaction with society and low degrees of success in life make them \"identify with the cult\" and \"adore the cultists as if they were pop idols\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2014/03/20/national/social-issues/aum-cultists-inspire-a-new-generation-of-admirers|title=Aum cultists inspire a new generation of admirers|first=Tomohiro|last=Osaki|date=20 March 2014|accessdate=6 July 2018| work=Japan Times}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013 investigation and media coverage ===\nSometime after April 2013, the [[Public Security Intelligence Agency]] took a photograph inside of Aleph's facilities.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news-postseven.com/archives/20130808_204027.html|title=\u5143\u30aa\u30a6\u30e0\u306e\u9053\u5834\u3067\u898b\u3064\u304b\u3063\u305f\u516c\u5b89\u8abf\u67fb\u5e81\u9577\u5b98\u306e\u300c\u4e32\u523a\u3057\u5199\u771f\u300d|website=NEWS\u30dd\u30b9\u30c8\u30bb\u30d6\u30f3|language=ja|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref> In this photograph, a bundle of papers is pierced with a knife on an [[altar]]-like object.<ref name=\":0\" /> The papers included photographs of PSIA employees and directors, police officers, and lawyer Taro Takimoto, who helped followers leave Aum Shinrikyo.<ref name=\":0\" /> At least at this point in time, Aleph still displayed portraits of Shoko Asahara and demanded followers' dependence using videos of Asahara.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sankei.com/affairs/news/141108/afr1411080004-n1.html|title=\u516c\u5b89\u8abf\u67fb\u5b98\u306e\u5199\u771f\u4e32\u523a\u3057\u3001\u6559\u56e3\u540d\u96a0\u3057\u52e7\u8a98\u2026\u65e7\u30aa\u30a6\u30e0\u3001\u300c\u53cd\u793e\u4f1a\u6027\u300d\u306f\u7d99\u7d9a|last=INC|first=SANKEI DIGITAL|website=\u7523\u7d4c\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9|language=ja|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>\n\n===2016 Russian crackdown===\nOn 5 April 2016, the [[Investigative Committee of Russia]] announced it opened a criminal case against Aum Shinrikyo followers and that its investigators, along with [[Federal Security Service]] (FSB) forces, were conducting raids in [[Moscow]] and [[Saint Petersburg]] to find them and confiscate literature, religious items and electronic information.<ref>{{cite news|title=Searches underway in Moscow, St. Pete in order to expose Aum Shinrikyo followers|url=http://tass.ru/en/society/867313|newspaper=[[Russian News Agency TASS|TASS]]|location=Moscow|date=5 April 2016|access-date=5 April 2016}}</ref> On 20 September 2016, the Russian government banned Aum Shinrikyo in the country, declaring it a terrorist organization.<ref name=rt>[https://www.rt.com/politics/360006-russia-bans-murderous-japanese-sect Russia bans murderous Japanese sect Aum Shinrikyo as terrorist group], rt.com; accessed 12 July 2018.</ref>\n\n===2017 Aleph raids===\nIn November 2017, Japanese police raided five offices of Aleph in an investigation into the group's recruiting practices after a woman paid tens of thousands of yen for study sessions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2017/11/13/national/crime-legal/offices-aum-successor-adelph-raided-recruiting-practices|title=Offices of Aum successor Aleph raided over recruiting practices|date=13 November 2017|accessdate=6 July 2018|work=Japan Times}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 Tokyo car attack ===\nOn January 1, 2019, in [[Tokyo]], Aum sympathizer Kazuhiro Kusakabe told authorities he [[2019 Tokyo car attack|intentionally rammed into pedestrians]] crowded into narrow [[Takeshita Street]] in [[Harajuku]] district as a terrorist attack in \"retaliation for an execution\". It remains unclear whether he was referencing the 2018 executions of Aum Shinrikyo doomsday cult members directly or making a broader statement. The attack, on [[Japanese New Year|New Year's Day]], left eight injured. A ninth person was also directly injured by the driver.<ref name=\"japantoday1\">{{cite news|url=https://japantoday.com/category/crime/9-injured-as-man-rams-car-into-pedestrians-in-Harajuku-in-retaliation-for-execution|title=9 injured as man rams car into pedestrians in Harajuku in 'retaliation for execution'|newspaper=Japan Today|date=January 1, 2019|access-date=January 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Japan|Religion}}\n*[[List of dates predicted for apocalyptic events]]\n*[[List of people claimed to be Jesus]]\n*[[Yoshihiro Yasuda]], a lawyer who represented Shoko Asahara\n*[[Masaki Kito]], a lawyer who represents Aum victims\n*[[New religious movement]]\n*[[Guhyasam\u0101ja Tantra]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* [[Shoko Asahara]], ''Supreme Initiation: An Empirical Spiritual Science for the Supreme Truth'', 1988, AUM USA Inc., {{ISBN|0-945638-00-0}}. Highlights the main stages of Yogic and Buddhist practice, comparing Yoga-sutra system by Patanjali and the Eightfold Noble Path from Buddhist tradition.\n* [[Shoko Asahara]], ''Life and Death'', (Shizuoka: Aum, 1993). Focuses on the process of Kundalini-Yoga, one of the stages in Aum's practice.\n* [[Shoko Asahara]], ''Disaster Approaches the Land of the Rising Sun: Shoko Asahara's Apocalyptic Predictions'', (Shizuoka: Aum, 1995). A controversial book, later removed by Aum leadership, speaks about possible destruction of Japan.\n* Stefano Bonino, ''Il Caso Aum Shinrikyo: Societ\u00e0, Religione e Terrorismo nel Giappone Contemporaneo'', 2010, Edizioni Solfanelli, {{ISBN|978-88-89756-88-1}}. Preface by Erica Baffelli.\n* Ikuo Hayashi, ''Aum to Watakushi (Aum and I)'', Tokyo: Bungei Shunju, 1998. Book about personal experiences by former Aum member.\n* [[Robert Jay Lifton]], ''Destroying the World to Save It: Aum Shinrikyo, Apocalyptic Violence, and the New Global Terrorism'', Henry Holt, {{ISBN|0-8050-6511-3}}, LoC BP605.088.L54, 1999\n* [[Haruki Murakami]], ''[[Underground (stories)|Underground: The Tokyo Gas Attack and the Japanese Psyche]]'', Vintage, {{ISBN|0-375-72580-6}}, LoC BP605.O88.M8613, 2001. Interviews with victims.\n* ''Global Proliferation of Weapons of Mass Destruction: A Case Study on the Aum Shinrikyo'', [USA] Senate Government Affairs Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations, 31 October 1995. [https://fas.org/irp/congress/1995_rpt/aum/index.html online]\n* [[David E. Kaplan (author)|David E. Kaplan]], and [[Andrew Marshall (Asia journalist)|Andrew Marshall]], ''The Cult at the End of the World: The Terrifying Story of the Aum Doomsday Cult, from the Subways of Tokyo to the Nuclear Arsenals of Russia'', 1996, Random House, {{ISBN|0-517-70543-5}}. An account of the cult from its beginnings to the aftermaths of the Tokyo subway attack, including details of facilities, weapons and other information regarding Aum's followers, activities and property.\n* Ian Reader, ''Religious Violence in Contemporary Japan: The Case of Aum Shinrikyo'', 2000, Curzon Press\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisourcecat|Aum Shinrikyo}}\n{{Commons}}\n*{{official|url=http://English.aleph.to}}\n*[http://www.culteducation.com/asahara.html Shoko Asahara and the Aum Gas Attack]\n*{{in lang|en}} [http://www.moj.go.jp/ENGLISH/PSIA/psia01-04.html PSIA (Public Security Investigative Agency) report]\n\n{{Aum Shinrikyo}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aum Shinrikyo}}\n[[Category:Aum Shinrikyo| ]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Japanese new religions]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist in Asia]]\n[[Category:1984 establishments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Terrorism in Japan]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by the United States]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by Japan]]\n[[Category:Buddhist new religious movements]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by the European Union]]\n[[Category:Apocalypticism]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIncidents before 1995:Journal cites:, added 1 DOI, added 1 PMC, added 1 issue number", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aleph_(Japanese_cult)"}
{"title_page": "Neha Kakkar", "text_new": "{{Short description|Indian playback singer}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{Close paraphrasing|source=|date=April 2020}}\n{{Cleanup-PR|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Neha Kakkar\n| image              = Neha Kakka hate Story.jpg\n| caption            = Kakkar at the song launch event of \"Aashiq Banaya Aapne\" from ''[[Hate Story 4]]'', 2018\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=y|1988|6|6}}\n| birth_place        = [[Rishikesh]], [[Uttarakhand]]), India\n| residence          = \n| nationality        = Indian\n| occupation         = Singer\n| years_active       = 2006\u2013present\n| home_town          = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| relatives       = {{plain list|\n* [[Sonu Kakkar]] (sister)\n* [[Tony Kakkar]] (brother) }}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background         = solo_singer\n| genre              = {{flatlist|\n* Pop\n* [[Filmi]]\n}}\n| instrument          = Vocals\n| label               = {{flatlist|\n* [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]\n* [[Zee Music Company]]\n* Desi Music Factory\n}}\n| website            = {{URL|nehakakkar.com}}\n}}\n| signature          = \n}}\n'''Neha Kakkar''' (born 6 June 1988) is an Indian singer. She began performing at religious events at the age of four and participated in the second season of the singing reality show, ''[[Indian Idol]],'' in which she was eliminated early in the show. After several struggles in her career, she made her Bollywood debut as a chorus singer in the film ''[[Meerabai Not Out]]'' (2008). She rose to prominence upon the release of the dance track \"Second Hand Jawani\" from ''[[Cocktail (2012 film)|Cocktail]]'' (2012), which was followed by several other popular party songs including \"Sunny Sunny\" from ''[[Yaariyan (2014 film)|Yaariyan]]'' (2014) and \"London Thumakda\" from ''[[Queen (soundtrack)|Queen]]'' (2014).\n\nAfterwards, she mostly performed party tracks like \"Aao Raja\" from ''[[Gabbar Is Back]]'' (2015), \"Tu Isaq Mera\" from ''[[Hate Story 3]]'' (2015), \"Humne Pee Rakhi Hai\" from ''[[Sanam Re]]'' (2016) and \"Kar Gayi Chull\" from ''[[Kapoor & Sons]]'' (2016). She proved her versatility in musical range with the release of \"Mile Ho Tum\" from ''[[Fever (2016 film)|Fever]]'' (2016) which topped the [[List of most-viewed Indian videos on YouTube|list of most-viewed Bollywood songs on YouTube]]. She then released several chart-busters which made into the same list, including \"[[Aankh Maarey]]\" from ''[[Simmba]]'' (2018), \"[[Dilbar (song)|Dilbar]]\" from ''[[Satyameva Jayate]]'' (2018), \"Badri Ki Dulhania\" from ''[[Badrinath Ki Dulhania]]'' (2017), \"Cheez Badi\" from ''[[Machine (2017 film)|Machine]]'' (2017), \"Kala Chashma\" for the film ''[[Baar Baar Dekho]]''(2016)  and the non-film song \"[[Nikle Currant]]\", where all crossed over six hundred million views. Similarly, \"Dilbar\" marks the first Indian song to reach number three spot on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' YouTube Music Chart.\n\nFrom 2017 onwards, Kakkar, primarily, in collaboration with [[Tanishk Bagchi]], became more associated with the trend of remaking old to very recent songs, which resulted in several backlashes targeted for the singer though she personally favored the trend of recreations and opined that they have been well appreciated. Apart from playback singing, Kakkar has appeared in several music videos and as a judge on several television reality shows including ''Indian Idol'', the same show she participated during her early days. On these shows, she has been trolled in social media several times, for crying on-screen, while she openly admits that she is a \"proud emotional girl\". She has appeared two times in ''[[Forbes]]''' Celebrity 100 of India (2017 and 2019).\n\n==Early life==\nKakkar was born on 6 June 1988 in [[Rishikesh]], [[Uttarakhand]].<ref name=\"birthday\">{{cite news | url=http://www.india.com/showbiz/neha-kakkar-birthday-special-the-queen-of-blockbuster-hits-turns-28-1237772/ | title=Neha Kakkar birthday special: The Queen of blockbuster hits turns 28 | author=India.com Entertainment Desk|date=6 June 2016 | work=India.com | accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=bio>{{cite web | url=http://www.sify.com/indianidol2/contestants/neha/ | title=Indian Idol profile - Neha Kakkar | work=[[Sify]] | accessdate=11 February 2014 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140608031628/http://www.sify.com/indianidol2/contestants/neha/ | archivedate=8 June 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> She is the younger sister of playback singer [[Sonu Kakkar]] and singer-composer [[Tony Kakkar]].<ref name=Tony>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Tony-Kakkar-One-gets-a-lot-more-popularity-as-a-singer-than-a-composer/articleshow/53209745.cms |title=Tony Kakkar: One gets a lot more popularity as a singer than a composer |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=17 March 2017 |access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> During the early days, her father, Rishikesh Kakkar used to sell [[samosa]] outside a college for a living while her mother Niti Kakkar is a homemaker.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/indian-idols-neha-kakkar-and-aditya-to-get-married-on-valentines-day-she-calls-his-mother-sasu-maa-watch-hilarious-video/articleshow/73232215.cms |title=Indian Idol's Neha Kakkar and Aditya to get married on Valentine's Day? She calls his mother 'Sasu maa' |work=The Times of India |date=14 January 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mensxp.com/entertainment/celebrities/72373-from-samosa-sellers-daughter-to-a-singing-sensation-neha-kakkar-shows-hard-work-always-pays-off.html |title=From Samosa Seller's Daughter To A Singing Sensation, Neha Kakkar Shows Hard Work Always Pays Off |publisher=MensXP |last=Chakraborty |first=Rimi |date=28 January 2020 |access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> In the city, Kakkar shared a rented one-room house with her whole family, in which they used to sleep and simultaneously convert to a kitchen by putting a table.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siasat.com/neha-kakkars-journey-1-room-house-luxurious-bungalow-1850567/ |title=Neha Kakkar's journey from 1-room house to luxurious bungalow |work=[[The Siasat Daily]] |author=Sameer |date=9 March 2020 |access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 90s, Kakkar along with her family moved to [[Delhi]], in order to try her luck in singing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/neha-kakkar-delhi-is-full-of-talent-dilliwaale-hote-hi-kamal-ke-hain/articleshow/64931780.cms |title=Neha Kakkar: Delhi is full of talent, Dilliwaale hote hi kamal ke hain |work=The Times of India |last=Kaushik |first=Divya |date=11 July 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> At that time, the family was reeling under a financial crisis.<ref name=Tony/> Hence, hoping to \"contribute\" to the family, Kakkar, at the age of four, with her siblings started performing at local gatherings and religious event which she credited for \"boosting\" her self-confidence.<ref name=versatile>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/screen/versatile-notes-neha-kakkar/ |title=Versatile Notes: 'Neha Kakkar' |work=The Indian Express |date=27 February 2015 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> \"I only sang [[bhajans]] from four to sixteen years. I would attend four to five [[jagran]]s in a day, which became my training ground\".<ref name=Delhi>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/music/i-am-a-delhiite-and-my-journey-as-a-singer-began-in-the-city-neha-kakkar/story-rkeSDF4dRSfustXi93WEAJ.html |title=I am a Delhiite and my journey as a singer began in the city: Neha Kakkar |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |last=Arora |first=Naina |date=7 April 2017 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Having music talent at home, she never felt the need to get any formal training in singing.<ref name=ShakiraB>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/289083 |title=Meet the Indian Shakira of the Film Industry - Neha Kakkar |magazine=[[Entrepreneur (magazine)|Entrepreneur]] |last=Sabharwal |first=Punita |date=11 February 2017 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> In 2004, she moved to [[Mumbai]] with her brother, Tony Kakkar.<ref name=Tony/>\n\nIn 2006, at the age of sixteen, Kakkar auditioned for the second season of ''[[Indian Idol]]'' where she got eliminated early in the show.<ref name=ShakiraB/> Being the youngest participant, she was naturally \"pampered\" on the sets, and recalls that the show gave her \"great memories and fame\".<ref name=watchout/> Commenting on her short-journey, she stated, \"I feel, whatever happens, happens for a reason. I am just glad the way my journey worked out. It has been a tremendous learning experience\".<ref name=acting>{{cite news|url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/singer-neha-kakkar-willing-to-take-up-acting-but-theres-a-condition-1878043 |title=Singer Neha Kakkar Willing To 'Take Up Acting.' But, There's A Condition |work=NDTV |date=4 July 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> According to her, people \"appreciated my voice saying that you sing well but nobody ever told me that I am a great singer\".<ref name=Shakira/> Hence, determined to prove that she can sing, Kakkar worked on \"polishing\" her voice afterwards.<ref name=Shakira/>\n\n==Career==\n===2006\u20132012: Career beginnings and breakthrough with ''Cocktail''===\nKakkar anticipated that her participation in ''Indian Idol'' and the association with her brother, Tony Kakkar, would translate her career into playback singing.<ref name=SRK/> However, five years post ''Indian Idol'', Kakkar fails to gather any work in Bollywood films which she believes is due to her \"negligence in pleading the music directors and producers, unlike the rest of participants from the show\".<ref name=SRK/> Hence, she became herself more occupied with the concerts and event performances that took her \"across the world\".<ref name=watchout/> According to her, during this phase she started getting recognised and people started referring her as the \"Jai Mata Di girl\".<ref name=watchout/>\n\n[[File:Neha Kakkar at Cinemax.jpg|thumb|left|upright|200px|alt=Neha Kakkar smiling looking at camera wearing a white top|Kakkar at the premiere event of Premiere of Marathi film ''Janiva'', 2015]]\nIn 2008, she launched her debut album ''Neha The Rockstar'' with music by [[Meet Bros]] in which she performed some romantic songs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/television/celebrity/story/indian-idol-10-judge-neha-kakkar-is-unrecognisable-in-this-viral-video-1286726-2018-07-16 |title=Indian Idol 10 judge Neha Kakkar is unrecognisable in this viral video |publisher=India Today |date=16 July 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> During the time, she recorded for a music album, ''Romeo Juliet'' composed by her brother, Tony Kakkar. The song \"Mohabbat Hai\" from the album received limited recognition from the listeners which resulted in the offer to render her first Kotak Mahindra jingle, \"Mera Jaisa Koi Mere Zindagi Main Aaye\".<ref name=SRK>{{cite news|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/report/slide-show-1-neha-kakkar-on-shah-rukh-khan-anthem/20120320.htm#4 |title=Thought of meeting SRK makes me go weak in the knees |publisher=Rediff.com |last=N |first=Patcy |date=20 March 2012 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nA year later, a friend of Kakkar called her from the studio of composer [[Sandesh Shandilya]], who was looking for a new voice to record the song \"Hai Rama\" from ''[[Meerabai Not Out]]'' (2008). The following year, she was featured in an [[A.R. Rahman]]'s composition, the theme song of ''[[Blue (2009 film)|Blue]]'' (2009) where she provided the chorus vocals for the song.<ref name=watchout/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/entertainment-others/blue-music-review-cocktail-of-genres/ |title=Blue music review: Cocktail of genres |work=The Indian Express |date=15 September 2009 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=SRK/> She then lent her voice for the title track of the Hindi-language soap opera''[[Na Aana Is Des Laado]]'' (2009) which holds a special place in her heart, as the \"song was a touching experience since it focused on women\".<ref name=watchout/>\n\nIn 2010, Kakkar made her film debut with [[Sooraj Barjatya]]'s film ''[[Isi Life Mein...!]]'' (2010) in which she played the role of a college student.<ref name=IsiLifeMein/> The film received negative reviews from critics and was a box office failure.<ref name=IsiLifeMein>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.filmfare.com/features/7-singers-who-shouldnt-act-9544-6.html |title=7 singers who shouldn't act |magazine=Filmfare |last=Fernandes |first=Bradley |date=19 June 2015 |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> The same year, she debuted in both the Kannada and Telugu music industry by performing a total of four tracks for [[Sandeep Chowta]].<ref name=Thamassu/><ref name=Kedi/> She lent her voice for the title track of the Kannada film ''[[Thamassu]]'' and the song \"Nodu Baare\" alongside [[Master Saleem]], which were appreciated by the reviewers from ''[[Bangalore Mirror]]'' and the former resulted in her only [[Filmfare Awards South]] nomination as the [[Filmfare Award for Best Female Playback Singer \u2013 Kannada|Best Female Playback Singer]].<ref name=FFAS11nom>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-06-11/hyderabad/29646891_1_filmfare-awards-tarun-rai-filmfare-trophy|title=Idea Filmfare awards ceremony on July 2|date=11 June 2011|accessdate=31 July 2013|work=The Times Of India}}</ref><ref name=Thamassu>{{cite news|url=https://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/reviews/thamassu-chowta-is-back/articleshow/21884459.cms |title=Thamassu: Chowta is back! |work=[[Bangalore Mirror]] |date=26 April 2010 |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> Also, the same publication complimented Kakkar's rendition in the song \"Neeve Na Neeve Na\" and \"Jaaniya Jaane\" from the Telugu film ''[[Kedi (2010 film)|Kedi]]''.<ref name=Kedi>{{cite news|url=https://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/reviews/kedi-sandeeps-best-in-a-long-time/articleshow/21942832.cms |title=Kedi : Sandeep's best, in a long time! |work=Bangalore Mirror |date=26 April 2010 |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe had a single Bollywood release in 2011, Sandeep Chowta-composed \"Woh Ek Pal\", performed alongside Arijit Dutta, which lacked the needed coverage from the music listeners.<ref name=SRK/> She then made an appearance in the second season of ''[[Comedy Circus|Comedy Circus Ke Taansen]]'' alongside [[Kapil Sharma]] and [[Ali Asgar]] which she considered an \"amazing experience\" where the \"atmosphere on the sets was positive and the jokes had us all cracking up. I particularly enjoyed it since I am bubbly and always smiling\".<ref name=watchout/> The following year, her collaboration with [[Pritam]] for the dance track \"Second Hand Jawani\" from ''[[Cocktail (2012 film)|Cocktail]]'' proved to be a major breakthrough for Kakkar. The song went to become popular among the music listeners, though it received mixed to negative reviews from critics, calling it a \"distraction amidst rest of the album\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/cocktail/songs/music-critic-review/ |title=Cocktail Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=18 June 2012 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-movies/music-reviews/cocktail-music-review/|title=Cocktail Music Review |publisher=Koimoi |author=Shivi |date=20 June 2012 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> Besides, she got a \"tremendous response\" for her \"Shah Rukh Khan Anthem\" on [[Youtube]], for which [[Shah Rukh Khan]] thanked her by saying he \"loved the song\".<ref name=watchout/>\n\n===2013\u20132016: Chart-busters with ''Fever'' and ''Baar Baar Dekho''===\nKakkar's first release of 2013, \"Botal Khol\" from ''[[Prague (2013 film)|Prague]]'' met with controversy, where Central Board of Film Certification raised objection on the song citing that its lyrics contain double meaning.<ref name=Shakira/> In an interview with ''[[Hindustan Times]]'', Kakkar stated, \"We do discuss with our lyricists when we are recording. But we cannot stop making or singing such songs just because certain sections of the society do not like it\".<ref name=Shakira>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/feels-great-to-be-compared-to-shakira-neha-kakkar/story-msQdOYQ0MinjkxNADGM5rL.html;jsessionid=95B7C0B6319D829E627E7F4FB284B5C2 |title=Feels great to be compared to Shakira: Neha Kakkar |work=Hindustan Times |last=Sen |first=Torsha |date=14 November 2013 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> This was followed by a [[Sachin-Jigar]]'s item number composed for ''[[Ramaiya Vastavaiya]]''.<ref name=Ramaiya/> Titled \"Jadoo Ki Jhappi\", the song met with negative reception from critics, where Rajiv Vijayakar from [[Bollywood Hungama]] rated the song as weakest track on the album and wrote: \"Kakkar cannot impart the magic that marks the vocals of the most successful item numbers\".<ref name=Ramaiya>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/ramaiya-vastavaiya/songs/music-user-reviews/music-review-of-ramaiya-vastavaiya-by-rajiv-vijayakar/|title=Ramaiya Vastavaiya - Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Vijayakar |first=Rajiv |date=14 November 2013 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> She next collaborated with Pritam for another item song \"Dhating Nach\", performed alongside [[Nakash Aziz]] and [[Shefali Alvares]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/report/review-phata-poster-nikhla-hero-music-is-entertaining/20130907.htm |title=Review: Phata Poster Nikhla Hero music is entertaining |publisher=Rediff.com |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=7 September 2013 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n2014 saw the rise of Kakkar with the release of three popular songs.<ref name=high>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Neha-Kakkar-ends-the-year-on-a-high-note/articleshow/45511546.cms |title=Neha Kakkar ends the year on a high note |work=The Times of India |last=Kotwani |first=Hiren |date=15 December 2014 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/2014-when-actors-turned-playback-singers/articleshow/45532648.cms |title=2014: When actors turned playback singers |newspaper=[[The Economic Times]] |date=16 December 2014 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> The first release of the year was a collaboration with [[Yo Yo Honey Singh]] for the film ''[[Yaariyan (2014 film)|Yaariyan]]'', for which, ''[[The Times of India]]'' credited her as the \"perfect voice for dance numbers\".<ref name=high/><ref name=high/> The duo collaborated once again for Bollywood's first trance number, \"Manali Trance\" from ''[[The Shaukeens]]'', which was recorded in twenty-five minutes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-yo-yo-honey-singh-s-manali-trance-from-the-shaukeens-released-lisa-haydon-rocks-it-2026958 |title=Yo Yo Honey Singh's 'Manali Trance' from 'The Shaukeens' released, Lisa Haydon rocks it! |work=Daily News and Analysis |date=17 October 2014 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> The song mainly received positive reviews from critics, due to the \"innovative contribution to this Bollywood-unfriendly genre\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-movies/music-reviews/the-shaukeens-music-review/ |title=The Shaukeens Music Review |publisher=Koimoi |last=Redkar |first=Surabhi |date=30 October 2014 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> Her first work with [[Amit Trivedi]], a wedding song titled \"London Thumakda\" was released in the same year, which received positive reviews from music critics. Mohar Basu from [[Koimoi]] wrote: \"Singers [did] a brilliant job as this one remains the album most energetic number\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-movies/music-reviews/queen-music-review/ |title=Queen Music Review |publisher=Koimoi |last=Basu |first=Mohar |date=4 February 2014 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> On the occasion of Mother's Day, Kakkar shot and released a song for her mother which resulted in positive response among the audience.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/I-had-to-deal-with-a-lot-of-vicious-rumours-Kanika-Kapoor/articleshow/35150257.cms |title=Neha Kakkar's song on her mother goes viral |work=The Times of India |last=Chatterjee |first=Swasti |date=16 May 2014 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Neha Kakkar Fever.jpg|thumb|right|upright|200px|alt=Neha Kakkar smiling wearing a black top|Kakkar at the audio release event of ''[[Fever (2016 film)|Fever]]'', 2016]]\nKakkar's first release of 2015 came with \"Ek Do Teen Chaar\" from ''[[Ek Paheli Leela]]'' which was composed, penned and co-sung by Tony Kakkar.<ref name=EkPaheliLeela/> The song received mainly negative reviews from critics, calling it a \"failed attempt on a potential number\".<ref name=EkPaheliLeela>{{cite news|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/report/review-ek-paheli-leelas-music-is-worth-a-listen/20150321.htm |title=Review: Ek Paheli Leela's music is worth a listen |publisher=Rediff.com |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=21 March 2015 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Rajiv Vijayakar from Bollywood Hungama, reviewing the soundtrack album wrote: \"Neha tries to be saucy and coquettish, but the composition lacks the strength to let this mood bloom\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/ek-paheli-leela/songs/music-user-reviews/music-review-of-ek-paheli-leela-by-rajiv-vijayakar/ |title=Ek Paheli Leela Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Vijayakar |first=Rajiv |date=22 March 2015 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> She then collaborated with the music composer duo, Amjad-Nadeem where she performed the tracks \"Naughty No 1\" and \"Daaru Peeke Dance\" for ''[[Barkhaa]]'' and ''[[Kuch Kuch Locha Hai]]'' respectively; where none of them performed well commercially.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/Kuch-Kuch-Locha-Hai/articleshow/47198410.cms |title=Kuch Kuch Locha Hai - Music Review |work=The Times of India |last=Fernandes |first=Kasmin |date=8 May 2014 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> Followed by few other \"dull\" releases, Kakkar received recognition with her \"seductive\" performance in the [[Meet Bros Anjjan]]-composed \"Tu Isaq Mera\" from ''[[Hate Story 3]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/hate-story-music-review-a-typical-t-series-score-that/article_05dee8e2-8fc5-11e5-aa4b-33712b4911a9.html |title='Hate Story 3' Music Review: A Typical T-Series Score That Is a Mixed Bag |work=India West |last=Vijayakar |first=RM |date=20 November 2015 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Her last release of the year was \"Tukur Tukur\" from ''[[Dilwale (2015 film)|Dilwale]]'', an \"energetic number\" which captures the spirit of [[Goa]] and performed alongside [[Arijit Singh]], [[Kanika Kapoor]], [[Siddharth Mahadevan]] and [[Nakash Aziz]] as a separate, video version of the song.<ref name=Dilwale/> Kakkar, an ardent fan of [[Shah Rukh Khan]], expressed her excitement once she figured out the song was recorded for his album, \"When I recorded \"Tukur Tukur\", I did not know it was for his film. I am over the moon\".<ref name=sex>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Neha-Kakkar-Honey-Singh-says-my-voice-is-like-sex/articleshow/50342445.cms |title=Neha Kakkar: Honey Singh says my voice is like sex |work=The Times of India |last=Basu |first=Mohar |date=28 December 2015 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> However, the version was criticised for Kakkar's \"jarring\" vocals and the \"lack of the sheer exuberance\" compared to that of the audio version performed by Singh.<ref name=Dilwale>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/dilwale-music-review-a-seamless-blend-of-classical-and-contemporary/article_790d09e0-a28d-11e5-b62a-0bb63a4dd8ac.html |title='Dilwale' Music Review: A Seamless Blend of Classical and Contemporary Numbers |work=India West |last=Vijayakar |first=RM |date=14 December 2015 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The same year, she featured alongside [[Shilpa Shetty]] in the video single \"Wedding Da Season\", composed by [[Amaal Malik]], as insisted by the choreographer [[Ganesh Acharya]], who saw her performing off-screen.<ref name=sex/>\n\n2016 was a successful year for Kakkar where she performed the popular song \"Mile Ho Tum\" from the film ''[[Fever (2016 film)|Fever]]'', composed, written and co-sung by Tony Kakkar, which she considers as the \"closest song to her heart\".<ref name=Fever/> Credited as the [[List of most-viewed Indian videos on YouTube|most-viewed Bollywood song on Youtube]], the song received a positive response from music critics and audience. Reviewing the song from ''[[The Times of India]]'', Mohar Basu wrote: \"Kakkar shows her versatile vein with [the song, where] she keeps her voice subtle and sticks to the mellow meter\".<ref name=Fever>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/Fever/articleshow/52987308.cms |title=Music Review: Fever |work=The Times of India |last=Basu |first=Mohar |date=17 January 2017 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Also, she contributed to the soundtrack album of ''[[Baar Baar Dekho]]'' by performing the wedding-song \"Kala Chashma\" which became the \"the party anthem of the year\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/baar-baar-dekho-music-review-katrina-kaif-sidharth-malhotra-film-is-not-all-about-kala-chashma-2961322/ |title=Baar Baar Dekho music review: Katrina Kaif, Sidharth Malhotra film is not all about Kala Chashma |work=The Indian Express |date=7 September 2016 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Included in the list of the most viewed Bollywood songs on Youtube, \"Kala Chashma\" was admired by the critics for its use of \"dub-step, hip-hop beats, and a very groovy bass\" while Surabhi Redkar from Koimoi applauded Kakkar's \"powerful vocals\" in the song.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/baar-baar-dekho-special/story/baar-baar-dekho-music-review-kala-chashma-jasleen-royal-333937-2016-08-08 |title=Baar Baar Dekho music review: Jasleen Royal, welcome to Bollywood! |publisher=India Today |last=Mukherjee |first=Tatsam |date=8 August 2016 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-movies/music-reviews/baar-baar-dekho-music-review/ |title=Baar Baar Dekho Music Review |publisher=Koimoi |last=Redkar |first=Surabhi |date=16 August 2016 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> She worked with Epic Bhangra for the film ''[[Sanam Re]]'', where they released the song \"Humne Pee Rakhi Hai\", a mix of club and EDM which was deemed as an \"unncesessary addition to the album\" and Kakkar vocals were noted to be \"awfully shrill\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/sanam-re-music-review-decent-album-lyrics-and-vocals-could/article_f07996fe-b8b5-11e5-839b-7b7ce2f790eb.html |title='Sanam Re' Music Review: Decent Album, Lyrics and Vocals Could've Been Better |publisher=India West |last=Vijayakar |first=RM |date=11 January 2016 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> She also provided her vocals for an additional song in the album, \"Akkad Bakkad\", a [[rap]] song performed alongwith [[Badshah (rapper)|Badshah]] to celebrate the music of the film.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Mumbais-musical-date-with-Lucky-Ali-on-February-14/articleshow/50863077.cms|title=Divya Khosla Kumar wraps up 'Sanam Re' with Badshah's rap song|work=[[The Times Of India]]|accessdate=7 February 2016}}</ref> Apart from lending her vocals to the party song, \"Kar Gayi Chull\" from ''[[Kapoor & Sons]]'', which was a remake of the Haryanvi track \"Chull\" and her first recording for [[Dharma Productions]], Kakkar performed several other recreated songs during the year including, \"Maahi Ve\"\u2013a remake of the song \"Maahi Ve\" from ''[[Kaante]]'' (2002)\u2013 and \"O Janiya\"\u2013a remake of the song \"Kaante Nahi Kat Te\" from ''[[Mr. India (1987 film)|Mr. India]]'' (1987)\u2013for ''[[Wajah Tum Ho]]'' and ''[[Force 2]]'' respectively.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/kapoor-and-sons-music-review-nothing-exciting-in-this-album-apart-from-kar-gayi-chull-2656386.html |title='Kapoor and Sons' music review: Nothing exciting in this album apart from 'Kar Gayi Chull' |work=Firstpost |last=Swetha |first=Ramakrishnan |date=5 March 2016 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Joginder Tuteja from Bollywood Hungama opined that Kakkar's rendition in the former is \"decent but not as good as the original\" while he noted that \"Kakkar, the young woman is just the right follow up to [[Alisha Chinai]] as her voice comes with the right mix of naughtiness and seduction\" in the latter.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/wajah-tum-ho/songs/music-critic-review/ |title=Wajah Tum Ho Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=16 November 2017 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/force-2/songs/music-critic-review/ |title=Force 2 Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=7 November 2017 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u2013present: Collaboration with Bagchi and series of remade songs===\n2017 marks Kakkar's first collaboration with [[Tanishk Bagchi]] which resulted in the rehashing of several Bollywood songs in the coming years. Their first release, \"Badri Ki Dulhania\" from ''[[Badrinath Ki Dulhania]]'' performed with [[Dev Negi]], [[Ikka Singh]] and [[Monali Thakur]] has few segments lifted from the [[Shankar-Jaikishen]] classic, \"Chalat Musafir\" from ''[[Teesri Kasam]]'' (1966).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/badrinath-ki-dulhania-music-review/article_b5bafd2c-035b-11e7-9c97-43fd39d90102.html |title='Badrinath Ki Dulhania' Music Review |work=India West |last=Vijayakar |first=RM |date=7 March 2017 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The song was well received by the critics, where Swetha Ramakrishnan from ''[[Firstpost]]'' commended the overall work for \"living up to previous expectations\" while announcing Kakkar as the \"perfect fit for the title track\".<ref name=Badri>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/badrinath-ki-dulhania-music-review-this-album-has-chart-buster-written-all-over-it-3283908.html |title=Badrinath Ki Dulhania music review: This album has chart-buster written all over |work=Firstpost |last=Ramakrishnan |first=Swetha |date=16 February 2017 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The version became an instant chart-buster among the audience and was included in the [[list of most-viewed Indian videos on YouTube]] with over 500 million views.<ref name=Badri/> This was followed by another chart-buster by the duo, \"Cheez Badi\" from ''[[Machine (2017 film)|Machine]]'', a re-creation of the 1994-released ''[[Mohra]]'' song \"Tu Cheez Badi Hai Mast Mast\", which got mixed reviews from critics; Vijayakar from India West found Kakkar to be \"strictly okay to ho-hum as co-singer\" while the re-creation \"lacks the obnoxious quotient\" of the original.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/machine-music-review-mechanical-songs-sans-feeling/article_a0fc8276-0427-11e7-b059-37539bd8dffd.html |title='Machine' Music Review: Mechanical Songs Sans Feeling |work=India West |last=Vijayakar |first=RM |date=8 March 2017 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Her next release was the dance song \"[[Main Tera Boyfriend]]\" from ''[[Raabta (film)|Raabta]]'' which was a recreation of a non-film track \"Na Na Na Na\".<ref name=PP/> Reviewing the song from [[Daily News and Analysis]], Prachita Pandey wrote: \"Kakkar complements [Arijit] well, but we felt her vocals to be a bit toned down in terms of energy\".<ref name=PP>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-sushant-singh-rajput-kriti-sanon-are-slaying-it-with-their-hot-bods-and-killer-moves-in-main-tera-boyfriend-2447109|title=Sushant Singh Rajput and Kriti sanon are slaying it with their hot bod and killer moves in main tera boyfriend|author=Prachita Pandey|publisher=Daily News and Analysis|date=22 May 2017|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref> The trend was carried forward with ''[[Judwaa 2]]'' where she rendered two remake songs, co-composed by Sandeep Shirodkar and [[Anu Malik]] and one original song composed by Meet Bros. Tuteja from Bollywood Hungama credited Kakkar and co-singers for \"retaining the impact as the originals\" with their vocals in the remade songs of the same name while complimenting her as \"quite impressive in her trademark naughty vocals\" in the song \"Aa Toh Sahi\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/judwaa-2/songs/music-critic-review/ |title=Judwaa 2 Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=12 September 2017 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> During the year, she appeared as a judge alongside [[Himesh Reshammiya]] and [[Javed Ali]] in the [[Sa Re Ga Ma Pa L'il Champs 2017|sixth season]] of the Indian television music competition, ''[[Sa Re Ga Ma Pa L'il Champs]]''.<ref name=Saregama/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tv/nia-sharma-beats-alia-bhatt-and-katrina-kaif-becomes-asias-third-sexiest-woman/articleshow/55961395.cms |title=Neha Kakkar to judge Sa Re Ga Ma Pa little champs |work=[[Mumbai Mirror]] |date=14 December 2016 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Reminiscing her participation in the music competition, Kakkar stated, \"I started from being a contestant to now becoming a judge. Being on another side of the table is a different feeling altogether. I travel back in time and see myself standing there and being scared of judges remarks\".<ref name=Delhi/><ref name=Saregama>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/television/himesh-reshammiya-neha-kakkar-sa-re-ga-ma-pa-judge-4426987/ |title=Himesh Reshammiya, Neha Kakkar to judge Sa Re Ga Ma Pa Li'l Champs |work=The Indian Express |date=14 December 2016 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> The year ended with another recreated song, \"Mehbooba\" from ''[[Fukrey Returns]]'', originally performed by [[Mohammed Rafi]] ''[[Dharam Veer (film)|Dharam Veer]]'' (1977), where the new version was commended for the \"stylish rendition\" of the singers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/music-review-fukrey-returns/articleshow/61878735.cms |title=Music Review: Fukrey Returns |last=Sen |first=Debarati |work=The Times of India |date=2 December 2017 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Neha Kakkar High Fever.jpg|thumb|left|upright|alt=Neha Kakkar smiling wearing a red top|Kakkar on the show ''High Fever'', 2018]]\nKakkar's first release of 2018 was the [[Yo Yo Honey Singh]]'s \"Chhote Chhote Peg\" from''[[Sonu Ke Titu Ki Sweety]]'', a remake of the [[Anand Raj Anand]]-composition \"Tote Tote Ho Gaya\" from ''[[Bichhoo]]'' (2000), and was positively received by the music critics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/sonu-ke-titu-ki-sweety/songs/music-critic-review/ |title=Sonu Ke Titu Ki Sweety Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=19 February 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> This was followed by Bagchi's recreation of \"Aashiq Banaya Apne\" included in the soundtrack album of ''[[Hate Story 4]]'', originally performed by [[Himesh Reshamiyya]] and [[Shreya Ghoshal]].<ref name=HateStory4/> Umesh Punwani from Koimoi feels that Kakkar did a \"good job\" while trying to \"give her voice a new shape\" although the retained original portions of the song were the only good thing about this version.<ref name=HateStory4>{{cite web|url=https://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-movies/music-reviews/hate-story-4-music-review-the-only-good-thing-is-himesh-reshammiyas-retained-voice/ |title=Hate Story 4 Music Review: The Only Good Thing Is Himesh Reshammiya's Retained Voice |publisher=Koimoi |last=Punwani |first=Umesh |date=8 March 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> The duo collaborated for five other projects, from which \"[[Dilbar (song)|Dilbar]]\" from''[[Satyameva Jayate]]'' and \"[[Aankh Maarey]]\" from ''[[Simmba]]'' became popular with music listeners, both songs reaching the [[list of most-viewed Indian videos on YouTube]] and the former being the first Indian song to reach number three on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' YouTube Music Chart.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/music/dhvani-bhanushali-s-dilbar-tops-billboard-youtube-chart/story-GxYPXbKZxa7g3cx7lm9wRK.html |title=Dhvani Bhanushali's Dilbar tops Billboard YouTube chart |work=Hindustan Times |last=Mukherjee |first=Shreya |date=13 July 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Benjamin |first1=Jeff |title=Bollywood Channel T-Series Is YouTube's First To Hit 100 Million Subscribers |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffbenjamin/2019/05/30/bollywood-youtube-channel-t-series-first-to-hit-100-million-subscribers/ |accessdate=11 June 2019 |work=[[Forbes]] |date=30 May 2019}}</ref> Devansh Sharma from ''[[Firstpost]]'' praised the former and remarked, \"The soul of the new track is Neha Kakkar who brings a sensual-yet-never-raunchy appeal through her vocals. Her range allows her to switch from the meditative stanzas to the uninhibited chorus like a chameleon\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/bollywood/satyamev-jayate-music-review-neha-kakkars-dilbar-is-a-clear-winner-but-tanishk-bagchi-can-do-better-4944461.html |title=Satyamev Jayate music review: Neha Kakkar's Dilbar is a clear winner, but Tanishk Bagchi can do better |work=Firstpost |last=Devansh |first=Sharma |date=13 August 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Apart from rendering the folk pop song \"Dholida\" from ''[[Loveyatri]]'' alongside [[Udit Narayan]] and [[Palak Muchhal]], Kakkar performed a traditional-themed-contemporary Punjabi track \"Bhangra Da Sajda\" from ''[[Veere Di Wedding]]'', composed and co-sung by [[Shashwat Sachdev]].<ref name=loveyatri/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/veere-di-wedding/songs/music-critic-review/ |title=Veere Di Wedding Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=16 May 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> ''Firstpost'' in its review of ''[[Badhaai Ho]]'' appraised Kakkar's accent and \"good support in the smaller\" part of the song \"Nain Na Jodeen\" while crediting \"her versatility\" in the [[Bhangra (music)|bhangra number]] \"Morni Banke\" which was a remake of the 2010 release of [[Panjabi MC]]'s song of the same name.<ref name=BadhaaiHo>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/bollywood/badhaai-ho-music-review-a-fun-inventive-album-replete-with-hilarious-lyrics-quirky-compositions-5392311.html |title=Badhaai Ho music review: A fun, inventive album replete with hilarious lyrics, quirky compositions |work=Firstpost |last=Devansh |first=Sharma |date=17 October 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> The trend continued with the item number \"Gali Gali\" included in the Hindi-dubbed version of the Kannada film ''[[K.G.F: Chapter 1]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mouni Roy teases a glimpse of her KGF dance number, Gali Gali. Watch here |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/mouni-roy-teases-a-glimpse-of-her-kfg-dance-number-gali-gali-watch-here/story-HjsohSRSCzx8xOwMOcyb2I.html |accessdate=22 December 2018 |work=Hindustan Times |date=11 December 2018 |language=en}}</ref> During the year, she appeared as a judge alongside [[Anu Malik]] and [[Vishal Dadlani]] in the tenth season of the Indian television music competition, ''[[Indian Idol]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/television/neha-kakkar-indian-idol-5153931/ |title=Neha Kakkar returns to Indian Idol, this time as a judge |work=The Indian Express |date=27 April 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n2019 began with the release of three remade songs in collaboration with Bagchi. \"[[Chamma Chamma]]\", recreated for the film ''[[Fraud Saiyyan]]''\u2013original composition from the film ''[[China Gate (1998 film)|China Gate]]'' (1998)\u2013was considered \"memorable\", while \"[[Coca Cola Tu]]\" from ''[[Luka Chuppi]]'' and \"[[Hauli Hauli]]\" from ''[[De De Pyaar De]]'' were acknowledged by some critics for giving the songs \"a new flavor\" though other critics disapproved her latest trend of \"annoying\" association in the remade song. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/fraud-saiyaan/critic-review/fraud-saiyaan-movie-review/ |title=Fraud Saiyaan Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |date=18 January 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/luka-chuppi/songs/music-critic-review/ |title=Luka Chuppi Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=25 February 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koimoi.com/reviews/luka-chuppi-movie-review-its-all-about-finding-the-missing-story-sense-substance/|title=Luka Chuppi Movie Review: It's All About Finding The Missing Story, Sense & Substance! |publisher=Koimoi |last=Punwani |first=Umesh |date=2 March 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> The year marks her first collaboration with [[Vishal Mishra]] and [[Vishal-Shekhar]], where she performed the female version of \"Ki Honda Pyaar\" from ''[[Jabariya Jodi]]'' for the former and \"The Hook Up Song\" for the latter, which was well received by critics; Sen from ''The Times of India'' wrote: \"The zing in Neha Kakkar\u2019s sultry voice adds to the flirty feel of the upbeat track\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/music-review-student-of-the-year-2/articleshow/69159568.cms |title=Music review: Student of the Year 2 |work=The Times of India |last=Sen |first=Debarti |date=9 May 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/jabariya-jodi-music-review-sidharth-malhotra-parineeti-chopras-film-offers-a-soulless-fragmented-album-lacking-in-originality-7117101.html |title=Jabariya Jodi music review: Sidharth Malhotra, Parineeti Chopra's film offers a soulless, fragmented album, lacking in originality |work=Firstpost |last=Ganguly |first=Pratishruti |date=7 August 2019 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The trio of Kakkar, Bagchi and the dancer [[Nora Fatehi]] re-united for two other chart-buster songs, \"O Saki Saki\" from ''[[Batla House]]'' and \"Ek Toh Kum Zindagani\" from ''[[Marjaavaan]]''. The former being a remake of ''[[Musafir (2004 film)|Musafir]]'''s \"Saaki\", originally performed by [[Sukhwinder Singh]] and [[Sunidhi Chauhan]] was criticised for the lack of \"power\" compared to the original version.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/inspirational-but-not-memorable/article29112356.ece |title='Mission Mangal' and 'Batla House' music review: Inspirational, but not memorable |newspaper=The Hindu |last=Nair |first=Vipin |date=16 August 2019 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/music-review-marjaavaan/articleshow/71970281.cms|title=Music review: Marjaavaan |work=The Times of India |last=Sen |first=Debarti |date=9 November 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> During the year, Kakkar lent her voice for the foot-tapping club number \"Dheeme Dheeme\", composed by Bagchi and the romantic love song \"Tu Hi Yaar Mera\" composed by [[Rochak Kohli]], in which Tuteja from Bollywood Hungama appraised her \"different avatar\" in the latter.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/pati-patni-aur-woh-2/songs/music-critic-review/ |title=Pati Patni Aur Woh Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=30 December 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\n===Voice===\nKakkar possesses a [[contralto]] [[vocal range]] and has the ability to reach E5 note.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4eDK5UBWV1A |title=Neha Kakkar : Voice Study & Deep Analysis - Vocal Range - Paarth singh |publisher=YouTube |date=20 February 2019 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> Her voice has been described several times in the media as \"distinct\", \"unique\", \"chirpy\", \"seductive\" and \"partially nasal\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodmusicreviews.com/artist-neha-kakkar/ |title=Artist of the Week \u2013 Neha Kakkar |work=Bollywood Music Reviews |author=KK |date=17 October 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=popular/> She did not take any formal vocal training.<ref name=versatile/> In an interview with ''[[The Indian Express]]'' she said, \"The fact that I am not formally trained never really bothered me. There were times I knew it could have been a brownie point, had I been trained but it never pulled me back\".<ref name=versatile/> Believing that she needs to be distinctive to be noticed from the crowd of competition, she keeps \"practicing by learning to sing songs that catch her fancy\" since her voice is her \"USP\".<ref name=watchout/>\n\nShe believes she modulates her song differently for each song, even if it falls under the same genre.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianewengland.com/2018/04/i-treat-every-song-like-a-different-character-neha/ |title=I treat every song like a different character: Neha |work=India New England News |date=23 April 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> According to her, from the very early days of her career, she has constantly been trying to \"polish\" her voice which helps her enhancing the required voice modulation.<ref name=Shakira/> She also admits that she tries hard to \"put a difference\" in her voice texture for each recording to avoid her voice being stereotyped.<ref name=singforthem>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/music/neha-kakkar-singer-best-songs-recreated-hits-music-mixtape-punjabi-5037351/ |title=Neha Kakkar: I put something new in my songs, that's why everyone wants me to sing for them |work=The Indian Express |last=Shekhar |first=Mimansha |date=9 April 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> After listening to her in the song \"Manali Trance\", she was asked by many fans if she was high when she recorded it, to which she replied, \"' I don't drink or smoke. It's just my vocal interpretation of it\".<ref name=selfie/>\n\nHer vocal tone has been subjected to mixed reviews. ''The Times of India'' complimented \"the kind of variation\" she brings to her voice in the song, \"Cheez Badi\" and wrote: \"While she is known for her party numbers, this song sees her voice take on a rather sultry quality that perfectly matches the mood of the song\".<ref name=popular>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/photo-features/neha-kakkar-songs-10-most-popular-songs-of-the-singer/sunny-sunny/photostory/62190992.cms |title=Neha Kakkar Songs: 10 most popular songs of the singer |work=The Times of India |date=17 February 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Shreya Paul, from ''Firstpost'', while reviewing the album of ''[[De De Pyaar De]]'' critised her \"auto-tuned\" vocals and the attempt to \"sound sexy and naughty\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/de-de-pyaar-de-music-review-soundtrack-of-ajay-devgns-film-is-as-problematic-as-the-plot-seems-to-be-6636041.html |title=De De Pyaar De music review: Soundtrack of Ajay Devgn's film is as problematic as the plot seems to be |work=Firstpost |last=Paul |first=Shreya |date=16 May 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Similarly, R.M. Vijayakar from ''India West'' calls her vocal performances \"petulant\" which she \"mistakes for sensuality\".<ref name=loveyatri>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/loveyatri-music-review-t-series-after-eons-a-riveting-score/article_a02ad7ce-c7eb-11e8-81d6-6f4d9eadedd6.html |title='LoveYatri' Music Review (T-Series): After Eons, a Riveting Score for a Film with a New Pair |work=India West |last=Vijayakar |first=R.M |date=4 October 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> In the media, Kakkar is often regarded as the voice behind the \"party anthems\" and \"recreated songs\". Due to the numerous contribution to the same, ''[[Gulf Today]]'' regarded her voice as an overexposure to the \"recreation and fast-paced songs\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gulftoday.ae/culture/2020/03/08/budding-bollywood-singer-says-voices-of-female-singers-need-to-be-heard |title=Budding Bollywood singers say more female voices need to be heard |work=Gulf Today |date=8 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Musical style===\n[[File:Neha Kakkar Birthday Bash.jpg|thumb|left|upright|alt=Neha Kakkar smiling looking at camera wearing a black dress|Kakkar mostly performed dance tracks and re-created songs]]\nKakkar's music contains elements of pop, hip hop, and R&B. She admits that she has mostly performed dance numbers which she believes suits her voice the most and complements her energetic vibe, though she expressed her desire to experiment other genres including \"soft romantic\" songs.<ref name=sex/><ref name=ballads/> Also, she appreciates Sufi music and expresses her fondness over the music of [[Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan]].<ref name=bio/>\n\nDevansh Sharma of ''Firstpost'' applauded Kakkar's \"impressive range\" where she can switch from a \"Dilbar\" to the romantic track \"Nain Na Jodeen\".<ref name=BadhaaiHo/>. Similarly, ''The Times of India'' complimented her musical \"diversity\" where she \"nails\" the melodic song, Mile Ho Tum, to \"perfection\" with the different \"intensity and passion\" as compared to her energetic numbers\".<ref name=popular/> ''[[The Asian Age]]'' notes that party songs have become almost synonymous with Kakkar and she should consider breaking away from the \"mould\".<ref name=ballads>{{cite news|url=https://www.asianage.com/music/i-d-love-sing-romantic-ballads-too-neha-kakkar-629 |title=I'd love to sing romantic ballads too: Neha Kakkar |work=The Asian Age |last=Tarannum |first=Asira |date=15 March 2016 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe becomes omnipresent in numerous recreated song which stirred up several hatred comments to her for \"ruining\" the original songs.<ref name=classics>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/music/bollywood-recreated-songs-old-original-classics-remixes-5246828/ |title=Music industry explains why Bollywood is recreating old songs |work=The Indian Express |last=Shekhar |first=Mimansha |date=27 August 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Conversely, she favored the recreations of old songs and opined that they have been well appreciated and loved by the audience when \"good old melodies are given a new touch\"; \"The only drawback is people have high expectations as they love the old songs. At times, it can go down since there have been songs that haven't done well so one has to be very careful\".<ref name=punjabi>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/entertainment/bollywood-kala-chashma-singer-neha-kakkar-launches-original-punjabi-song-378150|title=Kala chashma singer Neha Kakkar launches original Punjabi song |publisher=India TV News |date=21 April 2017 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/recreating-old-songs-positive-711695.html |title=Recreating old songs a positive trend: Neha Kakkar |work=[[Deccan Herald]] |last=Kumar |first=Ashwani |date=9 January 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Further elaborating her take on this trend, she said, \"even if people claim it takes away the original song, they still hear it. There is a lot of negative audience on social media. They would comment on anything. But they are the ones who are dancing on all these songs\".<ref name=classics/> Most of the re-created songs received mixed reactions from fans of the original version.<ref name=punjabi/>\n\nKakkar mentioned that she prefers to release singles over albums since \"releasing music albums is not a feasible idea for musicians, as it requires a lot of money\".<ref name=albums/> While she admits that a Bollywood actor featuring in a music video helps an independent song reach a wider audience, she prefers that the musicians feature in the music videos themselves.<ref name=albums>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/music/neha-kakkar-on-why-musicians-prefer-singles-over-albums/story-eAIOaDzvxtJudgD2oAUirI.html |title=Neha Kakkar on why musicians prefer singles over albums |work=Hindustan Times |last=Goyal |first=Samath |date=10 April 2017 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> She also expresses her fondness towards live performance since she \"loves being on stage and when I hear fans chant my name and ask for an encore\".<ref name=watchout/> According to her, live performance prove the real talent of a singer as there no \"no scope for making or rectifying mistakes on stage; you just need to go on. In the recording studio, we can have several retakes\".<ref name=watchout/>\n\n===Influence===\n[[File:Neha Kakkar and Sonu Kakkar at Global Indian Music Academy Awards.jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=Neha Kakkar and Sonu Kakkar smiling|Sonu Kakkar (left) has significantly influence Neha Kakkar (right) and her music]]\nKakkar admits that she has always looked up to her elder sister Sonu, as her singing inspiration and she \"guides me on how to sing particular songs\".<ref name=versatile/> She named her brother Tony as a constant pillar of strength.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/neha-kakkars-siblings-join-her-on-sa-re-ga-ma-pa-lil-champs/articleshow/58416560.cms |title=Neha Kakkar's siblings join her on Sa Re Ga Ma Pa Li'l Champs |work=The Times of India |date=28 April 2017 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nApart from her siblings, Kakkar mentioned [[Arijit Singh]], [[Shreya Ghoshal]] and [[Sunidhi Chauhan]] as her favorite music artists. \"Like, there have been singers like [[Kishore Kumar]], [[Mohammed Rafi]] and [[Lata Mangeshkar]] who have defined music and left their legacies, I believe they fit in the same league\".<ref name=key/> Also inspired by [[Sonu Nigam]]'s versatility, she \"hopes\" that she will be able to sing diverse kinds of music.<ref name=bio/> In spite of the musical artists, she called [[Govinda]] an \"inspiration\" and a \"role model\" to her. \"I have been following him since an age where we ourselves do not have an understanding about life\".<ref name=govinda>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioandmusic.com/entertainment/editorial/news/180927-neha-kakkar-receives-the-biggest-compliment |title=Neha Kakkar receives the biggest compliment from Govinda on Indian Idol 10|work=Radio and Music |date=27 September 2018 |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nKakkar has also been influenced by many artists outside the country like [[John Mayer]], [[Demi Lovato]] and [[Ariana Grande]].<ref name=candid>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/songstress-neha-kakkar-reveals-that-marshmallows-describe-her-best/story-Cg5XyqvXxSQcTIlGEBCdlJ.html |title=The best part about being a playback singer in Bollywood is that it gives good faces to my voice!\" Neha Kakkar gets candid |work=Hindustan Times |last=Dhankar |first=Riya |date=14 July 2018 |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> She named [[Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan]], [[Sukhwinder Singh]], [[Kavitha Krishnamurthy]] and [[Honey Singh]] as some of her favorite and inspiring vocalists.<ref name=watchout/>\n\n==Public image==\n[[File:Neha Kakkar SRK.jpg|thumb|left|upright|200px|alt=Neha Kakkar laughing while hugging Shah Rukh Khan|The public describes Kakkar as a \"bubbly\" person]]\nKnown for experimenting with her style and image, Kakkar's music and fashion sense are noted by the media. According to [[Republic TV|Republic World]], she has an \"impeccable taste\" in fashion, and \"whatever she wears becomes a trend\" from her \"outlandish outfits, voguish hairstyles or flawless makeup\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.republicworld.com/entertainment-news/bollywood-news/neha-kakkars-inspired-hairstyles-you-can-wear-on-any-occasion.html |title=Neha Kakkar Inspired Uber-chic Hairstyles You Can Style For Any Occasion; See Pics |publisher=Republic World |last=Rai |first=Aishwarya |date=26 February 2020 |access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> Neha feels her happy-go-lucky attitude reflects in her work too making her one of the most flamboyant singers today.<ref name=singforthem/> \"I am a very energetic. I have fun during shootings and on stage. If you do things from heart, it reaches out to people\".<ref name=singforthem/>\n\nIn 2015, Kakkar was noted as the \"innovative brain\" behind the selfie videos of several songs that got viral on [[YouTube]], which she started in 2012 with the song \"Botal Khol\" from ''[[Prague (2013 film)|Prague]]''.<ref name=key/> The trend which media attributed to her, was considered by her as \"lively interaction with her fans\" which have sound, actions and emotions.<ref name=key/> Rewarding her with the title \"Expression Queen\", Aastha Banan from ''[[Mid Day]]'' wrote: \"She sings looking into her phone, smiling sensuously and raising her eyebrows to the tune, emoting skillfully which helped her earn the title\".<ref name=selfie>{{cite news|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/how-neha-kakkars-decision-to-give-the-selfie-a-twist-changed-her-life/17034179 |title=How Neha Kakkar's Decision To Give The Selfie A Twist Changed Her Life |work=Mid Day |last=Banan |first=Aastha |date=17 March 2016 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe is credited as a \"lively performer\" on stage. In an interview with ''[[The Hindu]]'' she said, \"People look at my expressions and gestures and the way I move on stage. If I am entertained by what I sing, it will entertain those around me\".<ref name=key>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/Versatility-is-key/article16960487.ece |title=Versatility is key |newspaper=The Hindu |last=Yadav |first=Sidharth |date=29 December 2016 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Also, the media calls her an \"emotional person\" where she is seeing shedding tears a lot of times on the singing competition shows.<ref name=key/> During the shows, Kakkar was often brutally trolled as a \"cry baby\" on social media for frequently crying on-screen, to which she admits that she is a \"proud emotional girl\" who does not wish to become \"heartless\" or \"emotionless\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/indian-idol-10-neha-kakkar-gets-trolled-for-being-a-cry-baby-gives-a-befitting-reply/articleshow/64963029.cms |title=Indian Idol 10: Neha Kakkar gets trolled for being a cry baby; gives a befitting reply |work=The Times of India |date=12 July 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nKakkar is very active on social media platforms including Instagram, Twitter, Facebook and Youtube page, where she interact with her fans and regularly post updates about her life.<ref name=selfie/><ref name=Instagram>{{cite news|url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/neha-kakkar-becomes-first-indian-musician-to-receive-instagram-award-2341727.html |title=Neha Kakkar Becomes First Indian Musician to Receive Instagram Award |publisher=News18 |date=11 October 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> She is one of the most followed Indian artiste on Instagram.<ref name=acting/> In October 2019, she received the Instagram trophy, celebrating the first Indian musician and the fifth Indian to reach the milestone.<ref name=Instagram/> In 2017, Kakkar was included in the list of 35 boldest entrepreneurs of India who are changing the game in various industries.<ref name=ShakiraB/> The same year she appeared in the ''[[Forbes]]'' Celebrity 100, a list based on income and popularity of India's celebrities. She was listed at the sixty-fourth spot in 2017 and twenty-ninth spot in 2019.<ref>{{cite news|title=2017 Celebrity 100 List&nbsp;\u2013 Forbes India|url=https://www.forbesindia.com/lists/2017-celebrity-100/1665/7 |work=Forbes India|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=2019 Celebrity 100 List&nbsp;\u2013 Forbes India|url=https://www.forbesindia.com/lists/2019-celebrity-100/1819/all |work=Forbes India|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact and recognition==\nKakkar's work has received praise from several artists. Her co-judge in ''[[Indian Idol]]'', [[Vishal Dadlani]] praised her for the \"impressive progress\" from a contestant to judge of the same reality show.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/music/vishal-dadlani-neha-kakkar-indian-idol-10-5235707/ |title=Indian Idol 10 judge Vishal Dadlani: We should take tips from Neha Kakkar |work=The Indian Express |date=27 June 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Singer [[Jassi Gill]] named Kakkar as his favorite playback singer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/neha-kakkar-on-indian-idol-co-judges-wondered-what-i-was-doing-here/19891172 |title=Neha Kakkar On Indian Idol: Co-Judges Wondered What I Was Doing Here |work=Mid Day |last=Lulla |first=Sonia |date=15 October 2018 |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nHer work has been recognized by several actors, where [[Kriti Sanon]] stated that every time she hears Kakkar singing, \"it brings a smile to my face\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestatesman.com/entertainment/music/neha-kakkar-s-voice-makes-kriti-sanon-smile-1495777076.html |title=Neha Kakkar's voice makes Kriti Sanon 'smile' |work=[[The Statesman (India)|The Statesman]] |date=26 May 2017 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Actor [[Sara Ali Khan]] revealed that she is a huge fan of Kakkar and an \"inspiration\" to her weight-loss.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tv/neha-kakkars-celebrity-fan/articleshow/66598572.cms |title=Neha Kakkar's celebrity fan |work=Mumbai Mirror |date=13 November 2018 |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> [[Govinda]] referred her as the \"female-Govinda\" due to her expressions and stated that she is a \"very good singer and a nice human being\".<ref name=govinda/> Choreographer [[Farah Khan]] defined her as a \"Rock Star\" while actress [[Mandira Bedi]] referred her as the next \"Indian [[Shakira]]\".<ref name=watchout>{{cite news|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/content/361335/a-voice-watch-for.html |title=A voice to watch out for |work=Deccan Herald |last=Rao |first=Bindu Gopal |date=5 October 2013 |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKakkar and actor [[Himansh Kohli]] were in a romantic relationship since 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/bollywood/report-the-truth-about-neha-kakkar-s-relationship-with-himansh-kohli-revealed-2604084|title=The truth about Neha Kakkar's relationship with Himansh Kohli revealed|work=[[Daily News and Analysis|DNA]]|author=DNA Web Team|date=12 April 2018|accessdate=4 May 2018}}</ref> In September 2018, they officially announced their relationship on national television and revealed that they will tie the knot soon.<ref name=Himansh/> However, three months later, the couple broke-up which was hinted by an emotional message she posted on Instagram.<ref name=Himansh>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/television/reality-tv/story/neha-kakkar-posts-emotional-note-after-breakup-with-himansh-breaks-down-on-indian-idol-10-sets-1410477-2018-12-16 |title=Neha Kakkar posts emotional note after break-up with Himansh, breaks down on Indian Idol 10 sets |work=India Today |date=16 December 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Bombay Times]]'' she opened up about her life post the split and revealed how she regrets \"making her personal life so public\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/television/celebrity/story/neha-kakkar-regrets-breaking-up-with-himansh-kohli-publicly-here-s-why-1475967-2019-03-12 |title=Neha Kakkar regrets breaking up with Himansh Kohli publicly. Here's why |work=India Today |date=12 March 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> In August 2019, she shared an alarming post on Instagram about \"depression\" and \"thinking of ending her life\" after rumours of affair with an Indian Idol contestant surfaced.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/music/neha-kakkar-writes-post-on-ending-life-after-rumours-of-affair-with-indian-idol-contestant-surface/story-ort67XVhttyZ6yCHNvePuL.html |title=Neha Kakkar writes post on 'ending life' after rumours of affair with Indian Idol contestant surface |work=Hindustan Times |date=11 August 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and achievements==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=col |Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Ceremony\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Nominated Song\n! scope=\"col\" | Film\n! scope=\"col\" |Result\n! class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference(s)}}\n|- \n| 2011\n!scope=\"row\"| [[58th Filmfare Awards South]]\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Female Playback Singer \u2013 Kannada|Best Female Playback Singer \u2013 Kannada]]\n| \"Horage Haradide Thamassu\" \n| ''[[Thamassu]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"| <ref name=FFAS11nom/>\n|-\n| 2016\n!scope=\"row\"| 3rd [[PTC Punjabi Music Awards]]\n| Best Duo / Group\n| colspan=\"2\"| \"Pyaar Te Jaguar\" <small>(Shared with Harshit Tomar)</small>\n|{{nom}}\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PEKvYmURO-Y |title=Best Duo / Group - PTC Punjabi Music Awards 2016 - Nominations - PTC Punjabi |publisher=YouTube |date=18 May 2016 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n!scope=\"row\"| 4th [[PTC Punjabi Music Awards]]\n| Best Duet Vocalist\n| colspan=\"2\"| \"Patt Lainge\" <small>(Shared with [[Gippy Grewal]])</small>\n|{{won}}\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oll2vnUppiw |title=Best Duet Vocalists - Nominations - PTC Punjabi Music Awards 2017 |publisher=YouTube |date=15 March 2017 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Zee Rishtey Awards]]\n| Favourite Judge Award\n| colspan=\"2\"| ''[[Sa Re Ga Ma Pa L'il Champs 2017]]''<br/><small>(Shared with [[Himesh Reshammiya]] and [[Javed Ali]])</small>\n|{{won}}\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"| <ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/tv-awards/zee-rishtey-awards/2017/112 |title=Zee Rishtey Awards 2017 Winner |work=The Times of India |date=20 February 2017 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n!scope=\"row\"| [[10th Mirchi Music Awards]]\n| [[Mirchi Music Award for Female Vocalist of The Year|Female Vocalist of The Year]]\n| \"Badri Ki Dulhania\"\n| ''[[Badrinath Ki Dulhania]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"| <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mirchimusicawards.com/hindi-2017/nominations/|title=Nominations - Mirchi Music Awards 2017|publisher=MirchiMusicAwards|access-date=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2020\n!scope=\"row\"| 15th Mirchi Music Awards\n| colspan=\"3\"| Mirchi Social Media Icon of the year\n| {{won}}\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"| <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mirchimusicawards.com/hindi-2020/winners-hindi-2020/ |title=Winners - Mirchi Music Awards 2020|publisher=MirchiMusicAwards|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=col |Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" | Notes\n! class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference(s)}}\n|- \n| 2010\n!scope=\"row\"|''[[Isi Life Mein...!]]''\n| Sam\n| \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=IsiLifeMein/>\n|-\n|2016\n!scope=\"row\"|''[[Tum Bin II]]''\n| Herself\n|Special appearance in song \"Nachna Aaonda Nahin\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/television/tun-bin-2-mouni-roy-is-making-tv-stars-dance-to-nachna-aunda-nahi-watch-video-4368209/ |title=Tum Bin 2: Mouni Roy is making TV stars dance to Nachna Aunda Nahi |work=The Indian Express |last=Jain |first=Arushi |date=10 November 2016 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Role\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Indian Idol]] \u2013 Season 2''\n| Contestant\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Jo Jeeta Wohi Super Star]] \u2013 Season 1''\n| Challenger<ref name=watchout/>\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Comedy Circus|Comedy Circus Ke Taansen]] \u2013 Season 2''\n| Various characters<ref name=watchout/>\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Comedy Nights with Kapil]]''\n| Special appearance\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Comedy Classes]]''\n| Special appearance\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Comedy Nights Bachao]]''\n| Special appearance\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Comedy Nights Live]]'' \n| Special appearance\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The Kapil Sharma Show]]''\n| Special appearance\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Voice India Kids]]''\n| Special appearance\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Sa Re Ga Ma Pa L'il Champs 2017]]''\n| Judge\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Indian Idol]] \u2013 Season 10''\n| Judge\n|-\n| 2019\n| '' [[Indian Idol]] \u2013 Season 11''\n| Judge\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Super Dancer]]''\n| Special appearance\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Khatra Khatra Khatra]]''\n| Special appearance\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[The Kapil Sharma Show]]''\n| Special appearance\n|-\n|}\n\n== Selected discography ==\n{{Main|List of songs recorded by Neha Kakkar}}\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* \"Second Hand Jawani\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Cocktail (2012 film)|Cocktail]]'' (2012)\n* \"Sunny Sunny\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Yaariyan (2014 film)|Yaariyan]]'' (2014)\n* \"London Thumakda\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Queen (soundtrack)|Queen]]'' (2014)\n* \"Kar Gayi Chull\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Kapoor & Sons]]'' (2016)\n* \"Mile Ho Tum\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Fever (2016 film)|Fever]]'' (2016)\n* \"Kala Chashma\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Baar Baar Dekho]]'' (2016)\n* \"Badri Ki Dulhania\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Badrinath Ki Dulhania]]'' (2017)\n* \"Cheez Badi\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Machine (2017 film)|Machine]]'' (2017)\n* \"[[Dilbar (song)|Dilbar]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Satyameva Jayate]]'' (2018)\n* \"[[Aankh Maarey]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Simmba]]'' (2018)\n* \"[[Coca Cola Tu|Coca Cola]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Luka Chuppi]]'' (2019)\n* \"O Saki Saki\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Batla House]]'' (2019)\n* \"Ek Toh Kum Zindagani\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Marjaavaan]]'' (2019)\n* \"Garmi\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Street Dancer 3D]]'' (2020)\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of Indian playback singers]]\n*[[List of most-viewed Indian music videos on YouTube]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://nehakakkar.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|3833975|name=Neha Kakkar}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kakkar, Neha}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bollywood playback singers]]\n[[Category:Indian female film singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Women musicians from Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language singers]]\n[[Category:Bengali-language singers]]\n[[Category:Punjabi-language singers]]\n[[Category:Indian Idol participants]]\n[[Category:Indian pop-folk singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Indian playback singer}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{Close paraphrasing|source=|date=April 2020}}\n{{Cleanup-PR|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Neha Kakkar\n| image              = Neha Kakka hate Story.jpg\n| caption            = Kakkar at the song launch event of \"Aashiq Banaya Aapne\" from ''[[Hate Story 4]]'', 2018\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=y|1988|6|6}}\n| birth_place        = [[Rishikesh]], [[Uttarakhand]]), India\n| residence          = \n| nationality        = Indian\n| occupation         = Singer\n| years_active       = 2006\u2013present\n| home_town          = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| relatives       = {{plain list|\n* [[Sonu Kakkar]] (sister)\n* [[Tony Kakkar]] (brother) }}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background         = solo_singer\n| genre              = {{flatlist|\n* Pop\n* [[Filmi]]\n}}\n| instrument          = Vocals\n| label               = {{flatlist|\n* [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]\n* [[Zee Music Company]]\n* Desi Music Factory\n}}\n| website            = {{URL|nehakakkar.com}}\n}}\n| signature          = \n}}\n'''Neha Kakkar''' (born 6 June 1988) is an Indian singer. She began performing at religious events at the age of four and participated in the second season of the singing reality show, ''[[Indian Idol]],'' in which she was eliminated early in the show. After several struggles in her career, she made her Bollywood debut as a chorus singer in the film ''[[Meerabai Not Out]]'' (2008). She rose to prominence upon the release of the dance track \"Second Hand Jawani\" from ''[[Cocktail (2012 film)|Cocktail]]'' (2012), which was followed by several other popular party songs including \"Sunny Sunny\" from ''[[Yaariyan (2014 film)|Yaariyan]]'' (2014) and \"London Thumakda\" from ''[[Queen (soundtrack)|Queen]]'' (2014).\n\nAfterwards, she mostly performed party tracks like \"Aao Raja\" from ''[[Gabbar Is Back]]'' (2015), \"Tu Isaq Mera\" from ''[[Hate Story 3]]'' (2015), \"Humne Pee Rakhi Hai\" from ''[[Sanam Re]]'' (2016) and \"Kar Gayi Chull\" from ''[[Kapoor & Sons]]'' (2016). She proved her versatility in musical range with the release of \"Mile Ho Tum\" from ''[[Fever (2016 film)|Fever]]'' (2016) which topped the [[List of most-viewed Indian videos on YouTube|list of most-viewed Bollywood songs on YouTube]]. She then released several chart-busters which made into the same list, including \"[[Aankh Maarey]]\" from ''[[Simmba]]'' (2018), \"[[Dilbar (song)|Dilbar]]\" from ''[[Satyameva Jayate]]'' (2018), \"Badri Ki Dulhania\" from ''[[Badrinath Ki Dulhania]]'' (2017), \"Cheez Badi\" from ''[[Machine (2017 film)|Machine]]'' (2017), \"Kala Chashma\" for the film ''[[Baar Baar Dekho]]''(2016)  and the non-film song \"[[Nikle Currant]]\", where all crossed over six hundred million views. Similarly, \"Dilbar\" marks the first Indian song to reach number three spot on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' YouTube Music Chart.\n\nFrom 2017 onwards, Kakkar, primarily, in collaboration with [[Tanishk Bagchi]], became more associated with the trend of remaking old to very recent songs, which resulted in several backlashes targeted for the singer though she personally favored the trend of recreations and opined that they have been well appreciated. Apart from playback singing, Kakkar has appeared in several music videos and as a judge on several television reality shows including ''Indian Idol'', the same show she participated during her early days. On these shows, she has been trolled in social media several times, for crying on-screen, while she openly admits that she is a \"proud emotional girl\". She has appeared two times in ''[[Forbes]]''' Celebrity 100 of India (2017 and 2019).\n\n==Early life==\nKakkar was born on 6 June 1988 in [[Rishikesh]], [[Uttarakhand]].<ref name=\"birthday\">{{cite news | url=http://www.india.com/showbiz/neha-kakkar-birthday-special-the-queen-of-blockbuster-hits-turns-28-1237772/ | title=Neha Kakkar birthday special: The Queen of blockbuster hits turns 28 | author=India.com Entertainment Desk|date=6 June 2016 | work=India.com | accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=bio>{{cite web | url=http://www.sify.com/indianidol2/contestants/neha/ | title=Indian Idol profile - Neha Kakkar | work=[[Sify]] | accessdate=11 February 2014 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140608031628/http://www.sify.com/indianidol2/contestants/neha/ | archivedate=8 June 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> She is the younger sister of playback singer [[Sonu Kakkar]] and singer-composer [[Tony Kakkar]].<ref name=Tony>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Tony-Kakkar-One-gets-a-lot-more-popularity-as-a-singer-than-a-composer/articleshow/53209745.cms |title=Tony Kakkar: One gets a lot more popularity as a singer than a composer |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=17 March 2017 |access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> During the early days, her father, Rishikesh Kakkar used to sell [[samosa]] outside a college for a living while her mother Niti Kakkar is a homemaker.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/indian-idols-neha-kakkar-and-aditya-to-get-married-on-valentines-day-she-calls-his-mother-sasu-maa-watch-hilarious-video/articleshow/73232215.cms |title=Indian Idol's Neha Kakkar and Aditya to get married on Valentine's Day? She calls his mother 'Sasu maa' |work=The Times of India |date=14 January 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mensxp.com/entertainment/celebrities/72373-from-samosa-sellers-daughter-to-a-singing-sensation-neha-kakkar-shows-hard-work-always-pays-off.html |title=From Samosa Seller's Daughter To A Singing Sensation, Neha Kakkar Shows Hard Work Always Pays Off |publisher=MensXP |last=Chakraborty |first=Rimi |date=28 January 2020 |access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> In the city, Kakkar shared a rented one-room house with her whole family, in which they used to sleep and simultaneously convert to a kitchen by putting a table.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siasat.com/neha-kakkars-journey-1-room-house-luxurious-bungalow-1850567/ |title=Neha Kakkar's journey from 1-room house to luxurious bungalow |work=[[The Siasat Daily]] |author=Sameer |date=9 March 2020 |access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 90s, Kakkar along with her family moved to [[Delhi]], in order to try her luck in singing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/neha-kakkar-delhi-is-full-of-talent-dilliwaale-hote-hi-kamal-ke-hain/articleshow/64931780.cms |title=Neha Kakkar: Delhi is full of talent, Dilliwaale hote hi kamal ke hain |work=The Times of India |last=Kaushik |first=Divya |date=11 July 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> At that time, the family was reeling under a financial crisis.<ref name=Tony/> Hence, hoping to \"contribute\" to the family, Kakkar, at the age of four, with her siblings started performing at local gatherings and religious event which she credited for \"boosting\" her self-confidence.<ref name=versatile>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/screen/versatile-notes-neha-kakkar/ |title=Versatile Notes: 'Neha Kakkar' |work=The Indian Express |date=27 February 2015 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> \"I only sang [[bhajans]] from four to sixteen years. I would attend four to five [[jagran]]s in a day, which became my training ground\".<ref name=Delhi>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/music/i-am-a-delhiite-and-my-journey-as-a-singer-began-in-the-city-neha-kakkar/story-rkeSDF4dRSfustXi93WEAJ.html |title=I am a Delhiite and my journey as a singer began in the city: Neha Kakkar |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |last=Arora |first=Naina |date=7 April 2017 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Having music talent at home, she never felt the need to get any formal training in singing.<ref name=ShakiraB>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/289083 |title=Meet the Indian Shakira of the Film Industry - Neha Kakkar |magazine=[[Entrepreneur (magazine)|Entrepreneur]] |last=Sabharwal |first=Punita |date=11 February 2017 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> In 2004, she moved to [[Mumbai]] with her brother, Tony Kakkar.<ref name=Tony/>\n\nIn 2006, at the age of sixteen, Kakkar auditioned for the second season of ''[[Indian Idol]]'' where she got eliminated early in the show.<ref name=ShakiraB/> Being the youngest participant, she was naturally \"pampered\" on the sets, and recalls that the show gave her \"great memories and fame\".<ref name=watchout/> Commenting on her short-journey, she stated, \"I feel, whatever happens, happens for a reason. I am just glad the way my journey worked out. It has been a tremendous learning experience\".<ref name=acting>{{cite news|url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/singer-neha-kakkar-willing-to-take-up-acting-but-theres-a-condition-1878043 |title=Singer Neha Kakkar Willing To 'Take Up Acting.' But, There's A Condition |work=NDTV |date=4 July 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> According to her, people \"appreciated my voice saying that you sing well but nobody ever told me that I am a great singer\".<ref name=Shakira/> Hence, determined to prove that she can sing, Kakkar worked on \"polishing\" her voice afterwards.<ref name=Shakira/>\n\n==Career==\n===2006\u20132012: Career beginnings and breakthrough with ''Cocktail''===\nKakkar anticipated that her participation in ''Indian Idol'' and the association with her brother, Tony Kakkar, would translate her career into playback singing.<ref name=SRK/> However, five years post ''Indian Idol'', Kakkar fails to gather any work in Bollywood films which she believes is due to her \"negligence in pleading the music directors and producers, unlike the rest of participants from the show\".<ref name=SRK/> Hence, she became herself more occupied with the concerts and event performances that took her \"across the world\".<ref name=watchout/> According to her, during this phase she started getting recognised and people started referring her as the \"Jai Mata Di girl\".<ref name=watchout/>\n\n[[File:Neha Kakkar at Cinemax.jpg|thumb|left|upright|200px|alt=Neha Kakkar smiling looking at camera wearing a white top|Kakkar at the premiere event of Premiere of Marathi film ''Janiva'', 2015]]\nIn 2008, she launched her debut album ''Neha The Rockstar'' with music by [[Meet Bros]] in which she performed some romantic songs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/television/celebrity/story/indian-idol-10-judge-neha-kakkar-is-unrecognisable-in-this-viral-video-1286726-2018-07-16 |title=Indian Idol 10 judge Neha Kakkar is unrecognisable in this viral video |publisher=India Today |date=16 July 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> During the time, she recorded for a music album, ''Romeo Juliet'' composed by her brother, Tony Kakkar. The song \"Mohabbat Hai\" from the album received limited recognition from the listeners which resulted in the offer to render her first Kotak Mahindra jingle, \"Mera Jaisa Koi Mere Zindagi Main Aaye\".<ref name=SRK>{{cite news|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/report/slide-show-1-neha-kakkar-on-shah-rukh-khan-anthem/20120320.htm#4 |title=Thought of meeting SRK makes me go weak in the knees |publisher=Rediff.com |last=N |first=Patcy |date=20 March 2012 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nA year later, a friend of Kakkar called her from the studio of composer [[Sandesh Shandilya]], who was looking for a new voice to record the song \"Hai Rama\" from ''[[Meerabai Not Out]]'' (2008). The following year, she was featured in an [[A.R. Rahman]]'s composition, the theme song of ''[[Blue (2009 film)|Blue]]'' (2009) where she provided the chorus vocals for the song.<ref name=watchout/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/entertainment-others/blue-music-review-cocktail-of-genres/ |title=Blue music review: Cocktail of genres |work=The Indian Express |date=15 September 2009 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=SRK/> She then lent her voice for the title track of the Hindi-language soap opera''[[Na Aana Is Des Laado]]'' (2009) which holds a special place in her heart, as the \"song was a touching experience since it focused on women\".<ref name=watchout/>\n\nIn 2010, Kakkar made her film debut with [[Sooraj Barjatya]]'s film ''[[Isi Life Mein...!]]'' (2010) in which she played the role of a college student.<ref name=IsiLifeMein/> The film received negative reviews from critics and was a box office failure.<ref name=IsiLifeMein>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.filmfare.com/features/7-singers-who-shouldnt-act-9544-6.html |title=7 singers who shouldn't act |magazine=Filmfare |last=Fernandes |first=Bradley |date=19 June 2015 |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> The same year, she debuted in both the Kannada and Telugu music industry by performing a total of four tracks for [[Sandeep Chowta]].<ref name=Thamassu/><ref name=Kedi/> She lent her voice for the title track of the Kannada film ''[[Thamassu]]'' and the song \"Nodu Baare\" alongside [[Master Saleem]], which were appreciated by the reviewers from ''[[Bangalore Mirror]]'' and the former resulted in her only [[Filmfare Awards South]] nomination as the [[Filmfare Award for Best Female Playback Singer \u2013 Kannada|Best Female Playback Singer]].<ref name=FFAS11nom>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-06-11/hyderabad/29646891_1_filmfare-awards-tarun-rai-filmfare-trophy|title=Idea Filmfare awards ceremony on July 2|date=11 Jun 2011|accessdate=31 July 2013|work=The Times Of India}}</ref><ref name=Thamassu>{{cite news|url=https://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/reviews/thamassu-chowta-is-back/articleshow/21884459.cms |title=Thamassu: Chowta is back! |work=[[Bangalore Mirror]] |date=26 April 2010 |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> Also, the same publication complimented Kakkar's rendition in the song \"Neeve Na Neeve Na\" and \"Jaaniya Jaane\" from the Telugu film ''[[Kedi (2010 film)|Kedi]]''.<ref name=Kedi>{{cite news|url=https://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/reviews/kedi-sandeeps-best-in-a-long-time/articleshow/21942832.cms |title=Kedi : Sandeep's best, in a long time! |work=Bangalore Mirror |date=26 April 2010 |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe had a single Bollywood release in 2011, Sandeep Chowta-composed \"Woh Ek Pal\", performed alongside Arijit Dutta, which lacked the needed coverage from the music listeners.<ref name=SRK/> She then made an appearance in the second season of ''[[Comedy Circus|Comedy Circus Ke Taansen]]'' alongside [[Kapil Sharma]] and [[Ali Asgar]] which she considered an \"amazing experience\" where the \"atmosphere on the sets was positive and the jokes had us all cracking up. I particularly enjoyed it since I am bubbly and always smiling\".<ref name=watchout/> The following year, her collaboration with [[Pritam]] for the dance track \"Second Hand Jawani\" from ''[[Cocktail (2012 film)|Cocktail]]'' proved to be a major breakthrough for Kakkar. The song went to become popular among the music listeners, though it received mixed to negative reviews from critics, calling it a \"distraction amidst rest of the album\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/cocktail/songs/music-critic-review/ |title=Cocktail Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=18 June 2012 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-movies/music-reviews/cocktail-music-review/|title=Cocktail Music Review |publisher=Koimoi |author=Shivi |date=20 June 2012 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> Besides, she got a \"tremendous response\" for her \"Shah Rukh Khan Anthem\" on [[Youtube]], for which [[Shah Rukh Khan]] thanked her by saying he \"loved the song\".<ref name=watchout/>\n\n===2013\u20132016: Chart-busters with ''Fever'' and ''Baar Baar Dekho''===\nKakkar's first release of 2013, \"Botal Khol\" from ''[[Prague (2013 film)|Prague]]'' met with controversy, where Central Board of Film Certification raised objection on the song citing that its lyrics contain double meaning.<ref name=Shakira/> In an interview with ''[[Hindustan Times]]'', Kakkar stated, \"We do discuss with our lyricists when we are recording. But we cannot stop making or singing such songs just because certain sections of the society do not like it\".<ref name=Shakira>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/feels-great-to-be-compared-to-shakira-neha-kakkar/story-msQdOYQ0MinjkxNADGM5rL.html;jsessionid=95B7C0B6319D829E627E7F4FB284B5C2 |title=Feels great to be compared to Shakira: Neha Kakkar |work=Hindustan Times |last=Sen |first=Torsha |date=14 November 2013 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> This was followed by a [[Sachin-Jigar]]'s item number composed for ''[[Ramaiya Vastavaiya]]''.<ref name=Ramaiya/> Titled \"Jadoo Ki Jhappi\", the song met with negative reception from critics, where Rajiv Vijayakar from [[Bollywood Hungama]] rated the song as weakest track on the album and wrote: \"Kakkar cannot impart the magic that marks the vocals of the most successful item numbers\".<ref name=Ramaiya>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/ramaiya-vastavaiya/songs/music-user-reviews/music-review-of-ramaiya-vastavaiya-by-rajiv-vijayakar/|title=Ramaiya Vastavaiya - Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Vijayakar |first=Rajiv |date=14 November 2013 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> She next collaborated with Pritam for another item song \"Dhating Nach\", performed alongside [[Nakash Aziz]] and [[Shefali Alvares]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/report/review-phata-poster-nikhla-hero-music-is-entertaining/20130907.htm |title=Review: Phata Poster Nikhla Hero music is entertaining |publisher=Rediff.com |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=7 September 2013 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n2014 saw the rise of Kakkar with the release of three popular songs.<ref name=high>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Neha-Kakkar-ends-the-year-on-a-high-note/articleshow/45511546.cms |title=Neha Kakkar ends the year on a high note |work=The Times of India |last=Kotwani |first=Hiren |date=15 December 2014 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/2014-when-actors-turned-playback-singers/articleshow/45532648.cms |title=2014: When actors turned playback singers |newspaper=[[The Economic Times]] |date=16 December 2014 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> The first release of the year was a collaboration with [[Yo Yo Honey Singh]] for the film ''[[Yaariyan (2014 film)|Yaariyan]]'', for which, ''[[The Times of India]]'' credited her as the \"perfect voice for dance numbers\".<ref name=high/><ref name=high/> The duo collaborated once again for Bollywood's first trance number, \"Manali Trance\" from ''[[The Shaukeens]]'', which was recorded in twenty-five minutes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-yo-yo-honey-singh-s-manali-trance-from-the-shaukeens-released-lisa-haydon-rocks-it-2026958 |title=Yo Yo Honey Singh's 'Manali Trance' from 'The Shaukeens' released, Lisa Haydon rocks it! |work=Daily News and Analysis |date=17 October 2014 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> The song mainly received positive reviews from critics, due to the \"innovative contribution to this Bollywood-unfriendly genre\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-movies/music-reviews/the-shaukeens-music-review/ |title=The Shaukeens Music Review |publisher=Koimoi |last=Redkar |first=Surabhi |date=30 October 2014 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> Her first work with [[Amit Trivedi]], a wedding song titled \"London Thumakda\" was released in the same year, which received positive reviews from music critics. Mohar Basu from [[Koimoi]] wrote: \"Singers [did] a brilliant job as this one remains the album most energetic number\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-movies/music-reviews/queen-music-review/ |title=Queen Music Review |publisher=Koimoi |last=Basu |first=Mohar |date=4 February 2014 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> On the occasion of Mother's Day, Kakkar shot and released a song for her mother which resulted in positive response among the audience.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/I-had-to-deal-with-a-lot-of-vicious-rumours-Kanika-Kapoor/articleshow/35150257.cms |title=Neha Kakkar's song on her mother goes viral |work=The Times of India |last=Chatterjee |first=Swasti |date=16 May 2014 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Neha Kakkar Fever.jpg|thumb|right|upright|200px|alt=Neha Kakkar smiling wearing a black top|Kakkar at the audio release event of ''[[Fever (2016 film)|Fever]]'', 2016]]\nKakkar's first release of 2015 came with \"Ek Do Teen Chaar\" from ''[[Ek Paheli Leela]]'' which was composed, penned and co-sung by Tony Kakkar.<ref name=EkPaheliLeela/> The song received mainly negative reviews from critics, calling it a \"failed attempt on a potential number\".<ref name=EkPaheliLeela>{{cite news|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/report/review-ek-paheli-leelas-music-is-worth-a-listen/20150321.htm |title=Review: Ek Paheli Leela's music is worth a listen |publisher=Rediff.com |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=21 March 2015 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Rajiv Vijayakar from Bollywood Hungama, reviewing the soundtrack album wrote: \"Neha tries to be saucy and coquettish, but the composition lacks the strength to let this mood bloom\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/ek-paheli-leela/songs/music-user-reviews/music-review-of-ek-paheli-leela-by-rajiv-vijayakar/ |title=Ek Paheli Leela Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Vijayakar |first=Rajiv |date=22 March 2015 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> She then collaborated with the music composer duo, Amjad-Nadeem where she performed the tracks \"Naughty No 1\" and \"Daaru Peeke Dance\" for ''[[Barkhaa]]'' and ''[[Kuch Kuch Locha Hai]]'' respectively; where none of them performed well commercially.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/Kuch-Kuch-Locha-Hai/articleshow/47198410.cms |title=Kuch Kuch Locha Hai - Music Review |work=The Times of India |last=Fernandes |first=Kasmin |date=8 May 2014 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> Followed by few other \"dull\" releases, Kakkar received recognition with her \"seductive\" performance in the [[Meet Bros Anjjan]]-composed \"Tu Isaq Mera\" from ''[[Hate Story 3]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/hate-story-music-review-a-typical-t-series-score-that/article_05dee8e2-8fc5-11e5-aa4b-33712b4911a9.html |title='Hate Story 3' Music Review: A Typical T-Series Score That Is a Mixed Bag |work=India West |last=Vijayakar |first=RM |date=20 November 2015 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Her last release of the year was \"Tukur Tukur\" from ''[[Dilwale (2015 film)|Dilwale]]'', an \"energetic number\" which captures the spirit of [[Goa]] and performed alongside [[Arijit Singh]], [[Kanika Kapoor]], [[Siddharth Mahadevan]] and [[Nakash Aziz]] as a separate, video version of the song.<ref name=Dilwale/> Kakkar, an ardent fan of [[Shah Rukh Khan]], expressed her excitement once she figured out the song was recorded for his album, \"When I recorded \"Tukur Tukur\", I did not know it was for his film. I am over the moon\".<ref name=sex>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Neha-Kakkar-Honey-Singh-says-my-voice-is-like-sex/articleshow/50342445.cms |title=Neha Kakkar: Honey Singh says my voice is like sex |work=The Times of India |last=Basu |first=Mohar |date=28 December 2015 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> However, the version was criticised for Kakkar's \"jarring\" vocals and the \"lack of the sheer exuberance\" compared to that of the audio version performed by Singh.<ref name=Dilwale>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/dilwale-music-review-a-seamless-blend-of-classical-and-contemporary/article_790d09e0-a28d-11e5-b62a-0bb63a4dd8ac.html |title='Dilwale' Music Review: A Seamless Blend of Classical and Contemporary Numbers |work=India West |last=Vijayakar |first=RM |date=14 December 2015 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The same year, she featured alongside [[Shilpa Shetty]] in the video single \"Wedding Da Season\", composed by [[Amaal Malik]], as insisted by the choreographer [[Ganesh Acharya]], who saw her performing off-screen.<ref name=sex/>\n\n2016 was a successful year for Kakkar where she performed the popular song \"Mile Ho Tum\" from the film ''[[Fever (2016 film)|Fever]]'', composed, written and co-sung by Tony Kakkar, which she considers as the \"closest song to her heart\".<ref name=Fever/> Credited as the [[List of most-viewed Indian videos on YouTube|most-viewed Bollywood song on Youtube]], the song received a positive response from music critics and audience. Reviewing the song from ''[[The Times of India]]'', Mohar Basu wrote: \"Kakkar shows her versatile vein with [the song, where] she keeps her voice subtle and sticks to the mellow meter\".<ref name=Fever>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/Fever/articleshow/52987308.cms |title=Music Review: Fever |work=The Times of India |last=Basu |first=Mohar |date=17 January 2017 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Also, she contributed to the soundtrack album of ''[[Baar Baar Dekho]]'' by performing the wedding-song \"Kala Chashma\" which became the \"the party anthem of the year\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/baar-baar-dekho-music-review-katrina-kaif-sidharth-malhotra-film-is-not-all-about-kala-chashma-2961322/ |title=Baar Baar Dekho music review: Katrina Kaif, Sidharth Malhotra film is not all about Kala Chashma |work=The Indian Express |date=7 September 2016 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Included in the list of the most viewed Bollywood songs on Youtube, \"Kala Chashma\" was admired by the critics for its use of \"dub-step, hip-hop beats, and a very groovy bass\" while Surabhi Redkar from Koimoi applauded Kakkar's \"powerful vocals\" in the song.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/baar-baar-dekho-special/story/baar-baar-dekho-music-review-kala-chashma-jasleen-royal-333937-2016-08-08 |title=Baar Baar Dekho music review: Jasleen Royal, welcome to Bollywood! |publisher=India Today |last=Mukherjee |first=Tatsam |date=8 August 2016 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-movies/music-reviews/baar-baar-dekho-music-review/ |title=Baar Baar Dekho Music Review |publisher=Koimoi |last=Redkar |first=Surabhi |date=16 August 2016 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> She worked with Epic Bhangra for the film ''[[Sanam Re]]'', where they released the song \"Humne Pee Rakhi Hai\", a mix of club and EDM which was deemed as an \"unncesessary addition to the album\" and Kakkar vocals were noted to be \"awfully shrill\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/sanam-re-music-review-decent-album-lyrics-and-vocals-could/article_f07996fe-b8b5-11e5-839b-7b7ce2f790eb.html |title='Sanam Re' Music Review: Decent Album, Lyrics and Vocals Could've Been Better |publisher=India West |last=Vijayakar |first=RM |date=11 January 2016 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> She also provided her vocals for an additional song in the album, \"Akkad Bakkad\", a [[rap]] song performed alongwith [[Badshah (rapper)|Badshah]] to celebrate the music of the film.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Mumbais-musical-date-with-Lucky-Ali-on-February-14/articleshow/50863077.cms|title=Divya Khosla Kumar wraps up 'Sanam Re' with Badshah's rap song|work=[[The Times Of India]]|accessdate=7 February 2016}}</ref> Apart from lending her vocals to the party song, \"Kar Gayi Chull\" from ''[[Kapoor & Sons]]'', which was a remake of the Haryanvi track \"Chull\" and her first recording for [[Dharma Productions]], Kakkar performed several other recreated songs during the year including, \"Maahi Ve\"\u2013a remake of the song \"Maahi Ve\" from ''[[Kaante]]'' (2002)\u2013 and \"O Janiya\"\u2013a remake of the song \"Kaante Nahi Kat Te\" from ''[[Mr. India (1987 film)|Mr. India]]'' (1987)\u2013for ''[[Wajah Tum Ho]]'' and ''[[Force 2]]'' respectively.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/kapoor-and-sons-music-review-nothing-exciting-in-this-album-apart-from-kar-gayi-chull-2656386.html |title='Kapoor and Sons' music review: Nothing exciting in this album apart from 'Kar Gayi Chull' |work=Firstpost |last=Swetha |first=Ramakrishnan |date=5 March 2016 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Joginder Tuteja from Bollywood Hungama opined that Kakkar's rendition in the former is \"decent but not as good as the original\" while he noted that \"Kakkar, the young woman is just the right follow up to [[Alisha Chinai]] as her voice comes with the right mix of naughtiness and seduction\" in the latter.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/wajah-tum-ho/songs/music-critic-review/ |title=Wajah Tum Ho Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=16 November 2017 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/force-2/songs/music-critic-review/ |title=Force 2 Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=7 November 2017 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u2013present: Collaboration with Bagchi and series of remade songs===\n2017 marks Kakkar's first collaboration with [[Tanishk Bagchi]] which resulted in the rehashing of several Bollywood songs in the coming years. Their first release, \"Badri Ki Dulhania\" from ''[[Badrinath Ki Dulhania]]'' performed with [[Dev Negi]], [[Ikka Singh]] and [[Monali Thakur]] has few segments lifted from the [[Shankar-Jaikishen]] classic, \"Chalat Musafir\" from ''[[Teesri Kasam]]'' (1966).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/badrinath-ki-dulhania-music-review/article_b5bafd2c-035b-11e7-9c97-43fd39d90102.html |title='Badrinath Ki Dulhania' Music Review |work=India West |last=Vijayakar |first=RM |date=7 March 2017 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The song was well received by the critics, where Swetha Ramakrishnan from ''[[Firstpost]]'' commended the overall work for \"living up to previous expectations\" while announcing Kakkar as the \"perfect fit for the title track\".<ref name=Badri>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/badrinath-ki-dulhania-music-review-this-album-has-chart-buster-written-all-over-it-3283908.html |title=Badrinath Ki Dulhania music review: This album has chart-buster written all over |work=Firstpost |last=Ramakrishnan |first=Swetha |date=16 February 2017 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The version became an instant chart-buster among the audience and was included in the [[list of most-viewed Indian videos on YouTube]] with over 500 million views.<ref name=Badri/> This was followed by another chart-buster by the duo, \"Cheez Badi\" from ''[[Machine (2017 film)|Machine]]'', a re-creation of the 1994-released ''[[Mohra]]'' song \"Tu Cheez Badi Hai Mast Mast\", which got mixed reviews from critics; Vijayakar from India West found Kakkar to be \"strictly okay to ho-hum as co-singer\" while the re-creation \"lacks the obnoxious quotient\" of the original.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/machine-music-review-mechanical-songs-sans-feeling/article_a0fc8276-0427-11e7-b059-37539bd8dffd.html |title='Machine' Music Review: Mechanical Songs Sans Feeling |work=India West |last=Vijayakar |first=RM |date=8 March 2017 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Her next release was the dance song \"[[Main Tera Boyfriend]]\" from ''[[Raabta (film)|Raabta]]'' which was a recreation of a non-film track \"Na Na Na Na\".<ref name=PP/> Reviewing the song from [[Daily News and Analysis]], Prachita Pandey wrote: \"Kakkar complements [Arijit] well, but we felt her vocals to be a bit toned down in terms of energy\".<ref name=PP>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-sushant-singh-rajput-kriti-sanon-are-slaying-it-with-their-hot-bods-and-killer-moves-in-main-tera-boyfriend-2447109|title=Sushant Singh Rajput and Kriti sanon are slaying it with their hot bod and killer moves in main tera boyfriend|author=Prachita Pandey|publisher=Daily News and Analysis|date=22 May 2017|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref> The trend was carried forward with ''[[Judwaa 2]]'' where she rendered two remake songs, co-composed by Sandeep Shirodkar and [[Anu Malik]] and one original song composed by Meet Bros. Tuteja from Bollywood Hungama credited Kakkar and co-singers for \"retaining the impact as the originals\" with their vocals in the remade songs of the same name while complimenting her as \"quite impressive in her trademark naughty vocals\" in the song \"Aa Toh Sahi\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/judwaa-2/songs/music-critic-review/ |title=Judwaa 2 Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=12 September 2017 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> During the year, she appeared as a judge alongside [[Himesh Reshammiya]] and [[Javed Ali]] in the [[Sa Re Ga Ma Pa L'il Champs 2017|sixth season]] of the Indian television music competition, ''[[Sa Re Ga Ma Pa L'il Champs]]''.<ref name=Saregama/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tv/nia-sharma-beats-alia-bhatt-and-katrina-kaif-becomes-asias-third-sexiest-woman/articleshow/55961395.cms |title=Neha Kakkar to judge Sa Re Ga Ma Pa little champs |work=[[Mumbai Mirror]] |date=14 December 2016 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Reminiscing her participation in the music competition, Kakkar stated, \"I started from being a contestant to now becoming a judge. Being on another side of the table is a different feeling altogether. I travel back in time and see myself standing there and being scared of judges remarks\".<ref name=Delhi/><ref name=Saregama>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/television/himesh-reshammiya-neha-kakkar-sa-re-ga-ma-pa-judge-4426987/ |title=Himesh Reshammiya, Neha Kakkar to judge Sa Re Ga Ma Pa Li'l Champs |work=The Indian Express |date=14 December 2016 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> The year ended with another recreated song, \"Mehbooba\" from ''[[Fukrey Returns]]'', originally performed by [[Mohammed Rafi]] ''[[Dharam Veer (film)|Dharam Veer]]'' (1977), where the new version was commended for the \"stylish rendition\" of the singers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/music-review-fukrey-returns/articleshow/61878735.cms |title=Music Review: Fukrey Returns |last=Sen |first=Debarati |work=The Times of India |date=2 December 2017 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Neha Kakkar High Fever.jpg|thumb|left|upright|alt=Neha Kakkar smiling wearing a red top|Kakkar on the show ''High Fever'', 2018]]\nKakkar's first release of 2018 was the [[Yo Yo Honey Singh]]'s \"Chhote Chhote Peg\" from''[[Sonu Ke Titu Ki Sweety]]'', a remake of the [[Anand Raj Anand]]-composition \"Tote Tote Ho Gaya\" from ''[[Bichhoo]]'' (2000), and was positively received by the music critics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/sonu-ke-titu-ki-sweety/songs/music-critic-review/ |title=Sonu Ke Titu Ki Sweety Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=19 February 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> This was followed by Bagchi's recreation of \"Aashiq Banaya Apne\" included in the soundtrack album of ''[[Hate Story 4]]'', originally performed by [[Himesh Reshamiyya]] and [[Shreya Ghoshal]].<ref name=HateStory4/> Umesh Punwani from Koimoi feels that Kakkar did a \"good job\" while trying to \"give her voice a new shape\" although the retained original portions of the song were the only good thing about this version.<ref name=HateStory4>{{cite web|url=https://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-movies/music-reviews/hate-story-4-music-review-the-only-good-thing-is-himesh-reshammiyas-retained-voice/ |title=Hate Story 4 Music Review: The Only Good Thing Is Himesh Reshammiya's Retained Voice |publisher=Koimoi |last=Punwani |first=Umesh |date=8 March 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> The duo collaborated for five other projects, from which \"[[Dilbar (song)|Dilbar]]\" from''[[Satyameva Jayate]]'' and \"[[Aankh Maarey]]\" from ''[[Simmba]]'' became popular with music listeners, both songs reaching the [[list of most-viewed Indian videos on YouTube]] and the former being the first Indian song to reach number three on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' YouTube Music Chart.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/music/dhvani-bhanushali-s-dilbar-tops-billboard-youtube-chart/story-GxYPXbKZxa7g3cx7lm9wRK.html |title=Dhvani Bhanushali's Dilbar tops Billboard YouTube chart |work=Hindustan Times |last=Mukherjee |first=Shreya |date=13 July 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Benjamin |first1=Jeff |title=Bollywood Channel T-Series Is YouTube's First To Hit 100 Million Subscribers |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffbenjamin/2019/05/30/bollywood-youtube-channel-t-series-first-to-hit-100-million-subscribers/ |accessdate=11 June 2019 |work=[[Forbes]] |date=30 May 2019}}</ref> Devansh Sharma from ''[[Firstpost]]'' praised the former and remarked, \"The soul of the new track is Neha Kakkar who brings a sensual-yet-never-raunchy appeal through her vocals. Her range allows her to switch from the meditative stanzas to the uninhibited chorus like a chameleon\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/bollywood/satyamev-jayate-music-review-neha-kakkars-dilbar-is-a-clear-winner-but-tanishk-bagchi-can-do-better-4944461.html |title=Satyamev Jayate music review: Neha Kakkar's Dilbar is a clear winner, but Tanishk Bagchi can do better |work=Firstpost |last=Devansh |first=Sharma |date=13 August 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Apart from rendering the folk pop song \"Dholida\" from ''[[Loveyatri]]'' alongside [[Udit Narayan]] and [[Palak Muchhal]], Kakkar performed a traditional-themed-contemporary Punjabi track \"Bhangra Da Sajda\" from ''[[Veere Di Wedding]]'', composed and co-sung by [[Shashwat Sachdev]].<ref name=loveyatri/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/veere-di-wedding/songs/music-critic-review/ |title=Veere Di Wedding Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=16 May 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> ''Firstpost'' in its review of ''[[Badhaai Ho]]'' appraised Kakkar's accent and \"good support in the smaller\" part of the song \"Nain Na Jodeen\" while crediting \"her versatility\" in the [[Bhangra (music)|bhangra number]] \"Morni Banke\" which was a remake of the 2010 release of [[Panjabi MC]]'s song of the same name.<ref name=BadhaaiHo>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/bollywood/badhaai-ho-music-review-a-fun-inventive-album-replete-with-hilarious-lyrics-quirky-compositions-5392311.html |title=Badhaai Ho music review: A fun, inventive album replete with hilarious lyrics, quirky compositions |work=Firstpost |last=Devansh |first=Sharma |date=17 October 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> The trend continued with the item number \"Gali Gali\" included in the Hindi-dubbed version of the Kannada film ''[[K.G.F: Chapter 1]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mouni Roy teases a glimpse of her KGF dance number, Gali Gali. Watch here |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/mouni-roy-teases-a-glimpse-of-her-kfg-dance-number-gali-gali-watch-here/story-HjsohSRSCzx8xOwMOcyb2I.html |accessdate=22 December 2018 |work=Hindustan Times |date=11 December 2018 |language=en}}</ref> During the year, she appeared as a judge alongside [[Anu Malik]] and [[Vishal Dadlani]] in the tenth season of the Indian television music competition, ''[[Indian Idol]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/television/neha-kakkar-indian-idol-5153931/ |title=Neha Kakkar returns to Indian Idol, this time as a judge |work=The Indian Express |date=27 April 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n2019 began with the release of three remade songs in collaboration with Bagchi. \"[[Chamma Chamma]]\", recreated for the film ''[[Fraud Saiyyan]]''\u2013original composition from the film ''[[China Gate (1998 film)|China Gate]]'' (1998)\u2013was considered \"memorable\", while \"[[Coca Cola Tu]]\" from ''[[Luka Chuppi]]'' and \"[[Hauli Hauli]]\" from ''[[De De Pyaar De]]'' were acknowledged by some critics for giving the songs \"a new flavor\" though other critics disapproved her latest trend of \"annoying\" association in the remade song. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/fraud-saiyaan/critic-review/fraud-saiyaan-movie-review/ |title=Fraud Saiyaan Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |date=18 January 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/luka-chuppi/songs/music-critic-review/ |title=Luka Chuppi Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=25 February 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koimoi.com/reviews/luka-chuppi-movie-review-its-all-about-finding-the-missing-story-sense-substance/|title=Luka Chuppi Movie Review: It's All About Finding The Missing Story, Sense & Substance! |publisher=Koimoi |last=Punwani |first=Umesh |date=2 March 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> The year marks her first collaboration with [[Vishal Mishra]] and [[Vishal-Shekhar]], where she performed the female version of \"Ki Honda Pyaar\" from ''[[Jabariya Jodi]]'' for the former and \"The Hook Up Song\" for the latter, which was well received by critics; Sen from ''The Times of India'' wrote: \"The zing in Neha Kakkar\u2019s sultry voice adds to the flirty feel of the upbeat track\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/music-review-student-of-the-year-2/articleshow/69159568.cms |title=Music review: Student of the Year 2 |work=The Times of India |last=Sen |first=Debarti |date=9 May 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/jabariya-jodi-music-review-sidharth-malhotra-parineeti-chopras-film-offers-a-soulless-fragmented-album-lacking-in-originality-7117101.html |title=Jabariya Jodi music review: Sidharth Malhotra, Parineeti Chopra's film offers a soulless, fragmented album, lacking in originality |work=Firstpost |last=Ganguly |first=Pratishruti |date=7 August 2019 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The trio of Kakkar, Bagchi and the dancer [[Nora Fatehi]] re-united for two other chart-buster songs, \"O Saki Saki\" from ''[[Batla House]]'' and \"Ek Toh Kum Zindagani\" from ''[[Marjaavaan]]''. The former being a remake of ''[[Musafir (2004 film)|Musafir]]'''s \"Saaki\", originally performed by [[Sukhwinder Singh]] and [[Sunidhi Chauhan]] was criticised for the lack of \"power\" compared to the original version.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/inspirational-but-not-memorable/article29112356.ece |title='Mission Mangal' and 'Batla House' music review: Inspirational, but not memorable |newspaper=The Hindu |last=Nair |first=Vipin |date=16 August 2019 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/music-review-marjaavaan/articleshow/71970281.cms|title=Music review: Marjaavaan |work=The Times of India |last=Sen |first=Debarti |date=9 November 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> During the year, Kakkar lent her voice for the foot-tapping club number \"Dheeme Dheeme\", composed by Bagchi and the romantic love song \"Tu Hi Yaar Mera\" composed by [[Rochak Kohli]], in which Tuteja from Bollywood Hungama appraised her \"different avatar\" in the latter.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/pati-patni-aur-woh-2/songs/music-critic-review/ |title=Pati Patni Aur Woh Music Review |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |last=Tuteja |first=Joginder |date=30 December 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\n===Voice===\nKakkar possesses a [[contralto]] [[vocal range]] and has the ability to reach E5 note.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4eDK5UBWV1A |title=Neha Kakkar : Voice Study & Deep Analysis - Vocal Range - Paarth singh |publisher=YouTube |date=20 February 2019 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> Her voice has been described several times in the media as \"distinct\", \"unique\", \"chirpy\", \"seductive\" and \"partially nasal\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodmusicreviews.com/artist-neha-kakkar/ |title=Artist of the Week \u2013 Neha Kakkar |work=Bollywood Music Reviews |author=KK |date=17 October 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=popular/> She did not take any formal vocal training.<ref name=versatile/> In an interview with ''[[The Indian Express]]'' she said, \"The fact that I am not formally trained never really bothered me. There were times I knew it could have been a brownie point, had I been trained but it never pulled me back\".<ref name=versatile/> Believing that she needs to be distinctive to be noticed from the crowd of competition, she keeps \"practicing by learning to sing songs that catch her fancy\" since her voice is her \"USP\".<ref name=watchout/>\n\nShe believes she modulates her song differently for each song, even if it falls under the same genre.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianewengland.com/2018/04/i-treat-every-song-like-a-different-character-neha/ |title=I treat every song like a different character: Neha |work=India New England News |date=23 April 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> According to her, from the very early days of her career, she has constantly been trying to \"polish\" her voice which helps her enhancing the required voice modulation.<ref name=Shakira/> She also admits that she tries hard to \"put a difference\" in her voice texture for each recording to avoid her voice being stereotyped.<ref name=singforthem>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/music/neha-kakkar-singer-best-songs-recreated-hits-music-mixtape-punjabi-5037351/ |title=Neha Kakkar: I put something new in my songs, that's why everyone wants me to sing for them |work=The Indian Express |last=Shekhar |first=Mimansha |date=9 April 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> After listening to her in the song \"Manali Trance\", she was asked by many fans if she was high when she recorded it, to which she replied, \"' I don't drink or smoke. It's just my vocal interpretation of it\".<ref name=selfie/>\n\nHer vocal tone has been subjected to mixed reviews. ''The Times of India'' complimented \"the kind of variation\" she brings to her voice in the song, \"Cheez Badi\" and wrote: \"While she is known for her party numbers, this song sees her voice take on a rather sultry quality that perfectly matches the mood of the song\".<ref name=popular>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/photo-features/neha-kakkar-songs-10-most-popular-songs-of-the-singer/sunny-sunny/photostory/62190992.cms |title=Neha Kakkar Songs: 10 most popular songs of the singer |work=The Times of India |date=17 February 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Shreya Paul, from ''Firstpost'', while reviewing the album of ''[[De De Pyaar De]]'' critised her \"auto-tuned\" vocals and the attempt to \"sound sexy and naughty\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/de-de-pyaar-de-music-review-soundtrack-of-ajay-devgns-film-is-as-problematic-as-the-plot-seems-to-be-6636041.html |title=De De Pyaar De music review: Soundtrack of Ajay Devgn's film is as problematic as the plot seems to be |work=Firstpost |last=Paul |first=Shreya |date=16 May 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Similarly, R.M. Vijayakar from ''India West'' calls her vocal performances \"petulant\" which she \"mistakes for sensuality\".<ref name=loveyatri>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/loveyatri-music-review-t-series-after-eons-a-riveting-score/article_a02ad7ce-c7eb-11e8-81d6-6f4d9eadedd6.html |title='LoveYatri' Music Review (T-Series): After Eons, a Riveting Score for a Film with a New Pair |work=India West |last=Vijayakar |first=R.M |date=4 October 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> In the media, Kakkar is often regarded as the voice behind the \"party anthems\" and \"recreated songs\". Due to the numerous contribution to the same, ''[[Gulf Today]]'' regarded her voice as an overexposure to the \"recreation and fast-paced songs\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gulftoday.ae/culture/2020/03/08/budding-bollywood-singer-says-voices-of-female-singers-need-to-be-heard |title=Budding Bollywood singers say more female voices need to be heard |work=Gulf Today |date=8 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Musical style===\n[[File:Neha Kakkar Birthday Bash.jpg|thumb|left|upright|alt=Neha Kakkar smiling looking at camera wearing a black dress|Kakkar mostly performed dance tracks and re-created songs]]\nKakkar's music contains elements of pop, hip hop, and R&B. She admits that she has mostly performed dance numbers which she believes suits her voice the most and complements her energetic vibe, though she expressed her desire to experiment other genres including \"soft romantic\" songs.<ref name=sex/><ref name=ballads/> Also, she appreciates Sufi music and expresses her fondness over the music of [[Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan]].<ref name=bio/>\n\nDevansh Sharma of ''Firstpost'' applauded Kakkar's \"impressive range\" where she can switch from a \"Dilbar\" to the romantic track \"Nain Na Jodeen\".<ref name=BadhaaiHo/>. Similarly, ''The Times of India'' complimented her musical \"diversity\" where she \"nails\" the melodic song, Mile Ho Tum, to \"perfection\" with the different \"intensity and passion\" as compared to her energetic numbers\".<ref name=popular/> ''[[The Asian Age]]'' notes that party songs have become almost synonymous with Kakkar and she should consider breaking away from the \"mould\".<ref name=ballads>{{cite news|url=https://www.asianage.com/music/i-d-love-sing-romantic-ballads-too-neha-kakkar-629 |title=I'd love to sing romantic ballads too: Neha Kakkar |work=The Asian Age |last=Tarannum |first=Asira |date=15 March 2016 |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe becomes omnipresent in numerous recreated song which stirred up several hatred comments to her for \"ruining\" the original songs.<ref name=classics>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/music/bollywood-recreated-songs-old-original-classics-remixes-5246828/ |title=Music industry explains why Bollywood is recreating old songs |work=The Indian Express |last=Shekhar |first=Mimansha |date=27 August 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Conversely, she favored the recreations of old songs and opined that they have been well appreciated and loved by the audience when \"good old melodies are given a new touch\"; \"The only drawback is people have high expectations as they love the old songs. At times, it can go down since there have been songs that haven't done well so one has to be very careful\".<ref name=punjabi>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/entertainment/bollywood-kala-chashma-singer-neha-kakkar-launches-original-punjabi-song-378150|title=Kala chashma singer Neha Kakkar launches original Punjabi song |publisher=India TV News |date=21 April 2017 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/recreating-old-songs-positive-711695.html |title=Recreating old songs a positive trend: Neha Kakkar |work=[[Deccan Herald]] |last=Kumar |first=Ashwani |date=9 January 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Further elaborating her take on this trend, she said, \"even if people claim it takes away the original song, they still hear it. There is a lot of negative audience on social media. They would comment on anything. But they are the ones who are dancing on all these songs\".<ref name=classics/> Most of the re-created songs received mixed reactions from fans of the original version.<ref name=punjabi/>\n\nKakkar mentioned that she prefers to release singles over albums since \"releasing music albums is not a feasible idea for musicians, as it requires a lot of money\".<ref name=albums/> While she admits that a Bollywood actor featuring in a music video helps an independent song reach a wider audience, she prefers that the musicians feature in the music videos themselves.<ref name=albums>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/music/neha-kakkar-on-why-musicians-prefer-singles-over-albums/story-eAIOaDzvxtJudgD2oAUirI.html |title=Neha Kakkar on why musicians prefer singles over albums |work=Hindustan Times |last=Goyal |first=Samath |date=10 April 2017 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> She also expresses her fondness towards live performance since she \"loves being on stage and when I hear fans chant my name and ask for an encore\".<ref name=watchout/> According to her, live performance prove the real talent of a singer as there no \"no scope for making or rectifying mistakes on stage; you just need to go on. In the recording studio, we can have several retakes\".<ref name=watchout/>\n\n===Influence===\n[[File:Neha Kakkar and Sonu Kakkar at Global Indian Music Academy Awards.jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=Neha Kakkar and Sonu Kakkar smiling|Sonu Kakkar (left) has significantly influence Neha Kakkar (right) and her music]]\nKakkar admits that she has always looked up to her elder sister Sonu, as her singing inspiration and she \"guides me on how to sing particular songs\".<ref name=versatile/> She named her brother Tony as a constant pillar of strength.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/neha-kakkars-siblings-join-her-on-sa-re-ga-ma-pa-lil-champs/articleshow/58416560.cms |title=Neha Kakkar's siblings join her on Sa Re Ga Ma Pa Li'l Champs |work=The Times of India |date=28 April 2017 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nApart from her siblings, Kakkar mentioned [[Arijit Singh]], [[Shreya Ghoshal]] and [[Sunidhi Chauhan]] as her favorite music artists. \"Like, there have been singers like [[Kishore Kumar]], [[Mohammed Rafi]] and [[Lata Mangeshkar]] who have defined music and left their legacies, I believe they fit in the same league\".<ref name=key/> Also inspired by [[Sonu Nigam]]'s versatility, she \"hopes\" that she will be able to sing diverse kinds of music.<ref name=bio/> In spite of the musical artists, she called [[Govinda]] an \"inspiration\" and a \"role model\" to her. \"I have been following him since an age where we ourselves do not have an understanding about life\".<ref name=govinda>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioandmusic.com/entertainment/editorial/news/180927-neha-kakkar-receives-the-biggest-compliment |title=Neha Kakkar receives the biggest compliment from Govinda on Indian Idol 10|work=Radio and Music |date=27 September 2018 |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nKakkar has also been influenced by many artists outside the country like [[John Mayer]], [[Demi Lovato]] and [[Ariana Grande]].<ref name=candid>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/songstress-neha-kakkar-reveals-that-marshmallows-describe-her-best/story-Cg5XyqvXxSQcTIlGEBCdlJ.html |title=The best part about being a playback singer in Bollywood is that it gives good faces to my voice!\" Neha Kakkar gets candid |work=Hindustan Times |last=Dhankar |first=Riya |date=14 July 2018 |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> She named [[Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan]], [[Sukhwinder Singh]], [[Kavitha Krishnamurthy]] and [[Honey Singh]] as some of her favorite and inspiring vocalists.<ref name=watchout/>\n\n==Public image==\n[[File:Neha Kakkar SRK.jpg|thumb|left|upright|200px|alt=Neha Kakkar laughing while hugging Shah Rukh Khan|The public describes Kakkar as a \"bubbly\" person]]\nKnown for experimenting with her style and image, Kakkar's music and fashion sense are noted by the media. According to [[Republic TV|Republic World]], she has an \"impeccable taste\" in fashion, and \"whatever she wears becomes a trend\" from her \"outlandish outfits, voguish hairstyles or flawless makeup\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.republicworld.com/entertainment-news/bollywood-news/neha-kakkars-inspired-hairstyles-you-can-wear-on-any-occasion.html |title=Neha Kakkar Inspired Uber-chic Hairstyles You Can Style For Any Occasion; See Pics |publisher=Republic World |last=Rai |first=Aishwarya |date=26 February 2020 |access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> Neha feels her happy-go-lucky attitude reflects in her work too making her one of the most flamboyant singers today.<ref name=singforthem/> \"I am a very energetic. I have fun during shootings and on stage. If you do things from heart, it reaches out to people\".<ref name=singforthem/>\n\nIn 2015, Kakkar was noted as the \"innovative brain\" behind the selfie videos of several songs that got viral on [[YouTube]], which she started in 2012 with the song \"Botal Khol\" from ''[[Prague (2013 film)|Prague]]''.<ref name=key/> The trend which media attributed to her, was considered by her as \"lively interaction with her fans\" which have sound, actions and emotions.<ref name=key/> Rewarding her with the title \"Expression Queen\", Aastha Banan from ''[[Mid Day]]'' wrote: \"She sings looking into her phone, smiling sensuously and raising her eyebrows to the tune, emoting skillfully which helped her earn the title\".<ref name=selfie>{{cite news|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/how-neha-kakkars-decision-to-give-the-selfie-a-twist-changed-her-life/17034179 |title=How Neha Kakkar's Decision To Give The Selfie A Twist Changed Her Life |work=Mid Day |last=Banan |first=Aastha |date=17 March 2016 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe is credited as a \"lively performer\" on stage. In an interview with ''[[The Hindu]]'' she said, \"People look at my expressions and gestures and the way I move on stage. If I am entertained by what I sing, it will entertain those around me\".<ref name=key>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/Versatility-is-key/article16960487.ece |title=Versatility is key |newspaper=The Hindu |last=Yadav |first=Sidharth |date=29 December 2016 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Also, the media calls her an \"emotional person\" where she is seeing shedding tears a lot of times on the singing competition shows.<ref name=key/> During the shows, Kakkar was often brutally trolled as a \"cry baby\" on social media for frequently crying on-screen, to which she admits that she is a \"proud emotional girl\" who does not wish to become \"heartless\" or \"emotionless\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/indian-idol-10-neha-kakkar-gets-trolled-for-being-a-cry-baby-gives-a-befitting-reply/articleshow/64963029.cms |title=Indian Idol 10: Neha Kakkar gets trolled for being a cry baby; gives a befitting reply |work=The Times of India |date=12 July 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nKakkar is very active on social media platforms including Instagram, Twitter, Facebook and Youtube page, where she interact with her fans and regularly post updates about her life.<ref name=selfie/><ref name=Instagram>{{cite news|url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/neha-kakkar-becomes-first-indian-musician-to-receive-instagram-award-2341727.html |title=Neha Kakkar Becomes First Indian Musician to Receive Instagram Award |publisher=News18 |date=11 October 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> She is one of the most followed Indian artiste on Instagram.<ref name=acting/> In October 2019, she received the Instagram trophy, celebrating the first Indian musician and the fifth Indian to reach the milestone.<ref name=Instagram/> In 2017, Kakkar was included in the list of 35 boldest entrepreneurs of India who are changing the game in various industries.<ref name=ShakiraB/> The same year she appeared in the ''[[Forbes]]'' Celebrity 100, a list based on income and popularity of India's celebrities. She was listed at the sixty-fourth spot in 2017 and twenty-ninth spot in 2019.<ref>{{cite news|title=2017 Celebrity 100 List&nbsp;\u2013 Forbes India|url=https://www.forbesindia.com/lists/2017-celebrity-100/1665/7 |work=Forbes India|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=2019 Celebrity 100 List&nbsp;\u2013 Forbes India|url=https://www.forbesindia.com/lists/2019-celebrity-100/1819/all |work=Forbes India|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact and recognition==\nKakkar's work has received praise from several artists. Her co-judge in ''[[Indian Idol]]'', [[Vishal Dadlani]] praised her for the \"impressive progress\" from a contestant to judge of the same reality show.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/music/vishal-dadlani-neha-kakkar-indian-idol-10-5235707/ |title=Indian Idol 10 judge Vishal Dadlani: We should take tips from Neha Kakkar |work=The Indian Express |date=27 June 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Singer [[Jassi Gill]] named Kakkar as his favorite playback singer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/neha-kakkar-on-indian-idol-co-judges-wondered-what-i-was-doing-here/19891172 |title=Neha Kakkar On Indian Idol: Co-Judges Wondered What I Was Doing Here |work=Mid Day |last=Lulla |first=Sonia |date=15 October 2018 |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nHer work has been recognized by several actors, where [[Kriti Sanon]] stated that every time she hears Kakkar singing, \"it brings a smile to my face\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestatesman.com/entertainment/music/neha-kakkar-s-voice-makes-kriti-sanon-smile-1495777076.html |title=Neha Kakkar's voice makes Kriti Sanon 'smile' |work=[[The Statesman (India)|The Statesman]] |date=26 May 2017 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Actor [[Sara Ali Khan]] revealed that she is a huge fan of Kakkar and an \"inspiration\" to her weight-loss.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tv/neha-kakkars-celebrity-fan/articleshow/66598572.cms |title=Neha Kakkar's celebrity fan |work=Mumbai Mirror |date=13 November 2018 |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> [[Govinda]] referred her as the \"female-Govinda\" due to her expressions and stated that she is a \"very good singer and a nice human being\".<ref name=govinda/> Choreographer [[Farah Khan]] defined her as a \"Rock Star\" while actress [[Mandira Bedi]] referred her as the next \"Indian [[Shakira]]\".<ref name=watchout>{{cite news|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/content/361335/a-voice-watch-for.html |title=A voice to watch out for |work=Deccan Herald |last=Rao |first=Bindu Gopal |date=5 October 2013 |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKakkar and actor [[Himansh Kohli]] were in a romantic relationship since 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/bollywood/report-the-truth-about-neha-kakkar-s-relationship-with-himansh-kohli-revealed-2604084|title=The truth about Neha Kakkar's relationship with Himansh Kohli revealed|work=[[Daily News and Analysis|DNA]]|author=DNA Web Team|date=12 April 2018|accessdate=4 May 2018}}</ref> In September 2018, they officially announced their relationship on national television and revealed that they will tie the knot soon.<ref name=Himansh/> However, three months later, the couple broke-up which was hinted by an emotional message she posted on Instagram.<ref name=Himansh>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/television/reality-tv/story/neha-kakkar-posts-emotional-note-after-breakup-with-himansh-breaks-down-on-indian-idol-10-sets-1410477-2018-12-16 |title=Neha Kakkar posts emotional note after break-up with Himansh, breaks down on Indian Idol 10 sets |work=India Today |date=16 December 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Bombay Times]]'' she opened up about her life post the split and revealed how she regrets \"making her personal life so public\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/television/celebrity/story/neha-kakkar-regrets-breaking-up-with-himansh-kohli-publicly-here-s-why-1475967-2019-03-12 |title=Neha Kakkar regrets breaking up with Himansh Kohli publicly. Here's why |work=India Today |date=12 March 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> In August 2019, she shared an alarming post on Instagram about \"depression\" and \"thinking of ending her life\" after rumours of affair with an Indian Idol contestant surfaced.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/music/neha-kakkar-writes-post-on-ending-life-after-rumours-of-affair-with-indian-idol-contestant-surface/story-ort67XVhttyZ6yCHNvePuL.html |title=Neha Kakkar writes post on 'ending life' after rumours of affair with Indian Idol contestant surface |work=Hindustan Times |date=11 August 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and achievements==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=col |Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Ceremony\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Nominated Song\n! scope=\"col\" | Film\n! scope=\"col\" |Result\n! class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference(s)}}\n|- \n| 2011\n!scope=\"row\"| [[58th Filmfare Awards South]]\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Female Playback Singer \u2013 Kannada|Best Female Playback Singer \u2013 Kannada]]\n| \"Horage Haradide Thamassu\" \n| ''[[Thamassu]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"| <ref name=FFAS11nom/>\n|-\n| 2016\n!scope=\"row\"| 3rd [[PTC Punjabi Music Awards]]\n| Best Duo / Group\n| colspan=\"2\"| \"Pyaar Te Jaguar\" <small>(Shared with Harshit Tomar)</small>\n|{{nom}}\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PEKvYmURO-Y |title=Best Duo / Group - PTC Punjabi Music Awards 2016 - Nominations - PTC Punjabi |publisher=YouTube |date=18 May 2016 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n!scope=\"row\"| 4th [[PTC Punjabi Music Awards]]\n| Best Duet Vocalist\n| colspan=\"2\"| \"Patt Lainge\" <small>(Shared with [[Gippy Grewal]])</small>\n|{{won}}\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oll2vnUppiw |title=Best Duet Vocalists - Nominations - PTC Punjabi Music Awards 2017 |publisher=YouTube |date=15 March 2017 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Zee Rishtey Awards]]\n| Favourite Judge Award\n| colspan=\"2\"| ''[[Sa Re Ga Ma Pa L'il Champs 2017]]''<br/><small>(Shared with [[Himesh Reshammiya]] and [[Javed Ali]])</small>\n|{{won}}\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"| <ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/tv-awards/zee-rishtey-awards/2017/112 |title=Zee Rishtey Awards 2017 Winner |work=The Times of India |date=20 February 2017 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n!scope=\"row\"| [[10th Mirchi Music Awards]]\n| [[Mirchi Music Award for Female Vocalist of The Year|Female Vocalist of The Year]]\n| \"Badri Ki Dulhania\"\n| ''[[Badrinath Ki Dulhania]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"| <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mirchimusicawards.com/hindi-2017/nominations/|title=Nominations - Mirchi Music Awards 2017|publisher=MirchiMusicAwards|access-date=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2020\n!scope=\"row\"| 15th Mirchi Music Awards\n| colspan=\"3\"| Mirchi Social Media Icon of the year\n| {{won}}\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"| <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mirchimusicawards.com/hindi-2020/winners-hindi-2020/ |title=Winners - Mirchi Music Awards 2020|publisher=MirchiMusicAwards|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=col |Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" | Notes\n! class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference(s)}}\n|- \n| 2010\n!scope=\"row\"|''[[Isi Life Mein...!]]''\n| Sam\n| \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=IsiLifeMein/>\n|-\n|2016\n!scope=\"row\"|''[[Tum Bin II]]''\n| Herself\n|Special appearance in song \"Nachna Aaonda Nahin\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/television/tun-bin-2-mouni-roy-is-making-tv-stars-dance-to-nachna-aunda-nahi-watch-video-4368209/ |title=Tum Bin 2: Mouni Roy is making TV stars dance to Nachna Aunda Nahi |work=The Indian Express |last=Jain |first=Arushi |date=10 November 2016 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Role\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Indian Idol]] \u2013 Season 2''\n| Contestant\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Jo Jeeta Wohi Super Star]] \u2013 Season 1''\n| Challenger<ref name=watchout/>\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Comedy Circus|Comedy Circus Ke Taansen]] \u2013 Season 2''\n| Various characters<ref name=watchout/>\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Comedy Nights with Kapil]]''\n| Special appearance\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Comedy Classes]]''\n| Special appearance\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Comedy Nights Bachao]]''\n| Special appearance\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Comedy Nights Live]]'' \n| Special appearance\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The Kapil Sharma Show]]''\n| Special appearance\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Voice India Kids]]''\n| Special appearance\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Sa Re Ga Ma Pa L'il Champs 2017]]''\n| Judge\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Indian Idol]] \u2013 Season 10''\n| Judge\n|-\n| 2019\n| '' [[Indian Idol]] \u2013 Season 11''\n| Judge\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Super Dancer]]''\n| Special appearance\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Khatra Khatra Khatra]]''\n| Special appearance\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[The Kapil Sharma Show]]''\n| Special appearance\n|-\n|}\n\n== Selected discography ==\n{{Main|List of songs recorded by Neha Kakkar}}\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* \"Second Hand Jawani\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Cocktail (2012 film)|Cocktail]]'' (2012)\n* \"Sunny Sunny\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Yaariyan (2014 film)|Yaariyan]]'' (2014)\n* \"London Thumakda\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Queen (soundtrack)|Queen]]'' (2014)\n* \"Kar Gayi Chull\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Kapoor & Sons]]'' (2016)\n* \"Mile Ho Tum\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Fever (2016 film)|Fever]]'' (2016)\n* \"Kala Chashma\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Baar Baar Dekho]]'' (2016)\n* \"Badri Ki Dulhania\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Badrinath Ki Dulhania]]'' (2017)\n* \"Cheez Badi\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Machine (2017 film)|Machine]]'' (2017)\n* \"[[Dilbar (song)|Dilbar]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Satyameva Jayate]]'' (2018)\n* \"[[Aankh Maarey]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Simmba]]'' (2018)\n* \"[[Coca Cola Tu|Coca Cola]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Luka Chuppi]]'' (2019)\n* \"O Saki Saki\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Batla House]]'' (2019)\n* \"Ek Toh Kum Zindagani\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Marjaavaan]]'' (2019)\n* \"Garmi\"&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Street Dancer 3D]]'' (2020)\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of Indian playback singers]]\n*[[List of most-viewed Indian music videos on YouTube]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://nehakakkar.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|3833975|name=Neha Kakkar}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kakkar, Neha}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bollywood playback singers]]\n[[Category:Indian female film singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Women musicians from Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language singers]]\n[[Category:Bengali-language singers]]\n[[Category:Punjabi-language singers]]\n[[Category:Indian Idol participants]]\n[[Category:Indian pop-folk singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian singers]]\n", "name_user": "Fylindfotberserk", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neha_Kakkar"}
