 = {{PH wikidata|language}}\n| blank2_name_sec1                = Sister localities\n| blank2_info_sec1                = \n| blank3_name_sec1                = \n| blank3_info_sec1                = \n| blank4_name_sec1                = \n| blank4_info_sec1                = \n| blank5_name_sec1                = \n| blank5_info_sec1                = \n| blank6_name_sec1                = \n| blank6_info_sec1                = \n| blank7_name_sec1                = \n| blank7_info_sec1                = \n| blank1_name_sec2                = Major religions\n| blank1_info_sec2                = \n| blank2_name_sec2                = Feast date\n| blank2_info_sec2                = \n| blank3_name_sec2                = Catholic diocese\n| blank3_info_sec2                = \n| blank4_name_sec2                = Patron saint\n| blank4_info_sec2                = \n| blank5_name_sec2                = \n| blank5_info_sec2                = \n| blank6_name_sec2                = \n| blank6_info_sec2                = \n| blank7_name_sec2                = \n| blank7_info_sec2                = \n| short_description               = \n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n\n'''{{PH wikidata|name}}''', officially the '''{{PH wikidata|official_name}}''', ({{lang-pag|Baley na {{PH wikidata|name}}}}; {{lang-ilo|Ili ti {{PH wikidata|name}}}}; {{lang-tgl|Bayan ng {{PH wikidata|name}}}}), is a {{PH wikidata|income_class_ordinal}} [[{{PH wikidata|settlement_text}} of the Philippines|{{PH wikidata|settlement_text}}]] in the [[Philippine Province|province]] of {{PH wikidata|province}}, {{PH wikidata|country}}. According to the {{PH wikidata|population_as_of}}, it has a population of {{PH wikidata|population_total}} people.{{PH census|current}}\n\nOn the western part of [[Pangasinan]], along the coast of the China Sea lies a town called - Burgos, perched on a broad plateau. This town is located at the edge of the Zambales mountain ranges, West of Mabini, South of Agno, North of Dasol and East of the China Sea. About 65 kilometers away from the capital town of Lingayen.\n\nBurgos was founded as an independent town in 1830 by the early Ilocanos from [[Paoay|Paoay, Ilocos Norte]] headed by Don Matias Guiang. The provincial government of [[Zambales]] has not ignored the ever increasing population and as it saw the necessity of a government to oversee the village. Don Matias Guiang made history, as quoted from the Philippine Archives, when on May 15, 1830 the Spanish Governor of [[Zambales]] issued a decree creating his settlement into a \"pueblo\" and appointed him as the first [[gobernadorcillo]] and was first named San Isidro in honor of its Patron Saint. Since there was another locality named San Isidro along the Lingayen Gulf, the residents later decided to add \"Potot\" derived from the description of the Amburayan River which appeared to be cut or \"potot\". Confusion however continued and persisted as mails for San Isidro de Potot were missent to the town of [[Labrador, Pangasinan|Labrador]] and those of the latter to the former town to finally solved the confusion and was finally renamed Burgos, after the Filipino Martyr priest who was executed during the Spanish regime. The renaming of the town was done in 1913 during the administration of Don Anacleto Ruiz.\n\nThe town of Burgos was ceded to the Province of Pangasinan, by virtue of Republic Act No. 1004 dated November 30, 1903 of the Philippine Commission. There also holds the westernmost point in Luzon.<br />\n[[File:Burgos, Pangasinan Welcome Sign.jpg|thumb|right|Welcome signage]]\n[[File:Burgos,Pangasinanjf0797 24.JPG|thumb|right|Burgos Town Hall]]\n\n==Etymology==    \n\nBurgos, so-called today, this being the present official name, was known before as\u00a0San Isidro\u00a0during the Spanish time and was then within the geographical jurisdiction of the province of [[Zambales]].\n\nHow this place got its name is not definitely known. Judging from the fact that there were no accounts left circulating in the lips of the old people today as to how is got its name. \n\nThe early immigrants were God-fearing people. The have come to this place, lured by its vast agri-cultural possibilities. They were charmed by the rolling hills and the nice valleys cut-ting the plain. They envisioned that this is an ideal place that would give them ease, peace and comfort in their later life. When the early settlers migrated, to this place, they brought with them their religious beliefs. They worshipped fervently, revered highly [[Isidore the Laborer|Saint Isidore the Laborer]]\u00a0and pinned their fates and hopes of bountiful harvest upon the blessings of the Saint.\n\nAfter some years the settlers have increased their tribe and number and then came necessity of organizing their settlement into a public with Don Matias Guiang, who was then the most prosperous land owner of the place and the most influential personage to the settler, as the first\u00a0\"'''[[Gobernadorcillo]]'''\"\u00a0of the town. '''San Isidro''' was its incorporated name in honor of\u00a0St. Isidore the Laborer, whom the settlers have adopted, loved and revered as their Patron Saint. \n\nDuring the Spanish period and the early part of the American era, Burgos, Dasol and Mabini was a part of a settlement as one municipality known as San Isidro de Potot. Burgos may have been the last place to be found in the settlement but even though it still became the settlement's capital due to its fast-growing economy that it was declared an independent town upon its founding. The term \"'''Potot'''\" appended to the name San Isidro in an Ilocano adjective meaning \"'''clipped'''\", \"'''cut-off'''\" or disconnected. Not far from poblacion there is a brook or stream which during dry common ages has not continuous water. This stream, therefore, is discontinued and disconnected during summer months and to those now-comers in the place, this condition of the stream served as identification of the location of the town.\n\nThere were being then two municipalities in Pangasinan with the name of San Isidro Labrador and Potot, But the term \"'''Potot'''\" identified it well more from the other.\n\n===Folktale===\n\nThe Locals unveils the tale of how the town may have got its first name.\n\nLong ago when there were only few people living in the area where now the town of Burgos located, there were hunters who were hunting for wild animals. When these hunters got tired and thirsty, they looked for water to drink. As they were walking, they saw a man with a beard carrying a long cane. The hunters inquired from the man where they may be able to get water. The man drove his cane through the ground and suddenly water came flowing. Much to their surprise, the hunters remained silent for a moment. The man carrying a long cane was believed to be the patron saint, of the town, [[Isidore the Laborer|Saint Isidore the Laborer]]. From that time up to the present we can still see the spring with its made wall, which is also the source of water supply of some folks of the town.\n\n===Renaming===\nIn 1913, as mayor, Don Anacleto Ruiz, the name of the town was changed to\u00a0Burgos, in memory of one of the greatest Filipino martyrs, Padre [[Jos\u00e9 Burgos|Jos\u00e9 Apolonio Burgos]], who together with Padre Gomez and Zamora were mercilessly executed in the field of Bagumbayan on February 17, 1872. Padre Burgos, a very influential and able man was an [[Ilocano people|Ilocano]], he being a native of [[Vigan|Vigan, Ilocos Sur]]. He was highly praised in the real of priesthood and was very much loved by his people but more so by the Ilocanos. Before his death, he was a great reformer, his execution was deeply resented and mourned for the people believed in his innocence. To perpetuate his memory, the authorities changed the name of this town from '''San Isidro''' to '''Burgos''' in a grateful remembrance of this overwhelming love and admiration of the people for priesthood, as a profession.\n\n==History==\nIn the first part of the 19th century, '''Mat\u00edas Guiang''', a powerful sailor from [[Paoay|Paoay, Ilocos Norte]] regularly traveled the China Sea between the [[Ilocos Region|Ilocos]] and [[Zambales]] region for commercial purposes. He decided to emigrate with his neighbors, family and friends to Zambales del Norte, now the western part of the province of Pangasinan. They disembarked at the mouth of the [[Agno River]] by tracing it.\n\n===Philippine Revolution===\nIn the late 19th century in San Isidro de Potot, [[Zambales]] (now,'''\u00a0Burgos''', '''Pangasinan'''). The municipal Gobernadorcillo was Don Tomas Braga, and the parish priest of the town before the revolution was a native of\u00a0[[Barcelona|Barcelona, Spain]], and his name was Mariano Torrente.\n\nThe town was a prosperous community of farming and ranching. But the atmosphere was already seething with dissidence; winds of rebellion disturb the people.\n\nTwenty Spanish \"'''Cazadores'''\" had their cuartel or barracks in the big house of Don Gaspar Ruiz. Cazadores literally means \"'''hunters'''\" their aim was to hunt the Filipino outlaws or dissidents.\n\nAcross the plaza from the cuartel was the big convent which stood at the same place where now stands the small convent. This convent was made out of adobe stones, 24 meters long and 12 meters wide; It was two stories high.\n\nAcross the plaza from the convent was the \"'''tribunal'''\" or municipal hall where now stands the present municipal hall building. This tribunal was made out of adobe stones. It was ten meters high.\n\nA tower was being constructed at the town plaza between the convent and the tribunal. This tower or fort was made of stones, 5 meters square inside dimensions, 3 stories high, and its walls are 1/2 meter thick.\n\nInsurgency was becoming widespread; the measures adopted by the Spaniards increased the number of outlaws. In Northern Zambales, which is now Western, Pangasinan, the soprano of the surgent was Ramon Manalang whose headquarters was in a hideout somewhere in Alaminos, Zambales (now '''[[Pangasinan]]''').\n\nIn San Isidro (now '''Burgos'''), the captain of the outlaws was Juanso Viado. The outlaws or dissidents were very numerous, had very few defective guns, and mostly armed with crude sabers, sharp spears and long bolos.\n\nIt was in February 1898. The outlaws attacked the cuartel of the Cazadores in the big house of Don Gaspar Ruiz. The attackers greatly outnumbered the Cazadores. The Cazadores, armed with mauzzers, were poor shooters; while the Filipino outlaws, currently armed, were nomatoli for the well-armed Cazadores.\n\nThe twenty Spanish Cazadores managed to escape to the convent across the plaza. The Filipino attackers laid a siege to them.\n\nOne day, about mealtime, when the Filipino besiegers slackened their vigilance, the Cazadores were able to escape to the tower at the middle of the plaza. Already the cuartel was occupied by the outlaws.\n\nFor two nights and three days, the Cazadores stayed in the tower or fort without food. The people of the town including the municipal gobernadorcillo gone to distant the place.\n\nBut Padre Mariano Torrente reminded, being a peaceful man, and maintaining maturity in the fight, he acted as the lissome between the Spanish Cazadores and the Filipino outlaws.\n\nCaptain Juanso Viado of the outlaws told Padre Mariano Torrente that the cazadores should better surrender, or they would die of hunger. The priest was able to prevail upon the Spaniards to low down their arms.\n\nOn the third afternoon, the Spanish Cazadores threw their guns out of the windows of the tower in token of surrender. The Filipino outlaws took the guns, then the Cazadores went out of the tower, and the Filipino outlaws and Spanish Cazadores shook hands and embraced each other as good friends.\n\nBut such good friendship was short-lived. A fatal coincidence happened which turned the friendship into tragedy.\n\nThe morning following the surrender, news reached San Isidro that a big Spanish troop heavily armed arrived in Alaminos, Zambales (now '''[[Pangasinan]]''') on their way to San Isidro. This news alarmed the outlaws who reacted immediately seizing the Cazadores and taking them as prisoners. For the gladdened Cazadores naturally; the Spanish troop was being sent to save all Spaniards.\n\nThe Spanish Cazadores including Padre Mariano Torrente and also Padre Juan Naves of Dasol, were taken to the forest of Alimpayukan between San Isidro and Balincaguin (now'''\u00a0[[Mabini, Pangasinan]]'''). The Spaniards, upon being assured of their safety, and that no harm would happen, went willingly.\n\nUpon arriving at the forest, Alimpayukan, 20 Spanish Cazadores and 2 Spanish priests were blindfolded and their heads out-off. For the Spanish troop is about to arrive, and the Spaniards might escape to join them.\n\nShortly after the Spaniards were murdered, the big Spanish troop arrived in San Isidro and encircled the town. There were 20 uniformed Filipino outlaws or insurgents who were to form a local government. These were caught, taken to Mt. Polipol just a few kilometers east from the town, and were shot in a single file.\n\nAt that time, there was known as \"'''Juez de Cuchillo'''\", which means that if a priest was murdered in a town, the said town, being listed to\u00a0Juez de Cuchillo,\u00a0shall have its people killed and even their houses destroyed.\n\nIn San Isidro, no people could be seen for they had evacuated, and only the twenty Filipino insurgents were seen and caught and killed. The Spanish troop burned down the big houses that are owned by the richest and the most influential personage of the town.\n\nThe big Spanish troop left San Isidro, and then proceeded to [[Dasol]], in this place they killed the \"[[Principal\u00eda|'''principal\u00edas''']]\" and \"'''captains'''\", that is, the rich and the influential, and also burned their big houses. Because the Spanish priest of Dasol, Padre Juan Naves was beheaded in the forest of Alimpayukan; and many of the insurgents were from Dasol for the body of outlaws, headed by captain Juanso Viado, came from many places.\n\nThe big Spanish troop left [[Dasol]] empty-handed, a lot of people were killed including the rich and influential, so was their big houses were also burned down and left into ashes.\n\nThe Spanish detachments in the northern towns of Zambales was defeated and around 50 Spanish Friars were annihilated. These were the parish priests of [[Anda, Pangasinan|Anda]], [[Bolinao, Pangasinan|Bolinao]], [[Bani, Pangasinan|Bani]], [[Mabini, Pangasinan|Balincaguin]], [[Dasol]] and San Isidro de Potot.\n\nNothing more was heard of the Spanish troop. Perhaps they were secured or perhaps imprisoned by the outlaws.\n\n===American Occupation===\nThe Katipunan Government was functioning smoothly, at least in San Isidro. In November 1900, Gen. Miguel and Don Miguel and Don Mauro Ortis came to recruit volunteers to meet the Americans in\u00a0[[Mangatarem]]. The volunteers went to Mangatarem, but poorly armed, had to retreat before the heavy American arms and cobranded. Nicolas Guiang, who was among those recruited, back across the mountains to Mt. Pita, then went to Infanta, and then back to San Isidro.\n\nThe Americans moved swiftly. They occupied San Isidro by December 1900 and established peace and order. They came with their wives. The costumes of the American women had decided influences in changing the Filipino costumes from oriental to occidental.\n\nThe Americans established a policy of attraction and launched it literally. They gave clothes, freely goods and tolerated the local customs.\n\nIn 1901 a severe storm hit San Isidro. The big convent was wrecked. So was the municipal building. The town church managed to survive and some of the original structures of the church still stands in some years, but It faced several renovations through the years due to avoid collapsing possibilities.\n\nIn 1903, the northern part of Zambales was annexed to the Province of Pangasinan. The municipalities ceded were [[Alaminos, Pangasinan|Alaminos]], [[Bolinao, Pangasinan|Bolinao]], [[Anda, Pangasinan|Anda]], [[Bani, Pangasinan|Bani]],\u00a0[[Agno, Pangasinan|Agno]], [[Infanta, Pangasinan|Infanta]] and San Isidro de Potot (Burgos, [[Dasol]], and [[Mabini, Pangasinan|Mabini]]). Townsfolk cited alleged lack of concern for the town's interest and welfare by the Zambales provincial government therefore they were incorporated to Pangasinan.\n\nShortly after, the towns of Northern Zambales were incorporated in Pangasinan. [[Dasol]] and [[Mabini, Pangasinan|Balincaguin]] seceded from San Isidro de Potot,  Balincaguin was renamed as Mabini (in honor of\u00a0'''[[Apolinario Mabini]]'''). San Isidro de Potot was changed to Burgos (in honor of Padre '''[[Jos\u00e9 Burgos]]'''), and in order not to confuse it to\u00a0[[Labrador, Pangasinan|San Isidro Labrador de Tobuang]] of Pangasinan.\n\n==List of Municipal Heads==\n\nThe name of persons who held a leading official position during the Spanish period and thereafter were the following.\n\n\n[[Gobernadorcillo]]:\n\n*Don Matias Guiang (1830)\n*\n\n*Don Pascual Bonostro (1831)\n*\n\n*Don Diego Bustamante (1832)\n*\n*Don Fernando Bonilla (1833)\n*\n*Don Paulo Padua (1834)\n*\n*Don Matias Guiang (1835)\n*\n*Don Juan Discoloso (1836)\n*\n*Don Juan Bonostro (1837)\n*\n*Don Agustin Cuaresma (1838)\n*\n*Don Pascual de Guzman (1839)\n*\n*Don Paulo Doctor (1840)\n*\n*Don Pedro Guiang (1841)\n*\n*Don Vicente Bondal (1842)\n*\n*Don Miguel Cuaresma (1843)\n*\n*Don Ramon Bustria (1844)\n*\n*Don Exequel Ugto (1845)\n*\n*Don Agapito Tolentino Braga (1846)\n*\n*Don Domingo Valdez (1847)\n*\n*Don Tomas Guiang (1848)\n*\n*Don Jose de Leon (1849)\n*\n*Don Juan Bonilla (1850)\n*\n*Don Henenio Doctor (1851)\n*\n*Don Raymundo Bonostro (1852)\n*\n*Don Romualdo Braga (1853)\n*\n*Don Melchor Ruiz (1854)\n*\n*Don Paulino Bustamante (1855)\n*\n*Don Feliciano de Guzman (1856)\n*\n*Don Eldefonzo Bona (1857)\n*\n*Don Cornelio Valdez (1858)\n*\n*Don Agapito Ugto (1859)\n*\n*Don Martin Gallardo (1860)\n*\n*Don Mariano Mendoza (1861)\n*\n*Don Anborcio Guiang (1862)\n*\n*Don Santiago Ruiz (1863)\n*\n*Don Santiago Ruiz (1864)\n*\n*Don Justo Bonada (1865)\n*\n*Don Victorio Braga (1867)\n*\n*Don Mauricio Gallardo (1869)\n*\n*Don Silvestro Ruiz (1871)\n*\n*Don Cornelio Braga (1873)\n*\n*Don Flaviano Cudal (1875)\n*\n*Don Francisco Guiang (1877)\n*\n*Don Lorenzo Bonando (1879)\n*\n*Don Raymundo Boricano (1881)\n*\n*Don Simon Ruiz (1883)\n*\n*Don Simon Guiang (1885)\n*\n*Don Vinancio Gallardo (1887)\n*\n*Don Pablo Boricano (1889)\n*\n*Don Lauriano Kadarang (1891)\n*\n*Don Luiz Bonilla (1893)\n*\n*Don Tomas Braga (1895)\n\n===President during the Revolution===\n\n*Don Mauricio Gallardo (1898\u20131900)\n*\n*Don Tomas Braga (1900\u20131901)\n*\n*Don Carlos Ruiz (1901\u20131902) \n\n\n===Municipal President during the civil government===\n\n*Don Paulino Mendoza (1904\u20131905)\n*\n*Don Francisco Bustamante (1906\u20131907)\n*\n*Don Jacinto Braga (1908\u20131911)\n*\n*Don Nicolas Guiang (1911\u20131912)\n*\n*Don Anacleto Ruiz (1912\u20131916)\n*\n*Don Juan Eonado (1916\u20131919)\n*\n*Don Matias Ruiz (1919\u20131922)\n*\n*Don Agustin R. Braga (1922)\n*\n*Don Nazario Bonilla (1925\u20131928)\n*\n*Don Matias Bustamante (1928\u20131931)\n*\n*Don Meloniades Ruiz (1931\u20131934)\n*\n*Don Lorenzo Bonado (1934\u20131943)\n*\n*Don Miguel Braga (1944)\n*\n*Don Matias Bustamante (1945)\n*\n*Don Lorenzo Bonado (1946\u20131947)\n*\n*Don Severano Rayos (1948)\n*\n*Don Andres Ramos (1949\u20131951)\n*\n*Don Antonio Bonilla (1952)\n*\n*\n*\n*\n\n==Saint Isidore The Farmer Parish Church==\n'''Burgos''', formerly known as '''San Isidro''' is a mountainous land of hard-working [[Ilocano people|Ilocanos]], descendants of God-fearing men and women from the town of Paoay, Ilocos Norte, who came in their sailboats to found a settlement in the eastern part of the present town proper. During the Spanish rule this municipality was part of the province of [[Zambales]].\n\n*Saint Isidore The Farmer Parish Church\n*\n[[File:Burgos,Pangasinanjf0737 01.JPG|thumb|right|]]\nIn 1876, the Dominicans created the Parish church of St. Isidore, the patron saint of farmers, seeing that the town\u2019s chief industry was farming. The inhabitants, who were already steeped in Christian ways and they longed for a church where they can worship God. They realized their wish when the Spanish missionaries came and founded the Parish of St. Isidore the Farmer in the year 1876. The patron\u2019s feast is annually celebrated on May 15. It is also the town fiesta.\n[[File:Burgos,Pangasinanjf0737 23.JPG|thumb|right|]]\nIt was the founding missionaries who built the present fa\u00e7ade of the church, made mostly of quarried adobe stones contributed by the faithful. The Dominicans left during the American regime and were succeeded by Filipino clergymen who continued the improvement of the house of God and the ministration of the faithful. The church edifice, made mostly of quarried adobe stones and rough-hewn lumber, was painstakingly built through many years. It is tribute to the Spanish missionaries that the present fa\u00e7ade which they had built a century ago has withstood the elements and ravages of time.\n==Tourist destinations==\n\n*'''Cabongaoan White Sand Beach'''\n\n[[File:Cabongaoan Beach, Burgos, Pangasinan.jpg|thumb|right|Cabongaoan Beach]]\n*'''Death Pool/Depth Pool (Lagoon)'''\n\n[[File:Death Pool, Cabongaoan Beach, Burgos, Pangasinan.jpg|thumb|right|Death Pool]]\n*'''Sangbay Falls'''\n\n[[File:Sangbay Falls.jpg|thumb|right|Sangbay Falls]]\n*'''Danao Lake'''\n*'''Rolling Hills'''\n*'''Pao Beach'''\n*'''Paratec Beach'''\n\n==Barangays==\n\nBurgos is politically subdivided into 14 [[Barangay|barangays]].\n\n* Anapao (Bur Anapac)\n* Cacayasen\n* Concordia\n* Ilio-ilio (Iliw-iliw)\n* Papallasen\n*[[Poblacion]]\n* Pogoruac\n* Don Matias\n* San Miguel\n* San Pascual\n* San Vicente\n* Sapa Grande\n* Sapa Peque\u00f1a\n* Tambacan\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Philippine Census|align=none\n| title = Population census of Burgos\n| 1903 = 3488\n| 1918 = 5143\n| 1939 = 8075\n| 1948 = 7891\n| 1960 = 10030\n| 1970 = 10586\n| 1975 = 12430\n| 1980 = 12817\n| 1990 = 14774\n| 1995 = 17003\n| 2000 = 18142\n| 2007 = 20187\n| 2010 = 18315\n| 2015 = 21637\n| 2020 =\n| 2025 =\n| 2030 =\n| footnote= Source: [[Philippine Statistics Authority]]{{PH census|2015}}{{PH census|2010}}{{PH census|2007}}{{LWUA population data}} \n}}\n\n==Climate==\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n|location = Burgos, Pangasinan\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n| Jan high C = 31\n| Feb high C = 31\n| Mar high C = 32\n| Apr high C = 34\n| May high C = 35\n| Jun high C = 34\n| Jul high C = 32\n| Aug high C = 32\n| Sep high C = 32\n| Oct high C = 32\n| Nov high C = 32\n| Dec high C = 31\n| Jan low C = 22\n| Feb low C = 22\n| Mar low C = 22\n| Apr low C = 24\n| May low C = 24\n| Jun low C = 24\n| Jul low C = 24\n| Aug low C = 24\n| Sep low C = 24\n| Oct low C = 23\n| Nov low C = 23\n| Dec low C = 22\n| Jan precipitation mm = 13.6\n| Jan rain days = 3 \n| Feb precipitation mm = 10.4 \n| Feb rain days = 2\n| Mar precipitation mm = 18.2 \n| Mar rain days = 2\n| Apr precipitation mm = 15.7 \n| Apr rain days = 4\n| May precipitation mm = 178.4\n| May rain days = 14    \n| Jun precipitation mm = 227.9 \n| Jun rain days = 16\n| Jul precipitation mm = 368\n| Jul rain days = 23\n| Aug precipitation mm = 306.6 \n| Aug rain days = 21\n| Sep precipitation mm = 310.6 \n| Sep rain days = 21\n| Oct precipitation mm = 215.7 \n| Oct rain days = 15\n| Nov precipitation mm = 70.3 \n| Nov rain days = 10\n| Dec precipitation mm = 31.1 \n| Dec rain days = 6\n|source 1 = World Weather Online<ref name=\"met_norms\">\n{{cite web \n| url = http://www.worldweatheronline.com/Burgos-weather-averages/Pangasinan/PH.aspx\n| title = Burgos, Pangasinan: Average Temperatures and Rainfall\n| publisher = World Weather Online\n| accessdate = 26 September 2015}}</ref>\n| date=September 2015}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170202040236/http://www.competitive.org.ph/cmcindex/pages/profile/?lgu=Burgos%20(PS)  Municipal Profile at the National Competitiveness Council of the Philippines]\n* [http://pangasinan.gov.ph/the-province/cities-and-municipalities/burgos/ Burgos at the Pangasinan Government Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20161010201809/http://www.blgs.gov.ph/lgpmsv2/cmshome/index.php?pageID=23 Local Governance Performance Management System]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120413163013/http://www.nscb.gov.ph/activestats/psgc/default.asp Philippine Standard Geographic Code]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081120024509/http://www.census.gov.ph/data/census2007/index.html Philippine Census Information]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130715074746/https://pangasinan.org/burgos/  Pangasinan.org : Burgos Family and School Reunion Archives]\n\n{{Geographic location\n| Centre = Burgos\n| North  = [[Agno, Pangasinan|Agno]]\n| East   = [[Mabini, Pangasinan|Mabini]]\n| South  = [[Dasol, Pangasinan|Dasol]]\n| West   = ''[[South China Sea]]'' / \n[[File:Flag of Vietnam.svg|30px]]\n''[[Da Nang]], [[Vietnam]]''\n}}\n{{Pangasinan}}\n{{One Pangasinan Alliance}}\n\n[[Category:Municipalities of Pangasinan]]\n[[Category:1830 establishments in the Spanish East Indies]]\n\n\n{{IlocosR-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SharpV1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Burgos,_Pangasinan"}
{"title_page": "Mary Barra", "text_new": "{{short description|American businesswoman|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mary Barra\n| image              = Mary Barra 2014.jpg\n| caption            = August 2014\n| birth_name         = Mary Teresa Makela\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1961|12|24|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Royal Oak, Michigan]], US\n| nationality        = \n| education          = [[Kettering University]]<br> [[Stanford University]]\n| occupation         = [[Chairman]] and [[CEO]], [[General Motors]]\n| employer           = \n| net_worth          = \n| boards             = [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]]<br> [[Stanford University]] Board of Trustees<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/business/autos/general-motors/2015/07/15/gm-ceo-barra-joins-stanford-university-board/30181281/|title=GM CEO Barra joins Stanford University board|publisher=|accessdate=April 26, 2017}}</ref>\n| spouse             = Anthony E. Barra\n| children           = 2\n| website            = {{url|http://www.gm.com/company/leadership/corporate-officers/mary-barra.html|GM Corporate Officers}}\n}}\n\n'''Mary Teresa Barra''' (n\u00e9e '''Makela'''; born December 24, 1961) is an American [[Women in business|businesswoman]]. She has been the chairman and CEO of [[General Motors|General Motors Company]] since January 15, 2014, and she is the first female [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of a major automaker.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/11/business/gm-names-first-female-chief-executive.html | title=G.M. Names First Female Chief Executive | last1=Vlasic | first1=Bill | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=December 10, 2013 | accessdate=December 11, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"General Motors\">{{cite web | url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/emergency_news/1210-gm-execs.html | title=Dan Akerson to Retire as GM CEO in January 2014 Mary Barra to Become Next CEO; Dan Ammann Named President\n| publisher=[[General Motors]] | accessdate=December 10, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/05/general-motors-gm-earnings-q4-2019.html|title=GM swings to a loss in the fourth quarter as 40-day strike erodes profits|last=Wayland|first=Michael|date=2020-02-05|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> On December 10, 2013, GM named her to succeed [[Daniel Akerson|Dan Akerson]] as [[chief executive officer]], and prior to that, Barra served as the executive vice president of Global Product Development, Purchasing, and Supply Chain at [[General Motors]].<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref name=\"General Motors\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nBarra was born in [[Royal Oak, Michigan]]. Barra's parents are of [[Finnish American|Finnish]] descent.<ref name=CNNFortune>{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Alex|title=Mary Barra: GM's next CEO?|url=http://management.fortune.cnn.com/2012/12/17/gm-mary-barra/|work=CNN/Fortune|accessdate=December 11, 2013|date=December 17, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214071920/http://management.fortune.cnn.com/2012/12/17/gm-mary-barra/|archivedate=December 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=HelsinginSanomat>{{cite web|last=Niskakangas|first=Tuomas|title=New CEO of automotive icon is of Finnish descent|url=http://www.helsinkitimes.fi/business/8707-new-ceo-of-automotive-icon-is-of-finnish-descent.html|date=December 16, 2013|work=[[Helsinki Times]]}}</ref> Barra's ancestors are from the village of [[Kankaanp\u00e4\u00e4, S\u00e4kyl\u00e4|Kankaanp\u00e4\u00e4]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aamulehti.fi/a/24138832 |title=Trumpin uusi neuvonantaja on moottorimimmi \u2013 osaa sanoa suomeksi \u201dOnks tankissa bensaa?\u201d |last1=Tapio |first1=Ilari |date=December 13, 2016 |website=[[Aamulehti]] |language=fi |access-date=July 8, 2019 |quote=Amerikkalaisen autoj\u00e4tin toimitusjohtajan Mary Barran sukujuuret ovat M\u00e4kel\u00e4n torpassa K\u00f6yli\u00f6n Kankaanp\u00e4\u00e4n kyl\u00e4ss\u00e4.}}</ref> in [[Satakunta|Satakunta province]] in Finland, from the former municipality of [[K\u00f6yli\u00f6]]. Her grandfather, Viktor M\u00e4kel\u00e4, moved to the [[United States]] and married Maria Luoma, a Finnish immigrant from [[Teuva]]. They lived in [[Minnesota]], in the small mining town of [[Mountain Iron]]. They had three children, including a son named Reino,<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://blogs.wsj.com/corporate-intelligence/2013/12/10/a-look-at-mary-barra-gms-first-female-ceo/ | title=A Look at Mary Barra, GM\u2019s First Female CEO | work=The Wall Street Journal | date=December 10, 2013 | accessdate=December 11, 2013}}</ref> also called Ray. Her father Ray married a second-generation Finnish American named Eva Pyykk\u00f6nen, and Mary was born in 1961. Ray worked for 39 years at the [[Pontiac]] car factory in [[Detroit]], and the family lived in [[Waterford Township, Oakland County, Michigan|Waterford, Michigan]]. Barra attended Waterford schools in Michigan. She is a graduate of [[Waterford Mott High School]].\n\n== Education ==\nBarra graduated from the General Motors Institute (now [[Kettering University]]), where she obtained a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[electrical engineering]]. Barra was inducted into the engineering honor society [[Tau_Beta_Pi#Undergraduate_eligibility_requirements|Tau Beta Pi]].<ref name=\"taubetapi2018\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tbp.org/other/NAEclass18.cfm|title=Tau Beta Pi - NAE class 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402082529/https://www.tbp.org/other/NAEclass18.cfm|archive-date=2 April 2020|publisher=[[Tau Beta Pi]]|access-date=2020-04-02|quote=Mary T. Barra, Michigan Zeta '85|location=[[Knoxville, Tennessee]]}}</ref> She then attended [[Stanford Graduate School of Business]] on a GM fellowship, receiving her [[Masters in Business Administration]] degree in 1990.<ref name=bb/>\n\n==Career==\n\n=== General Motors ===\nBarra started working for General Motors, at age 18,<ref name=shm/> as a [[Cooperative education|co-op student]], in 1980, checking fender panels and inspecting hoods to pay for her college tuition.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://work.qz.com/1175673/general-motors-ceo-mary-barra-on-her-leadership-style-and-career/|title=GM CEO Mary Barra says too many women quit their jobs for the wrong reason|work=Quartz at Work|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en-US}}</ref> and subsequently held a variety of engineering and administrative positions, including managing the [[Detroit/Hamtramck Assembly]] plant.<ref name=bb>{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=40221799&privcapId=61206100 | title=Mary Barra: Executive Profile & Biography | work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] | access-date=December 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2008, she became vice president of Global Manufacturing Engineering. In July 2009, she advanced to the position of vice president of Global [[Human Resources]], which she held until February 2011, when she was named executive vice president of Global Product Development.<ref name=bb/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/21/business/21auto.html | title=G.M. Names New Leader for Global Development | last1=Bunkley | first1=Nick | last2=Vlasic | first2=Bill | work=The New York Times | date=January 20, 2011 | access-date=December 11, 2013}}</ref> The latter position included responsibilities for design; she has worked to reduce the number of [[automobile platforms]] in [[List of GM platforms|GM]].<ref name=\"nyt\"/> In August 2013, her vice president responsibility was extended to include Global Purchasing and Supply Chain.<ref name=gm>{{cite web | url=http://www.gm.com/company/aboutGM/GM_Corporate_Officers/mary_barra.html | title=About GM: Mary T. Barra | publisher=General Motors| access-date=December 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhen Barra took over as chief executive of General Motors in January 2014, she became the first female head of an automobile manufacturer.<ref>[http://www.new-corner.com/rebuilding-a-giant-mary-barra-ceo-general-motors/ Rebuilding a Giant: Mary Barra, CEO, General Motors], New Corner, June 5, 2015</ref>\n\nDuring her first year as CEO, General Motors issued 84 [[safety recall]]s involving over 30 million cars.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.zacks.com/stock/news/159304/general-motors-gm-safety-recalls-add-up-to-84-in-2014l | title=General Motors (GM): Safety Recalls Add Up to 84 in 2014 | publisher=Zacks Equity Research | access-date=January 5, 2015}}</ref> Barra was called before the Senate to testify about the recalls and deaths attributed to the faulty ignition switch.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2014/07/23/gm-ignition-senate-mary-barra-editorials-debates/13068081/ | title=GM reverses openness pledge: Our view | publisher=USA Today | access-date=July 23, 2014 | date=July 23, 2014}}</ref> Barra and General Motors also came under suspicion of paying for awards to burnish the CEO and corporation's image during that time.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.autoblog.com/2015/01/21/gm-buying-awards-mary-barra-report/ | title=Is General Motors buying awards for Mary Barra? | publisher=Autoblog | access-date=January 21, 2015}}</ref> The recalls led to the creation of new policies encouraging workers to report problems they encounter in an attempt to change company culture.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://work.qz.com/1175673/general-motors-ceo-mary-barra-on-her-leadership-style-and-career/|title=GM CEO Mary Barra says too many women quit their jobs for the wrong reason|work=Quartz at Work|access-date=February 26, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAs CEO, Barra has placed GM's focus as a company transitioning into the tech space by moving forward in the automated driverless car space with major acquisitions including Strobe, a startup focused on driverless technology.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/09/business/general-motors-driverless.html|title=G.M. Acquires Strobe, Start-Up Focused on Driverless Technology|last=Vlasic|first=Bill|date=October 9, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 17, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In 2017 she pushed GM to develop the Chevy Bolt EV, beating rival Tesla in developing the first electric car priced under $40,000 with a range of 200 miles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-day-in-the-life-of-gm-ceo-mary-barra-1461601044|title=A Day in the Life of GM CEO Mary Barra|last=Ross|first=Christopher|date=April 26, 2016|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=November 15, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Barra was the highest paid [[Detroit Three]] executive, with a total remuneration of $21.96 million.<ref name=\"detroitnews.com\">{{cite web|url=https://detroitnews.com/story/business/autos/general-motors/2018/04/27/gm-proxy-mary-barra-compensation/34313299/|title=GM paid CEO Mary Barra nearly $22M in 2017|publisher=}}</ref> In November 2018, Barra announced the closure of five North American plants and 14,000 worker [[lay off]]s.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/11/26/gm-unallocating-several-plants-in-2019-to-take-3-billion-to-3point8-billion-charge-in-future-quarters.html|title=GM to halt production at several plants, cut more than 14,000 jobs|first=Robert|last=Ferris|date=November 26, 2018|publisher=}}</ref> Her decision was criticized by [[President Trump]], who threatened to remove the company's government subsidies in response.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n=== Disney ===\nIn August 2017, she was elected to the board of [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Golum|first1=Rob|last2=Welch|first2=David|title=Barra elected to Walt Disney board|url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20170824/OEM02/170829852/barra-elected-to-walt-disney-board|publisher=Automotive News|date=August 24, 2017}}</ref> She was the 12th person elected to this board, and the fourth woman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disney-adds-general-motors-ceo-board-directors-1032380|title=Disney Adds General Motors CEO to Board of Directors|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Other boards and councils ===\nBarra was a member of the [[General Dynamics]] board of directors. She serves on the board of directors of the Detroit Economic Club and Detroit Country Day School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dykema.com/news-press-kellett-elected-to-detroit-economic-club-board_041015.html|title=Dykema Chairman and CEO Peter Kellett Elected to the Detroit Economic Club Board of Directors|website=www.dykema.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theoaklandpress.com/news/detroit-country-day-school-announces-new-trustees-including-gm-ceo/article_f3d4a985-3f8e-5e98-a477-182d5e586370.html|title=Detroit Country Day School announces new trustees, including GM CEO Mary Barra|website=The Oakland Press|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hometownlife.com/story/news/local/birmingham/2014/10/12/gm-ceo-mary-barra-joins-detroit-country-day-school-board-trustees/17041271/|title=GM CEO Mary Barra joins Detroit Country Day School Board of Trustees|last=Grossman|first=Jay|website=HometownLife|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref> She also serves as a member of [[The Business Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/business/autos/general-motors/2015/07/15/gm-ceo-barra-joins-stanford-university-board/30181281/|title=GM CEO Barra joins Stanford University board|last=Burden|first=Melissa|website=Detroit News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> She is a member of the Stanford University board of trustees, and the Stanford Graduate School of Business advisory council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/business/autos/general-motors/2015/07/15/gm-ceo-barra-joins-stanford-university-board/30181281/|title=GM CEO Barra joins Stanford University board|last=Burden|first=Melissa|website=Detroit News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nBarra was listed as 35th on [[Forbes list of The World's 100 Most Powerful Women|''Forbes'' Most Powerful Women]] list, in 2013, rising in rank to second most powerful, in 2018.<ref name=Forbes14>{{cite news|title=The World's 100 Most Powerful Women|url=https://www.forbes.com/power-women/list/#tab:overall|website=Forbes|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=June 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, she delivered the [[commencement address]] for [[University of Michigan]]'s Ann Arbor campus at [[Michigan Stadium]], and received an [[honorary degree]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/mary-barra/ | title=Mary Barra | work=[[Forbes]] | last=Goudreau|first=Jenna | year=2012|accessdate=September 7, 2012}}</ref>\nIn 2018, she received an honorary Doctorate from [[Duke University]].\n\nBarra was first in [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'s Most Powerful Women list in 2015, up from second the year before.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Mary Barra|url = http://fortune.com/most-powerful-women/mary-barra-1/|website = Fortune|accessdate = October 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe remained in the number one spot in [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'s Most Powerful Women of 2017<ref>{{Cite web|title = Mary Barra|url = http://fortune.com/most-powerful-women/|website = Fortune|accessdate = April 3, 2017}}</ref> and Number 5 on [[Forbes]] World's 100 Most Powerful Women List in the same year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/power-women/list/|title=World's Most Powerful Women|work=Forbes|access-date=March 29, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, Barra was featured on the cover of [[Time (magazine)|Time]]'s \"100 Most Influential People in the World.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Iacocca|first1=Lee|title=Mary Barra: The World\u2019s 100 Most Influential People|url=http://time.com/collection-post/70843/mary-barra-2014-time-100/|work=TIME.com}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, Barra joined a business forum assembled by [[Donald J. Trump|then President-Elect Donald Trump]] to provide strategic and policy advice on economic issues.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bryan|first1=Bob|title=Trump is forming an economic advisory team with the CEOs of Disney, General Motors, JPMorgan, and more|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/trump-strategic-and-policy-forum-includes-dimon-iger-schwarzman-2016-12|accessdate=June 1, 2017|publisher=Business Insider|date=December 2, 2016}}</ref> However, she left the forum in 2017, following Trump's response to the Charlottesville protests.\n\nBarra was elected to the [[National_Academy_of_Engineering#Membership|National Academy of Engineering]] in February 2018.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|url=https://www.nae.edu/178117.aspx|archive-date=8 February 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208182205/https://www.nae.edu/178117.aspx|title=National Academy of Engineering Elects 83 Members and 16 Foreign Members|date=2018-02-07|publisher=[[National Academy of Engineering]]|access-date=2020-04-02|quote=For leadership in automotive manufacturing, product engineering, and product development.|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|last2=|date=Spring 2018|title=Class of 2018 Elected : New Members|url=https://www.nae.edu/File.aspx?id=181157#page=49|url-status=live|journal=The Bridge|publisher=[[National Academy of Sciences]]|volume=48|issue=1|page=47|issn=0737-6278|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402090303/https://www.nae.edu/File.aspx?id=181157|archive-date=2 April 2020|via=}}</ref> In September 2018, Barra was awarded the Yale Chief Executive Leadership Institute's Legend in Leadership Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://som.yale.edu/news/2018/09/chief-executive-leadership-institute-honors-mary-t-barra-with-legend-in-leadership-award|title=Chief Executive Leadership Institute Honors Mary T. Barra with Legend in Leadership Award|date=2018-09-24|website=Yale School of Management|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Institutional Investor (magazine)|Institutional Investor]]''{{'}}s yearly survey of top executives, the 2019 All-America Executive Team, Barra achieved the first place in the autos and auto parts sector.<ref name=\"Whyte\">{{cite news |last1=Whyte |first1=Amy |title=These Are America\u2019s Top Executives  Jamie Dimon, Tim Cook, and Mary Barra are among members of II\u2019s 2019 All-America Executive Team |url=https://www.institutionalinvestor.com/article/b1bsssqc9w0p5v/These-Are-America-s-Top-Executives |accessdate=29 March 2019 |work=Institutional Investor |date=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBarra is married to consultant Tony Barra, whom she met while studying at [[Kettering University]], and has two children and two dogs,.<ref name=\"nyt\"/> They live in [[Northville Township, Michigan|Northville]], a suburb of Detroit. She also owns an apartment in [[Downtown Detroit]]<ref name=wsj>{{cite news| last=Bennett | first=Jeff | title=Longtime Insider Is GM's First Female CEO | url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303560204579249952766187032?mod=WSJ_hps_LEFTTopStories | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | author2=Murray, Sara | pages=A1, A10 | date=December 11, 2013 | accessdate=December 11, 2013}}</ref> \n\nShe has named the [[Chevrolet Camaro]] and the [[Pontiac Firebird]] as her favorite cars.<ref name=\"shm\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/11/business/mary-barra-gms-new-chief-speaking-her-mind.html | title=Mary Barra, G.M.\u2019s New Chief, Speaking Her Mind | work=The New York Times | date=December 10, 2013 | accessdate=December 11, 2013}}</ref> Barra can speak a little [[Finnish language|Finnish]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/mondays_papers_barras_finnish_roots_amorella_aftermath_and_tamperes_unemployment_problem/6986456|title=Barra's Finnish roots|date=December 16, 2013|website=Yle Uutiset|language=en|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Daniel Akerson]] | title= CEO of [[General Motors]] | after= current| years= since January 15, 2014}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Tim Solso]] | title= Chairmen of the Board of [[General Motors]] | after= current| years= since January 4, 2016}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barra, Mary}}\n[[Category:American women chief executives]]\n[[Category:General Motors executives]]\n[[Category:Kettering University alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford Graduate School of Business alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University trustees]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of manufacturing companies]]\n[[Category:American chief executives in the automobile industry]]\n[[Category:Women corporate directors]]\n[[Category:American people of Finnish descent]]\n[[Category:People from Royal Oak, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:American corporate directors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of Fortune 500 companies]]\n[[Category:21st-century businesswomen]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businesswoman|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mary Barra\n| image              = Mary Barra 2014.jpg\n| caption            = August 2014\n| birth_name         = Mary Teresa Makela\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1961|12|24|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Royal Oak, Michigan]], US\n| nationality        = \n| education          = [[Kettering University]]<br> [[Stanford University]]\n| occupation         = [[Chairman]] and [[CEO]], [[General Motors]]\n| employer           = \n| net_worth          = \n| boards             = [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]]<br> [[Stanford University]] Board of Trustees<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/business/autos/general-motors/2015/07/15/gm-ceo-barra-joins-stanford-university-board/30181281/|title=GM CEO Barra joins Stanford University board|publisher=|accessdate=April 26, 2017}}</ref>\n| spouse             = Anthony E. Barra\n| children           = 2\n| website            = {{url|http://www.gm.com/company/leadership/corporate-officers/mary-barra.html|GM Corporate Officers}}\n}}\n\n'''Mary Teresa Barra''' (n\u00e9e '''Makela'''; born December 24, 1961) is an American [[Women in business|businesswoman]]. She has been the chairman and CEO of [[General Motors|General Motors Company]] since January 15, 2014, and she is the first female [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of a major automaker.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/11/business/gm-names-first-female-chief-executive.html | title=G.M. Names First Female Chief Executive | last1=Vlasic | first1=Bill | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=December 10, 2013 | accessdate=December 11, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"General Motors\">{{cite web | url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/emergency_news/1210-gm-execs.html | title=Dan Akerson to Retire as GM CEO in January 2014 Mary Barra to Become Next CEO; Dan Ammann Named President\n| publisher=[[General Motors]] | accessdate=December 10, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/05/general-motors-gm-earnings-q4-2019.html|title=GM swings to a loss in the fourth quarter as 40-day strike erodes profits|last=Wayland|first=Michael|date=2020-02-05|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> On December 10, 2013, GM named her to succeed [[Daniel Akerson|Dan Akerson]] as [[chief executive officer]], and prior to that, Barra served as the executive vice president of Global Product Development, Purchasing, and Supply Chain at [[General Motors]].<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref name=\"General Motors\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nBarra was born in [[Royal Oak, Michigan]]. Barra's parents are of [[Finnish American|Finnish]] descent.<ref name=CNNFortune>{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Alex|title=Mary Barra: GM's next CEO?|url=http://management.fortune.cnn.com/2012/12/17/gm-mary-barra/|work=CNN/Fortune|accessdate=December 11, 2013|date=December 17, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214071920/http://management.fortune.cnn.com/2012/12/17/gm-mary-barra/|archivedate=December 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=HelsinginSanomat>{{cite web|last=Niskakangas|first=Tuomas|title=New CEO of automotive icon is of Finnish descent|url=http://www.helsinkitimes.fi/business/8707-new-ceo-of-automotive-icon-is-of-finnish-descent.html|date=December 16, 2013|work=[[Helsinki Times]]}}</ref> Barra's ancestors are from the village of [[Kankaanp\u00e4\u00e4, S\u00e4kyl\u00e4|Kankaanp\u00e4\u00e4]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aamulehti.fi/a/24138832 |title=Trumpin uusi neuvonantaja on moottorimimmi \u2013 osaa sanoa suomeksi \u201dOnks tankissa bensaa?\u201d |last1=Tapio |first1=Ilari |date=December 13, 2016 |website=[[Aamulehti]] |language=fi |access-date=July 8, 2019 |quote=Amerikkalaisen autoj\u00e4tin toimitusjohtajan Mary Barran sukujuuret ovat M\u00e4kel\u00e4n torpassa K\u00f6yli\u00f6n Kankaanp\u00e4\u00e4n kyl\u00e4ss\u00e4.}}</ref> in [[Satakunta|Satakunta province]] in Finland, from the former municipality of [[K\u00f6yli\u00f6]]. Her grandfather, Viktor M\u00e4kel\u00e4, moved to the [[United States]] and married Maria Luoma, a Finnish immigrant from [[Teuva]]. They lived in [[Minnesota]], in the small mining town of [[Mountain Iron]]. They had three children, including a son named Reino,<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://blogs.wsj.com/corporate-intelligence/2013/12/10/a-look-at-mary-barra-gms-first-female-ceo/ | title=A Look at Mary Barra, GM\u2019s First Female CEO | work=The Wall Street Journal | date=December 10, 2013 | accessdate=December 11, 2013}}</ref> also called Ray. Her father Ray married a second-generation Finnish American named Eva Pyykk\u00f6nen, and Mary was born in 1961. Ray worked for 39 years at the [[Pontiac]] car factory in [[Detroit]], and the family lived in [[Waterford Township, Oakland County, Michigan|Waterford, Michigan]]. Barra attended Waterford schools in Michigan. She is a graduate of [[Waterford Mott High School]].\n\n== Education ==\nBarra graduated from the General Motors Institute (now [[Kettering University]]), where she obtained a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[electrical engineering]]. Barra was inducted into the engineering honor society [[Tau_Beta_Pi#Undergraduate_eligibility_requirements|Tau Beta Pi]].<ref name=\"taubetapi2018\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tbp.org/other/NAEclass18.cfm|title=Tau Beta Pi - NAE class 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402082529/https://www.tbp.org/other/NAEclass18.cfm|archive-date=2 April 2020|publisher=[[Tau Beta Pi]]|access-date=2020-04-02|quote=Mary T. Barra, Michigan Zeta '85}}</ref> She then attended [[Stanford Graduate School of Business]] on a GM fellowship, receiving her [[Masters in Business Administration]] degree in 1990.<ref name=bb/>\n\n==Career==\n\n=== General Motors ===\nBarra started working for General Motors, at age 18,<ref name=shm/> as a [[Cooperative education|co-op student]], in 1980, checking fender panels and inspecting hoods to pay for her college tuition.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://work.qz.com/1175673/general-motors-ceo-mary-barra-on-her-leadership-style-and-career/|title=GM CEO Mary Barra says too many women quit their jobs for the wrong reason|work=Quartz at Work|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en-US}}</ref> and subsequently held a variety of engineering and administrative positions, including managing the [[Detroit/Hamtramck Assembly]] plant.<ref name=bb>{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=40221799&privcapId=61206100 | title=Mary Barra: Executive Profile & Biography | work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] | access-date=December 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2008, she became vice president of Global Manufacturing Engineering. In July 2009, she advanced to the position of vice president of Global [[Human Resources]], which she held until February 2011, when she was named executive vice president of Global Product Development.<ref name=bb/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/21/business/21auto.html | title=G.M. Names New Leader for Global Development | last1=Bunkley | first1=Nick | last2=Vlasic | first2=Bill | work=The New York Times | date=January 20, 2011 | access-date=December 11, 2013}}</ref> The latter position included responsibilities for design; she has worked to reduce the number of [[automobile platforms]] in [[List of GM platforms|GM]].<ref name=\"nyt\"/> In August 2013, her vice president responsibility was extended to include Global Purchasing and Supply Chain.<ref name=gm>{{cite web | url=http://www.gm.com/company/aboutGM/GM_Corporate_Officers/mary_barra.html | title=About GM: Mary T. Barra | publisher=General Motors| access-date=December 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhen Barra took over as chief executive of General Motors in January 2014, she became the first female head of an automobile manufacturer.<ref>[http://www.new-corner.com/rebuilding-a-giant-mary-barra-ceo-general-motors/ Rebuilding a Giant: Mary Barra, CEO, General Motors], New Corner, June 5, 2015</ref>\n\nDuring her first year as CEO, General Motors issued 84 [[safety recall]]s involving over 30 million cars.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.zacks.com/stock/news/159304/general-motors-gm-safety-recalls-add-up-to-84-in-2014l | title=General Motors (GM): Safety Recalls Add Up to 84 in 2014 | publisher=Zacks Equity Research | access-date=January 5, 2015}}</ref> Barra was called before the Senate to testify about the recalls and deaths attributed to the faulty ignition switch.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2014/07/23/gm-ignition-senate-mary-barra-editorials-debates/13068081/ | title=GM reverses openness pledge: Our view | publisher=USA Today | access-date=July 23, 2014 | date=July 23, 2014}}</ref> Barra and General Motors also came under suspicion of paying for awards to burnish the CEO and corporation's image during that time.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.autoblog.com/2015/01/21/gm-buying-awards-mary-barra-report/ | title=Is General Motors buying awards for Mary Barra? | publisher=Autoblog | access-date=January 21, 2015}}</ref> The recalls led to the creation of new policies encouraging workers to report problems they encounter in an attempt to change company culture.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://work.qz.com/1175673/general-motors-ceo-mary-barra-on-her-leadership-style-and-career/|title=GM CEO Mary Barra says too many women quit their jobs for the wrong reason|work=Quartz at Work|access-date=February 26, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAs CEO, Barra has placed GM's focus as a company transitioning into the tech space by moving forward in the automated driverless car space with major acquisitions including Strobe, a startup focused on driverless technology.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/09/business/general-motors-driverless.html|title=G.M. Acquires Strobe, Start-Up Focused on Driverless Technology|last=Vlasic|first=Bill|date=October 9, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 17, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In 2017 she pushed GM to develop the Chevy Bolt EV, beating rival Tesla in developing the first electric car priced under $40,000 with a range of 200 miles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-day-in-the-life-of-gm-ceo-mary-barra-1461601044|title=A Day in the Life of GM CEO Mary Barra|last=Ross|first=Christopher|date=April 26, 2016|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=November 15, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Barra was the highest paid [[Detroit Three]] executive, with a total remuneration of $21.96 million.<ref name=\"detroitnews.com\">{{cite web|url=https://detroitnews.com/story/business/autos/general-motors/2018/04/27/gm-proxy-mary-barra-compensation/34313299/|title=GM paid CEO Mary Barra nearly $22M in 2017|publisher=}}</ref> In November 2018, Barra announced the closure of five North American plants and 14,000 worker [[lay off]]s.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/11/26/gm-unallocating-several-plants-in-2019-to-take-3-billion-to-3point8-billion-charge-in-future-quarters.html|title=GM to halt production at several plants, cut more than 14,000 jobs|first=Robert|last=Ferris|date=November 26, 2018|publisher=}}</ref> Her decision was criticized by [[President Trump]], who threatened to remove the company's government subsidies in response.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n=== Disney ===\nIn August 2017, she was elected to the board of [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Golum|first1=Rob|last2=Welch|first2=David|title=Barra elected to Walt Disney board|url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20170824/OEM02/170829852/barra-elected-to-walt-disney-board|publisher=Automotive News|date=August 24, 2017}}</ref> She was the 12th person elected to this board, and the fourth woman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disney-adds-general-motors-ceo-board-directors-1032380|title=Disney Adds General Motors CEO to Board of Directors|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Other boards and councils ===\nBarra was a member of the [[General Dynamics]] board of directors. She serves on the board of directors of the Detroit Economic Club and Detroit Country Day School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dykema.com/news-press-kellett-elected-to-detroit-economic-club-board_041015.html|title=Dykema Chairman and CEO Peter Kellett Elected to the Detroit Economic Club Board of Directors|website=www.dykema.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theoaklandpress.com/news/detroit-country-day-school-announces-new-trustees-including-gm-ceo/article_f3d4a985-3f8e-5e98-a477-182d5e586370.html|title=Detroit Country Day School announces new trustees, including GM CEO Mary Barra|website=The Oakland Press|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hometownlife.com/story/news/local/birmingham/2014/10/12/gm-ceo-mary-barra-joins-detroit-country-day-school-board-trustees/17041271/|title=GM CEO Mary Barra joins Detroit Country Day School Board of Trustees|last=Grossman|first=Jay|website=HometownLife|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref> She also serves as a member of [[The Business Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/business/autos/general-motors/2015/07/15/gm-ceo-barra-joins-stanford-university-board/30181281/|title=GM CEO Barra joins Stanford University board|last=Burden|first=Melissa|website=Detroit News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> She is a member of the Stanford University board of trustees, and the Stanford Graduate School of Business advisory council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/business/autos/general-motors/2015/07/15/gm-ceo-barra-joins-stanford-university-board/30181281/|title=GM CEO Barra joins Stanford University board|last=Burden|first=Melissa|website=Detroit News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nBarra was listed as 35th on [[Forbes list of The World's 100 Most Powerful Women|''Forbes'' Most Powerful Women]] list, in 2013, rising in rank to second most powerful, in 2018.<ref name=Forbes14>{{cite news|title=The World's 100 Most Powerful Women|url=https://www.forbes.com/power-women/list/#tab:overall|website=Forbes|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=June 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, she delivered the [[commencement address]] for [[University of Michigan]]'s Ann Arbor campus at [[Michigan Stadium]], and received an [[honorary degree]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/mary-barra/ | title=Mary Barra | work=[[Forbes]] | last=Goudreau|first=Jenna | year=2012|accessdate=September 7, 2012}}</ref>\nIn 2018, she received an honorary Doctorate from [[Duke University]].\n\nBarra was first in [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'s Most Powerful Women list in 2015, up from second the year before.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Mary Barra|url = http://fortune.com/most-powerful-women/mary-barra-1/|website = Fortune|accessdate = October 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe remained in the number one spot in [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'s Most Powerful Women of 2017<ref>{{Cite web|title = Mary Barra|url = http://fortune.com/most-powerful-women/|website = Fortune|accessdate = April 3, 2017}}</ref> and Number 5 on [[Forbes]] World's 100 Most Powerful Women List in the same year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/power-women/list/|title=World's Most Powerful Women|work=Forbes|access-date=March 29, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, Barra was featured on the cover of [[Time (magazine)|Time]]'s \"100 Most Influential People in the World.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Iacocca|first1=Lee|title=Mary Barra: The World\u2019s 100 Most Influential People|url=http://time.com/collection-post/70843/mary-barra-2014-time-100/|work=TIME.com}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, Barra joined a business forum assembled by [[Donald J. Trump|then President-Elect Donald Trump]] to provide strategic and policy advice on economic issues.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bryan|first1=Bob|title=Trump is forming an economic advisory team with the CEOs of Disney, General Motors, JPMorgan, and more|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/trump-strategic-and-policy-forum-includes-dimon-iger-schwarzman-2016-12|accessdate=June 1, 2017|publisher=Business Insider|date=December 2, 2016}}</ref> However, she left the forum in 2017, following Trump's response to the Charlottesville protests.\n\nBarra was elected to the [[National_Academy_of_Engineering#Membership|National Academy of Engineering]] in February 2018.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|url=https://www.nae.edu/178117.aspx|archive-date=8 February 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208182205/https://www.nae.edu/178117.aspx|title=National Academy of Engineering Elects 83 Members and 16 Foreign Members|date=2018-02-07|publisher=[[National Academy of Engineering]]|access-date=2020-04-02|quote=For leadership in automotive manufacturing, product engineering, and product development.|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|last2=|date=Spring 2018|title=Class of 2018 Elected : New Members|url=https://www.nae.edu/File.aspx?id=181157#page=49|url-status=live|journal=The Bridge|publisher=[[National Academy of Sciences]]|volume=48|issue=1|page=47|issn=0737-6278|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402090303/https://www.nae.edu/File.aspx?id=181157|archive-date=2 April 2020|via=}}</ref> In September 2018, Barra was awarded the Yale Chief Executive Leadership Institute's Legend in Leadership Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://som.yale.edu/news/2018/09/chief-executive-leadership-institute-honors-mary-t-barra-with-legend-in-leadership-award|title=Chief Executive Leadership Institute Honors Mary T. Barra with Legend in Leadership Award|date=2018-09-24|website=Yale School of Management|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Institutional Investor (magazine)|Institutional Investor]]''{{'}}s yearly survey of top executives, the 2019 All-America Executive Team, Barra achieved the first place in the autos and auto parts sector.<ref name=\"Whyte\">{{cite news |last1=Whyte |first1=Amy |title=These Are America\u2019s Top Executives  Jamie Dimon, Tim Cook, and Mary Barra are among members of II\u2019s 2019 All-America Executive Team |url=https://www.institutionalinvestor.com/article/b1bsssqc9w0p5v/These-Are-America-s-Top-Executives |accessdate=29 March 2019 |work=Institutional Investor |date=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBarra is married to consultant Tony Barra, whom she met while studying at [[Kettering University]], and has two children and two dogs,.<ref name=\"nyt\"/> They live in [[Northville Township, Michigan|Northville]], a suburb of Detroit. She also owns an apartment in [[Downtown Detroit]]<ref name=wsj>{{cite news| last=Bennett | first=Jeff | title=Longtime Insider Is GM's First Female CEO | url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303560204579249952766187032?mod=WSJ_hps_LEFTTopStories | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | author2=Murray, Sara | pages=A1, A10 | date=December 11, 2013 | accessdate=December 11, 2013}}</ref> \n\nShe has named the [[Chevrolet Camaro]] and the [[Pontiac Firebird]] as her favorite cars.<ref name=\"shm\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/11/business/mary-barra-gms-new-chief-speaking-her-mind.html | title=Mary Barra, G.M.\u2019s New Chief, Speaking Her Mind | work=The New York Times | date=December 10, 2013 | accessdate=December 11, 2013}}</ref> Barra can speak a little [[Finnish language|Finnish]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/mondays_papers_barras_finnish_roots_amorella_aftermath_and_tamperes_unemployment_problem/6986456|title=Barra's Finnish roots|date=December 16, 2013|website=Yle Uutiset|language=en|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Daniel Akerson]] | title= CEO of [[General Motors]] | after= current| years= since January 15, 2014}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Tim Solso]] | title= Chairmen of the Board of [[General Motors]] | after= current| years= since January 4, 2016}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barra, Mary}}\n[[Category:American women chief executives]]\n[[Category:General Motors executives]]\n[[Category:Kettering University alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford Graduate School of Business alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University trustees]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of manufacturing companies]]\n[[Category:American chief executives in the automobile industry]]\n[[Category:Women corporate directors]]\n[[Category:American people of Finnish descent]]\n[[Category:People from Royal Oak, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:American corporate directors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of Fortune 500 companies]]\n[[Category:21st-century businesswomen]]\n", "name_user": "Lent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add cite location", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_Barra"}
{"title_page": "2014\u201315 La Liga", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox football league season\n| competition        = [[La Liga]]\n| season             = 2014\u201315\n| dates              = 24 August 2014 \u2013 24 May 2015\n| winners            = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]<br><small>23rd title</small>\n| relegated          = [[Elche CF|Elche]]<br>[[UD Almer\u00eda|Almer\u00eda]]<br>[[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n| continentalcup1    = [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]<br>[[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]<br>[[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]<br>[[Valencia CF|Valencia]]<br>[[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] (as [[2015 UEFA Europa League Final|Europa League champions]])\n| continentalcup2    = [[2015\u201316 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers = [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]<br>[[Athletic Bilbao]]\n| league topscorer   = [[Cristiano Ronaldo]]<br>(48 goals)<ref name=\"topscorer\"/>\n| best goalkeeper    = [[Claudio Bravo (footballer)|Claudio Bravo]]<br>(0.51 goals/match)\n| biggest home win   = {{nobreak|[[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] 9\u20131 [[Granada CF|Granada]]}}<br />(5 April 2015)\n| biggest away win   = {{nobreak|[[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]] 0\u20138 [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]}}<br />(2 May 2015)\n| highest scoring    = {{nobreak|[[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]] 2\u20138 [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]}}<br />(20 September 2014)<br />{{nobreak|[[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] 9\u20131 [[Granada CF|Granada]]}}<br />(5 April 2015)<br />{{nobreak|[[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] 7\u20133 [[Getafe CF|Getafe]]}}<br />(23 May 2015)\n| matches            = 380\n| total goals        = 1009\n| longest wins       = 12 matches<ref name=\"stattostatistics\">{{cite web |url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/spain/primera-division/2014-2015/longest-sequences/full |title=Spanish Primera Division 2014\u201315 |publisher=statto.com |accessdate=22 April 2015}}</ref><br />[[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]\n| longest unbeaten   = 14 matches<ref name=\"stattostatistics\"/><br />[[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n| longest winless    = 20 matches<ref name=\"stattostatistics\"/><br />[[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n| longest losses     = 10 matches<ref name=\"stattostatistics\"/><br />[[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n| highest attendance = 98,760<ref name=stats>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/spanish-primera-division/15/statistics/performance |title=Spanish Primera Divisi\u00f3n Statistics \u2013 2014\u201315 |work=ESPN FC |publisher=Entertainment and Sports Programming Network (ESPN) |accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref><br />[[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] 2\u20131 [[Real Madrid]]<br />(22 March 2015)\n| lowest attendance  = 3,500<ref name=\"stats\"/><br />[[Getafe CF|Getafe]] 2\u20131 [[Celta de Vigo|Celta Vigo]]<br />(26 January 2015)\n| attendance         = 10,161,726<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n| average attendance = 26,741<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n| prevseason = [[2013\u201314 La Liga|2013\u201314]]\n| nextseason = [[2015\u201316 La Liga|2015\u201316]]\n}}\nThe '''2014\u201315 [[La Liga]]''' season (known as the ''Liga BBVA'' for sponsorship reasons) was the 84th season of the premier [[association football]] league in Spain. The campaign began on 23 August 2014 and ended on 24 May 2015.\n\n[[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] won its 23rd title on 17 May 2015 after defeating defending champions [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] at the [[Vicente Calder\u00f3n Stadium]], and also equalled the all-time record goal difference of +89 (110 goals scored and 21 conceded), originally set by [[Real Madrid]] in the [[2011\u201312 La Liga|2011\u201312]] season.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/may/17/atletico-madrid-barcelona-la-liga-match-report|title=Barcelona clinch title with Lionel Messi magic against Atl\u00e9tico Madrid|date=17 May 2015|work=Guardian|accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/barcelona/11611738/Lionel-Messi-hands-Barcelona-23rd-La-Liga-title.html|title=Lionel Messi hands Barcelona 23rd La Liga title|date=17 May 2015|work=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\n===Promotion and relegation (pre-season)===\nA total of 20 teams contest the league, including 17 sides from the [[2013\u201314 La Liga|2013\u201314 season]] and three promoted from the [[2013\u201314 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]. This includes the two top teams ([[SD Eibar|Eibar]] and [[Real Club Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]]) from the Segunda Divisi\u00f3n, and the winner of the  [[2014 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n play-offs|play-offs]], [[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]].\n\n[[SD Eibar|Eibar]] became the first club from Segunda Divisi\u00f3n to achieve promotion to La Liga after its 1\u20130 victory over [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|Alav\u00e9s]] on 25 May 2014. Eibar made their La Liga debut in the 2014\u201315 season.<ref>[http://www.goal.com/en-sg/news/3882/spain/2014/05/26/4840739/eibar-seal-stunning-promotion-to-la-liga Eibar seal stunning promotion to La Liga]; Goal.com, 26 May 2014</ref>\n\n[[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]] won promotion back to La Liga after one season in Segunda Divisi\u00f3n with a 1\u20130 victory over [[Real Ja\u00e9n]] on 31 May 2014.<ref>[http://www.sportsmole.co.uk/football/deportivo-la-coruna/result/result-deportivo-promoted-to-la-liga_157753.html Result: Deportivo La Coruna promoted to La Liga]; SportsMole, 31 May 2014</ref>\n\n[[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]] won the promotion play-off against [[UD Las Palmas|Las Palmas]] and returned to the top level after 42 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Las Palmas-Cordoba La Liga play-off ends with pitch invasion|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/138/spain/2014/06/23/4905144/las-palmas-cordoba-la-liga-play-off-ends-with-pitch-invasion|accessdate=30 June 2014|publisher=Goal.com|date=23 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Stadia and locations===\n{{Location map+ |Spain |width=450 |float=right |caption=Location of teams in '''2014\u201315 La Liga''' |places=\n{{Location map~ |Spain |lat=36.840028 |long=-2.435436 |label=<small>[[UD Almer\u00eda|Almer\u00eda]]</small> |position=top}}\n{{Location map~ |Spain |lat=43.264283 |long=-2.950153 |label=<small>[[Athletic Bilbao]]</small> |position=left}}\n{{Location map~ |Spain |lat=40.401703 |long=-3.720628 |label=<small>[[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid|Atl\u00e9tico&nbsp;Madrid]]</small> |position=left}}\n{{Location map~ |Spain |lat=41.380889 |long=2.1228167 |label=<small>[[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]</small> |position=right}}\n{{Location map~ |Spain |lat=37.872219 |long=-4.764550 |label=<small>[[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]]</small> |position=top}}\n{{Location map~ |Spain |lat=42.211842 |long=-8.739706 |label=<small>[[Celta de Vigo|Celta Vigo]]</small> |position=top}}\n{{Location map~ |Spain |lat=43.368717 |long=-8.417514 |label=<small>[[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]]</small> |position=top}}\n{{Location map~ |Spain |lat=43.181706 |long=-2.475803 |label=<small>[[SD Eibar|Eibar]]</small> |position=bottom}}\n{{Location map~ |Spain |lat=38.267111 |long=-0.663272 |label=<small>[[Elche CF|Elche]]</small> |position=bottom}}\n{{Location map~ |Spain |lat=41.347861 |long=2.0756667 |label=<small>[[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]]</small> |position=left}}\n{{Location map~ |Spain |lat=40.325728 |long=-3.714950 |label=<small>[[Getafe CF|Getafe]]</small> |position=bottom}}\n{{Location map~ |Spain |lat=37.152925 |long=-3.595744 |label=<small>[[Granada CF|Granada]]</small> |position=top}}\n{{Location map~ |Spain |lat=39.494703 |long=-0.363842 |label=<small>[[Levante UD|Levante]]</small>}}\n{{Location map~ |Spain |lat=36.734217 |long=-4.426603 |label=<small>[[M\u00e1laga CF|M\u00e1laga]]</small> |position=bottom}}\n{{Location map~ |Spain |lat=40.391828 |long=-3.658586 |label=<small>[[Rayo Vallecano|Rayo&nbsp;Vallecano]]</small> 